<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHTENING LABOR MARKET MEANS RATE INCREASES ARE LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change percentage figure in 7th graf from 6.18 to 6.17,
and adds ``on Thursday.'' No other changes.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Employers hired new workers at a surprisingly
robust pace last month and had to pay substantially more to find
them, the government reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While good news in most respects, the report underscored the
mounting pressures in the labor market and substantially increased
the likelihood that the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates
at its next meeting, on Aug. 24, as insurance against an
inflationary spiral in wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate in July remained steady at 4.3 percent,
the Labor Department said. Meanwhile, employers added an estimated
310,000 non-farm jobs in the month, 50 percent more than analysts
had anticipated, suggesting that economic growth rebounded early in
the summer after tailing off during the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly earnings in July rose by one-half of one percent,
to $13.29 from $13.23, continuing a gradual acceleration of wage
growth in recent months. Earnings in July grew 3.8 percent over the
previous year, up from a 3.5 percent annual pace in May and a 3.7
percent annual rate in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor is getting more expensive per hour, and we're still
using a lot of it,'' said Donald Ratajczak, the director of the
Economic Forecasting Center at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, which is far more attuned to the dangers of
resurgent inflation and higher interest rates than to the benefits
of full employment and rising wages, stock and bond prices fell.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 79.79 points to close
at 10,714.03. The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond
plummeted, sending its yield, which moves inversely with the price,
to 6.17 percent late in the day from 6.04 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy eight-and-a-half years into an expansion that
has kicked promptly back into high gear every time it has shown
signs of flagging, the Labor Department report showed that job
growth, adjusted to take account of normal seasonal variations, was
strong in almost all industries.
</P>
<P>
   Of special note was a jump of 31,000 in manufacturing
employment, the first increase in that sector since General Motors
workers returned from a strike last August, and the first not
related to the strike since March 1998. Manufacturers had been hit
especially hard last year by the fallout from the global financial
crisis that began in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, said last month
that the central bank was watching especially intently for any
signs that the combination of low unemployment and strong job
growth was generating wage increases that could ignite inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists said that Friday's data provided more than
enough ammunition for the Federal Reserve to raise its benchmark
federal funds target rate by another quarter point later this
month, to 5.25 percent. The central bank last raised the rate by a
quarter point in June, citing the potential for wage growth in a
tight labor market to outstrip the strong gains in productivity
generated by huge investments in computers and other technology.
</P>
<P>
   The economists said that Friday's numbers reinforced a trend
seen in various economic reports in the last few weeks, including
signs of a dropoff in the growth of productivity, or hourly output
per worker, and a rise in the wage component of the employment cost
index.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data confirm the reacceleration in the economy that I've
been looking for in the summer,'' said Richard Berner, an economist
at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. He estimated that growth is now
running at a 4 percent annual rate, up from 2.3 percent in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time they also suggest we're seeing the impact of
tight labor markets on wage setting,'' he said. ``The gentle
acceleration we're seeing in average hourly earnings confirms the
trend we're seeing in the employment cost index and means the Fed
will almost certainly tighten policy on Aug. 24.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on trading in the futures markets, investors are all but
certain that the Fed will raise rates this month. Futures contracts
on federal funds for September yielded 5.23 percent Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said the case for a rate increase this month was
not air tight, although they conceded that if the Federal Reserve
did not move this month it would probably do so at its subsequent
meeting in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed cut interest rates three times in quarter-point
increments last fall when economies and financial markets around
the world showed signs of seizing up. Many analysts now expect the
central bank to take back the remaining two of those cuts and
perhaps tighten policy a bit more over the next six months or so if
the economy remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect is already generating political pressure on
Greenspan not to squeeze the economy too hard in an effort to
eliminate inflationary pressures that so far have been more
theoretical than real. Despite rising wages, general price
increases so far have been well-contained, and some sectors of the
economy, including agriculture and manufacturing, complain that
monetary policy is too tight.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the Republican presidential candidate, began
running radio advertising this week in Iowa, ground zero in the
dismal farm sector, criticizing Greenspan for pushing rates too
high at a time when crop prices are depressed. The National
Association of Manufacturers released a pointed analysis Friday
concluding that even an acceleration in labor cost growth to four
percent would result in only a small pickup in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Greenspan has made clear that he views an ever-tighter
labor market as a clear threat to generate inflation and endanger
the stability of the long expansion, which, if it continues, will
surpass at the end of this year the record set in the 1960s. And
while the unemployment rate has hovered at 4.2 percent to 4.3
percent since March, the pace of job creation has picked up in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The 310,000 new jobs created in July ``followed a 273,000 gain
in June and was well above the average monthly increase of 208,000
for the first half of 1999,'' said Katharine Abraham, the Labor
Department's commissioner of labor statistics. ``Manufacturing and
construction employment increased over the month, and several
service-producing industries posted sizable gains.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate of job growth over the last year is still relatively
moderate at 2.3 percent, said David Orr, chief economist at First
Union Bank. But he said that even at that rate the pool of
available workers is being steadily depleted because the labor
force has been growing at only 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In congressional testimony last month, Greenspan said that ``if
the pool of job seekers shrinks sufficiently, upward pressures on
wage costs are inevitable,'' and that such wage increases ``have
invariably presaged rising inflation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
