</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-VALENTINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: WIN OR LOSE, VALENTINE CARRIES A BURDEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Years and years from now, fans of the 1999 New York
Mets will tell their grandchildren the tale of how, 55 games and
three fired coaches into the season, Bobby Valentine declared to
the world, ``In the next 55 games, if we're not better, I shouldn't
be the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   That story was related to Davey Johnson Friday night, and when
he was told that the Mets had run up a 39-15 record since the
Valentine declaration, he said, ``Those three new coaches must
really be something.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has had experience losing a job as manager, was at
Shea Stadium with his woefully underachieving Los Angeles Dodgers,
just in time to complete Valentine's 55-game cycle. The Mets' 2-1
victory even made their manager a prophet in his own time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said, `Do you want to win eight in a row?''' Valentine
said, recalling that agonizing night exactly two months earlier,
when the Mets had just lost eight in a row. ``I said, no, I'd
rather have a sustained run; something like 40 and 15 would be
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty and 15 has been terrific for the Mets. The run has
catapulted them from 27-28, in third place, six games out of the
lead, to 67-43, in first place, 1 1/2 games ahead of the perennial
champion Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident that they'd play better,'' Valentine said
Friday night. ``That's why I said it. I'm really proud of them, the
way they've come together. It's a good team right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips is the man who made necessary the news conference
at which Valentine issued his declaration. As the general manager,
Phillips had fired half of the manager's coaching staff, including
the two coaches with whom he was the closest.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Valentine uttered his 55-game remark, some listeners
suspected he did it before Phillips could suggest that the
manager's job was on the line. Last night Phillips took no credit
for the timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my line of demarcation,'' he said. ``He threw it out
there. It does not have any special significance to me. I like
where we are today. We responded to the challenges of the season
and to adversity. I don't think we could ask for much more from
where we were to where we are today.''
</P>
<P>
   As much credit as the manager has to receive, along with the
players, for the two-month turnaround, he has not been free of
questionable and puzzling behavior during that time. A series of
incidents and comments have left Valentine's employers and others
shaking their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Will the season produce a more bizarre sight than Valentine
standing at the fringe of the dugout in a sunglasses-and-mustache
disguise after he had been ejected from that June 9 game?
</P>
<P>
   A few days later he engaged in a startling bit of revisionist
history, talking about the great job he had done cleaning up ``the
abyss that was here 2 1/2 years ago'' and about the ``placid and
peaceful'' atmosphere he had created. He apparently forgot that
Dallas Green, his predecessor, had cleaned up the mess and that
Pete Harnisch and Todd Hundley did not find peace and serenity in
Valentine's clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Valentine made a string of incredible statements,
starting with his criticism of the team's front office for filling
Shea Stadium by playing merengue music and honoring Sammy Sosa. The
crowd, Valentine complained, cheered for Sosa and not the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   (Friday night was Hispanic Night at Shea. Asked before the game
if he felt the Mets would fare better than they did on Sosa night,
Valentine said: ``It's Latin night. We have a few very good Latin
players, so they should definitely be behind us.'')
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets acquired Kenny Rogers in a trade, Valentine was
asked what it meant to manage the pitcher he once had in Texas. His
reply said nothing about Rogers but a lot about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just means,'' he said, ``that everyone who has tried to run
me out of the game hasn't succeeded. I've stayed around a while.''
Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Then a week ago, after the Mets arrived in first place for the
first time, Valentine again took an innocuous question and answered
with an eyebrow-raising response. Did it seem, he was asked, like a
long progression from the day he took over late in the 1996 season
to that day?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been obviously a progression of nonrecognition,'' he
said. ``No matter what we do, there's very little credit. And now
that we're in first, we'll still get no credit until we finish the
job. Nothing's going to change what's said or felt about our team
until it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   To a follow-up question, Valentine said the feeling was directed
mostly at him. ``But that just comes with the territory,'' he said,
the territory of being Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   It is a heavy burden. With eight more games (the eighth comes
next Saturday in San Francisco), he will go to No. 3 on the list of
people who have managed the most games without finishing first. His
1,659 games will trail only the 1,837 of Paul Richards and the
2,962 of Jimmy Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine is only 52 games away from removing himself from
that list. ``No predictions on that,'' he said after the game. ``I
think we're going to be a good team right to the end of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
