<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT MOVE AND WRIGHT MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's lesson in NBA-sponsored fiscal responsibility is
provided by Eric Piatkowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a genius to look around the league and see
there's really no money out there,'' said Piatkowski, who seemed to
challenge his own theory Friday by noticing the wisdom in agreeing
to a four-year, $12 million deal that will prolong what has been a
five-year career with the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   His alternative was a two-year, $4.2 million contract with
Golden State. Piatkowski, it would seem, chose the smarter money.
</P>
<P>
   A genius also isn't necessary to figure out that by threatening
to sign a one-year, $2 million middle-class exception with the
Lakers, Lorenzen Wright, Piatkowski's teammate the past three
seasons, is threatening to chuck conventional economic wisdom into
the drink.
</P>
<P>
   But Wright's agent, Robert Fayne, met with the Lakers on Friday
to kick that notion around. The Lakers also contacted the Clippers
about possible sign-and-trade deals involving bit players on the
Laker roster whose unloading could provide a more lucrative deal
for Wright.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite outdated map readings to the contrary, turnip
trucks no longer take the scenic route past the Sports Arena.
According to a Clippers source, any sign-and-trade notions
involving Wright and the NBA's two L.A. teams are going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves Wright staring at the Laker exception, while his
agent hopes another interested team can make the Clips an
acceptable sign-and-trade offer. Atlanta could be back in the
picture with $4.5 million in cap room and the enticement of draft
picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still talk,'' said Elgin Baylor, the Clippers' vice
president of basketball operations. ``But I have no idea what he's
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'' is Fayne, who could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Piatkowski, when reached at his off-season home in Nebraska,
said Wright would be wise to follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just have to swallow your pride,'' Piatkowski
said, ``and accept the deal that is best for you and your family.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wright, such strategy would have allowed him to grab the
six-year, $30 million deal the Clippers offered. Instead, Wright
and Fayne shopped around for a team willing to spend, oh, $8
million per season on a 6-foot-11 backup center/power forward.
</P>
<P>
   When that animal left no tracks, Fayne turned back to the
Clippers, who could have helped out his client by signing and
trading Wright to a team that would clear acceptable cap space by
sending its wretched refuse to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   But accepting a deal for draft picks is less risky for the
Clips, because they wouldn't be obligated to pay unwanted players.
So they are still listening to offers, while Fayne keeps the
Lakers, who reportedly would prefer adding Toronto free agent
Charles Oakley, on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the rush for us?'' a Clippers source said.
</P>
<P>
   But time did become an issue for Piatkowski, who responded to a
take-it-or-leave-it deadline for reasons of cash and familiarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the money, and there's a comfort level there for me and
my wife,'' said Piatkowski of the Clippers, for whom he provided 10
points per game last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' unfinished business includes signing draft prize
Lamar Odom (Monday), dealing with Maurice Taylor and agent David
Falk on a contract extension (Aug. 20), re-signing last season's
undrafted rookie surprise Tyrone Nesby (whenever) and mulling their
point-guard prospects.
</P>
<P>
   One name surfacing as a possible answer to the last issue is
Haywoode Workman, a free agent who played for the Milwaukee Bucks
last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
