<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LA-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKERS OF FOOTBALL FOR L.A. RENEW EFFORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even as critics threatened a referendum to block
any public spending, Los Angeles officials rallied to save the
Memorial Coliseum as the home of a new National Football League
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas and
representatives of the competing ownership groups appealed in
private phone calls and public pronouncements that the NFL should
reconsider its decision to end its agreement to consider only the
Coliseum as a site for football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in contact with the NFL and assured them that the
Coliseum is still the most attractive option,'' Ridley-Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gov. Gray Davis withdrew the state as a dealmaker
and the NFL responded by announcing that other stadium sites in the
metropolitan area would be considered until the Sept. 15 deadline
on talks with Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's action left Los Angeles' chances of winning a
franchise in serious doubt and made Houston the favorite for the
league's 32nd team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working on this for three years and it should not
be discarded overnight because of problems with one person,'' said
Ridley-Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   That one person is investment banker Bill Chadwick, who was
designated by Davis to be the point man for the state in the
negotiations and who drew the NFL's ire this week when he tried to
pull out of the negotiations, saying nothing further could be done.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials, in response to Chadwick's comments, said they
would open the field of sites under consideration to any in the Los
Angeles market interested in becoming home to a new professional
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick left the city on Friday and aides said he would have no
comment on the new controversy. Davis aides said all state dealings
with the NFL would continue to be through Chadwick.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials, however, held out hope L.A. could still win a
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find if you're cool in defeat, you can turn it around,''
Riordan said during an interview on the Michael Jackson show on
KRLA-AM (1110). ``And I think that's what Eli Broad is doing, what
I'm doing and what Mark Ridley-Thomas is doing. It ain't over until
the lady sings.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said he still considers having a football team at the
Coliseum as a top priority, a means of reviving the Exposition Park
area as well as attracting businesses to the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much the jobs created at the Coliseum as the
corporations that look at having a professional football team as
important,'' Riordan said. ``They move here and bring high-paying
jobs with them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Councilman Joel Wachs and Jon Coupal
of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association threatened to stage a
statewide vote over whether public money should be used to attract
a professional sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason tax dollars should be used to help
billionaire owners and gazillionaire athletes,'' Wachs said. ``We
ask the people to vote on whether we should build more police and
fire stations or libraries. Well, we can ask them if they want
their money to go for a professional football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachs dismissed the threat of the NFL going to a site other than
the Coliseum, saying he saw it as a bargaining ploy to try to get
more money from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Under one proposal, the state would provide $150 million from a
bond issue to be repaid with revenue from the parking structures
the money would pay for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be watching,'' said Wachs, who emerged as a critic of
public financing in the debate over the Staples Center Arena. ``I
am hearing all these words about no net cost. Well, I think there
should be no cost to the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupal released a survey of 600 voters statewide that showed 80
percent opposed use of any tax dollars for professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the NFL understands the depth of feeling about
this issue,'' Coupal said.
</P>
<P>
   Ridley-Thomas said he will be talking with NFL officials over
the weekend as he renewed his criticism of Chadwick's handling of
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just go in there and make demands and then walk
away,'' Ridley-Thomas said. ``This is a process and there are
certain steps to be followed.''
</P>
<P>
   The councilman said he would be talking with NFL officials
throughout the weekend to try to reverse the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum Commission has scheduled an emergency meeting for
Monday, in part to consider a proposal submitted by Broad.
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire businessman said he remains committed to the
Coliseum, and offered the NFL a nonrefundable payment of $2 million
to give him six days to develop a final plan.
</P>
<P>
   His proposals include the $150 million state bond issue for
parking and public responsibility for any work done outside the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The owners would pay $1 million a rent a year for 55 years and
an NFL franchise fee of $550 million with half to be paid up front
and the remainder to be paid over a period to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be looking at that proposal specifically and I think
it's something we can live with,'' Commission President Sheldon
Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, who serves as Coliseum Commission
vice chairman, questioned the NFL's sincerity on wanting to come to
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic case of snatching defeat from the jaws of
victory,'' Yaroslavsky said. ``It's hard to know what's going on.
If someone was trying to blow up this deal, then the way the NFL
has behaved in the last week would be the way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all blaming Chadwick, but he came up with a proposal.
If they were serious, they would come up with a counteroffer.
Instead, they publicly challenged the taxpayers of Los Angeles to
come up with more cash. It makes you wonder if all this talk of the
Coliseum was a charade.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky said the NFL could cut $200 million off the cost of
the Coliseum deal by reducing parking by half and eliminating
extras.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking about the owners fielding a competitive team,
but they keep adding costs to the construction,'' Yaroslavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Another official, asking not to be identified, voiced similar
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL keeps moving the goal line and we never are able to
find out what they really want,'' the official said. ``At some
point, someone has to make a decision and they don't seem to want
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL pronouncement raised many new possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Hollywood Park in Inglewood said they were studying
the latest proposal and were not sure what steps would be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Businessman Marvin Davis has an option on 100 acres on the site
for a potential stadium. That option runs through September.
</P>
<P>
   In Irwindale, City Manager Bob Griego said residents would
likely be lukewarm to any proposal to build an NFL stadium in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The residents would be very cautious about any dealings with a
stadium after what they went through the last time,'' Griego said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the city suffered a very expensive and painful lesson
when it put down a $10 million deposit for its deal with Raiders
owner Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the agreement to build a stadium in the city fall
through, but the city was never refunded its deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Griego, who has been following the recent negotiations,
said: ``It crossed my mind that if the NFL was to come to
California, they might have to increase their options.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
