<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO WHAT IS VALDES' VALUE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last offseason, Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
locked up Carlos Perez with a three-year contract and offered Chan
Ho Park a four-year, $32 million contract that he turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Economics may keep the Dodgers from taking a similar path with
right-hander Ismael Valdes, eligible for arbitration after the
season and free agency after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're considering, but one thing we don't have
is payroll flexibility,'' Malone said. ``That's something that
factors into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who said he wants to remain with the Dodgers' long-term
plans, makes $4.275 million this season and is in line to make
about $6 million next season. But if the Dodgers were to agree on a
multi-year deal with the 25-year-old, it would most likely cost
them $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, that would create a further crimp in the Dodgers'
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are in the position of wanting to move a few players
with expensive, multi-year contracts to lessen the $80 million
payroll burden and create flexibility. If they can trade Eric
Young, Perez or even Raul Mondesi _ who combined are owed $42.1
million over the next two seasons _ it would ease the payroll
situation. Signing Valdes to a long-term deal could minimize the
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, seeing what in-season contract talks did to Park, said
he doesn't even want to think about a deal until after the season,
but indicated it was possible he would sign a multi-year pact.
Valdes is 8-10, but he leads Dodgers starters with a 3.31 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Honor this: The Mets have grown accustomed to honoring players
before games, but a ceremony for ex-Met Todd Hundley was wiped off
the agenda a few weeks ago by Mets manager and Hundley antagonist
Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Daily News, Valentine flipped when the
Mets honored Chicago Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa before a recent game.
Given the feud between Hundley and Valentine over the last two
years, a presentation honoring the ultra-popular Hundley wouldn't
go over well with the Mets skipper. Sources told the newspaper Mets
management opted not hold a ceremony because it didn't want to
agitate a delicate situation.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was greeted by shrieking girls before the game and
received a standing ovation before his first at-bat. He then struck
out on three pitches and finished 0 for 3, his average dropping to
.216.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth in rotation: One of the things the Dodgers will
likely try to find out in the next 53 games is whether outfielder
Todd Hollandsworth can be an everyday player.
</P>
<P>
   But to do that, manager Davey Johnson will have to sit a bunch
of salary in either left fielder Gary Sheffield ($10 million),
Mondesi ($9 million), center fielder Devon White ($2.5 million) or
first baseman Eric Karros ($5.5 million).
</P>
<P>
   It was Sheffield who felt the sting of it Friday. He sat against
righty Octavio Dotel so Hollandsworth could start in left field.
Hollandsworth started in center and at first in the previous two
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this period might be, like (management) said, a trial
period to see who can play every day, and that means
Hollandsworth,'' White said. ``There's nothing wrong with trying
it. I don't worry about that. I feel if I'm going out there and
doing my job, it's going to be tough for (Johnson) to take me out
of the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Johnson and injured Mets outfielder Bobby Bonilla talked
before the game on the field, and both said the statements
regarding their feud were overblown. . . . Former Dodger Roger
Cedeno stole two more bases to set up the Mets' run in the third.
He has 54 stolen bases. . . . Approximately 6,000 fans of Asian
descent were in the stands and cheering for Dodgers pitcher Chan Ho
Park, a native of Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
