<HEADLINE>
GORE, SON REACH THE SUMMIT OF MOUNT RAINIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARADISE, Wash. _ A weary, unshaven Vice President Al Gore and
his 16-year-old son successfully finished their climb of Mount
Rainier Friday night, striding out of a cold mist before sunset to
shake hands with well wishers.
</P>
<P>
   With exhausted Secret Service agents leading the way off the
mountain, the vice president summed up his climb as simply
``fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable experience,'' a tired looking Gore told
reporters from beneath his mountain backpack. ``It was just great.
And it's very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The two days Gore and his son, Albert Gore III, have been on the
14,411 foot-volcano have been filled with terrible weather _ hail,
wind, fog and snow.
</P>
<P>
   None of it stopped the Gore party: ``We were bound to do it,''
Gore said. As a father-son experience, summiting Mount Rainier
``couldn't have been better.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather was fierce enough to keep many climbers off the
mountain, or hunkered down in tents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thunderstorms up there are pretty mean,'' said Don
Wallace, who has been hiking since 1952 and was at the lodge at
Paradise Friday afternoon. Wallace spent Wednesday and Thursday at
Camp Muir at about the 10,000-foot level, never braving the nasty
conditions to make an attempt on the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Others who had heard rumors of Gore's attempt on the mountain's
summit praised the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad he's out here doing this kind of stuff. I think
it's important for the future of the park and the environment in
general,'' said Dave Sahms, 46, of Olympia, who mistakenly thought
he had spotted the vice president at Paradise Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's party headed up the mountain from Paradise Wednesday
morning, according to Mount Rainier National Park Superintendent
Jon Jarvis, who said only a handful of park staff were told the
vice president would be there.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Gore's staff described the getaway by Gore and his
son as so secret that even many senior White House staff and
presidential campaign aides were not informed of it.
</P>
<P>
   The secrecy was at Gore's ``specific request _ he wanted to
climb with his son,'' Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores have been running and lifting weights together at home
for months. All along, the vice president's said he was training
for a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Gore's son was hit by a car, thrown 30 feet and
severely injured as the family was leaving a baseball game at
Baltimore's Memorial Stadium. The episode in part galvanized Gore
to write his best-selling book ``Earth in the Balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, an avid jogger and hiker, told the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer last September that he was eager to climb Mount
Rainier at some point this year if he could spare the time.
</P>
<P>
   His climbing party this week did not use the park guides; Gore
and his son were led by a family friend who has climbed Mount
Rainier as well as Mount Everest, park officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The climbers spent part of Wednesday night at Anvil Rock,
roughly four miles above Paradise, then pushed onward to Ingraham
Flats at the 11,100-foot elevation. They left the Flats before dawn
yesterday morning for the summit, reaching it at about 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors on the mountain Friday spent much of the day discussing
whether or not Gore was even there. Few knew anything, but rumors
abounded about whether Gore had already left in a helicopter _ or
even hiked the mountain at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe some of the stories going through
(Paradise) _ it's a rumor mill,'' Chris Henley, a cook at the
Paradise lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Next week marks the 238,000-acre national park's centennial,
which will be celebrated with a ceremony at Paradise on the south
side of Mount Rainier on Thursday. Gore was invited to the party,
but it's not known if he will return.
</P>
<P>
   A runner who has completed the Marine Corps Marathon in
Washington, D.C., and competed in Seattle's 1998 Breast Cancer
Foundation Race for the Cure, Gore has talked extensively for years
about climbing Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many climbers, Gore reached the summit on his first try.
An online tour guide to Mount Rainier warns that half of the 10,000
men and women who attempt to climb itnever make it, turned back by
weather or exhaustion. Reaching the peak requires a vertical climb
of more than 9,000 feet over eight miles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was taken off the mountain by helicopter to Air Force Two,
which was parked at McChord Air Force Base near Tacoma. He was
scheduled to arrive in Chicago at 3 a.m. for a speech later
Saturday to Jesse Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Judd Slivka contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
