<SLUG> BC-SPORT-STADIUMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTLY RENOVATIONS TO KAUFFMAN AND ARROWHEAD STADIUMS CONSIDERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY and GLENN E. RICE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Civic leaders are considering how extensively
to remodel Kauffman and Arrowhead stadiums, a makeover that would
cost at least $100 million but could run up to $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some wish lists even envision building the long-ago abandoned
roof that would slide over either stadium. One concept incorporates
a St. Louis-style arch into the sliding roof.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in the talks are saying it's more likely they'll
settle on less dramatic upgrades, such as enclosing with glass the
middle level of each stadium to create heated or cooled zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total stadium improvement, from ground level to the top
of the stadium,'' said Jack Steadman, chairman of the Kansas City
Chiefs football team.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals baseball team and the Chiefs have been
crafting wish lists for more than a year. But now civic leaders are
grappling with those wish lists and the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not long term. This is something for the immediate
future. I would say within the next five years,'' said Nelson
Thompson, chairman of the Jackson County Sports Complex Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Still, leaders cautioned that they've only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no meat on these bones at all yet. It's just ideas,''
said banker William Nelson, who heads a sports committee of the
Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson and others said they don't know what the improvements
will look like or who'll pay for them _ although taxpayers or
ticket buyers are the likely candidates.
</P>
<P>
   A renovated stadium that includes pricier seats would make more
money for the Royals, which would help the team stay in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Royals need that extra revenue to make it,'' said John
Bondon, the vice chairman of the Sports Authority, which is
landlord for the county-owned Truman Sports Complex. ``They need
more than just the price of admission and parking and a hot dog.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Royals get extensive improvements to Kauffman
Stadium, then it's only fair that the Chiefs get similar treatment
for Arrowhead, said local leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Chiefs and Royals will be expected to sign new
leases. Current leases expire in 2015, but new leases could tie the
teams to the stadiums until perhaps 2025 or well beyond.
Plenty of discussion
</P>
<P>
   Political and civic leaders have spent a fair portion of the
summer talking and meeting about stadium improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The main meeting was called by the chamber and held June 28 in
its downtown offices. About 25 persons attended, including
representatives of the Chiefs and Royals along with state and local
political leaders, such as Jackson County Executive Katheryn
Shields and Mayor Kay Barnes. HOK Sport, the local architecture
firm, made a presentation. Nelson presided.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to get a narrowed-down wish list from each
team, figure out what it costs and then appoint a committee to plan
a way to get it financed, said Nelson and others.
</P>
<P>
   Cost estimates vary widely. Nelson figured $100 million to $150
million for both stadiums. The roof _ which he termed ``a frill'' _
would add perhaps $60 million to $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, the Sports Authority chairman, said estimates range up
to $250 million if the roof were included.
</P>
<P>
   Paying for the improvements is a big question mark. Some
possibilities that officials mentioned:
</P>
<P>
   - User fees. For example, each ticket would cost an extra buck
or two. However, the sports teams have opposed such fees in the
past, and it's doubtful that this method by itself could raise
enough money.
</P>
<P>
   - A sports lottery. Tickets could be sold periodically in
special lotteries. The profits would pay for or help pay for the
stadium improvements.
</P>
<P>
   - A new bistate tax in Missouri and Kansas. The current bistate
tax is an eighth-cent sales tax on both sides of the state line
that raises about $23 million a year to renovate Union Station. A
new bistate tax could be grafted onto the current one when it
expires, expected about the second quarter of 2002. It would
require a law change by each state because legislation currently
prohibits using bistate tax money for sports stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   - Some new tax or a combination of taxes, perhaps including one
or more of the above.
Costly ideas
</P>
<P>
   Some officials said they're a bit daunted by the price of the
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   A sliding roof was planned in the late 1960s but abandoned as
too costly by the time the twin stadiums opened in the early 1970s.
It could slide over a stadium to protect it from hot sun, rain or
snow.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who typically have only two or three rainouts a
year, somewhat favor the roof. The Chiefs are enthusiastic
supporters. It would keep fans from suffering as they did Oct. 4,
when a game was played during intense rain that flooded the
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   And the roof could be parked between the stadiums, creating a
virtual convention center in the parking lot there, said Steadman.
It could be a shady venue for outdoor concerts as well as big truck
shows or aircraft shows and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Upgrades that appear more likely are those that improve the
stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Fans got a sample this year of the kinds of improvements
envisioned when the Royals opened the on-field Crown seats and
dugout suites, which quickly sold out.
</P>
<P>
   On the Royals' wish list is a hope to dramatically alter the
middle level, or so called club level, said M.A. Chaudry, senior
vice president of business operations for the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The press box could be moved down to the first level, and the
under-used Stadium Club would vanish or shrink. That would open up
the club level, which could be glassed in, both on the field side
and parking lot side, and the area could be air conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals would like to build glass cylinders in the now-vacant
cores of the corkscrew walkways, and place mall-like shops into
them. The team would like additional stores and restaurants, and it
wants to build roofs over the back ends of the bullpens to create
picnic areas. Team executives visualize a walkway beyond the
outfield so fans could move completely around the stadium during
games.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Santee, a senior vice president with the Kansas City sports
architecture firm of HOK Sport, said the cramped concession stands
on the first level could be dismantled and rebuilt further back.
They'd be much larger.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs visualize a similar redo of Arrowhead.
</P>
<P>
   The press box on the club level could be moved up to the third
level, said Steadman. The club level could be glassed in for
heating and air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   There would be new lounge areas, roomier concession stands,
wider concourses and more rest rooms. Arrowhead is particularly
short of women's rest rooms because it was built at a time when few
women were expected to attend football games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
