<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DOTEL, 10 STRIKEOUTS WERE WORTH THE WAIT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Octavio Dotel wanted to forget his last outing a week
ago in Chicago. Dotel had no control of his breaking pitches, so
the Cubs waited for his fastball. The result was an unsightly
pitching line: nine runs on four hits and five walks in two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel had to wait six agonizing days, but it was worthwhile. The
hard-throwing 23-year-old rookie struck out 10 batters to lead the
New York Mets to a 2-1 victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers Friday
night before 43,825 fans on Hispanic Night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what place we're in,'' Dotel said, referring to the 1
1/2-game lead the Mets maintained over the Atlanta Braves in the
National League East. ``I'm just trying to keep the team there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel, whose record improved to 4-1, allowed only three hits in
outdueling the Dodgers' starter, Chan Ho Park. The Mets' record
since the All-Star Game break improved to 17-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``His breaking balls were very effective,'' Mike Piazza said of
Dotel. ``He threw them with confidence for strikes. And it made his
fastball faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel explained his improvement this way: ``The difference is,
sometimes you have a bad day, and you lose your mechanics in the
game. After that day, I just threw it away.'' Dotel worked hard
Friday night to keep his shoulder from flying open, something Dave
Wallace, the pitching coach, had detected in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Benitez provided ninth-inning anxiety. Again. Struggling
with his control, Benitez, the Mets' closer, allowed two runners to
reach base when Eric Karros blooped a single to center and Todd
Hundley walked. The Mets' coaches placed a call to the bullpen and
told the newly acquired Billy Taylor to warm up. Quickly. But
Benitez struck out Raul Mondesi on three pitches, the last a 97 mph
fastball, for the second out, and struck out Adrian Beltre to end
the game and secure his 12th save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of bad games, where I was in trouble because I
walked too many people,'' Benitez said. ``I had to get my
confidence back. I kept telling myself, `It's not me.' I have to be
great and let the people know.''
</P>
<P>
   If the people at Shea learned anything Friday night, it was that
Dotel can pitch at the major league level.
</P>
<P>
   In his first visit to Shea since the Mets traded him last Dec.
1, Hundley was warmly applauded as he made his way to the plate in
the second inning. Ignoring the few boos that were mixed in,
Hundley doffed his batting helmet and waved to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   That was the highlight of the evening for Hundley, who struck
out three times against Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 1-0 lead in the third inning on a two-out
single by Park (the first hit Dotel allowed), followed by a hit
batsman (Mark Grudzielanek), a full-count walk to Todd
Hollandsworth and a balk. Dotel, who had fanned the first two
batters in the inning, then struck out Devon White with runners on
second and third to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other Dodger advanced past first off Dotel. In the
fourth, Mondesi singled with two outs and stole second.
</P>
<P>
   The only other batter to reach base against Dotel _
Hollandsworth on a sixth-inning single _ was erased when White
grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tied the score in the third. Roger Cedeno hit a one-out
infield single and stole second and third _ his major
league-leading 53nd and 54th on the season _ before Edgardo Alfonzo
lifted a sacrifice fly to right. Mondesi made a terrific throw to
the plate, but Cedeno's head-first dive beat Hundley's tag.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets took a 2-1 lead in the fourth. Robin Ventura opened the
inning with an inside-out double into the left-field corner to
extend his hitting streak to 10 games. Darryl Hamilton sacrificed
Ventura to third, and Ventura scored easily on Benny Agbayani's fly
to deep center field.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel was strong all night. He struck out two batters in the
second, the side in the third, two in the fourth, one in the fifth
and two in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Dotel threw 104 pitches, 70 for strikes. ``I felt
good,'' he said. ``And when you feel good, you want to keep on
going.'' But Manager Bobby Valentine decided to pinch-hit for him
in the bottom of the seventh with two outs and a runner on second.
Matt Franco grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   After 110 games, the Mets are still looking for their first
complete game. But they are also still very much in first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
