<SLUG> BC-VJ-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. VICTORY OVER JAPAN IN WWII HAS NEVER BEEN FORGOTTEN IN ARMA,
KAN. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMA, Kan. _ World War II is very personal for this small
southeast Kansas mining town, even though the fighting was in
places many residents knew little about.
</P>
<P>
   The community of 1,500 residents, about five miles west of the
border with Missouri, this weekend is expected to swell by a few
thousand coming to celebrate the victory over Japan that put an end
to World War II on Aug. 14, 1945. The victory also brought home the
survivors of the 629 men from the Arma area who went off to war.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six who weren't so lucky also are being remembered this
weekend, as they have been every year since 1946.
</P>
<P>
   The town traditionally celebrates on the first weekend of
August, said Steffany Peternell, this year's chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest single community event,'' Mayor Frank Blazic
said. ``It varies from year to year, depending on the weather, but
the streets are full. It still is the Arma V-J celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Peternell said the lineup included a high school reunion, a
parade, carnival rides, a horse-pulling contest, horseshoe
pitching, a women's nail-driving contest, a boccie tournament and
even mud volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Again this year, Jim Varone was to offer spaghetti dinners at
the American Legion hall. He was to make 15 gallons of sauce and
600 meatballs for 200 dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Varone and hundreds of others from Arma and the surrounding area
went into the military after Japan attacked Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7,
1941. Some enlisted, some were drafted, but they all served.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial at the edge of the city park displays a plaque with
the names of the men from the Arma area who went off to war.
</P>
<P>
   The Varsolona, Kmetz and Kovacic families each sent five sons to
the Pacific or Europe. Miraculously, all 15 returned safely.
</P>
<P>
   John Varsolona, the next to last to go from his family, recalled
his parents' reactions:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only one who was bitter was my dad. He said: `To hell with
(President Franklin D.) Roosevelt. I'll never vote for him no
more.'
</P>
<P>
   ``All my mother would do was pray, but she was proud to tell
everyone she had five boys in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kovacic remembered when he left: ``I know my mother was
sick, I can tell you that. But as far as I was concerned, everyone
was in the same boat. They were all going the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Varsolona, Kmetz and Kovacic families all lived within three
blocks of each other in Arma, and the parents often talked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would visit about how they felt and how their boys were
getting along,'' said Andy Kmetz, who served in the Army as a truck
and jeep driver.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing their boys leave for war was a blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad felt it wasn't right, that they shouldn't take five
boys,'' Kmetz said. ``The other families felt the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his mother ``felt bad about it. She wasn't happy, but
there was nothing she could do about it. They gave us their
blessing and we all came home in good condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue-collar town where European immigrants settled to mine
the veins of coal deep underground never forgot those who died, and
the ones who returned were constant reminders of the sacrifices
that were made.
</P>
<P>
   To keep those memories alive, a homecoming party was organized.
</P>
<P>
   The first V-J Homecoming Celebration was in 1946. A handful of
veterans put together the impromptu event.
</P>
<P>
   Varsolona, who served in the Navy, was one of them:
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1946, we had our own celebration. We set up at the Legion
hall and drank beer.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, things were more formal, and the entire town got
involved. There was a parade with floats. Veterans, some in their
uniforms, proudly marched down East Washington Street.
</P>
<P>
   It's been much like that each year since.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters of the Arma celebration believe there aren't more than
a handful of similar events left in the country.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is in Moosup, Conn., which will stage its 38th V-J
Day parade Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Harris, a spokesman for the American Legion at its national
headquarters in Indianapolis, said he was unaware of local
victory-over-Japan celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems a lot of the time V-J Day and December 7th slip by
without a lot of notice,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's plenty of notice in Arma.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jim Barone of nearby Frontenac grew up in Arma, and
as a boy he found the celebration always a highlight of his
summers. There was the candy tossed from parade floats, and there
were games to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also remember very clearly looking at the memorial to
the veterans, and there would always be some sense of pride and
patriotism when you thought about the purpose of the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it caused an early appreciation, at least for me in my
mind, of what the war was all about and how important our freedoms
are. Those World War II veterans were heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, those remaining veterans are in their 70s and 80s, and
there aren't as many of them gathering at the American Legion hall.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kovacic, a retired miner who went to war with his four
brothers, still participates in the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not as many veterans marching anymore,'' he said.
``The ones who are living can't walk, and the ones who are dead are
gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
