<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
 
TRENT'S DECISION GIVES MAVERICKS HOPE (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Don Nelson can breathe a little easier today after
Mavericks free agent forward Gary Trent turned down a three-year,
$11.28 million offer from the Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the situation said Trent wanted more money
than the Sonics were offering. Unless Seattle comes up with a
better offer, or another team steps up, Trent might wind back up in
a Mavericks uniform after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that he turned the Seattle offer down, but I'm not
surprised,'' said Nelson, who doubles as the Mavericks coach and
general manager. ``I think that was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   According to terms of the collective bargaining agreement, the
Mavericks can only offer Trent a one-year, $2 million contract, or
a two-year, $4.2 million deal. In today's market, that's not much,
but at least Nelson can cling to the fact that he's still in the
race to sign Trent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought our chances were good,'' Nelson said. ``I
think I mentioned that early on. But until he signs with us, we're
vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The source said the Sonics are still confident they can put a
package together to sign Washington Wizards free-agent guard Mitch
Richmond. They're also pursuing Mavericks free-agent forward Cedric
Ceballos, Sacramento free-agent guard Vernon Maxwell, Utah
free-agent forward Shandon Anderson and Cleveland free-agent
forward Cedric Henderson. Ceballos to Sacramento? Mavericks
free-agent forward Cedric Ceballos said the Sacramento Kings are
expressing strong interest in signing him to a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've stepped up to the plate, and it looks promising,''
Ceballos said. ``I hope it can be worked out, but we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos also said the Phoenix Suns, fresh off giving Penny
Hardaway a lucrative seven-year, $86 million deal, have called
about acquiring his services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix said once they got the Penny deal done they were going
to do something,'' Ceballos said. ``But we'll see if they have
anything left after giving all of that money away to Penny.''
Sesay's offer The Mavericks have extended a one-year, $500,000
non-guaranteed offer to free-agent forward Ansu Sesay.
</P>
<P>
   Sesay, a 6-foot-9, 225-pounder, has not decided whether he will
accept the offer. He hasn't played basketball for the Mavericks,
who selected him on the second round of the 1998 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Sesay had surgery Jan. 26 after he fractured the fifth
metatarsal of his right foot during the first week of training
camp. He spent the entire 1999 season on the injured list, and did
not play for the Mavericks' summer league team because he didn't
think he was physically ready.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson said: ``I think we're
going to see him in training camp \Rin October\S _ unless he gets a
better offer out there.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
