<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9105 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICANAMERICAN-POLIT     08-07 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICANAMERICAN-POLITICS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN-AMERICANS WAIT FOR POLITICAL PENDULUM TO SWING THEIR WAY,
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the early 1990s, a lot of political power
in Kansas City was based in the African-American community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the pivotal roles were held by black persons: the
mayor (Emanuel Cleaver), the chairman of the Jackson County
Legislature (James Tindall), the president of the school board
(Julia Hill), a congressman (Alan Wheat), the chairman of the Port
Authority (Elbert Anderson), the president of the Board of Police
Commissioners (Bailus Tate, who later was Port Authority chairman),
the president of the Board of Park and Recreation Commissioners
(Ollie Gates), and the president of the firefighters union (Ed
Phillips). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone. These prominent positions are no longer
held by African-Americans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although African-Americans hold several seats on the Kansas City
Council, the school board and other government bodies _ and were
pleased by the recent appointment of a black superintendent for the
Kansas City School District _ the perceived loss of political power
is the talk among leaders of the black community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get a large gathering of African-Americans
together, it will be the discussion,'' said former Mayor Emanuel
Cleaver. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is that we are clearly going backward,''
Cleaver said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perspectives differ on the reasons why the city's political
power has slipped from the hands of African-Americans. They include
the effect of term limits, the weakening of the political club
Freedom Inc., a lack of mentoring and grooming of young
African-American leaders, political corruption, and the cyclical
nature of politics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The intentional development and planning of leadership, we
have not done,'' said the Rev. Wallace Hartsfield, a Baptist
minister and leader in the African-American community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But I refuse to believe that this is the way it has to be,''
Hartsfield said. He believes the current structure of city
politics, wherein African-Americans are not in key power-positions,
is only temporary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions also differ on whether the reduction of
African-Americans in top positions means that less attention is
being paid to issues affecting minority communities. Some people
fear that issues of importance to the black community won't be
understood or addressed by officials who are not black. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some black persons serving in government said the power shift
has changed the dynamics they work under. They run the risk of
having their arguments dismissed as racial politics, without the
backing of other blacks to support their voice, they said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a choice: Be silent and watch things go by, or speak up
and say that it is not right, knowing that may sometimes be seen as
`playing the race card,' '' said City Councilman Kelvin Simmons,
who is one of four African-Americans serving on the council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers Troy Nash and Alvin Brooks have joined Simmons and
Mary Williams Neal as council members. Neal is the only black
person who holds a significant chairmanship, Neighborhood
Development. Brooks serves as mayor pro tem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Discussion about the weakening in black leadership accelerated
during the April elections, perhaps triggered by the end of
Cleaver's eight-year reign at City Hall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sobering idea that the town was going to be very
different and that access would be very different,'' said Stacey
Daniels-Young, a black member of the Board of Police Commissioners.
``It was like one day people woke up and said, `Wow, this is going
to be really different.' '' &QL; 
Dwindling leadership &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How different has the political scene become? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer depends on the point at which the head-counting
begins. African-Americans say they feel the effect of losing many
of their top leaders within a few years. But it represents an
erosion of gains that began years ago with the election of
now-deceased leaders such as state Rep. Leon Jordan and City
Council member Bruce Watkins, and continued through the 20-year
City Hall tenure of Councilman Charles Hazley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most recent examples begin with the loss of Cleaver, Kansas
City's first black mayor. Among others: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Ken Bacchus, formerly the chairman of the Planning and Zoning
Committee, was forced from the City Council by term limits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Ollie Gates, longtime chairman of the parks board, resigned
after Cleaver left office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Rep. Lloyd Daniel left the state legislature to take a
position with the Missouri Department of Economic Development. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Tindall, chairman of the Jackson County Legislature for six
years, in July began serving a three-year sentence for making false
statements on his 1992 income tax form. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tindall was the latest person to join an infamous list of local
black leaders convicted of crimes related to their positions,
including D. Jeanne Robinson (City Council), Elbert Anderson
(former chairman of the Port Authority) and the late Ed Phillips
(firefighters union). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield said the corruption trials have had an effect on
potential new black leaders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are being frightened away from public office,'' he
said. ``There seems to be this whole matter of African-American
leadership being scrutinized to a point that I don't know who could
stand it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claire McCaskill, former Jackson County prosecutor and now the
Missouri state auditor, said that a lack of African-Americans in
leadership positions should not be viewed as solely a problem of
the black community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority community has made it much more difficult for
young African-Americans to have the self-assurance and ability to
raise the money to run for public office,'' she said.
``Unfortunately, the political system has not made it a priority to
reach out and nurture young African-American leaders.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The black community also is discussing several recent key ``near
misses,'' wherein black persons were contenders for top jobs but
failed obtain them: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Daniels-Young stepped up from her position as vice president
of the Board of Police Commissioners to become acting president but
failed to get the post permanently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Simmons had been vice chairman of the City Council's Finance
Committee under Cleaver. Now he is simply a member of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - James Nunn, a deputy chief with the Police Department, was a
finalist for the job of chief but lost the appointment following a
behind-the-scenes battle over the post, which many black persons
perceived as being racially tinged. &QL; 
--MORE--
</P>
<P>
   Power shift &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many eyes now are focusing on Mayor Kay Barnes _ the city's
first woman mayor _ to assess how she handles the concerns of the
city's black constituents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barnes points to the appointments she has made so far for her
commitment to racial equity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the 121 she has made, 28 are African-Americans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very clear that by me being a white person, there might be
some ongoing concern in the minority community,'' Barnes said.
``But I do feel a responsibility to reach out and to be able to
build those relationships.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also stressed that she knows the importance of maintaining
ties to diverse communities, because of her years of political and
government experience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, some see problems in where Barnes is opting to pick
appointments throughout the city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, the largest bloc of selections (37) is from the 4th
District, which includes the Country Club Plaza, Brookside and
Waldo areas. The largely white 1st and 2nd districts, primarily
Clay and Platte counties, have 15 and 19 appointments,
respectively, from Mayor Barnes. The 6th District, south of the
Missouri River and reaching to Grandview, has 14 appointments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city's predominantly black districts, the 3rd and
5th, only have four and eight appointments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in a position that other people are picking who
is going to represent us, that is dangerous,'' said the Rev. Nelson
Thompson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he advocates the reconvening of groups such as the
Black Agenda Group, which met in the early 1990s. It was a Who's
Who of black political, civic and business leaders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our issues are important to the growth and development of the
community, so we need to get everyone together _ the Freedom
people, the Urban League, the NAACP, the churches,'' Thompson said.
``We need to do what we can do to maintain our leadership.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meetings have also been held lately to revamp Freedom Inc., the
political club that many think is sagging. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Freedom ``called the shots'' politically, said Lisa
White Hardwick, a lawyer and one of two black members of the
Jackson County Legislature. But Freedom has failed to get many of
its endorsed candidates into office in recent years, even in races
conducted largely within the urban core. Former Mayor Pro Tem
George Blackwood, who is white, lost to Barnes in the mayoral
election despite Freedom's endorsement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hardwick is optimistic African-Americans still can have an
impact politically and sees the current condition as somewhat
cyclical. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So community leaders are beginning to talk about the need to
begin nurturing and mentoring more black leaders, especially in
light of the term limits that voters passed in 1990. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to move this city forward, we have to look at
these issues,'' said Kelvin Perry, former president of the Black
Chamber of Commerce. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to develop leadership, and it doesn't get developed
if you don't have a plan,'' he said. ``And there simply hasn't been
any planning.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perry and others say it is foolish to think that simply having a
few black faces in positions within government will necessarily
translate into improved economic conditions for black Kansas
Citians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniels-Young thinks the situation also says much about the
status of race relations in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if I could have access and not have to have a
person of color in leadership,'' Daniels-Young said. ``I guess that
is the next goal for us to work toward.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
