<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-RETAILERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGUE RETAILERS JEOPARDIZE FEDERAL FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missouri retailers' unwillingness to stop selling tobacco to
teen-agers could cost the state nearly $10 million in federal
alcohol- and drug-treatment grants.
</P>
<P>
   The money represents more than 13 percent of the state's entire
budget for substance-abuse treatment programs, state officials
said. The potential loss of funding has mental-health programs in
the state worried.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Flory, president of Research Mental Health Services in
Lee's Summit, Mo., in suburban Kansas City, said state and federal
grants paid for his clinic to treat more than 400 addicts a year.
But it is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There tends to be a lot more people requiring these services
than we have room for,'' Flory said. ``If grants were reduced, it
would only get worse....A lot of these are people trying to get
clean so they can be productive. You have to treat them when they
want it, because that's when it's most effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state officials said they are negotiating to put
together a plan to save the grant by getting the state back into
compliance with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weber, spokesman for the Substance Abuse and Mental Health
Services Administration in Washington, said federal officials were
not unsympathetic to the effect of losing the grant. But Missouri
has to follow the law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about tobacco for underage kids,'' Weber said.
``It's one of the highest health-care priorities set by this
administration, and the states need to comply with this.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential loss of funds stems from a 1992 law that requires
states to reduce the number of retailers selling tobacco to people
under 18 to a maximum of 20 percent. Beginning in 1997 all states
set a schedule for reducing the percentage of rogue retailers every
year.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for failing to stay on schedule is the loss of 40
percent of the state's federal grant for drug- and alcohol-abuse
treatment programs. Missouri's grant is $24 million this year. So
the federal government is contemplating whether to withhold $9.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   The violation rate is determined by sting operations in which
youthful-looking teens are sent into stores to try to buy tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide the 1997 rate of retailers caught selling to minors
ranged from a low of 7 percent in Florida to a high of 73 percent
in Louisiana. Missouri's rate was 40 percent. Kansas' rate was 63
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri agreed to lower the number of violations to 35 percent
in 1998 and 28 percent in 1999. The state exceeded its target in
1998, when 29 percent of the stores tested got caught selling to
minors. This year the percentage grew to 33 percent, which put the
state's federal grant in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The problem stems from retailers in St. Louis and southeastern
Missouri. In the St. Louis area, more than half _ 51 percent _ of
the retailers were caught selling tobacco to teen-agers. In
southeast Missouri, 44 percent were caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously retailers in those areas haven't paid attention and
are willing to sell to minors,'' said Marsha Buckner, a deputy
director in the Division of Alcohol and Drug Abuse. ``We're doing
everything we can to say that is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The best performing regions were in northern Missouri, where
only 10 percent of the retailers sold to minors, and the Kansas
City area, where 15 percent got caught.
</P>
<P>
   Buckner said state officials had put up billboards urging
retailers to obey the law. They are meeting with retailing groups
to emphasize the $250 fine imposed for selling cigarettes to teens.
And they have formed a statewide network of 210 local groups
working to reduce teen smoking and alcohol and drug use, she said.
</P>
<P>
   All the enforcement measures are important, Buckner said,
because Missouri is scheduled to reduce its violation rate to 20
percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even states that already had a rate below 20 percent have had
trouble keeping it there,'' she said. ``It's called the `rebound
rate' after the initial publicity. Now it's hard to keep retailers
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber said federal officials could forgo withholding the grant
if the state came up with an acceptable plan to correct the
problems. If the grant is withheld, the state can appeal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas also missed its target rate for 1999. But its alcohol-
and drug-treatment grant is not in danger, because the state's
violation rate continues to drop, said Pete Bodyk, who oversees the
state's tobacco sales enforcement program.
</P>
<P>
   The state has cut its violation rate by more than half, from 63
percent in 1997 to 30 percent this year. Bodyk attributed the drop
to enforcement of a 1996 state law that provides fines of up to
$1,000 against stores and a minimum of $200 against clerks who sell
tobacco to teens under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas teens also have the date on which they turn 18 emblazoned
in green on their drivers' licenses. Bodyk said that step was taken
after a 1998 finding that in 58 percent of the violations, the
clerk checked identification showing that the teen was underage but
sold the tobacco anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is scheduled to reach the required 20 percent violation
rate in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0058EDT &QL; 
