<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9108 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIMARY-AZR &LR;      08-07 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE INTEREST IN ARIZONA GOP DEBATES AT EBB  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What if they gave a debate and nobody came?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question facing Arizona Republicans, along with those
in a handful of other states with early presidential primaries, as
planning for the political sparring matches cranks into gear.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials blame the low interest on candidates who won't
commit to the debates and on an increasingly front-loaded primary
calendar that could cause the debates to pile up on one another.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Arizona Republican Party, who want to host a
debate on the weekend before the state's Feb. 22 primary, are
worried that it might be overshadowed by a debate in Michigan,
which recently moved its primary up to fall on the same day as the
Arizona election.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the response to the Arizona debate plan has been tepid,
at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was jumping off the building to do it, but nobody told
me they were against it, either,'' said Mike Minnaugh, chairman of
the state Republican Party, who recently sent out letters to
candidates announcing the party's intent to host a debate. So far
this year, only Arizona Sen. John McCain has confirmed he will
show.
</P>
<P>
   According to Minnaugh, the response of the rest of the
candidates _ particularly publisher Steve Forbes, front-runner
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former Red Cross President Elizabeth
Dole _ could hinge on what Michigan, a state with 18 electoral
votes, does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Steve Forbes, if he has an opportunity to debate in
Michigan, where do you think he is going to go?'' Minnaugh asked.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the state's primary debate drew four GOP
candidates and made national news when front-runner Bob Dole
decided not to attend.
</P>
<P>
   In California, officials have postponed indefinitely planning
for a debate, believing that Bush has no intention of mixing it up
with his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Bush wants to debate anybody for quite a while
and without Bush there, it doesn't get much attention,'' said Jim
Camp, operations director for the California Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a debate black-out precipitated by Bush's
absence, while unhealthy, is understandable, according to Camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, if I were with the Bush people I wouldn't
(debate),'' Camp said. ``When you are 40 points ahead in the polls
why debate?''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's GOP chief agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not do it if I were him (Bush),'' Minnaugh conceded.
``But as chairman I am going to ask for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes officials said they have every intention of debating in
Arizona, but added a caveat: Forbes doesn't want to be a part of
any event that Bush skips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple fact of the matter is that unless Governor Bush is
debating, it's not a debate of any significance in the Republican
primary,'' said Juleanna Glover &UR; Weiss, a spokeswoman for Forbes.
``We would like very much to go, and we would hope that the
governor goes.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush said he has not committed to any of the
debates because it is too early in the election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early for the debate over debates,'' said Scott
McClellan, a spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Debates in at least three states _ Florida, Iowa, New Hampshire
and South Carolina _ already have been tentatively scheduled, while
states such as Arizona and Michigan are in the process of setting
dates.
</P>
<P>
   The first debate, hosted by Florida Republicans, will come in
October. South Carolina will hold its debate on Jan. 9, followed by
Iowa's debate on Jan. 15. New Hampshire Republicans will host a
debate during the week preceding their February primary.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing jockeying for a debate that will draw candidates
can also be traced to the desire of states to bask in the limelight
thrown off by a nationally televised debate.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, party officials are crowing about plans by
MSNBC to broadcast their candidate forum live.
</P>
<P>
   The state recently vaulted over Arizona to become the nation's
second primary, holding its election Feb. 19, a move that also
allows for its early debate.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina GOP Chairman Henry McMaster said he wasn't
concerned about whether candidates would show up.
</P>
<P>
   They have little choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured they were going to come here,'' McMaster said. ``It
is a very import debate. I think the most important one.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire is also expecting to field a crowd of candidates
and national reporters. Officials are so confident that they plan
to ditch their traditional focus on local politics for a debate
that includes local and national issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one isn't a hard bet,'' New Hampshire Republican Party
Chairman Stephen Duprey said. ``We are expecting to have a major
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   But after New Hampshire and South Carolina, all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   The field of candidates may be sliced down to two or three after
the South Carolina primary, making for a less than thrilling verbal
face-off, officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Republicans, who have just begun planning their debate,
said they intend to pick a date that will draw the most candidates
and create the biggest media splash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual states are left in a situation where we all
have to vie for position in the primary process and the next step
is vying for debates or rallies or events where we can get the
candidates in,'' said Sage Eastman, spokesman for the Michigan
Republican Party. `We are all sort of feeling the pains of a tight
primary schedule.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
