<HEADER>
A9112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-NATO-BOS &LR;      08-07 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-NATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL CLARK'S COMMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be regrettable if General Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme
commander, were replaced two months before his term is up because
of high-level bureaucratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   To complain about the workings of office politics in the
Pentagon is to risk seeming unworldly, and equally unworldly is any
expectation that the entire tale will be known to the public any
time soon. But one plausible reason for the decision to cut short
Clark's tenure was his publicized clash with the British commander
of ground forces in Kosovo, Sir Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   When 200 Russian troops raced to Pristina's airport early on
June 12, Clark ordered an airborne assault on the airfield by
British and French troops. Jackson would not carry out Clark's
orders. According to the London Times, when the two men met in
Kosovo on the 24th, Jackson explained his refusal by saying, ``I'm
not going to start the third world war for you.''
</P>
<P>
   During this showdown, Jackson received full support from his
government. Clark was not supported by his. And on June 24, Clark
complained to Jackson that the British commander had used political
channels to override Clark's order.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Clark managed to shepherd 19 NATO allies to a
complete military victory in 78 days and without a single NATO
casualty because of his political skill at preserving the
alliance's unity. His military decisions had to survive passage
through the political hierarchies of the European capitals and
Washington. The original constraints on NATO's tactics and the
Clinton administration's lack of foresight in the run-up to war
were not his fault. He had to win the war against Slobodan
Milosevic despite these hindrances.
</P>
<P>
   There were no victory parades for Clark, as there were General
Norman Schwarzkopf after the Gulf War, and no kudos from Congress.
Although he erred in trying to counter Russia's bravado in Pristina
airport, Clark carried out a difficult mission. He deserves more
generous recognition for his service than he has received from the
nation's political leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
