<HEADER>
A9114 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-MONEY-BOS &LR;      08-07 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITOL HILL CAPITALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Congress, campaign finance reform is highly partisan.
Democrats overwhelmingly support a bill to eliminate soft money and
tighten independent expenditures. Most Republicans are opposed,
some arguing that public concern over money in politics may be
genuine but is still thin _ not felt strongly enough to turn an
election.
</P>
<P>
   As frequently happens, the skeptical Washington perspective is
increasingly at odds with the reality in presidential campaigns and
in the states.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Senator John McCain's was a lonely voice pushing
the presidential contenders to address a bill he is cosponsoring
with Senator Russell Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat. Since then,
happily, he has been joined by others.
</P>
<P>
   --Former governor Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, a Republican,
has mounted an ad in Iowa decrying the dominance of big money in
the campaign. While George W. Bush, the Republican governor of
Texas, is not named, the reference to the candidate who broke all
fund-raising records _ and who announced that he will opt out of
the voluntary spending limits that would make him eligible for
federal campaign funds _ is clear.
</P>
<P>
   --Publisher Steve Forbes was accused of trying to buy votes by
paying attendees to the Iowa straw vote scheduled for Aug. 14, a
charge Forbes vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
   --Former senator Bill Bradley of New Jersey put out a detailed
list of proposals, including public financing of congressional as
well as presidential elections, free broadcast time, and a ban on
all soft money in federal elections. Bradley has already generated
a mini-debate with Vice President Al Gore over Bradley's suggestion
that all the current presidential candidates voluntarily eschew
soft money, even in the absence of a change in the law.
</P>
<P>
   The states, too, are at odds with Congress. Those with the
strongest reforms are Massachusetts, Arizona, Wisconsin, Maine, and
Vermont. The first three have Republican governors; Maine is led by
an independent.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson from outside the Washington Beltway is that more
candidates are realizing that democratic reforms are powerful as
well as right and that either party can claim the high ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-CULTURE-BOS     08-07 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CULTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GROWING OF CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, August 9, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the beach of life, culture is often the 98-pound weakling.
Congressional bullies kick sand on the national endowments for the
arts and the humanities. Sports stadiums draw public dollars; opera
houses crumble.
</P>
<P>
   But a new effort stands to give culture more muscle. Through its
multimillion-dollar project ``Optimizing America's Cultural
Resources,'' the Pew Charitable Trusts is addressing the nation's
cultural policies.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew initiative talks of building a stronger ``cultural
policy community.'' While this may sound like upbeat-speak for
culture police who crack down on free expression, Pew has something
very different in mind. It points to environmental activism as a
role model, noting that 35 years ago environmental issues had
little political support. Activists and philanthropy changed that;
a similar approach could help culture and the arts.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative has three components: establishing a central
national source for data and information; expanding advocacy and
media coverage; and measuring the impact of cultural programs.
</P>
<P>
   Information is essential. The national information bank should
provide insights on everything from improving children's education
to how cultural organizations can contribute to suburban and
inner-city communities.
</P>
<P>
   There are risks. Just the word ``culture'' can stir up
unproductive debates. One question Pew asks is, ``Does our system
enable gifted artists to earn a living and to contribute fully to
our economy and society?'' This suggests that properly supported,
artists could be a source of economic prosperity. But the query
could be misinterpreted as a call for handouts to the lazy. The
initiative will have to guard against such mudslinging.
</P>
<P>
   Devising a flexible cultural framework that won't harden into
dogma will take hard, pioneering work. Europe, with its tradition
of government patronage, isn't a role model, Pew concludes.
Instead, America will have to devise its own approach to supporting
the arts, a noble challenge on a promising frontier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-NIXON-BOS &LR;      08-07 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-NIXON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATION DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 8, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Dwight Eisenhower, the next five presidents left the White
House involuntarily. John Kennedy was shot. Lyndon Johnson was
forced to abandon his reelection campaign. Richard Nixon resigned.
Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter lost elections. Of these, Kennedy's
assassination, because of its shock and the tragic sense of lost
potential, still resonates powerfully with Americans who were alive
in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Nixon's stiff-lipped resignation, 25 years ago Monday,
that deserves the most space in the history books and the most
thoughtful contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   How could such a brilliant and resourceful strategist not
overcome the dark inner suspicions that proved his undoing? How
could the public and the press for so long overlook such deep
flaws? How could the subsequent legislative efforts to avert
another such scandal be corrupted and discarded so easily? How
could the lessons of Watergate, which seem so obvious, be forgotten
and Nixon's errors repeated so soon?
</P>
<P>
   These troubling questions still need answers, for the damage of
Watergate lingers.
</P>
<P>
   The dissolving passage of time has caused some analysts to
refocus on Nixon's achievements, such as the opening of relations
with China and his willingness to abandon doctrinaire approaches
when dealing with social problems and adopt innovative solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon's legacy at its core is the injury he caused to
democracy by bruising its very basis _ the bond of trust between
the governed and their elected leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that the capsulizing moment of Nixon's presidency
is its last _ when he became the only president to resign in
disgrace _ because no other president did as much damage to the
office and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Nixon polluted the reservoir of trust that most
people, as a matter of faith, held for him as the duly elected
president. And time and again, the reason he lost their trust was
that he didn't trust them.
</P>
<P>
   There was the phony secret plan to end the Vietnam War; the
covert bombing of Cambodia; the secret taping of Oval Office
conversations; the enemies list and the use of government agencies
to persecute those on it. Nixon was obsessed with secrecy, and his
downfall began with the publication in 1971 of the Pentagon Papers,
which aired some of the realities of Vietnam policy making and some
of the administration's secrets and lies. Had the Pentagon Papers
been made public earlier, there is no telling how many deaths and
how much national trauma might have been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Nixon set up the secret White House ``plumbers,'' whose
mission was to use the tactics of common criminals to stop further
leaks. When one of their bungled efforts was discovered _ they left
a piece of tape over a door latch when breaking into Democratic
Party headquarters in the Watergate complex _ Nixon himself led a
massive coverup of subterfuge and lies. In the end, he took many
down with him, including top White House aides and the attorney
general, John Mitchell, who also betrayed his office.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Nixon's choice of the corrupt Spiro Agnew to be
vice president may be laid to bad luck as well as bad judgment, but
no such excuse can be offered for the shameful dirty tricks
employed by Nixon's 1972 reelection campaign _ tactics that
cynically targeted the electoral process, democracy's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon never revealed much remorse or even indicated that he
recognized the enormity of his transgressions. His memoirs refer to
his brief resignation speech, in which he said: ``I am confident
that the world is a safer place today. . . . That, more than
anything, is what I hope will be my legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon never seemed to understand his real legacy, and looking
back, it is discouraging to see how poorly some of the Watergate
lessons were learned by others.
</P>
<P>
   Most obvious: President Clinton could have saved himself and the
nation an agonizing year if he had understood that his personal
behavior _ however rotten _ was less of a threat to his office than
lies and coverup.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the two leading Watergate reforms are now in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform worked well at the presidential level
for several elections but has been trampled by crafty consultants
and loopholes allowed by the Federal Election Commission. Congress,
whose members benefit from the corrupt system, does nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law had some successes and some
failures, the latter including Kenneth Starr's excesses last year.
Now it has been allowed to expire, so the public has little reason
to trust that Washington can police itself independently.
</P>
<P>
   Some optimists say Watergate proved that America's system works
well: A blemish was removed without bloodshed. But damage was done,
and it persists. Since 1972 voter turnout his declined almost
without interruption, to the point that only 49 percent of
voting-age Americans cast ballots in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This is Richard Nixon's record _ an abiding, hurtful legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Any list of the most important dates of the American century
must include August 9.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 29, 1929: Black Friday, the stock market crash.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 7, 1941: Pearl Harbor, Japan's day of infamy.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 22, 1963: John Kennedy is assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   July 20, 1969: The moon walk.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 9, 1974: Nixon resigns, America's day of shame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
