<HEADLINE>
DRUGS.COM DOMAIN NAME IS WORTH $823,456 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Eric MacIver did not get his predicted $1 million
bid for the Internet domain name Drugs.com, but he's hardly
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   An undisclosed bidder pledged to pay $823,456 Friday for the
right to use Drugs.com, which made the 21-year-old MacIver
financially healthier than he was three months ago when he acquired
the name _ for considerably less money. Entrepreneur, heal thyself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been pretty much happy with anything,'' MacIver
said, a few minutes after bidding closed at 5:30 p.m. ``I was happy
with the $300,000 bid that was posted this morning. We were hoping
for $1 million. The $3 million prediction was clearly an
overestimate, but that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Greatdomains.com, the Los Angeles online broker
that handled the auction, said the winning bidder wanted to remain
anonymous until a press conference that will take place ``soon,''
said Jeff Tinsley, Greatdomains.com's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know when it will be, and we can't say anything. But
the sooner they announce it the better,'' Tinsley said. ``People
want to know who ended up paying for the name. They got a great
deal, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley said his company usually commands a 7 to 10 percent
brokerage fee on sales, but he could not say what the cut was for
Drugs.com. He also said thousands of people watched the virtual
auction on his Web site, which carried real-time postings as the
bids rose.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding for the name, which had an original asking price of
$260,000, remained tame until about 15 minutes before the auction's
scheduled closeout at 5 p.m. Then bids started pouring in, each
topping the other by at least $10,000. By 5 p.m., the top offer was
$555,555.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding did not stop because the rule at Greatdomains.com is
bids can be accepted after the auction's close if received within
five minutes of the last bid. By the time the cyberdust had cleared
at 5:30 p.m., the final bid posted was $823,456.
</P>
<P>
   Although the winner was mum, the guy who came in second was
livid. Rick Schwartz of Boca Raton, Fla., had been bidding on
Drugs.com throughout the day on behalf of a ``cartel'' of 25 adult
Webmasters. Among them, Schwartz said, they own thousands of
sexually explicit Web sites and were banking up to $1 million that
Drugs.com would be a profitable addition to their collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to bid $850,000, but when I got through, they said
the (five minute) time limit had expired,'' Schwartz said. ``We
would have turned that million into a profit in 12 months. We don't
believe in losing money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bargain, really. Whoever got it, if it's one of the big
drug companies, which I doubt, the others in that market will be
kicking themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley said Schwartz knew the rules, so that's the breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the terms of the auction before it took place, so he
knew what was going to happen,'' Tinsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he could have made more money, and he wasn't told who
actually won, MacIver said he was relieved Schwartz's final bid did
not go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that it was an adult Webmaster, I'm not that
disappointed,'' MacIver said. ``I would have paid that much to make
sure they didn't get it. It would be much better if it went to
somebody that wasn't an adult site.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
