<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PAIR OF RACES, 3-YEAR-OLDS VIE TO REPLACE CHARISMATIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some have been rested after grueling Triple Crown campaigns,
others needed more time to develop and were prepped in
lower-profile stakes races. But the race for the title of the best,
or at least second-best, 3-year-old in the land resumes Sunday when
two compact fields go off in the Haskell Invitational and the Jim
Dandy Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   With the Kentucky Derby and Preakness champion Charismatic
retired to stud after fracturing a foreleg in the Belmont Stakes, a
number of seasoned colts have a chance to make a claim as the best
3-year-old in the second half of the racing season.
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, Cat Thief and the newcomer Forestry mount their bids at
the $1 million, Grade I, Haskell at Monmouth Park. The winner and
the runner-up in the Belmont, Lemon Drop Kid and Vision and Verse,
begin their assault at the $300,000, Grade II, Jim Dandy Stakes at
Saratoga. Both races are one and one-eighth miles and are important
preps for the most important summer race for 3-year-olds: the
Travers Stakes at Saratoga on Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the Travers is more of a horseman's race than the Derby
because you don't crucify your horse,'' said trainer Scotty
Schulhofer, who drew the No. 5 post Friday for Lemon Drop Kid and
the jockey Jose Santos. ``On the first Saturday in May, most horses
aren't up for going a mile and a quarter. I've always felt that I'd
rather win the Travers.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulhofer's colt was installed as a 2-1 favorite over the
Florida Derby winner Vicar, who is listed at 7-2, and Vision and
Verse, at 3-1. Seven horses have been entered, but that may change
if the trainer Elliott Walden decides to run Ecton Park in the
Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   The Jim Dandy has a slightly weaker field than the Haskell. At
Saratoga, Ecton Park would break from the No. 4 post, at odds of
4-1; at the Haskell he drew the No. 6 post, and odds of 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Walden's decision on where to send Ecton Park is complicated by
the fact that his better horse, Menifee, is the 9-5 favorite in a
stout field in the Haskell. Menifee, the Derby and Preakness
runner-up, has had two months off after finishing a disappointing
eighth in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   The Arthur Hancock-owned colt will carry the high weight of 124
pounds and break from the No. 7 post with his usual rider, Pat Day.
Menifee broke his maiden on the Monmouth Park course, and Walden
said he liked Menifee's chances to dominate the second half of the
season all the way to a showdown with his stablemate Victory Gallo,
the leading candidate for Horse of the Year, in the $4 million
Breeders' Cup Classic in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medium goal is the Travers,'' Walden said. ``I hate to
call a million-dollar race a prep race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Menifee will probably be closer to the pace than he usually
is. He's been off a while and he seems fresh, so it's likely he'll
be closer to the pace Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The pace at the Haskell is likely to be dictated by two West
Coast speed horses, the Triple Crown veteran Cat Thief and
Forestry, who is looking for a sixth consecutive victory. The D.
Wayne Lukas-trained Cat Thief faltered in the stretch of the Derby
and Belmont, but looked like a more inspired horse in winning the
Swaps Stakes last month in a stretch duel with General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's grown up and showed a little more fight, where before
he'd hang a little bit,'' said the jockey Mike Smith, who will
guide the colt from the No. 8 post. ``He doesn't need to be on the
lead. He can also stalk, too. But I think they'll have to come and
get him. He's quick from the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading that chase will likely be Forestry, with the jockey
Jerry Bailey, breaking from the No. 4 post. The colt ran down
Doneraille Court in the blistering fast Dwyer Stakes. The
performance broke the trainer Bob Baffert's 0-9 streak at Belmont,
and he thinks Forestry is getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dwyer was a good race, but I think he's better than
that,'' Baffert said. ``He's got the speed to be ahead or right
there with Cat Thief. He's a fresh horse; he didn't go through the
Triple Crown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
