<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-CART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRL FOUNDER DOESN'T FORESEE MERGER WITH CART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Indy Racing League founder Tony George says time
has expired on a possible reconciliation with the rival
Championship Auto Racing Teams for the 2000 Indianapolis 500 in
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``And time's ticking away on 2001,'' said George, who classified
the latest round of secret talks between leaders of the open-wheel
series as ``very fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A unified series would be in everyone's best interests,'' said
George, who also is president of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
``But I don't know if it's achievable, especially in the short
term. I don't see any way for a unification in 2000, and 2001 is
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of a possible reunification surfaced at the Speedway in
late May. George said the next 30 to 60 days would be critical
toward bringing together the sides, which split after the launch of
the IRL in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now August, and there's still too many important open
issues we haven't come together on,'' George said. ``But we're
still working on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The rumor mill cranked up last month during CART's U.S. 500 at
the Michigan Speedway. Representatives of the four manufacturers
supplying turbocharged V-8 engines to CART _ Ford, Honda,
Mercedes-Benz and Toyota _ said they would be willing to devise an
equivalency formula to allow their teams to compete against the
normally aspirated V-8 engines offered by Oldsmobile and Nissan for
the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, George said there would be no racing in the Indy 500
under an equivalency program that would necessarily have to reduce
the horsepower produced by CART's engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally against that,'' George said. ``It would be
difficult to achieve _ it would be impossible to achieve _ any kind
of an equivalency that wouldn't cause a lot of people a lot of
grief. So, I don't want to go down that road. A few people think
that would be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, George referred to the CART engine representatives
as the ``gang of four.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the engine companies created this little bend in the
track that derailed things,'' George said. ``The way we look at it,
we've already announced our rules. We did that last fall, and we're
pushing ahead.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
