<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NURSES'-AIDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CARING FOR THE CAREGIVERS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Some 90 percent of the hired care that old people get, either in
their own homes or in nursing homes, is given by nurses' aides. The
aides do the basic, intimate things _ the waking, toileting,
bathing, dressing, feeding and bedding down for the night. It is
their eyes, their voices, their manner and touch that form the
texture of daily life for millions of dependent old people _ a
population that suffers not only from collapsing mental and
physical states, but also from simple, profound feelings of
loneliness and depression.
</P>
<P>
   The work is not easy, or always safe. Nurses' aides injure
themselves or fall ill at twice the average of workers in private
industry. Many get no health insurance. Not surprisingly, in this
high-employment economy, such jobs have gotten hard to fill.
Ombudsmen in 41 states have reported that nursing homes cannot
recruit and retain the aides they need.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 1.6 million residents in nursing homes, with
positions for about 600,000 nurses' aides to care for them. There
may be an additional 250,000 or more aides working in private
homes. Ninety-three percent are female. Most are between 25 and 44.
Thirty percent are black, Hispanic or Asian. Ten years ago, when
the average wage for nurses' aides in nursing homes was $5.20 an
hour, the median income was $9,000. Today the national average wage
in nursing homes is thought to be $7 to $8 an hour. Their average
income is not known.
</P>
<P>
   That is not much, but not much training is required. Federal
standards mandate only 75 hours. Twenty-four percent of workers in
nursing homes have no high school degree. Ohio does not even ask
that they be able to read and write. Considering that the aged in
nursing homes suffer most from malnutrition, dehydration,
accidents, poor hygiene and bed sores _ most of which can be
prevented by adequate, well-trained care _ the quality of the work
force is critical.
</P>
<P>
   The miserly conditions of nurses' aides reflect the increasing
economic problems that nursing homes face. Thanks to stricter
reimbursement standards imposed in January, federal support of
long-term care may fall by 20 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   As federal and state governments wrestle with the cost of
nursing home care, they should consider raising the standards and
the wages of those who care for the very old at the end of the
budget line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
