<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S DEPTH PUT TO TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid had been eager to test
his team's depth.
</P>
<P>
   Now he'll be forced to.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles received a triple dose of major bad news late in the
week, with leading scorer Clint Mathis forced to undergo knee
surgery, Carlos Hermosillo experiencing continued pain in his lower
back and Daniel Hernandez succumbing to the effects of a severe
contusion.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, who tore the lateral meniscus in his left knee, is
expected to miss at least the rest of August. Hermosillo and
Hernandez are sidelined on a day-to-day basis.
</P>
<P>
   The timing could hardly be worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, which slipped back into fourth place in the Western
Conference standings in recent days, faces fifth-place San Jose
tonight at 7:30 at Spartan Stadium, kicking off a stretch of five
games in 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   A Galaxy victory in regulation would vault the team back into
second place. But a loss could become a psychological omen coming
on the heels ofthe injury setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to have depth, just in case,'' said Schmid
just hours before Wednesday's exhibition match against Mexican club
team Chivas de Guadalajara at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid's comment later took on an eery tone when Mathis suffered
a fateful foul doled out by Chivas defender Juan Pablo Alfaro late
in the first half. Mathis, who leads Los Angeles with 7 goals and
16 points, remained in the game and played the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   But a magnetic resonance imaging test taken on Thursday revealed
the tear. Mathis underwent surgery on Friday and will reportedly
miss from three to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo, who did not play in the Chivas match, had the
discomfort in his back resurface afterward. Hernandez, who had
started as a defender in the team's last three league games,
suffered the contusion on Wednesday after subbing into the match to
start of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Galaxy, the team welcomes back Cobi Jones
and Robin Frasier from national team duty. Both missed the Galaxy's
last three MLS games while representing the U.S. at the
Confederations Cup in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose, which had top management express very high
expectations in preseason, has been nothing short of abysmal thus
far. The Clash's two regulation victories are tied for last in the
league while the team has racked up a league-record nine shootout
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Since shootout triumphs are worth just a single point in the
standings -- as compared to three for a regulation victory -- the
team has fallen well behind in the race for playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Cerritos has 22 points to lead a San Jose team which has
lost three starters to major surgeries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
