<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYGOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRUCE AMONG NEW YORK REPUBLICANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, August 7:
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of Hillary Rodham Clinton's supporters, peace
seems to have broken out between the two squabbling Republicans
vying to run against her for the Senate seat from New York. With
only 10 days to go before Rep. Rick Lazio was scheduled to announce
his candidacy for the Republican nomination, Gov. George Pataki
exercised his prerogative as titular head of the party, endorsed
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and even asked Lazio to drop out if Giuliani
runs. Lazio's office says he is still in the race. But since the
congressman had said he would withdraw if asked by the governor, it
looks like easy sailing for New York City's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   For Pataki, who is still resentful over Giuliani's endorsement
of Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1994 and weary of endless battles with City
Hall, endorsing the mayor could not have been easy. Pataki made the
announcement late Friday before a sleepy summer weekend, minimizing
potential publicity. There were no balloons, speeches or cheers, as
there were when the governor endorsed Gov. George W. Bush for
president earlier in the summer. There was just the hard reality
that Pataki faced: growing pressure from national Republican
leaders to head off a fratricidal battle that could only help Mrs.
Clinton, and a growing realization that Lazio would probably lose
in the primary anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The governor once feared that if Giuliani dropped out of the
race there would be no backup candidate. Now Lazio has at least
gotten around the state and become well enough known to run if that
happens. Many Republicans feel that Lazio, a genial moderate on
many issues, might have been a better candidate than the
temperamental mayor. But as long as Giuliani looked likely to win
the primary, all the congressman could do was damage him.
</P>
<P>
   For his troubles, Lazio has put together a $3 million campaign
war chest that could serve him well in the future _ as a
gubernatorial candidate, say, if Pataki joins a Republican
administration in Washington or decides not to run for re-election
in three years. Rep. Peter King is still looking at challenging
Giuliani. That seems less likely now. Republicans are not eager to
do Mrs. Clinton any favors. She could not have entertained any
illusions that they would.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
