<HEADER>
A9130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      08-07 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE COMING BUDGET BLOWUP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, August 7:
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Hill is having a tough time putting together an honest
budget this year. Republicans have passed the biggest tax cut in
two decades, disproportionately rewarding the richest Americans,
who do not need it. The fact that only high-flying GOP donors and
special interests really want this tax cut was acknowledged by a
top party strategist who commended fellow lawmakers for defying
public opinion by passing it. Meanwhile, Republicans have slashed
children's health, school aid, crime-fighting and other vital
programs, while employing budget gimmicks to avoid even more cuts.
The whole exercise is designed to please the hard right and
precipitate a confrontation with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seems to have noticed that while Republican lawmakers are
eviscerating the federal safety net, their favorite presidential
candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, is moving at least
rhetorically in the opposite direction. Bush recently called for $8
billion in new spending for the poor. He could hardly do that under
the Republican Congressional budget.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they expect President Clinton to veto their
schemes and suffer political consequences for it. They cannot seem
to remember that since the government shutdown of 1995 they have
lost every single veto confrontation on the budget with Clinton.
This time Republicans know that eventually they will have to revise
the unrealistic budget ceilings enacted in 1997. They just hope
Clinton will be blamed for it. In an interesting admission, Rep.
Tom DeLay effectively acknowledged that the GOP never intended to
use the budget surplus next year to avoid budget cuts in domestic
programs. Rather, he said, the party's strategy was to use up the
money for defense, tax cuts and so-called budget ``emergencies,''
and push for a confrontation on everything else.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget strategy relies on the old gimmick of
labeling certain things, like the census, as ``emergencies'' so
that they are not governed by existing budget caps. A new gimmick
this year has to do with the fact that spending is broken down into
13 different spending bills. Republicans know that if they spread
cuts around to all of them, they would never get any passed. So
they have kept the cuts to a minimum in most of the spending bills
and, to pay for financing them, raided the one bill that is dearest
to the hearts of Democrats, which is for labor, health, social
services and education. The Republicans cut spending in these areas
so drastically they have not even dared bring the bill to the House
floor. They know it could not pass, and they are hoping that
sometime in the fall, in a final showdown with the White House, the
money will materialize to keep this problem from blowing up in
their faces.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that with $3 trillion in projected surpluses over
the next 10 years, there is enough money to save Social Security,
save Medicare, increase defense spending, run the government in a
way that would be satisfactory to most Americans and even provide a
modest tax cut. The posturing this year is only reinforcing the
public's already low opinion of Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
