For a kid raised on 166th Street in Queens, a boy who just had
moved to Florida but who grew up with a Yankees cap dangling from
the post of his bunkbed, it was also where the newscast ended.
</P>
<P>
   Munson owned that kind of magne tism, enough to be made a Yankee
cap tain, the first since Lou Gehrig, and enough to spark a
thousand arguments on the stoop of the red-brick walk-up where I
grew up.
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDSHIPS STRAINED
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on those three concrete steps and jawing about the
Yanks, you were ei ther a Munson guy or a Reggie Jackson guy, which
to me was the difference be tween being blue collar or fur collar,
wor shiping steadiness and professionalism or applauding ego and
flair.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees signed Reggie in 1976, and that spring, he labeled
himself ``the straw that stirs the drink'' _ a slight clearly aimed
at Munson, who'd been the league's MVP that year. Somehow, the two
managed to avoid coming to blows all through 1977, even if Frankie
Cava luzzi and I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   It strikes me as impossible now, post-Columbine, post-South
Park, post-Mortal Kombat: Two 12-year-olds brawling over baseball.
That was my 1977 in New York, though, all Munson arguments and
cracked wooden bats and hardballs cov ered in black electrical
tape, even as the Son of Sam pumped .44-caliber bullets through
teenagers and a city's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won the Series that sea son, when Jackson hit three
homers on three swings against the Dodgers. Mun son hit .320. When
it was over, he pushed the team to trade him to Cleveland, to be
nearer his wife, Diana, and his three kids.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of Munson in anything but pinstripes broke my heart
at age 12. Now, at age 34, his quote does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be home,'' he ex plained. ``I've talked to a
lot of guys around 40 who look back and say, `Gee, I wish I spent
more time with my kids, my family.' And they never will. I want to
be the guy who does.''
</P>
<P>
   That was why Munson got his pilot's license. When he wasn't
traded, he began to fly home after most every game. This he did all
through 1978, the year the Yanks came from 14 games back to beat
the Red Sox in a playoff, the Royals for the league championship _
Munson was MVP _ and the Dodgers for the title.
</P>
<P>
   A WHOLE DIFFERENT WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Then came 1979. First, Queens and our three-room apartment, my
school and my friends, became a memory. Then Munson.
</P>
<P>
   I remember his going now as a time when, for me, so much was
coming: first date, first day of high school, first beer, first
girlfriend. Munson seems to stand over that time period the way he
once stood over home plate at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The night after his death, the Yankees played Baltimore. When
the team took the field, eight men ran to their positions, leaving
the catcher's box vacant. There was no moment of silence, though.
For nearly 10 minutes, 51,000 people screamed Thurman Munson's
name.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, some of us still haven't stopped. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
