<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GWYNN-SIDE-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN A BIG HIT AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Twenty-two years ago, Liz Minor, an
administrative assistant at Poly High, kept pestering her husband,
Harry, a scout for the New York Mets, to take a look at this chubby
kid with a sweet swing who played for the Jackrabbits' baseball
team.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, he told her, the kid's going to be a basketball player.
And just as well baseball's not in his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could always get his bat on the ball, but his tools weren't
that great,'' Harry Minor recalled of the kid, Tony Gwynn. ``He was
a singles hitter who didn't throw all that well, run all that well
or play defense all that well. He wasn't anything to rave about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was also worried about his body he never did have the
athletic body. If he gained 10 to 15 pounds, he wasn't going to be
playing football or basketball, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the kid turned out to be one of baseball's all-time
great hitters. On Friday night, Gwynn became only the 22nd player
in major league history to reach the 3,000-hit plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Minor recalls all this with a laugh as does Liz, who jokes that
after Gwynn reached the big leagues, Frank Cashen, then the Mets'
general manager, told her, ``From now on, I don't want Harry's
reports, I want yours.''
</P>
<P>
   If Minor was not alone in his opinion of Gwynn then he was
undrafted out of high school and chose to play basketball and
baseball at San Diego State neither is he alone now.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach has produced 66 major leaguers and probably twice as
many scouts and coaches, prompting some boosters to refer to the
city as the best baseball town in the world per square mile.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the more prominent players are glad to count Gwynn as
one of their own. They credit Gwynn for not only his
accomplishment, but his class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a true professional his entire career,'' said Bob
Grich, a six-time All-Star second baseman with the Orioles and
Angels. ``He's been a gentleman on and off the field. There should
be nothing but pride and joy for the city of Long Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lemon, whom Gwynn will undoubtedly join as the only Hall of
Fame player from Long Beach, is recovering from a stroke earlier
this year and wasn't feeling well enough to be interviewed, but his
wife, Jane, says he has followed Gwynn's chase for the milestone
and is very happy for Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been so many exceptional athletes to come from Long
Beach over the years,'' said Jeff Burroughs, a former No.1 draft
pick and American League MVP. ``It's another feather in Long
Beach's hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal State L.A. coach John Herbold, who coached at Lakewood when
Gwynn played for Poly, praised Gwynn for taking time to address his
team a few years ago when it was playing at San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to do that,'' Herbold said. ``He's just a
different type of guy. He's never been in trouble, he gives clinics
time, he gives fans time. He's been good for Long Beach and good
for the West side.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is often boiled down to a game of numbers, leaving
careers and milestones to be assessed as if they were widgets.
</P>
<P>
   It is Gwynn's peers who truly appreciate the magnitude of
Gwynn's accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy gets 3,000 hits, you just shake your head,'' said
Grich, who lives in Coto de Caza. ``It's just a number to a lot of
people. I played hard for 15 years, man, I played almost every day
and I got (1,833) hits. Unless you struggle in the major leagues
for 10 or 15 years, you have no idea what an accomplishment this
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Grich greeted Reggie Jackson at home plate following his 500th
home run, was with the Angels for Rod Carew's 3,000th hit, and
shook the hand of Detroit's Al Kaline when he doubled against the
Orioles for his 3,000th hit.
</P>
<P>
   What was Grich thinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished it was me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bailey, who in 1961 received a then-record signing bonus of
$175,000 from the Pittsburgh Pirates after he graduated from Wilson
High, still remembers the electric atmosphere at Dodger Stadium in
1968 when Don Drysdale set a major-league record (since broken)
with 58fr 2/3 consecutive scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was spectacular,'' said Bailey, now living in Las Vegas
after his playing and minor-league managing career. ``Everybody was
rooting for Drysdale because they liked him so much as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   He can understand why people in baseball would feel similarly
about Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing in an old-timers game in Atlanta and I
introduced myself,'' Bailey said. ``He acknowledged that he knew
who I was. He was a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   That was also the description of Bill Powell, now the Poly
baseball coach who met Gwynn this winter when the school honored
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Poly kids were very impressed with Tony,'' Powell
said. ``He was very articulate and took time for everyone there. He
didn't brush anyone off he was super polite. It's too bad that more
of the younger kids in the community weren't exposed to that. I
know a couple of school classes got out, but not many.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Gwynn didn't get to 3,000 merely by being a gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to marvel at his swing, said Minor, but what really
has made Gwynn is his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting is such a science,'' Minor said. ``That's why you
don't see high school players go right to the big leagues. You can
judge everything in baseball a guy's arm, his speed, his hands, but
nobody can look at a high school player and see a .300 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a classic example of a guy who didn't have good tools,
but could play. His arm is just average (but Gwynn has won five
Gold Gloves). ... Those are the guys who are tough to scout. You
can't look inside a guy and measure his desire. I have all the
admiration in the world for Tony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
