</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES LOSE BRAWL BUT WIN GAME VS. MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Yankees and Mariners engaged in a long game that
turned ugly in the last two innings, with a bench clearing brawl.
</P>
<P>
   But long before the fight, the Yankees had slugged four home
runs and built a substantial lead that would hold up, in an 11-8
victory. But after Jason Grimsley knocked down and then hit Edgar
Martinez with successive pitches in the bottom of the eighth
inning, immediately after Alex Rodriguez hit a three-run home run,
Frankie Rodriguez hit Chuck Knoblauch in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch trotted to first base, as the Yankees began screaming
from their dugout for the ejection of Rodriguez, and home plate
umpire Gary Cederstrom began moving toward the Yankees' dugout,
answering their taunts, until Willie Randolph stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Piniella, the Seattle manager, came out to remove Rodriguez,
but soon many of the Yankees were shouting at Rodriguez as he
walked off the field, including catcher Joe Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez turned and screamed at Girardi, then charged, punching
Girardi three times and knocking him to the ground at home plate,
and players from both teams rushed onto the field. Bernie Williams,
Chili Davis and Shane Spencer all went after Rodriguez, and the
brawl spread to in front of the Seattle dugout on the first base
side.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires needed about 15 minutes to calm the situation, and
after they had cleared the field, Girardi and Rodriguez were
ejected, and Girardi reacted furiously, throwing his equipment,
yelling at Cederstrom. Don Zimmer _ acting as the Yankees' manager
because Joe Torre had been booted in the eighth for arguing a call
_ argued, and he, too, may have been ejected, although that was not
immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won three straight and improved their record to
66-42. With exactly two-thirds of the season complete, the Yankees
are on a pace to win 99 games.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Jeff Fassero retired the first two batters in the top
of the first inning, before Paul O'Neill homered, and Bernie
Williams homered, and after a couple of singles, Scott Brosius
slammed a three-run home run; five batters, five runs. Fassero
retreated to the back of the mound and discarded his chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of more guys would get on base, but Fassero would
escape further trouble. Orlando Hernandez strolled to the mound for
the bottom of the first inning, staked to a five-run lead, his
chances for his 13th victory excellent.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez's first pitch was high and inside to Brian Hunter,
and Hernandez proceeded to walk Hunter _ who does not walk often _
on five pitches, and matters would get worse for El Duque.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell singled and Ken Griffey, Jr. singled and after a
sacrifice fly, Edgar Martinez singled. Hernandez appeared to be
bothered a couple of times by the calls of Cederstrom, and he
walked Jay Buhner, loading the bases. That's when Allen Watson
began warming up in the Yankees' bullpen; Torre was not going to
allow a five-run lead to evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez walked Raul Ibanez on four pitches and forced in
Seattle's third run, and soon Girardi moved slowly to the mound.
Hernandez knew exactly what was happening, he knew Girardi was
trying to buy time, at Torre's behest, so Watson could finish
warming up and face the next hitter. John Mabry prepared to hit and
Hernandez stood on the top of the mound, glancing again and again
at the Yankees' dugout, and sure enough Torre stepped out to make
the pitching change. Hernandez tried dribbling the ball on the
mound, but it stayed down.
</P>
<P>
   Watson retired the next two hitters, ending a first inning that
required about 50 minutes to play. Hernandez's final line:
one-third of an inning, three hits, three walks, three runs. On
July 27, he lasted six innings and departed with a tired arm. Five
days later, the Boston Red Sox battered him for six extra-base hits
and five runs in five innings-plus. Friday night, he had the
shortest outing of his career. He had never pitched fewer than 3
1/3 innings in any start.
</P>
<P>
   But El Duque's quick demise seemed a distant memory as the pitch
counts mounted, the runs continued to score and the hurlers from
both sides struggled. Knoblauch lashed a two-run home run in the
top of the fourth, knocking Fassero from the game, but Tom Davey,
the left-hander's replacement, labored to throw strikes, walking
four and allowing four runs in the top of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella, who had been pacing in the Seattle dugout, finally sat
on the bench after Davey issued consecutive walks to Girardi and
then O'Neill _ the second forcing home the Yankees' ninth run of
the game _ and Stan Williams, the Seattle pitching coach, went to
the mound to remove Davey.
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken truce that sometimes occurs in these sort of games
took hold in the bottom of the fifth inning, when Buhner grounded
out on the first pitch thrown to him, with the Mariners trailing
11-5. Thereafter, hitters from both teams consistently swung the
bat early in the count, both managers employed their reserves, and
the game seemed to be moving along to a merciful conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But Alex Rodriguez bashed a three-run homer in the bottom of the
eighth off Jason Grimsley, and with his next pitch, Grimsley
knocked down Edgar Martinez; the fans that remained booed angrily.
Grimsley hit Martinez with his next pitch and was ejected by
Cederstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the same inning, Torre argued with Doug Eddings, the
first base umpire, about a close call. It was the second time Torre
had challenged Eddings' decision, and predictably, Torre was thrown
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
