<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE TO RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Baseball purists probably cringe at the thought, but
the Angels have taken on the role of ``Wild Card spoilers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox went into Friday night's game trailing the
Toronto Blue Jays by one game in the American League Wild Card
race, the Angels a mere after-thought.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs by Brian Daubach and Troy O'Leary off Angels starter
Steve Sparks provided all the offense the Red Sox would need in a
5-1 victory before 36,360 at Edison Field. O'Leary added a two-run
double in the ninth off Shigetoshi Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the Red Sox remain one game back of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox starter Bret Saberhagen (8-4) lasted only five innings,
but allowed just one run to earn the victory. Steve Decker, who
tied a career-high with three hits, drove in the Angels' only run
with a fourth-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   Decker's reward? After the game, Decker was optioned to triple-A
Edmonton to make room for pitcher Tim Belcher, who comes off the
disabled list to start today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get sent down any time,'' said Decker, 33.
``They have a lot of young guys they want to see. I understand it,
but it doesn't make it any more comforting. I did my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks (5-8) performed a high-wire act in the early innings, but
survived by getting outs in key situations. He walked two with one
out in the first and got out of it.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Mike Stanley and Jason Varitek opened the inning
with back-to-back singles, but Sparks retired the next three
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Sparks gave up a two-run home run to Daubach, but
it could have been a lot worse. After the home run, Sparks walked
Nomar Garciaparra, allowed a single to O'Leary and walked Stanley
to load the bases with none out.
</P>
<P>
   But Sparks escaped further damage by striking out Varitek,
getting Darren Lewis on a pop to third and striking out Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   The only other run Sparks allowed came on O'Leary's solo homer
in the fifth. Sparks went six innings, allowing three runs and six
hits. Not bad, but not as good as his eight-inning, one-run,
two-hit performance against the Twins his last time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had less command tonight, but one thing I did was I stayed
with my knuckleball in tough counts,'' he said. ``It wasn't as good
as my last game, but I think I'm headed in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels cut into the Red Sox lead in the fourth after
back-to-back walks by Darin Erstad and Troy Glaus with one out.
Decker followed with his second of three hits, an RBI double to
left. Third base coach Larry Bowa held Glaus at third on the play,
and that's where Glaus stayed as newly recalled second baseman
Trent Durrington popped out and Orlando Palmeiro struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Durrington, called up from double-A Erie, singled on the first
pitch in his first major league at-bat and finished the night 1 for
4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a nice, short, little swing,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said of Durrington. ``He hustles and plays hard. We'll take
another look at him (today).''
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, O'Leary hit his team-leading 21st homer of the
year just inside the right-field foul pole for a 3-1 Red Sox edge.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen labored through 92 pitches in five innings, but got
big outs when he needed them too. Angels' hitters faced Saberhagen
five times with runners in scoring position, but got just one hit
(Decker's RBI double).
</P>
</TEXT>
