<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANGELS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ By any measure, the difference between Brian
Daubach and Mo Vaughn is as vast as the difference between the Back
Bay and the Left Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Fame. Charisma. Paycheck ($80 million vs. $230,000). Pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   In every category, the Hit Dog dwarfs the Belleville Basher, who
was a minor league carny act until Dan Duquette and Dave Jauss
decided the mail carrier's son deserved one last look before being
stamped return to sender.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, while Vaughn's California dreamin' took a nightmarish
tumble with virtually his first step as an Angel, Daubach continues
to be an improbable godsend for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   While Vaughn made just a pregame cameo appearance here Friday
night before leaving because of a staph infection that has caused
him to miss the last three games, Daubach made another major impact
on the Sox' fortunes, hitting a two-run home run off Angels
knuckleballer Steve Sparks that started the Red Sox to a 5-1 win
against the Angels Friday night at Edison International Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we were fortunate that we picked the apple when it was
ripe, but the kid has done very well here,'' manager Jimy Williams
said of Daubach, whose 14th home run of the season followed a walk
to John Valentin in the third inning and helped make a winner of
Bret Saberhagen (8-4), who got three innings of scoreless relief
from Derek Lowe and a finishing touch in the ninth from Tim
Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good defensive player, a good offensive player, and a
good teammate. You can't ask for anything more than he's brought
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary, who grew up in the LA suburb of Compton and went
to high school in nearby Cypress, treated two dozen friends and
family members, including his mother, to a four-hit night,
including his team-leading 21st home run.
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Leary's first four-hit game of the season and third of
his career. His two-run double off reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa in
the ninth iced the win for the Sox, who kept pace with both Toronto
and Oakland in the wild-card race. The Blue Jays won to stay a game
ahead of the Sox; the A's also won to stay a game behind.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary recoiled when told that Williams said he doesn't get as
much credit nationally as he should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need it, I don't want it, I want to be able to go
places and not be bothered,'' O'Leary said. ``And my family's like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary is within two home runs of the career high he set last
season, and with 73 RBIs, he should easily eclipse his career-high
of 83 set last season. He remains sensitive, however, about his
poor second half last season, when he hit just .238 after the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I can get you guys (reporters) off my back about the
second half,'' he said. ``You talk about it, you make it stay in
people's heads. Just like when I came into the league, and people
said, `You can't play, you can't do this, you can't do that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get 100 RBIs, you can't mention that anymore. Then it
will be the playoffs, and I'll have to get you off my back about
the 1 for 16,'' O'Leary's output against the Indians last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen walked back-to-back hitters for the first time all
season and had runners on base in all five innings he pitched, but
he ended each of those innings with a strikeout before turning the
game over to Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who gave up an RBI double to Steve Decker after
walking Darin Erstad and Troy Glaus in the fourth, gave up six hits
and walked two, but finished with a season-high seven strikeouts.
Williams lifted him after he'd thrown 92 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, losers of three of their four previous games, had
numerous chances to break this one open early but failed to
capitalize. The Sox had two on and one out in the first and didn't
score. They had two on and nobody out in the second and didn't
score. They loaded the bases in the third after Daubach's home run
and didn't score. They had a leadoff single from Jose Offerman in
the fourth and didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   But the home runs stood up on a night the scoreboard already
showed a Toronto win and Oakland leading.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, widely mocked as a possible replacement for Vaughn when
he signed as a minor league free agent last winter, has completely
outplayed the former Sox slugger since June 1. Daubach is batting
.319 in 44 games since that date, while Vaughn was batting .250.
Daubach has 10 home runs and 32 RBIs in that span; Vaughn's numbers
are 5 and 26, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
