<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGGS A LONG WAY FROM BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG _ It's odd to see him here, now, surrounded by
all this peace and adulation. Wade Boggs is on the threshold of his
3,000th big league hit (he went 0 for 3 Friday night and is holding
at 2,997) _ a hit that will guarantee his enshrinement in
Cooperstown _ and he's going do it in a town that truly loves him.
</P>
<P>
   He's on the front page of the local papers. There are warm and
fuzzy articles about chicken and dumplings for dinner. There are
family photos, and suck-up standups by the local talking heads. The
Devil Rays' public relations department has issued a ``Wade Boggs
3,000 Hit Media Kit,'' which includes details (date, city, inning,
pitcher, etc.) of every one of Wade's hits and is only slightly
smaller than the Manhattan Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   He's Sweet Old Uncle Wade, and Tampa Bay is Pleasantville, USA.
</P>
<P>
   Good for him. Boggs worked his butt off for 24 professional
baseball seasons and made himself into one of the greatest singles
and doubles hitters of all time. He's earned his moment in the
Sunshine State, far, far away from the Horrible Hub.
</P>
<P>
   Wade doesn't talk much about Boston anymore. He's like those
World War II veterans who made it home, then never spoke of the
horrors of combat. Boston is where a lot of bad stuff happened to
Wade and it's where he still gets booed every time he returns.
</P>
<P>
   But this 3,000-hit quest is very much a Boston baseball story.
Wade can wear that traditional Tampa Bay Devil Rays hat to the Hall
of Fame if he wishes, but he got his first 2,098 major league hits
while he was wearing a Boston uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one was in Chicago (April 26, 1982) off Richard
Dotson,'' the 41-year-old Boggs recalled Friday night. ``It was a
1-2 pitch and was a base hit in the hole between short and third. I
remember when I got back in the dugout, I sat next to Jerry Remy,
who never said much. And he said, `You only need 2,999 more, kid.'
And that just stuck with me. He was the Nostradamus of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade is from Tampa. Debbie Boggs is from Tampa. Their son plays
in the Tampa Little League and their daughter is a student at the
University of South Florida. Wade's going to get his 3,000th hit at
Tropicana Field and the place is going to be awash in tears and
goodwill. It's a long way from Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston is the organization that signed Wade, supressed him
in the minors, then watched him rattle off seven consecutive
200-hit seasons (the only time that's been done in this century).
Boggs is a .369 career hitter in Fenway Park. In the Red Sox roll
call of hitters, Wade ranks second (to Ted Williams) in batting
average (.338), fifth in hits, fourth in doubles, and third in
on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   It was Wade who was seen crying in the dugout after the Sox blew
the seventh game of the World Series at Shea in 1986. Wade's the
one who struck out against Dennis Eckersley to end the first game
of the 1988 playoffs. Wade's the one who said he willed himself
invisible to get out of a Florida knife fight. When Debbie Boggs
put steel-belted radial tracks on his elbow, running him over with
the family Jeep after a night out at Nick Christey's restaurant in
Winter Haven, Wade announced, ``I'm the white Irving Fryar.'' And
what Sox fan will ever forget Margo, Penthouse, and Barbara Walters
setting up shop in Winter Haven?
</P>
<P>
   He was Our Wade for 11 big-league seasons before he went to the
hated Pinstripes, where he won a championship ring and rode a horse
in the Yankee Stadium outfield. And now he's in the late December
of a career, ready to join the rest of the 3,000-hit club.
</P>
<P>
   When Boggs addressed the national media, there was one bit of
old-timey contentiousness. Stung by radio nitwit Jim Rome's
criticism that he was orchestrating his plate appearances to make
sure he crashed the barrier at home, Wade said, ``For him to say
I've manipulated this is callous. It means so much for me to do
this at home in front of my father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get it out of the way,'' Boggs added. ``God knows what
2,999 will feel like when I walk to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen Friday night. While Boggs's West Coast
soulmate, Tony Gwynn, cracked No. 3,000 in Montreal, Wade flied to
left in the first, grounded to the mound in the third, grounded to
first in the sixth, and walked in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Son Brett Boggs (named after George Brett) is serving as batboy
for the series and Wade said, ``It's going to be special when he
picks up that bat and runs down the first-base line to give me a
hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game starts at 6:35. Charles Nagy will be on the
mound for the Tribe. Wade is 11 for 54 (.204) lifetime vs. Nagy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
