<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     08-07 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLDOUT GALLOWAY GOING LONG OR JUST CATCHING HIS BREATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Joey Galloway has made some big plays in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   He's got that speed. Everyone knows it. ``SportsCenter'' has
rolled the highlight tapes of him running back punts for touchdowns
and busting 69-yard TD gambols off simple post patterns.
</P>
<P>
   After he scores, No. 84 likes to run out of the end zone, legs
stepping high, not a defender near him, because who, after all, can
catch Galloway?
</P>
<P>
   He has the ability and the ego to look like a superstar.
</P>
<P>
   But when you think of Galloway, you don't just think about the
plays he has made. You think about the plays the 27-year-old
Seahawks receiver has not made. There have been just as many of
those, and not all the blame can go to Dennis Erickson or Warren
Moon or Jon Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes you wonder if No. 84 has the guts to be a true
franchise player _ which is basically what he is demanding with
this training camp holdout in which he seeks money usually
associated with Super Bowl winners and Pro Bowlers.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway's jersey may be a big seller for the Seahawks, but
something about him has always smacked of being too precious, too
special to be the gritty, anything-to-win player worthy of a club's
biggest contract.
</P>
<P>
   For the money, Keyshawn Johnson has done better for the New York
Jets than Galloway has for the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   For all the smack talk and ego that Johnson drove with him from
L.A. to the Big Apple, the kid has backed it all up. Johnson has
turned himself into one of the league's most fearless,
do-the-dirty-work receivers _ the kind of player who helps make a
team a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that has been Bill Parcells' influence. Maybe Johnson saw
that, under Parcells, sacrifice and effort would take him and the
Jets far.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the kind of lesson Galloway will learn with Mike
Holmgren, who is now at the start of turning around one of the most
underachieving franchises in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But how can Galloway fulfill his promise if he already thinks of
himself as the superstar who deserves extra-special consideration?
</P>
<P>
   Speed always shows up. But speed alone is not what makes the
NFL's greatest receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway obviously fails to understand that the team and the
coach and the general manager he is now testing in Holmgren
orchestrates the very system in which Galloway could actually
become the player he believes himself already to be. One hundred
catches. Twenty TDs. By next season, Galloway could be the next
Robert Brooks or Antonio Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, you can't fault a man who likes money. Money is
freedom. Money is respect. And none of his teammates faults
Galloway _ though they should _ because everyone understands that
this NFL thing is huge business.
</P>
<P>
   You also can't fault a man who likes to have his lungs filled
with deep gulps of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, who has routinely yanked himself off the field in the
middle of critical drives because he needs a blow, has elevated the
art of breathing to an art form.
</P>
<P>
   You want to forget about these small, human frailties in a
person. But when that person is a no-Pro Bowl receiver who is still
more potential than actual performance and he insists on asking for
more money than Jerry Rice, you come to expect a little more from
the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back to Pittsburgh last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks were 3-0, having feasted on Philadelphia, Arizona and
Washington to give themselves a nice season-starting record.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, it's crunch time. The Hawks are in a dog fight in
the Steel City, with the Steelers leading 13-10 with 1:32 left in
the game. The Seahawks have the ball on the Steelers' 32-yard line
with a last-chance efort to snatch the win.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what?
</P>
<P>
   When quarterback Warren Moon steps back and expects to execute a
play called for Galloway, Moon doesn't find Galloway in his target
range.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is James McKnight who has run Galloway's route. It
is McKnight who's in the end zone, dropping the pass that would
have given the Seahawks the win.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Galloway? On the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Why? No one has ever quite answered that question, partly
because not once during Galloway's tenure with the Hawks did former
coach Dennis Erickson, or anyone else for that matter, challenge
Galloway to suck it up and stop yanking himself out of games,
especially on critical second- and third-down plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have offered Galloway a king's ransom in a new
contract extension. The $35 million offer includes a $7 million
signing bonus and puts him ahead of Pro Bowlers such as Herman
Moore ($34 million) or Terrell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of offer, Galloway's agent should at least send
the guy over to Cheney with the stipulation that negotiations would
then go forward in good faith to work out exact terms.
</P>
<P>
   But Galloway is either getting rotten advice _ word is he is
seeking $40 million with a $12 million signing bonus _ or he does
not have a clue about what it takes to be a real winner.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
