<HEADER>
A9185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNO-SIGNATURE-BOS &LR;      08-07 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-SIGNATURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDWRITING MAY BE ON THE WALL FOR SIGNATURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John Hancock should have seen the writing on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1776, three weeks after Hancock drew his famous signature on
the Declaration of Independence, another signer fired off a
question: Why did delegates have to travel hundreds of miles to
scribble down their names?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to have the privilege, when necessarily
absent, of voting and signing by proxy,'' complained Elbridge
Gerry, a Massachusetts delegate.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken more than two centuries. But this week, as a
congressional panel approved ``digital signatures'' _ acknowleging
that computer symbols have been nudging out inked names for years _
Gerry appeared finally to be winning the argument.
</P>
<P>
   And the so-called ``John Hancock,'' a worldwide symbol of
commitment and in some cases a treasured art form, appeared to be
going the way of the horse-drawn buggy.
</P>
<P>
   The signals are everywhere. Drivers charge for gasoline without
signing a receipt. Cashiers rarely compare signatures to the backs
of buyers' credit cards. Consumers live their lives online, buying
products and getting mortgages with nary a flourish of the pen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with help from a bill drawn up in the House of
Representatives this week, businesses will most likely be able to
conduct all their transactions online within the next several
years. Many already do. But the legislation, which was sponsored by
Representative Anna Eshoo, a Democrat from Silicon Valley, would
mean that a series of encrypted numbers soon could replace the
personalized curlicue, having been given full legal status under
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which has widespread support in the business
community, was cleared without dissent by the House Commerce
Committee and is expected to pass the full House. Similar
legislation is pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   If the measure becomes law, everything from wills to bank loans
to book purchases from online booksellers could be ``signed''
online and considered legally solid in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handshakes and written signatures have bound people for a long
time,'' said Representative W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, chairman of the
House Telecommunications subcommittee and a Louisiana Republican.
``But you can't shake hands on the Internet. So what is the form of
agreement that is not only recognizable but also enforceable? The
digital handshake seems to be the way in which people can be bound
by an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect,'' Tauzin added with a laugh, ``if John Hancock were
around today and we were doing the Declaration of Independence on
the Internet, he'd use the whole Web site to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the name, digital signatures are, for the most part,
only marginally related to the physical act of signing one's name.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are times when a digital signature requires a
written signature. An example occurred when members of Congress
signed Y2K legislation in July and sent it to the President
Clinton. The lawmakers used ``pen ops,'' equipment similar to the
rubbery pads now used in some stores for credit card transactions.
The machines recieve a person's signature through a special pen,
then translate it into an encrypted digital code. That code is then
forwarded by computer to the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   What will be far more common, however, is just a simple
mathematical algorithm. Using a combination of the number zero and
the number one, a personalized code _ or signature _ is created. It
can be any number of digits and functions ``just like an electronic
seal,'' according to Barbara Boczek, director of marketing for
CyberTrust, a GTE company based in Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   It is not completely clear how this will work in practice for
the consumer, but the possible ways of sending a digital signature
include punching in numbers on a keyboard or having the data preset
in an account's software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas in the physical world a signature looks a certain way
and might be creative, in the electronic world, it's just a bunch
of 1s and 0s,'' Boczek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could potentially give out tens of millions of digital
signatures,'' said Ed Dixon, a spokesman for MasterCard
International. ``But face-to-face, physical transactions will still
be a part of credit card transactions. I do think your actual
signature will be important.''
</P>
<P>
   But already, it is not the signature that carries weight in
court in credit card disputes. It is the digital evidence _ the
time of the transaction, for example, and whether it was approved _
several industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the computer has led to the decline of
handwriting of all sorts, and signatures were bound to follow, said
Heidi Harrelson, president of the American Handwriting Analysis
Foundation. Already, she said, ``as computers are used more and
more, we see handwriting and signatures less and less, and that's a
bit of a controversy'' among the foundation's members.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern, particularly to forensic handwriting
analysts and consumer watchdog groups, is security. Handwriting is
specific to the individual, not subject to attack from computer
hackers. It cannot be spirited away to a national data base to
track people's movements, as some analysts fear could happen with a
digital signature. Forensic handwriting analyst Linda L. Collins
said that, with an exclusively digital system, ``you are opening
the door for even more fraud to take place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our signature is our stamp of approval, and if somebody else
uses it, there are ways to prove it,'' Collins said. ``It has
always authenticated everything. And even other than the fact that
it opens the door to fraud, it's a loss because it once represented
us and authenticated us. It's just another way of saying who we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the business world is planning to take digital
signatures a step further. Instead of just attaching them to
documents, companies are hoping the entire nature of commerce will
be revolutionized by a system now used primarily by the Pentagon: a
two-tiered system of encrypted signatures, or ``keys.''
</P>
<P>
   The system would allow two parties _ whether they know each
other or not _ to be assured that each is who it claims to be. It
also would prevent unwanted entities from being able to decode
documents sent over the Internet, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be huge advantages to the consumer,'' said
Lamar Smith, senior vice president for government relations at Visa
USA. ``I think the general feeling is that there is a huge
potential for stimulating growth through electronic commerce
channels. And what Congress and the (Clinton) administration are
trying to do is remove the barriers to letting that flower bloom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 0921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
