<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      08-07 1639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 8:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-PLO-REBELS (Damascus, Syria) _ Once, George Habash and
Nayef Hawatmeh were Palestinian revolutionaries in deed as well as
word, leading guerrilla warfare against Israel from Jordan and
Lebanon. One is remembered by some as a hijacker, the other as a
killer, though it has been more than a decade since they and their
groups suspended their armed struggle. Now, they live in limbo, not
wanted by Israel and wanting no part of Yasser Arafat's peace.
Their presence in Syria now could prove a complication to the
rekindling of peace talk between Syria and Israel. By Douglas Jehl.
(With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-PUB-MAKEOVER (London) _ The pub as downmarket watering
hole, a neighborly spot serving pints of warm beer, pickles and
starchy pies, a spot where the ghosts of Dickens and Dr. Johnson
hover in the air, is rapidly being displaced by the pub as trendy
cash cow. By Alan Cowell. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CHILDREN-WARRIORS (United Nations) _ According to UNICEF,
the U.N. Children's Fund, 300,000 children under 18 are serving as
regular soldiers, guerrilla fighters, spies, porters, cooks and
sexual slaves _ even suicide commandos _ in conflicts under way in
about 50 nations. The lightness, simplicity and low cost of modern
weapons make them ideal for use by children. By Judith Miller and
Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-WATER-STUDY (United Nations) _ The poorest people in the
world are paying many times more than their richer compatriots for
the water they need to live, and are getting more than their share
of deadly diseases because supplies are dangerously contaminated,
an international panel of experts concluded last week. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-CATTLE (Seoul, South Korea) _ Last summer, in an
encouraging sign that relations between the Koreas were improving,
a convoy of 50 trucks from the Hyundai Group of South Korea rolled
across the heavily fortified border into North Korea, carrying a
most precious cargo. Inside the trucks were 500 head of cattle, a
gift from Chung Ju Yung, Hyundai's billionaire founder. Now those
animals have become the focus of yet another dispute. By Calvin
Sims.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SHELTER (Vragolija, Yugoslavia) _ While it is unlikely
that many Albanians will freeze to death this winter, the U.N. goal
to have at least one, warm, dry room for every Albanian family is
not going to be met, officials now admit. A recent internal U.N.
report said, ``It is in shelter that the humanitarian community
faces its greatest challenge.'' By Steven Erlanger. (With photo and
map.)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-ILLICIT-DIAMONDS (Washington) _ Concerned that diamonds
are financing and perpetuating wars in Africa, the Clinton
administration is considering actions aimed at halting the
illicit-diamond trade, administration officials say. By Raymond
Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   IVORY-COAST-NATIONALISM (Ayame, Ivory Coast) _ In the Ivory
Coast, the debate over national identity _ so-called ivoirite _ has
sparked violence against non-Ivoirians and become the driving issue
in the upcoming presidential election. By Norimitsu Onishi. (With a
map.)
</P>
<P>
   GREATER-ALBANIA (Prizren, Yugoslavia) _ Kosovar Albanians, along
with their ethnic kin in Albania, Macedonia and Serbia, have long
dreamed of a ``Greater Albania.'' The departure of the Serbian
border police, opening up the frontier, has given most a taste of
what such a state might be like. Not many seem to like it. By Chris
Hedges. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-SMOKING-BAN (Madrid, Spain) _ Columbus brought back
tobacco from the New World 500 years ago, and Spain has been
enamored of smoking ever since. But the government recently has
stepped up its effort to change that situation, and the latest
decree bans smoking on all commercial flights and intercity buses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RANCH (Crawford, Texas) _ In any other year, the news that
the governor was shopping for a weekend getaway ranch would not
have amounted to much of a story. But when word leaked out that
Gov. George W. Bush was negotiating for a 1,550-acre spread in
central Texas, it prompted an obvious, if tantalizing, question:
Where exactly does he plan to be getting away from? By Jim Yardley.
(With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   SF-CHRONICLE-REACT (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Chronicle
once embarked on a long editorial crusade on what it saw as a
pressing issue _ improving the coffee served in restaurants. ``A
Great City's People Forced to Drink Swill,'' proclaimed one
headline. Over the years, some San Franciscans have wondered
something similar about the city's newspapers. Nevertheless, The
Chronicle's combination of provincialism and frivolity seemed to
match the city's psyche and earned the paper a certain affection.
So it was with some sadness that San Franciscans greeted the news
Friday that The Chronicle, owned by the same family for 134 years,
is being sold to Hearst Corp., publisher of the rival San Francisco
Examiner. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   WELLFLEET-PSYCH-RETREAT (Wellfleet, Mass.) _ So solid is the
area's reputation as a psychiatric summer retreat that Harry
Castleman, a marketing manager from Needham, Mass., on vacation
here, remarked that ``I've always heard that if you need a
psychiatrist in August, the only place to find one is in
Wellfleet.'' By Carey Goldberg. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE-MAYORAL-RACE (Baltimore) _ After weeks of political
chaos featuring 27 declared mayoral candidates, six of them with
arrest records, a campaign showdown loomed noisy as summer thunder
here last week in a rowdy scene outside City Hall. By Francis X.
Clines. (With photos and map.)
</P>
<P>
   MICH-CHERRIES-DECLINE (Traverse City, Mich.) _ Michigan, with
3.12 million bearing-age cherry trees, grows more cherries than any
other state. But 30,000 cherry trees were taken out last year
alone, most of them yanked out by their roots to make room for
retirement or vacation homes. By Robyn Meredith. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-JUDICIAL-WATCH (Los Angeles) _ Judicial Watch, the
conservative Washington organization that has filed more than 40
lawsuits against the Clinton administration and others seeking
evidence of alleged corruption, has opened its first satellite
office in the nation in a suburb of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   DEVELOPING NATIONAL STORIES THAT WILL MOVE BETWEEN 6 and 8 p.m.
ET
</P>
<P>
   HATE-RALLY (Washington) _ An extremist hate group is to hold a
demonstration in Washington on Saturday, and several
counter-demonstrations are planned. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   ARK-GORE-FUNDRAISER (Little Rock, Ark.) _ President Clinton is
with Vice President Al Gore for a fund-raiser Saturday evening. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-WOO-JACKSON (Chicago) _ Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley are wooing Jesse Jackson in Jackson's bailiwick.
First, Bradley showed up. Gore arrived on Saturday. By Dirk
Johnson. (EDS: This story may combine into ARK-GORE-FUNDRAISER.)
</P>
<P>
   OMAHA-REPUBS (Omaha, Neb.) _ A gaggle of second-tier Republican
presidential candidates are in Omaha for a Saturday political
shindig. Story will be full of their voices. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KIDS-MEDICAID (Washington) _ President Clinton will send
federal officials to all the states to investigate whether they
have improperly excluded people from Medicaid or from a new federal
health insurance program for children, White House officials said
Saturday. At the same time he will try to get schools across the
country to help arrange health coverage for millions of uninsured
children. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MOMS-MORTALITY (Washington) _ At a time when the Clinton
