<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-RANCH-ART-600(TR     08-07 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RANCH-ART-600(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EYES OF TEXAS ARE ON A RANCH BUSH WANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JIM YARDLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORD, Texas _ In any other year, the news that the governor
was shopping for a weekend getaway ranch would not have amounted to
much of a story. But when word leaked out that Gov. George W. Bush
was negotiating for a 1,550-acre spread in central Texas, it
prompted an obvious, if tantalizing, question:
</P>
<P>
   Where exactly does he plan to be getting away from?
</P>
<P>
   As the front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination,
Bush presumably envisions a commute from Washington. And even
though the first primary is months away, his real estate foray,
which first became news about six weeks ago, has already elicited
headlines of ``Little White House on the Prairie'' and evoked
comparisons to the ranch in Blanco County where President Lyndon B.
Johnson established his Texas White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself has remained silent about the ranch and is said to
be less than pleased that details have become public, especially
because the sale is not yet final. Friends have said that Bush and
his wife, Laura, simply want a retreat for their family where the
governor can indulge in his passion for bass fishing. But
presidential campaigns are as much about symbolism as substance,
and if he concludes the ranch deal Bush will have acquired a handy
piece of political imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have a specific property in mind for a specific
purpose, but the `ranch' has almost a mythical quality in Texas,''
said T.R. Fehrenbach, the San Antonio historian whose book ``Lone
Star'' is a highly respected account of Texas history. ``It goes
back to the frontier days. There is a mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Crawford, the closest town to the ranch, which lies 10
miles away on the western border of McLennan County, the unexpected
prospect of a governor in the county, much less a potential
president, has made for a pretty heady few weeks. Weekend ranching,
whether it entails 5 acres or 5,000, is a popular avocation and
status symbol for affluent city folks from Dallas, Houston and
Austin who still feel the pull of the land but have little interest
in pushing the plow.
</P>
<P>
   But McLennan County is not the most fashionable address. The
area is better known for the fatal siege that occurred six years
ago at the Branch Davidian complex east of the county seat of Waco.
Needless to say, the county welcomes the new attention.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal, it really is,'' said Chief Mike Gold of the
Crawford police. ``It's going to increase our tourism trade
immediately.'' Of course, Gold said that other than a park for
recreational vehicles, Crawford had no tourism trade. There is one
gas station, one coffee shop, a barber shop offering $3 haircuts,
no stoplights and not quite 700 people. The school district ranks
among the best in Texas, attracting a few dozen new residents in
recent years, but the town still does not have a fast-food
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   B.F. Engelbrecht, who has owned the ranch for 63 of his 82
years, said the deal had been scheduled to close on Monday but
could be delayed as final details are completed. Engelbrecht
declined to discuss the price of the ranch, but local real estate
agents have estimated $850 an acre. Last year, Bush earned $14.9
million from the sale of the Texas Rangers baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for the governor, confirmed that
Bush was interested in land in the area but offered no details,
except to hint at a possible announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have something to say about it soon,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Four months ago, Engelbrecht said, he and Bush began negotiating
for the 1,550-acre piece of property that is dominated by large
grazing pastures for cattle and the rusted remnants of buildings
that once housed chickens, turkeys and hogs. Engelbrecht said the
property had been up for sale for about four years. He and his
wife, Earlene, are moving closer to a hospital where she undergoes
regular treatment for kidney problems.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, Engelbrecht said, hired an engineer to insure that
a five-acre lake could be built for bass fishing. But Engelbrecht
said what most interested the governor and Mrs. Bush was the 200
acres of pristine canyons and woods that surround a stretch of
Rainey Creek, a tributary of the Middle Bosque River.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just liked the cliffs and the oak trees,'' Engelbrecht
said. ``That's where he wants to build his house.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Engelbrecht said he credited Mrs. Bush with cementing
the deal. ``She liked it more than he did. They looked at one in
Coryell County, but she liked this one. They just want a hideaway
place, especially if he gets to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   The property is sealed off from any public roads and accessible
only by a single entrance. Several local residents also have
remarked that the ranch is not only well located between Austin and
Dallas but also only about 20 miles from the Army base Fort Hood.
``It would be easy access in case he gets to be president,'' said
Celeste Mattlage, who lives a mile from the Engelbrechts.
``Diplomats could be flown in here and brought by helicopter.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, during the Johnson administration, Texans became
accustomed to dignitaries arriving at the 2,000-acre LBJ Ranch in
the hill country west of Austin. John T. Tiff, historian for the
Lyndon B. Johnson National Historical Park, which includes about
600 acres of the ranch as well as the Texas White House, said
Johnson enjoyed driving guests in his Lincoln convertibles to show
off the deer and the cattle. For Johnson, who always claimed that
the stars shined brighter in Texas, the ranch was a reminder of his
Hill Country boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiff said politics also played a role when Johnson bought
the ranch in 1951. With his national political ambitions rising,
Johnson wanted to change his political image and embrace the
frontier individualism embodied by the West. ``He had been
perceived as a Southern politician, and he wanted to change his
image,'' Tiff said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush already owns a house in East Texas at a fishing and hunting
camp, but with a ranch he joins a different caliber of Texans. A
few weeks ago, he unexpectedly stopped by a coffee shop in another
nearby town, McGregor, and pressed the flesh with his constituents
and possible future neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mattlage, for one, worries that Bush's presence might
disrupt the slow rhythm of a community where she says people do two
things: work and go to church. But she and her husband, Marvin,
were told by the Engelbrechts that governor and Mrs. Bush plan to
hold a get-to-know-you social on the ranch if the sale goes
through. The Mattlages plan to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like our quiet lifestyle,'' Mrs. Mattlage said. ``He's
really getting in a good community. Just so he'll be a good
neighbor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
