<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYRIA-PLO-RADICALS-AR     08-07 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-PLO-RADICALS-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE SYRIAN-ISRAELI PEACE THREATENS PALESTINIAN REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ They work from basement offices, with dim
fluorescent light. Faded posters and almanacs depict Fidel Castro,
Che Guevara and martyrs killed long ago, and these aging
Palestinian leaders, too, seem relics of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Once, George Habash and Nayef Hawatmeh were Palestinian
revolutionaries in deed as well as word, leading guerrilla warfare
against Israel from Jordan and Lebanon. One is remembered by some
as a hijacker, the other as a killer, though it has been more than
a decade since they and their groups suspended their armed
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they live in limbo, not wanted by Israel and wanting no
part of the peace sought by Yasser Arafat, the mainstream leader of
the Palestinian Authority. Damascus is their haven, as it has been
for years, and this city is home, too, to even more radical
Palestinians, like Ahmed Jibril, whose group has yet to unshoulder
its arms.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has played host with gusto, even though guests like Habash
and Hawatmeh have for many years remained largely out of Western
view. But the presence of such men now could prove a complication
to the rekindling of peace talk between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly, Syria's role as host served to tweak Arafat, who is
regarded by the leaders here as a traitor to the Arab cause for
making a separate peace. And by allowing the groups to operate in
Lebanon, where it is a dominant power, Syria has kept pressure on
the Israelis as well.
</P>
<P>
   But if Syria is to enter a new and determined peace effort with
Israel, what is to become of these radical Palestinian leaders now?
</P>
<P>
   ``According to one story, when one of the Palestinian leaders
asked the Syrians what he should do if peace comes, the answer was,
`Buy a farm,''' said a diplomat, conjuring up an image of one-time
terrorists in bucolic retirement.
</P>
<P>
   A desire to achieve peace with Israel in the months ahead would
present Syria with competing goals. It would almost certainly
require some reining in of the Palestinian groups, which could lead
to lifting of American economic sanctions on Syria.
</P>
<P>
   But limiting actions by the groups could also cause bad feelings
among exiled Palestinians, who include 700,000 refugees in Syria
and Lebanon _ particularly if a crackdown preceded a comprehensive
settlement between Israel and the Palestinians, which is to
determine the refugees' final status.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said one well-connected Syrian, ``I don't think many of
these guys are looking at a long-term active future in Damascus.''
</P>
<P>
   The radical Palestinian groups in Syria and Lebanon cover a wide
range. On the most radical extreme, perhaps, is Jibril's Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, whose forces
are involved in attacks against Israeli forces in southern Lebanon,
sometimes in conjunction with Syrian-backed Lebanese groups like
Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   The group's barracks in the southern suburbs of Beirut and in
the Bekaa region of Lebanon are regularly the target of Israeli air
raids.
</P>
<P>
   Hawatmeh's Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
which was an active fighting force from 1964 to 1987, is at the
other end of the spectrum. Now it is more of a social and political
body that opposes Arafat's Fatah faction and that operates openly
not only in Syria, Lebanon and Jordan, but also in Gaza and the
West Bank, where Arafat is leader of the limited self-rule
Palestinian government.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to terrorism, Syria has usually been deft in
trying to keep its hands just as clean as necessary. It does not
allow the radical Palestinians to carry out any operations from its
soil, and about the most radical statements that emerge from
Damascus are carried on Jibril's radio station, Al Quds.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is no evidence, the State Department has said, of
direct Syrian involvement in terrorist acts since 1986. At about
that time, under American pressure, the Syrians expelled the
notorious Abu Nidal. But the fact that Syria provides safe haven
and support to the most violent of the Palestinian rejectionists,
including Jibril's group and Islamic Jihad, is among the reasons
cited by the State Department for Syria's continuation on the
terrorism list.
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews here, Hawatmeh and Habash, who is the
leader of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, said
they were confident that their operations would continue without
interruption, even in the case of a Syrian-Israeli peace.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, Hawatmeh, a committed leftist who was born a
Greek Catholic in Salt, Jordan, led a Palestinian faction that lost
5,000 men in violence between 1965 and 1987, he said. Among the
acts for which he was labeled a terrorist by Israel was the 1974
takeover of a school in the Israeli town of Maalot by his
organization.
</P>
<P>
   In that hostage operation, more than 20 schoolchildren were
killed. Now Hawatmeh is 63, a slight man with a gentle demeanor who
sits beneath a tattered banner that traces the outlines of historic
Palestine and declares: ``God Bless Our Homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Habash, 72, was born in what is now Lod, Israel, to a Greek
Orthodox family, studied medicine, and went on to lead what became
the second-largest Palestinian group. He was an ardent Marxist
revolutionary and steadfast opponent of Israel's right to exist who
pioneered the tactic of airline hijackings in the late 1960s and
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   His most infamous act came in 1970, when his organization blew
up three airliners after parking them for a week in Jordan's
desert. ``When we hijack a plane it has more effect than if we
killed a hundred Israelis in battle,'' Habash once said. ``At least
the world is talking about us now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Today, Habash tires easily, his right side almost immobile from
a stroke suffered more than a decade ago. In 1992, France allowed
him to enter the country for medical treatment, but that turned
into a political scandal, with Jewish leaders and some French and
Israeli politicians calling for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The paths of the two men took them to Jordan, on to Lebanon, and
then, after the Israeli invasion of 1982 sent the Palestinians in
flight, on different tracks. Habash took refuge in Syria and
Hawatmeh went first to Algeria, where he stayed for nine years.
Their military operations stopped in 1987, when the Palestinian
focus shifted to the West Bank and Gaza, and the beginning of the
intifada, the uprising against the Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they run what are effectively political parties, both
strongly opposed to Arafat's pursuit of what they regard as a
deeply flawed peace. Their separate headquarters are near each
other, in a largely residential neighborhood, and their dingy
quarters with dated decor make it appear that time has all but
stood still.
</P>
<P>
   Hawatmeh suggested that the newer Palestinian groups that still
embrace violence, like Islamic Jihad, are more likely to face
Syrian restrictions. ``If there is a comprehensive peace between
Syria and Israel, I think the Syrians will say frankly to these
groups that they cannot continue military struggle,'' Hawatmeh
said.
</P>
<P>
   In subtle ways, it appears that that message is already being
sent, Western diplomats and well-connected Syrians say. After a
meeting last month between the Syrian vice president, Abdelhalim
Khaddam, and the leaders of some organizations, including Habash,
there were news reports that Khaddam had gone so far as to call on
the groups to halt armed activities in Lebanon now, in preparation
for a possible peace.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian authorities denied that, and Habash told a visitor that
he had heard no such instructions. In an interview, Syria's
information minister, Mohammed Salman, said that nothing about the
role played by the Palestinian groups in Syrian or Jordan had
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such measures would be a reward to Barak,'' Salman said,
referring to Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel. ``Why should
Syria reward Barak in spite of the fact that he has done nothing
yet to move the peace process forward?'' But Salman seemed to leave
the door open to future limits on the more militant Palestinian
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian groups that exist in Syria have the right to
exert political and informational activities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   People with knowledge of the talks said that some of the more
radical Palestinian groups in Damascus, including the one led by
Jibril, who is in his 60s, were working overtime to digest what
they had heard as a clear signal.
</P>
<P>
   Khaddam, these people said, had simply observed that a
Syrian-Israeli peace might come within a year, and either
implicitly or explicitly said there might be a need for the
Palestinians to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Damascus-based diplomats say it is unlikely that Syria would
expel members of the radical groups, even after a signed peace.
Such a step could tarnish Syria's claim that it, and not Arafat, is
the true defender of the Palestinian cause and of the right of the
refugees to return to their homeland. The diplomats say Syria would
be more likely to close some training camps and to enforce an order
for the fighters to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Radical leaders like Habash say they have no intention of
leaving Syria any time soon. Only if Arafat can somehow win a
promise that every Palestinian refugee will be allowed a right to
return, Habash said, will he shake hands with his rival and
conclude that the cause has been won.
</P>
<P>
   Hawatmeh, on the other hand, would like to visit the West Bank
and Gaza. He still disagrees deeply with Arafat, but at a time when
the Palestinians and Israel may be about to begin a final stage of
negotiations, it is his duty, he said, to make a personal appeal to
the Palestinian leader not to give up too much.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent past, Palestinians far more notorious than he,
including Mohammed Abbas, the mastermind of the 1985 hijacking of
the cruise ship Achille Lauro, have been able to win the necessary
permission from the Israelis to return. But despite three years of
trying, Hawatmeh said, he has been unable to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The awkwardness of his position was underscored in February,
when a quick handshake with Israel's president, Ezer Weizman, at
the funeral of King Hussein of Jordan, created an Israeli political
firestorm that may have added to his troubles. At the time,
Benjamin Netanyahu, then Israel's prime minister, acidly declared,
``Today he remains committed to the murder of the Jews.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
