<HEADER>
A9213 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KIDS-MEDICAID     08-07 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KIDS-MEDICAID-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FAULTS PROGRAM TO EXPAND HEALTH COVERAGE TO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mo., Neb., Ohio, S.C., Pa., Fla., Mass., R.I.)  (Eds: Note optional graf in 2nd take may be written through with
names of other three senators who signed letter to Shalala; also,
last graf contains phone number and Web site addresses for people
seeking information on health insurance for children.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will send federal officials to
all the states to investigate whether they have improperly excluded
people from Medicaid or from a new federal health insurance program
for children, White House officials said Saturday. At the same time
he will try to get schools across the country to help arrange
health coverage for millions of uninsured children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to announce the efforts on Sunday when he
addresses the 91st annual meeting of the National Governors'
Association in St. Louis. The steps reflect his disappointment at
the way some states have carried out the new health program for
children, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, the officials said, Clinton may take a more
confrontational approach than he usually does in discussions with
the governors, whose policy role he appreciates as a former
governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``States now have an unprecedented opportunity to expand health
coverage, and they should make the most of it,'' said Bruce Reed,
the president's chief domestic policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress created the Children's Health Insurance Program in
1997, it gave the states billions of dollars _ $24 billion over
five years, more than $39 billion over 10 years _ and considerable
flexibility in how the money may be used. In addition, White House
officials noted, states are getting billions more from the
settlement of lawsuits against tobacco companies, money that is
available for children's programs.
</P>
<P>
   But so far only 1.3 million children have been enrolled in the
new health program, the administration says. Clinton said recently
that he would have expected at least 3 million by now, and that he
was therefore ``a little disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also try to enlist the governors in his campaign
against tax and spending policies of the Republican Congress. He
will argue that the tax bill passed this week by Congress would not
only use up all the anticipated surpluses in the federal budget,
but also threaten federal-state programs like welfare, Medicaid,
education and social services, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Confidential White House documents show that Clinton will
instruct the Health Care Financing Administration to ``conduct
comprehensive on-site reviews of state Medicaid enrollment and
eligibility processes'' in all states. Federal officials will
interview state officials and check case files to ``assess
compliance with current laws and develop recommendations for
improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said a major purpose of this audit was ``to find out more
information about what's going on in each state.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a group of welfare recipients filed suit against
the state of Florida, contending that the state had illegally cut
off their Medicaid benefits when it ended their cash assistance. In
January, a federal district judge ruled that New York City had
improperly denied Medicaid to poor people who failed to comply with
work requirements of the city's welfare program. In Pennsylvania,
32,000 former welfare recipients won reinstatement of Medicaid only
after months of difficult negotiations with state officials.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, federal officials will highlight the best
practices developed by states like Nebraska, Ohio and South
Carolina to enroll eligible children in the new health insurance
program. Federal officials will also publicize the techniques used
by states to insure that people moving from welfare to work get
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, White House officials said, the Education Department
will send letters to 15,700 school superintendents and 27,000
elementary school principals, prodding them to help enroll children
in Medicaid and in the Children's Health Insurance Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``A staggering 11 million American children and teen-agers have
no health insurance,'' said Education Secretary Richard W. Riley on
a new Web site created especially to promote the Administration's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to school superintendents, Riley says more than 6
million of these children are eligible for Medicaid or the new
health program, but have not enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Uninsured children are more likely to suffer from asthma, ear
infections and vision problems _ ``treatable conditions that
interfere with classroom participation'' _ and they are absent more
often than their peers, Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Eligibility criteria for Medicaid and the new child health
program vary from state to state. Medicaid is intended for families
with somewhat lower incomes.
</P>
<P>
   White House documents show that the Clinton administration will
urge schools to take these steps to enroll children in the two
programs:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make enrollment part of the school registration process. Add a
question to school enrollment forms asking whether students have
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the school lunch application form to see if children are
eligible for subsidized health insurance and even to enroll them in
the health programs. ``Children who are eligible for free and
reduced-price school meals are usually eligible for free or
low-cost health insurance programs'' too, the Education Department
says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disseminate information on children's health insurance at
back-to-school nights, PTA meetings, sports events and school
plays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure all school employees, including teachers,
principals, school nurses, guidance counselors and coaches, know
about children's health insurance programs, so they can share the
information with students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also plans to criticize the states for
failing to submit required data on the number of children enrolled
in Medicaid and the new program. In the absence of such data,
federal officials cannot be sure if the programs are succeeding,
and Republicans in Congress are tempted to take back some of the
money earmarked for Medicaid and the children's health program.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting in St. Louis, the governors are expected to
adopt resolutions declaring that Congress should not reduce the
amount of money available to the states for the children's health
program, Medicaid or welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Seven senators deeply involved in creation of the new children's
health program sent a letter this week to Secretary of Health and
Human Services Donna Shalala lamenting ``the lack of reliable
data.'' They said they needed such data ``to evaluate whether we
have made overall progress in reducing the number of uninsured
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter also expressed concern that some states were using
money from the new program to cover children already eligible for
Medicaid, a practice forbidden by the 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
   States have a financial incentive to enroll children in the new
program, rather than in Medicaid, because the federal government
pays a larger share of the costs. Families often prefer the new
program because it carries less of a stigma than Medicaid, which is
widely but inaccurately viewed as something available only to
welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among the seven senators who signed the letter to Shalala were
William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee;
Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, the panel's senior Democrat;
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; John H. Chafee, R-R.I.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also prod the states to guarantee Medicaid coverage
for people who lose welfare benefits. Congress made $500 million
available to the states to help achieve this goal, but so far
states have spent only $39 million, the White House says.
Twenty-nine states will lose eligibility for the money at the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1996, people who received cash assistance were
automatically enrolled in Medicaid. But the 1996 welfare law
severed the link between the programs. Congress provided the $500
million because it assumed that states would incur new
administrative costs in evaluating eligibility for Medicaid and
welfare separately.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says states should use the money to ``conduct
aggressive outreach campaigns,'' to find people eligible for
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also challenge states to expand Medicaid
eligibility by taking advantage of several options authorized by
the 1996 welfare law. States can, for example, provide Medicaid for
many low-income families who no longer qualify for welfare.
</P>
<P>
   People seeking free or low-cost health insurance for children
can obtain information on a toll-free telephone number,
877-KIDS-NOW (877-543-7669) and on the Internet, at
www.insurekidsnow.gov. Another Web site is at www.ed.gov/chip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
