<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9217 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-REINVENT-REVI     08-07 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-REINVENT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AARP AND THE NEW OLD: THE RETIREMENT LOBBY GOES VA-VA-BOOM! 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) . 
 (bl)  
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First there was the name change. The American
Association of Retired Persons is no longer the American
Association of Retired Persons. It is AARP, and Horace Deets, its
executive director, insists that, ``It is no longer an acronym.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the gradual transformation of ``Modern
Maturity,'' the AARP's magazine. A year ago, the cover featured
Betty White, 77, looking lovely but also, well, mature. The
headline was, ``Betty White, on Life, Loss and Laughter.'' This
month, the cover features Susan Sarandon, 52, looking like she
belongs in an issue that is, in fact, headlined, ``Great Sex _
What's Age Got to Do With It?''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of sex, the AARP (note to copy editors: this is no
longer an acronym) released a survey last week focusing on the
sexual satisfaction of Americans 45 and up. Before the news
conference began, the nation's largest senior citizens' group
played cuts from James Brown (``I Feel Good'') and Gladys Knight
and the Pips (``You're the Best Thing That Ever Happened to Me'')
stirring up latent memories of college mixers among the assembled
reporters, who proceeded to ask a flurry of questions about
frequency and potency.
</P>
<P>
   AARP officials made much of the fact that over-45 boomers were
still having sex and, by and large, would continue to have sex for
many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Its officials make no secret of it: The AARP is trying to
retrofit itself for the baby boomers, the next great wave of the
aged, who began turning 50 three years ago and thus became eligible
for that fraught rite of passage, membership in the AARP.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the lobbying giant say they have no intention of
short-changing older members, who have more traditional
expectations of retirement and what they want from a senior
citizens' organization. (``We're not just showing people on the
cover who are 51 and 52 years old,'' said Martha Ramsey, publishing
director for the group.)
</P>
<P>
   But the boomers, those born from 1946 through 1964, are headed
inexorably through the life cycle, and the mighty AARP's struggle
to adjust says a lot about how they will remake paradigms of aging
and retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get the benefit or the burden, whichever way you see it, of
all the ambivalent feelings people have about aging,'' said John
Rother, the organization's chief lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the cultural collision between the boomers and what
Modern Maturity cheerfully calls the ``Big Five-Oh'' has launched a
thousand newspaper columns, essays, bad birthday greetings and
late-night monologues, including Jay Leno's ceremonial enrollment
of Mick Jagger, 56, into the AARP two weeks ago. (Leno produced a
mock version of Modern Maturity with Jagger on the cover, with
headlines like, ``From Rolling Stones to Kidney Stones'' and
``Can't Get No Satisfaction? Try Bran Muffins.'')
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is some evidence that the boomers are simply
denying the passage of time. A recent poll found that while the
median age of the boomers is now 42, the typical boomer says he or
she feels about 35.
</P>
<P>
   But polling done for the AARP and others suggests that boomers
are, in fact, beginning to think about their golden years _ and in
a very distinctive way. To begin with, lest you wonder why the AARP
moved away from the word ``retired,'' 80 percent of the boomers say
they expect to continue working during ``retirement,'' either part
time, full time in a new career or by going into business for
themselves, according to a 1998 poll by Roper Starch Worldwide for
the AARP. And more than a third say they will be doing that
primarily for ``interest and enjoyment.'' (Even now, 40 percent of
AARP's members are still working.)
</P>
<P>
   Only a fifth of the boomers expect to move to a new geographic
area when they retire _ in contrast with the previous generation's
dream of a mass exodus to Florida _ and only a third think they
will have to scale back their lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Big majorities say they expect to live longer than their
parents' generation, and that awareness makes a difference, said
Dr. James Birren, associate director of the UCLA Center on Aging.
``Boomers are thinking more about how they want to invest all those
years of the future as opposed to getting through them,'' he said.
Many of the previous generation, he added, simply did not
anticipate living as long as they have.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Peter Hart agreed that while boomers might expect to
live 25 years after retirement, the previous generation probably
anticipated five to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Dychtwald, the president of Age Wave, a research
organization and business focused on the ``mature market,'' argues
that boomers will live a ``cyclical lifestyle'' _ ``going back to
school, having multiple careers, retiring, rehiring.'' He added,
``They will not accept old age at all.'' Previous generations, the
49-year-old Dychtwald said, lived ``linear lives'' _ from work to
rest to death.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Delehanty, the 50-year-old new editor of Modern Maturity,
said he senses a hunger among the boomers for a ``new paradigm for
life after 50,'' a way of thinking about the next career or the
next work life. Delehanty, who once edited the Utne Reader, a
leftist, boomer-oriented digest of the alternative press, said he
plans a future issue of Modern Maturity on ``How to Reinvent Your
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Boomers are also more health and fitness conscious, analysts
say. And, not surprisingly, they tend to be more anti-authority,
more skeptical of government, more interested in ``empowerment''
and ``choice.'' As Deets puts it: ``They want to make their own
decisions. They don't want to be told what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
