<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9225 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-GUNS-REVIEW-N     08-07 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-GUNS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA AND GUNS: ARMED AND FASHIONABLE IN JOHANNESBURG 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Not long ago, outside the
razor-wire-topped fence around our house here, I drove past a man
in street clothes with a large pistol tucked in the leather holster
at his waist. After a second, I decided he must be a security
guard. But I looked at that gun and scoffed. What was he going to
do with such a puny gun, and holstered besides? Up the street was a
guard pacing a driveway with a pump-action shotgun. Now that might
do some good.
</P>
<P>
   I went about my business.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be me? Four years ago, when I lived on the Upper West
Side of Manhattan, the sight of a civilian with a gun on my block
would have left me slightly out of breath. I would have hustled my
kids inside, asked the doorman who that guy was and probably called
the police. At least I would make sure he was a licensed, trained
guard.
</P>
<P>
   But guns are everywhere in Africa, a legacy of conflict and a
result of lax gun control. Here the special line for checking guns
at the airport is often as long as the one to go through the metal
detector. There are gun stores in South Africa's fanciest malls,
within spitting distance of Godiva chocolates and Fendi handbags.
Of course, these are designer gun shops, where the rich buy slick,
showy little guns hoping to protect themselves from a crime rate
that is among the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the upscale stuff. Police and army roadblocks are
standard practice all over the continent, manned by young men with
huge automatic weapons dangling carelessly from their shoulders. In
South Africa, you might be asked for a bribe. In some other
countries, the roadblocks are often an encounter with hungry,
drunken youths itching to show their authority.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving here four years ago, I have learned to distinguish
an AK-47 from a South African R-4 or an R-5 from an Uzi _ though
this skill isn't much use. They can all kill you. Still, the
learning process is a little like getting to know the kinds of
trees and birds that are native here.
</P>
<P>
   I even know enough to laugh at the swaggering revolutionaries on
the Comoros Islands who taped three ammunition magazines together:
The move might look Rambo-ish, but it's pretty useless. Tape two
banana clips together and you save time loading. Three doesn't
work: You'll be tangled up in tape for half an hour. Yes, this is
me talking. The lady in the designer jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I arrived late at night at my hotel in Angola I
thought I was done for when two figures moved out of the shadows
with machine guns. Now I know they are the doormen, and I don't
like getting out of the car until I see the glint of their
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most unlikely South Africans carry guns. Early on, we
were invited to dinner by a couple _ both television producers.
They were smart and funny and we had journalism in common. You
might have met them on the Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   But then, as it often does here, the subject turned to crime.
The husband started talking about caliber, ammunition and, with
some modesty, of course, what a good shot he was.
</P>
<P>
   Could he be serious? He was. He favored ankle holsters. He
 &UR; always &LR;  carried a gun.
</P>
<P>
   More shocking still was the day we discovered that a woman my
husband drools over _ a woman who might actually have Barbie Doll
proportions _ drove around town with a little gun in her lap. She
was the mother of my youngest daughter's best friend. My daughter
was in that car a lot _ and had never been told to put on her seat
belt.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many guns here that cops even have to watch out for
the good guys. When I did a story about drug-trafficking in South
Africa, a group of undercover police officers told me the story of
how they tried to arrest one of the big bosses behind the street
sales. They lured him out of his mansion to make an exchange on the
street. But when a grungy looking undercover officer pulled his gun
out to arrest the man, more than a half dozen well-meaning citizens
misunderstood the situation. They saw only a white man in a
Mercedes being held up at gunpoint. Soon, the police officer was
begging for his life.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is now considering broad new anti-gun legislation
that would make all gun owners apply for new licenses, prove their
need to be armed and take a mental health test. Gun owners are
furious. Whether the law could be enforced is a question. After
all, the current laws already are pretty tough, and widely
circumvented. To buy a gun, you have to pass a police check which
can take months. But generally, the police are inept and corruption
is rampant. One of the biggest gangsters in Cape Town was recently
found to have a legitimate license for his gun.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter what South Africa's laws, there will always be
easy access to guns _ big guns _ nearby. Mozambique is awash with
weapons, left over from its long civil war. Even civilians were
armed by the various factions, and by some estimates there are
still enough AK-47s around to arm every man, woman and child in
that country.
</P>
<P>
   At night in our lush suburb with a pool in every yard, the pop
of gun fire can be heard regularly. But it usually takes a visitor
to remind me. Like the screeches of the ibises that peck the thatch
from our roof, I don't even hear them anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I do still draw the line at having a gun in my own household.
While I was away once, my husband _ who now brags that he outshot
everyone on a game-ranger course _ got into the game in a small
way. He bought a BB gun and swore our two girls to secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   But he forgot to clean up the packaging. Was there a gun to go
with the box, I asked the girls? They laughed. Oh yes, Dad had
showed them how to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   In a fury, I found the BB gun and buried it deep behind some
bushes in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Really, if we are going to do this, we need a better gun than
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
