<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MYSTICISM-REV     08-07 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MYSTICISM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S ECCENTRICS: THE STIFF UPPER LIP QUIVERS BEFORE AN
ECLIPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ When an eclipse brings night at mid-morning on
Wednesday in Cornwall, a county in southwestern England, there will
be a clear, predictable scientific explanation: The moon will
interpose itself between the Earth and the sun and a shadow will
fall on land for precisely two minutes and six seconds. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   The full solar eclipse will be the first seen from Britain in 72
years and the last one of the millennium. But with little regard
for the obvious explanation, pagans, druids, doomsayers and New Age
travelers are anxiously awaiting the approach of the eclipse and
translating its portents in many ways, seeing divine felicity, the
end of the world _ anything except celestial science.
</P>
<P>
   And that says something about a nation whose John Bull
stereotype of proud pragmaticism seems challenged by this strain of
mysticism questing for alternative meanings. It is as if within the
soul of every bulldog Briton there lurked a secret doppelganger,
mistrustful of the scientifically obvious and craving mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Duality, of course, has always been an object of fascination
here: consider Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde or Dorian Gray, both
presenting one visage to the world while another corrodes from
within. And the rejection of science's road map for the universe
yields a seam of alternative thinking, from the Luddites who
protested the mechanization of the Industrial Revolution in the
early 19th century, to the activists who, three times in the past
couple of months, have torn up experimental crops to protest the
genetic modification of the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   While Americans cheerfully embrace the fruits of scientific
advance as the harbingers of future wealth and well-being _ from
bug-free soya to Internet stocks _ it could be argued that some
people in this much older nation with its great imperial history
look backward for their coordinates. In Cornwall this week, that
means a long, long way back _ back to the times when the Earth's
unlocked mysteries were an explanation in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eclipse is the big event, the end of an era,'' said Andy
Norfolk, a member of the pagan Cornish Earth Mysteries Group. ``We
find divinity in the natural world. The sun and moon are very
important. There is a great power when they come together like
this.'' Pagan worshipers plan a sun dance to ward off what the
science of meteorology says is a 50 percent chance of cloudiness on
the fateful day.
</P>
<P>
   And if that seems implausible, just consider the omens.
</P>
<P>
   The eclipse is set to begin at 11 minutes past 11 o'clock on the
11th day of the month. Coincidence? Or necromancer's compass
bearings? Plenty of people prefer the latter explanation. Take the
Cornish Eclipse Stone Festival, for instance, which runs one whole
week around the eclipse and is billed as ``a celebration of bikes,
blues, stones and druids.'' Or the Moonshadow Rising, a three-week
assembly of New Age travelers, who are Britain's anarchic, nomadic
successors to the hippie travelers of the 1960s; they are expected
to join the 1 million converging on the county.
</P>
<P>
   This wild blossoming of mysticism is probably because the
70-mile-wide track of ``totality,'' as the complete blotting out of
the sun is known, will cross a county readily linked with the
supernatural. ``There's a mystical strain in every country and
eclipses are likely to bring that out,'' said Richard Dawkins,
professor of the Public Understanding of Science at Oxford
University. ``But Cornwall has a certain association with pixies,
fairies and standing stones and so it's fairly normal for people to
gravitate towards Cornwall.''
</P>
<P>
   But the last total eclipse in Britain, in 1927, was over the
bleak Yorkshire moors, which are not especially known for
mysticism, and it inspired the same awe and hype: Special trains
were scheduled, then as now, thousands converged on the track of
totality, including, most famously, Virginia Woolf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had very strongly the feeling as the light went out of some
vast obeisance; something kneeling down and suddenly raised up when
the colors came,'' she wrote in her diary. When the sun re-emerged,
she said, ``It was like recovery . . . We had seen the world
dead.'' Even hard-nosed newspapermen grew mystical. The London's
Daily Mail reported: ``It was just as if the light of the sun had
been extinguished for ever and the end of the world was at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Awe seems an appropriate emotion. ``It will be right to be awed
by the eclipse, and to draw on ideas from religion, myth and
literature,'' said John Casey, an academic at Cambridge University.
``It will be much healthier than all the Nostradamus and New Age
noodledom that has afflicted us with the approach of the third
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   But Britain's alternative strain is not driven simply by awe.
Environmental protesters routinely barricade themselves in trees or
caves to prevent the building of new highways and airports. In
June, druids converging on Stonehenge found their celebration of
the summer solstice disrupted by New Age travelers and anarchists
protesting the introduction of entrance fees to the site.
</P>
<P>
   The same month, anarchists who had promised only a day of street
carnivals in London's financial district instead trashed investment
banks and exchanges, baited, it was reported, by hot-shot
derivatives traders taunting them by waving gold credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   The same people have printed fliers advertising similar action
this week, calling for an ``anarchy jamboree'' in the Cornish town
of Penzance, targeting such disparate icons of capitalism as
McDonald's and organized rock concerts. ``Pay for absolutely
nothing. Help yourselves from corporate retailers,'' the leaflets
say, calling for a so-called dance-a-thon with ``lots of happy
people smashing up all the cars via the medium of dance.'' Mammon
is not the only target.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the outcry against genetically modified crops _ and the
readiness of protesters to risk arrest by uprooting them _ that the
authorities have decided to keep their location secret in future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly a lot of Ludditism and you see it in all the
hysteria about every scientific story,'' said Dawkins.
</P>
<P>
   This being Britain, though, John Bull's dogged pragmatism can be
expected to stand four square against such distractions, fusing
Britain's sundered soul into one single motif: profit. For
instance, two British Airways Concorde airliners flying in
formation 10 miles up and at 1,350 miles per hour will pursue the
track of totality as it speeds across the Atlantic, enabling
eclipse junkies to keep the darkened sun in sight for six minutes
instead of the terrestrial two _ blending science and superstition,
the supernatural and the supersonic, at a mere $2,500 a head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
