<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SHELTER-ART-60     08-07 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SHELTER-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO IS NOW LOSING WAR AGAINST WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VRAGOLIJA, Yugoslavia _ Under a bright red Albanian flag, with
its double-headed black eagle, Ali Sllamniku, two of his brothers
and a neighbor were scrambling to put up a roof on the burned-out
shell of their two-room house.
</P>
<P>
   They were expelled by the Serbs from this little village near
Pristina on March 9, and for six weeks now the 10 members of the
Sllamniku family have been living in a tent they brought back with
them from a refugee camp in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The family's possessions are gone, stolen or burned; they have
no furniture of any kind, just a few filthy cushions and some
plastic dishes and cheap utensils.
</P>
<P>
   But with the first chills of Kosovo's long and miserable winter
just two months away, Sllamniku has given up on his expectations
for reconstruction help from the Western powers that drove the
Serbs out of Kosovo. Borrowing from friends, he has scraped
together the $2,300 he needed to buy the timber and roof tiles to
give the family a modicum of shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell the Serbs! The Albanians are building again!'' his
brother, Hashim, shouted, picking up a corner of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   But not enough of them are, and not quickly enough, because the
money and the materials and the promised aid are simply not here.
</P>
<P>
   The rough estimate now is that there are 300,000 to 400,000
people in Kosovo ``who don't have habitable homes for the winter,''
said Dennis McNamara, the regional head of the U.N. refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unlikely that many Albanians will freeze to death,
the United Nations is unlikely to meet its goal of having at least
one warm, dry room for every Albanian family, officials now admit.
A recent internal U.N. report said, ``It is in shelter that the
humanitarian community faces its greatest challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   So aid officials are scrambling to come up with solutions, like
more winterized tents and finding host families and rehabilitating
existing buildings for collective housing, euphemistically called
transit centers, where the most vulnerable people can live until
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real race now with the winter,'' said Dan Philpott,
the field manager in Pec for Goal, an Irish aid agency working on
housing and school rehabilitation under contract for the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The nations that banded together to fight this war for the
Albanians of Kosovo are entwined in all the usual and inevitable
problems of bureaucracy, rivalry, staffing, funding, logistics and
politics. Then there is the sheer August indolence of home capitals
and factories, especially in Europe, when most officials and
workers are on vacation and professional administrators and civil
servants do not take on new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency shelter kits of plastic, window frames and tools,
promised and designed early on, are now not only thought to be
inadequate but are also very slow to arrive. Orders for timber are
going through tenders, even before contracts are signed and orders
compiled or delivered through the logistical nightmare of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Pec, the city with the most damaged or destroyed housing in
Kosovo, and the surrounding towns of Istok and Klina, only the U.N.
refugee agency has begun any emergency housing rehabilitation. The
Americans are still signing letters of intent with their aid agency
and the Europeans, one local official said, ``haven't done anything
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Philpott, of Goal, said: ``The Albanians are adaptable and have
a marvelous spirit. But I don't think the penny has dropped with
the international decision-makers about what we will face in the
winter.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And reality, as usual, has altered the best-intentioned plans.
</P>
<P>
   The quick end to the war surprised many officials and aid
workers, who were thinking about how to get the refugees through
the winter in the camps across the border. The fervent desire of
the Albanians to return to Kosovo as fast as possible also seemed
to surprise the Westerners, whose admonitions to remain in the
camps were completely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   More than 740,000 Albanians poured back by the end of July,
straining every unvandalized or unbombed resource, from water to
electricity to telephones.
</P>
<P>
   And extensive surveys of buildings and housing in Kosovo,
completed only at the end of July, showed considerably more damage
than had been estimated.
</P>
<P>
   There was less damage than expected to bridges and roads, but
more to houses and other shelter, said McNamara, who is also in
charge of humanitarian assistance for the United Nations here under
the chief administrator for Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a massive movement of population,'' he said. ``We
have a massive challenge ahead of us, and we're talking about two
months, just 60 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed severe damage to 67,326 buildings, most of
them houses, compared to an estimate of 28,346 made in December
1998, after a harsh summer offensive by the Serbs but before the
three-month bombing war that began in March. A European Union
survey of 1,383 villages found damage to 120,000 homes, with 78,000
severely damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In the villages, some of them 3,000 feet above sea level and
very cold, fewer than 25 percent of houses are not damaged, while
nearly 40 percent are considered destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the U.N. refugee agency, through its aid contractors,
has distributed partial shelter kits, largely consisting of thick
roofing plastic, to only 3,600 families. James Kovar, head of the
agency's field office in Pec, says that deliveries from the
contractors have been ``very slow.'' At least 40,000 more such kits
are expected from the United States and the European Union, but no
one knows when.
</P>
<P>
   Given the amounts of money involved, Kovar said, Washington and
Brussels insisted on designing and controlling their own housing
rehabilitation projects, separate from the U.N. refugee agency,
though supposedly coordinated through it.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has ordered at least 15,000 winterized tents with an
adapted stove inside, and 30,000 wood-burning stoves to deliver to
villages. But given the paucity of good roads and available trucks,
the likely time span between orders and delivery is worrying
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Matters were made worse by problems with customs and duties at
the Macedonian border, just resolved Friday, after the Macedonians
gave up their demand for a $350 ``inspection fee'' for all trucks
and rail cars carrying assistance.
</P>
<P>
   So in the Pec area, where between 200,000 and 250,000 people are
now living, Kovar said, ``there is bound to be a gap.'' He is
planning, he says, to secure emergency collective housing for
between 1,000 and 2,000 people. But Philpott of Goal thinks at
least 5,000 people in the Pec area will need such shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Kovar, who arrived in Pec in late June, is pushing hard. He is
working to get more and better shelter kits; to find some timber
and roof tiles; to identify buildings that could be used for
collective housing, and to persuade the commanders of the
peacekeeping troops here to use some of their abundant transport
equipment to deliver relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
   One idea being discussed is for the peacekeepers to set up
guarded municipal or regional distribution centers for building
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO-led peacekeeping force here is largely willing to help,
even with some emergency rehabilitation, say McNamara and Kovar,
although the military also has its own logistical and security
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Albanians, there is disappointment. They had expected
the West to provide timber and the region's ubiquitous red clay
roof tiles so they could do the work themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not in the plans for Kosovo's emergency
rehabilitation. Distribution of such supplies will apparently wait
for a larger reconstruction project that will be handled by the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruins of downtown Pec, Hajri Gjota, 71, watched some
workers as they put something like a roof over the first floor of
what had been his relatively lavish two-story house.
</P>
<P>
   On March 28, four days after NATO's bombing began, masked Serb
irregulars put a gun in his mouth and gave him five minutes to
leave the house, refusing to allow him to get shoes or a jacket.
``I was that evening in the mountains with nothing,'' he said
simply. ``I worked 50 years for this house.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned here only three weeks ago to find this ruin, and
Albanians in similar circumstances have moved into any available
and now vacant Serb apartment. ``Morally, I couldn't do that
anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of all this, I want at least one room,'' he said. He is
spending about $8,800, most of which comes from relatives abroad,
to repair walls, put up a roof, install windows, and buy a stove
and some furniture.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts to find some aid have been fruitless, he said
bitterly. ``These foreign workers sit in cafes and people line up
to see them, to try to get their names on a list,'' he said, but
could not identify their agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gjota knows he is lucky _ lucky to be alive, to have help from
relatives, to be able to pay others to put up a roof. But other
Albanians are not so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their houses are burned, too,'' he said, gesturing to the
workers slick with sweat in the unforgiving sun. ``Who will help
them? They're earning money to get bread and shelter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
