``They will not accept old age at all.'' Previous generations, the
49-year-old Dychtwald said, lived ``linear lives'' _ from work to
rest to death.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Delehanty, the 50-year-old new editor of Modern Maturity,
said he senses a hunger among the boomers for a ``new paradigm for
life after 50,'' a way of thinking about the next career or the
next work life. Delehanty, who once edited the Utne Reader, a
leftist, boomer-oriented digest of the alternative press, said he
plans a future issue of Modern Maturity on ``How to Reinvent Your
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Boomers are also more health and fitness conscious, analysts
say. And, not surprisingly, they tend to be more anti-authority,
more skeptical of government, more interested in ``empowerment''
and ``choice.'' As Deets puts it: ``They want to make their own
decisions. They don't want to be told what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What does all this mean for the 41-year-old AARP, which claims
more than 30 million members? Officials say they are doing a lot of
strategic planning these days, and a lot of research on the
diversity of the boomer generation.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, long known for its insurance products as well
as its formidable defense of Social Security and Medicare on
Capitol Hill, recently spun off a subsidiary to explore new
services and products for the over-50 population. And its magazine,
which has long published different versions for the working and
retired set (the sex report appeared in both), may be doing more
such demographically zoned editions in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Dychtwald, a critic of the AARP, asserts that the senior group
will have a hard time serving both the old old and the new old.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is worried about fixed incomes and entitlements, the other
is worried about paying for their kids' education and elder care
and mutual funds,'' he said. ``Can AARP maintain their relationship
with their core constituency, who are likely to be retired
grandparents with a lot of free time, who are very respectful of
government, while simultaneously trying to be irreverent,
anti-authority, hip and modern?''
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic pollster Mark Mellman argues that the boomers
will be traditionalists in one respect: their support for those New
Deal-Great Society entitlement programs. ``They are pro-Medicare
and pro-Social Security, for themselves and for their parents,''
Mellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Celinda Lake, another Democratic pollster, said the 50-to-64 age
group is ``more adamant'' about strengthening and protecting those
programs than any other.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying question, of course, is how much old age will
change the boomers, and how much the boomers will change old age.
Meanwhile, time stops for no generation. Welcomed into ``The Big
Five-Oh'' club in the latest issue of Modern Maturity were Annie
Leibovitz, Twiggy and, the headliner of this summer's big rock
tour, Bruce Springsteen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
