<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLFLEET-PSYCH-RETRE     08-07 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLFLEET-PSYCH-RETREAT-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE PSYCHS' OF AUGUST ARE BACK ON CAPE COD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLFLEET, Mass. _ Banish any image of a Shrinkland where the
streets are peopled by bearded, strategically taciturn men and
motherly but penetrating women all asking each other, ``And how did
that make you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   This is not even close. It is just one more quaint Cape Cod town
swamped by vacationers of all ilks in summer, one with pleasant
sandy surroundings and a reputation for attracting intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Boston and New York analysts who still perform the
traditional August abandonment ritual migrate out to all sorts of
places to enjoy the sunny hours that last longer than 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But enough of them do come here, and have for decades, that they
are a felt presence in Wellfleet and in neighboring Truro; a big
and active enough presence that some of the recent change in the
psychotherapy world is reflected in the evolution of their summer
chat and study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call them `the psychs,' and in August we say, `The psychs
are here,''' said Elden Gray, 86, a retired grocer from near Boston
who has summered here for 50 years. ``This town is known for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So solid is the area's reputation as a psychiatric summer
retreat that Harry Castleman, a marketing manager from Needham on
vacation here, remarked, ``I've always heard that if you need a
psychiatrist in August, the only place to find one is in
Wellfleet.''
</P>
<P>
   When Paul Buttenwieser, a psychoanalyst in Cambridge, wrote a
comic novel called ``Free Association'' in 1981, he placed the
chapter ``Where Do Analysts Go in August?'' in and around
Wellfleet, and described a scene of ``beached porpoises'' who could
not stop their earnest discussions even on the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Upon close examination, the Wellfleet area seems to have two
psychiatric traditions: the old, begun in the decades around World
War II, when informal groups of psychoanalysts gathered for long
stretches, creating casual traditions whose remnants last to this
day; and the new, a more formalized set of seminars, each usually
lasting a week, that funnels several thousand mental-health
professionals through the area each summer.
</P>
<P>
   The old tradition, said Dr. Robert Michels, a professor of
psychiatry at Cornell University, apparently arose because European
psychoanalysts, including Freud himself, used to go away for weeks
in summer to healthful climes and often take their patients with
them.
</P>
<P>
   When many moved to the United States, they continued that habit
here, Michels' psychoanalysis teachers told him. They were drawn to
the tip of Cape Cod, it seems, for its natural beauty, its quiet
and the stimulation of the artists' colony in Provincetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``And because in the analytic world, analysts get analyzed, you
start having extended family cultures,'' Michels said. ``An elderly
analyst, their middle-aged analysands, and their analysands who are
younger still. And people established patterns that would continue
after their analyses were over.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, few active therapists take vacations of several weeks.
Also, the numbers of European-born analysts have dwindled. But the
remnants and new versions of that tradition continue: houses bought
and passed down, family habits, groups of friends, some of them
therapists, who travel here together year after year.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the most visible signs of ``psych'' presence are at
schools and hotels, where psychiatrists, psychologists, social
workers and others mass for edifying, tax-deductible weeks of study
_ with a whale-watch or two thrown in.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Gilbert Levin, a professor of psychiatry at Albert Einstein
College of Medicine, founded the Cape Cod Institute 20 years ago,
and it puts about 1,300 mental-health professionals through courses
each summer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A similar group, the New England Educational Institute, serves
about 2,000, said its founder, Dr. Robert Guerette. Harvard Medical
School also offers courses here, Guerette said, as does the
Massachusetts Mental Health Center. Last week the Boston Graduate
School of Psychoanalysis ran seminars with intriguing titles such
as ``Is Sex Just Sex?'' and ``Is Love Necessary?''
</P>
<P>
   And there are others, like the seminar that Dr. Robert Jay
Lifton, professor of psychiatry at John Jay College and the City
University of New York, holds each year on psychology and history
for a few colleagues. Erik Erikson, the originator of the concept
``identity crisis,'' who died in 1994, used to attend that one.
</P>
<P>
   But here is the part about change. The courses at the two big
institutes have shifted their orientation somewhat in recent years.
If they once focused mainly on the psychology of individuals and
clinical therapy, now, with many psychologists chafing under the
strictures of managed care, they have branched more into areas like
organizational management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patient or client is a system rather than an individual,''
Levin said. ``Now, many people trained in the psychodynamic
tradition are looking to enter that venue.'' Hence institute
courses like this year's ``Creating Great Groups,'' about
team-building and creativity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the hobnobbing among participants, Guerette said, he has
noticed a rise in discussion of bread-and-butter issues as
therapists struggle with managed care. There is also, he and others
said, excited discussion about the potential of quicker,
post-Freudian methods.
</P>
<P>
   For all the summer seminars, however, Lifton objected to ``the
mythology of a shrink gathering here,'' saying that Wellfleet had
long been summer home to all kinds of people; that there was no
great organized social ``shrink scene.''
</P>
<P>
   His words are borne out in an essay by Alfred Kazin in his book
``Summer'' (Addison-Wesley, 1990). Kazin describes a scintillating
mix of beachside literati in the 1950s and '60s that included
Edmund Wilson and Mary McCarthy. The historian Arthur Schlesinger
might stroll by, or the polemicist Dwight Macdonald. One wit called
the place ``the beach of the intellectuals,'' Kazin wrote.
</P>
<P>
   To longtime residents like Gray, nearly all fit under the
``psych'' heading, and share telltale characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just go down the street and try to pass on the sidewalk _ they
block the sidewalk with their conversations!'' Gray said, more
amused than annoyed. ``They stand there and yak away and pat each
other on the back, and most all of them have chin whiskers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
