<HEADER>
A9262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-CHRONICLE-REACT-66     08-07 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-CHRONICLE-REACT-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF PAPER STIRS A MUTED SADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Chronicle once embarked on a
long editorial crusade on what it saw as a pressing issue _
improving the coffee served in restaurants. ``A Great City's People
Forced to Drink Swill,'' proclaimed one headline.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some San Franciscans have made a similar
observation about their newspapers, wondering why the people of
this wealthy, well-educated city were forced to read fluff.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, The Chronicle's combination of provincialism and
frivolity _ as embodied by the coffee campaign in 1963 and the more
than 50 years' of columns by the late Herb Caen _ seemed to match
the city's psyche and earned the paper a certain affection.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with some sadness that San Franciscans greeted the
news on Friday that The Chronicle, owned by the same family for 134
years, is being sold to Hearst Corp., publisher of the rival San
Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the end of an era,'' said Ed Moose, the proprietor of
Moose's, a bar and grill frequented by newspaper people. ``This is
a paper with a real history,'' he said, adding that Chronicle
columnists ``spoke for the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly which era is over, however, is not clear. The Chronicle,
a morning paper with a circulation of 482,000, will survive,
although under Hearst management it will probably change.
</P>
<P>
   It is The Examiner, with an equally rich history dating from the
days of the newspaper baron William Randolph Hearst, that is most
in danger. An afternoon paper with a circulation of only 114,000,
The Examiner is being put up for sale, but analysts think no one
will buy it.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, it will be combined with The Chronicle, ending a
newspaper battle that has lasted more than a century and adding San
Francisco to the growing list of cities with only one daily
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say you're shocked, but when it finally happens
it's sad,'' said Susan Rasky, an acting associate professor of
journalism at the University of California at Berkeley. ``It's like
an old friend died.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the trendy North Beach neighborhood, where the coffee
now draws few complaints, many people interviewed on Friday night
did not seem to care that one point of view might be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Although their news staffs compete vigorously, the two papers
have shared revenues and have published a combined Sunday edition
since 1965 under a joint operating agreement, contributing to the
impression here that the papers are not really distinct, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a one-paper town already _ it doesn't matter that
much,'' said Richard Levine, a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Elijah Curtis, a bicycle messenger, agreed. ``It's hard for me
to tell the difference between the two,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the papers have differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Examiner folks are more two-fisted, blue-collar, `We go
out and get the story,''' said Moose, the restaurant owner. ``The
Chronicle is more cerebral, slightly more sophisticated and more
eccentric.''
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner also focuses more closely on city, as opposed to
regional, news, and is more liberal editorially.
</P>
<P>
   Some said that with television, the Internet and national
newspapers like The New York Times and USA Today, there is no
shortage of news sources. San Francisco also has spirited
alternative newspapers like the Bay Guardian and SF Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the alternative weeklies anyway, so it doesn't matter
to me,'' Jeff Stewart, a department-store salesman, said of The
Chronicle purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Casper, a lawyer who is chairman of the San Francisco
Republican Party, said he worried that The Examiner's editorial
policy, which he called ``ultra PC knee-jerk left,'' will now be
transferred to the more conservative Chronicle. This is a
distinctly minority worry in this overwhelmingly Democratic city.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, he was not worried about the loss of either
newspaper. ``A newspaper no longer defines a city,'' Casper said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To some extent, the big newspaper competition here in recent
years has not been between The Chronicle and The Examiner, anyway.
It has been between The Chronicle and Knight Ridder, which owns The
San Jose Mercury News to the south of San Francisco and a string of
smaller papers to the east.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bay Area's growth in recent years coming from the
suburbs and not San Francisco itself, The Chronicle has been trying
to transform itself into a regional paper, with zoned local
editions. It has beefed up its coverage of technology and business.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, both The Chronicle and The Examiner, which in
the days when it was published by Hearst was known for its ``yellow
journalism,'' have become far more serious newspapers that no
longer seem to deserve their old reputations.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle was started in 1865 by two teen-age brothers,
Charles and Michael de Young, as The Daily Dramatic Chronicle.
Their descendants, who now own the paper, have fought among
themselves, helping lead to the decision to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner was taken over by Hearst, the model for the main
character in the movie ``Citizen Kane,'' in 1887 and made the
flagship of his newspaper chain. In recent years, as its
circulation has lagged, its demise has been rumored.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, The San Jose Mercury News published an article saying
that Hearst and The Chronicle were close to an agreement to shut
The Examiner and jointly produce a morning newspaper. The Examiner
denied that, and a year later staff members held a party and made
T-shirts bearing the slogan ``We're still here.''
</P>
<P>
   But to a lot of people it looks doubtful that they will have
such a party a year from now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
