<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-ILLICIT-DIAMON     08-07 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-ILLICIT-DIAMONDS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY TRY TO CURB DIAMOND TRADE THAT FUELS AFRICAN WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concerned that diamonds are financing and
perpetuating wars in Africa, the Clinton administration is
considering actions aimed at halting the illicit-diamond trade,
administration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of uncut diamonds from rebel-held mines to market
centers around the world _ valued at hundreds of millions of
dollars a year _ is keeping rebel armies in Angola, Congo and
Sierra Leone supplied with tanks and assault rifles and even
uniforms and beer, U.S. and European officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Control of these mines has been an obstacle to peace efforts in
African hot spots, and officials hope that by cutting off the
gray-market diamond trade they can also choke off the flow of arms,
stop the endless killing and hasten peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds are not the only way in which rebels pay for weapons,
but experts in Africa and the trade say cutting it off would have a
substantial impact.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is likely to propose a global marketing
system, by which diamond sales must be accompanied by documents
declaring the source of the precious stones and their destination.
</P>
<P>
   From the fields in Africa, diamonds reach dealers in Belgium,
Israel and Ukraine, where the unscrupulous turn the ready cash into
weapons. The largest weapons pipeline into Africa is controlled by
Russian organized crime figures who work with diamond brokers, U.S.
and European officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight years, the Angolan rebel organization, known
as Unita, has raised $3 billion to $4 billion from diamond sales,
according to a recent report by a U.N. committee on Angolan
sanctions. An arduously worked-out peace accord for that country
collapsed late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The brutal war in Sierra Leone, which left thousands maimed and
mutilated, was prolonged by at least 18 months because of the
ability of the rebels to quickly trade diamonds for arms, an
administration official said last week. A delicate agreement ending
that war was signed in July.
</P>
<P>
   At the middle levels of the State Department, the African
diamonds-for-weapons trade has been under study for several years.
But the problem has not penetrated more senior levels because wars
in Africa are not generally seen as affecting America's strategic
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after an intelligence study, which had been slow in coming,
illustrated how the trade works to perpetuate rebellion in Africa,
top administration officials appear to be ready to back a plan that
would try to regulate the diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how such a marketing regime would be implemented in
various African nations and European diamond centers is undecided,
officials say. It could take the form of a U.N. program, a
multilateral treaty or a voluntary agreement within the diamond
industry.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to be an idea that is gaining support outside
government channels. Human rights organizations, including those
that led the campaign to ban land mines, are now talking about a
public education campaign aimed at highlighting the
diamonds-for-weapons trade.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the world's largest diamond company, DeBeers
Consolidated Mines Ltd., said in an interview that it would support
tighter controls on the trade. DeBeers, which controls about 70
percent of the world's diamond sales, views the growing flow of
illicit diamonds as a potential threat to its ability to influence
prices.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Its support would surely be welcomed by the administration,
which had expected DeBeers to resist any move to regulate the
market since the company has done quite well under the current
system.
</P>
<P>
   DeBeers has repeatedly maintained that it does not buy illicit
diamonds, a claim that U.S. and British officials dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all for it,'' a DeBeers spokesman in London, Andrew
Lamont, said about any proposal that the administration might
advance to strengthen controls on the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suits our interests,'' he added. ``The illicit trade only
serves to destabilize the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamont added that he thought the countries of southern Africa
whose economies are heavily dependent on diamond sales _ Botswana,
Namibia and South Africa _ would also welcome more stringent
controls on the trade.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Belgium, which has resisted entreaties from the Clinton
administration to crack down on the gray-market diamond merchants,
appears to be changing its attitude. In Antwerp, the diamond
trading center of Europe, officials have asked for help from U.S.
law enforcement agencies to combat the growing power of Russian
organized crime figures, who launder money through diamond
merchants, according to U.S. officials in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The diamond trade, which is highly secretive and governed by
informal arrangements, has been difficult to regulate. A U.N.
embargo against buying diamonds from Unita, the Angolan rebel
movement, has been largely ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamond revenues constitute the essential component of Unita's
capacity to wage war,'' Robert R. Fowler, Canada's ambassador to
the United Nations, wrote in a recent report to the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is reluctant to talk publicly about
what steps it is considering to curb the diamond trade in order to
avoid the perception that a regulatory regime would be imposed on
African states by the powerful West, said an administration
official who spoke on the condition of anonymity. Britain is also
supportive of tighter controls and is working with the
administration on proposals, U.S. and British officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-CATTLE-NYT &LR;      08-07 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-CATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA SEES A PLOT AFTER DEATHS OF GIFT COWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Last summer, in an encouraging sign that
relations between the Koreas were improving, a convoy of 50 trucks
from Hyundai Group of South Korea rolled across the heavily
fortified border into North Korea, carrying a most precious cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the trucks were 500 head of cattle, a gift from Chung
Ju-yung, Hyundai's billionaire founder, to help feed the
famine-stricken North. At the time, Hyundai's cattle donation was
the most shining example yet that South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung's policy of constructively engaging the North was working.
</P>
<P>
   A Buddhist priest, on hand for the highly publicized cattle
drive, banged a wooden block and prayed that the animals would
survive until the Korean Peninsula was reunited.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, those prayers appear to have gone unanswered.
North Korea announced recently that about half the cattle had died,
casualties of what it said was a sinister plot by South Korea's
intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   The North accused the South's spy agency of force-feeding the
cows vinyl rope, large nails and other indigestible items before
the animals were shipped. The agency strenuously denied the
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Western diplomats would dismiss such claims as the
desperate propaganda of a hermetic communist state, but several
envoys and international aid workers here have confirmed that
scores of the donated cattle have died under mysterious
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we don't believe that the South Korean government had
anything to do with the cattle's untimely death,'' a senior Western
diplomat said, ``it is certainly curious that so many of these
cows, which were intended to relieve hunger, perished this way. If
we find this curious, one can only imagine the level of paranoia
spreading through North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   In a broadcast on North Korean radio last month, a government
spokesman said that 246 of the first 500 cows given by Hyundai in
June 1998 had died, along with 30 sent by a civic group, according
to South Korea's Yonhap News Agency, which monitors North Korean
radio transmissions. The North Korean spokesman said autopsies
found ``vinyl rope, vinyl sheeting, magnets, fragments of glass,
large nails and other indigestible items in the dead cattle's
stomachs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We severely reprove the intelligence service for resorting to
such a despicable trick in a bid to hinder and frustrate
nongovernmental cooperation between the North and South,'' the
spokesman said, referring to Chung's donation.
</P>
<P>
   International famine relief workers, who maintain contact with
their colleagues in North Korea, said they had received reports
that several hundred of the donated cows died. The workers said
that during the first autopsies, North Korean veterinarians
searched the animal carcasses for electronic devices and tested for
viruses.
</P>
<P>
   In denying that the agency was responsible for the deaths, a
spokesman for South Korea's National Intelligence Service said,
``It is absolutely untrue that we planted any type of surveillance
device on the cows.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea in no way blamed Hyundai for the deaths. When Chung
led the caravan of Hyundai trucks across the demilitarized zone
last year, the cows appeared healthy and were heard mooing softly.
According to news reports here, the animals had been given a
sedative to prevent motion sickness.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai donated an additional 500 cattle last September, but it
could not be learned how that herd has fared.
</P>
<P>
   Chung, a son of a poor farmer in Tonchon, Kangwon Province, in
North Korea, said he had decided to donate the cattle to pay a
family debt. At 18, Chung stole his father's cow in secret and used
the proceeds to travel to Seoul to make his fortune. He is now one
of South Korea's wealthiest men.
</P>
<P>
   A Hyundai spokesman, Kim Sang-ryun, said the company had
received no indication from North Korea that so many cows had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's now the case that hundreds of cows have died,'' Kim
said, ``we are very sad to hear that because we had hoped that the
cows would be bred and used to provide nourishment.''
</P>
<P>
   International relief agencies estimate that the North Korean
famine has killed a minimum of several hundred thousand and left
millions close to starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of Kim Dae-jung, the South Korean president, view
the cow debacle as further evidence of the faltering of his
so-called sunshine policy, which lifted bans on travel and trade
with North Korea to encourage reforms there.
</P>
<P>
   Although South Korea has provided the North with tens of
millions of dollars in food, fertilizer and tourist revenues in the
last year, the North recently provoked a navy skirmish, detained a
South Korean tourist and threatened to test a new long-range
missile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
