<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALTIMORE-MAYORAL-RAC     08-07 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-MAYORAL-RACE-ART-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVISIVENESS AND SURPRISES IN BALTIMORE MAYORAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ After weeks of political chaos featuring 27 declared
mayoral candidates, six of them with arrest records, a campaign
showdown loomed noisy as summer thunder here last week in a rowdy
scene outside City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, you're stabbing us in the back,'' one black politician
shouted at another as demonstrators disrupted a news conference,
called to endorse a mayoral candidate, and drove their rivals
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   But their target, Howard Rawlings, the state General Assembly
delegate, was determined to go forward with his role as a political
kingmaker. He called on this gritty city's black majority to
support the leading white mayoral contender, Martin O'Malley, a
city councilman.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Malley is a new generation of white political leadership,''
Rawlings, who is black, declared after he retreated from hooting
and hollering demonstrators bused to City Hall on Thursday by the
rival campaign of Lawrence Bell III, the City Council president and
the leading black candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Malley has a track record of empowering black Americans,''
Rawlings said in front of the television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who had been increasingly upset at the rise of O'Malley
from the status of also-ran to possible unity candidate, was
nowhere in sight on Thursday. But his political lieutenants
directed the disruptive rally and denounced the potentially
decisive endorsements of O'Malley as treachery by ``so-called
pseudo-Negro political leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   News reports would describe the scene at City Hall as a
dirty-tricks ``ambush'' by Bell forces frustrated that the formerly
underrated O'Malley was gaining momentum. He had garnered
endorsements from black leaders like Rawlings and state Sen. Joan
Carter Conway and from some well-organized, heavily black labor
unions, including the city's health care workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of being the best black candidate or the
best white candidate,'' Rawlings said in an interview. ``O'Malley's
the best candidate for Baltimore.'' He noted that he and other
black leaders had tried and failed to enlist black candidates like
Kweisi Mfume, the former U.S. representative who is president of
the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   And so they are urging voters to wrench some order from what
Rawlings described as a ``frightening'' and divisive campaign for
the Sept. 14 primary that will determine the next mayor in this
predominantly black Democratic city.
</P>
<P>
   The primary field includes 17 Democrats, seven Republicans and
three independents. But only the top three Democrats were rated as
having any chance of being elected mayor. All the candidates talked
of a turnout of little more than 100,000 voters in this city of
675,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The beneficiary of the black leaders' strategy, O'Malley, seemed
almost surprised to have risen to the center of attention as he
warned against ``the divisive politics of the past.'' He had used
his four terms on the council to make a show of visiting New York
and other urban renaissance spots in building an image _ tinged
with the sharp-edged resolve of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York
_ as the leading voice against Baltimore's persistently high
standing in drug and murder rates.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of O'Malley, a proven vote getter in his heavily black
council district, appeared to have as much to do with a process of
elimination as it did with his own dogged sense of opportunity in
suddenly entering the race after black leaders failed to produce a
unity candidate. Rawlings candidly admitted that after Mfume and
other prominent blacks spurned a candidacy, he was going to turn to
Carl Stokes, a black candidate and a former city councilman, as the
next best choice.
</P>
<P>
   But then Stokes became embroiled in a campaign resume
controversy for having falsely claimed a college degree. That left
O'Malley, who was unsullied thus far in the tragicomical series of
candidate gaffes that had provided this city with a bleak campaign
sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   One fringe candidate was recognized as a fugitive from a court
warrant by a police officer watching television, who then moved in
for an arrest. Controversy had even focused on the management
talents of Bell, who marshaled a formidable patronage machine in
trying to appear the odds-on heir to Mayor Kurt Schmoke. Bell has
had to deal with lawsuit disclosures of personal financial troubles
highlighted by the repossession of his car.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders are campaigning against a bittersweet subtext of
the end of the 12-year Democratic reign of Schmoke. Hailed
initially as an urban visionary, he is departing with various
politicians voicing disappointment that Baltimore had failed to
keep pace with other major cities during the national economic
boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad, although everybody likes the mayor,'' said Jim
Knight, a Democratic committeeman from south Baltimore. He was
campaigning for Stokes, faulting Bell for racial politics that
Knight considered deliberately divisive in a city that sorely
needed reconciliation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bell, vying to maintain his earlier career promise before an
electorate that is more than 60 percent black, had become openly
petulant about his former ally, O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of being a punching bag,'' Bell declared, pacing and
frowning before the voters as the two appeared Thursday night
before the 43/44 Democratic Club in the heart of the city's black
wards. ``I'm not going to take it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bell forces' commitment to an aggressive last-ditch
targeting of O'Malley became clear earlier in the week when they
rallied outside The Baltimore Sun newspaper. They complained that
negative stories had focused on black candidates, but that O'Malley
had been spared criticism and should be scored as a criminal lawyer
who sometimes represented drug defendants even as he campaigned
against them. The Sun reported that O'Malley's mixed criminal
caseload was far from lucrative and not atypical for a former
criminal prosecutor. O'Malley told voters that other public
figures, from Abraham Lincoln to Thurgood Marshall, pursued similar
livelihoods in the law.
</P>
<P>
   The crossover to O'Malley reflected growing wariness among some
black leaders about Bell, as well as their own political need to
play a decisive role in the city's affairs. Rawlings, appalled at
being cut off as he stood for O'Malley, accused the Bell campaign
of ``political vandalism.'' ``He's a child,'' snapped the black
Statehouse leader, joining the O'Malley camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-DROUGHT-NYT &LR;      08-07 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DROUGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A HANDFUL OF DUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Aug. 8:
</P>
<P>
   Drought is a slow emergency. It does not swoop down out of the
skies like a tornado or pull the earth apart at its seams like an
earthquake. A drought of the kind the Eastern seaboard is suffering
now, the worst of this century in at least four states, is the
product not of one summer's failed rains but of chronic dryness
over several seasons _ compounded by routine profligacy in our use
of water.
</P>
<P>
   It is the result of what we have all been taught to call good
weather _ hot, it is true, but blue skies day after day, mild
winters, little snow. It is also the result of what we have come to
call normal water use.
</P>
<P>
   The drought of 1999 has become severe enough to bring about a
flurry of administrative actions intended to mitigate its effects
on farms, businesses and communities.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, President Clinton ordered the appropriate federal
agencies to form a task force to organize timely drought relief.
New Jersey's governor, Christie Whitman, and the governors of
Maryland, Delaware and West Virginia have all imposed mandatory
restrictions on water use.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman has declared West Virginia
and 33 counties in five surrounding states a disaster area.
Meanwhile, the Senate approved $7.4 billion in aid to farmers, to
which a drought and disaster relief package will need to be added
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   This is all to the good, and it may also reconcentrate, for a
moment, our attention on this nation's patterns of water usage.
Drought is nothing new, and dealing with it does not require
radically new ideas. Any number of entities, including the Western
Drought Coordination Council and the National Drought Policy
Commission, have been spawned in recent years in order to monitor
drought conditions and respond to them as the long-term events they
are.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Drought Mitigation Center, no state
had a drought plan during the 1976-77 dry spell. This year 30
states do, and nearly every encounter with water scarcity leads to
a set of recommendations _ essentially the ones invoked in a
drought emergency _ meant to discourage consumption and encourage
recycling.
</P>
<P>
   But once the rains begin again and controls are lifted, water
use tends to rebound to previous levels. Drought dramatizes an
epistemological problem that has real, practical effects. There is
something almost intangible about the causes of drought, something
as abstract and as forceful as fate. A high-pressure dome has kept
rain from the mid-Atlantic states this summer, a weather pattern
related to the occurrence of La Nina, a drop in sea-surface
temperature in the eastern equatorial Pacific last winter.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tie any single drought unequivocally to the solid
evidence of global warming, but that too lurks in many people's
minds as the ultimate cause of this summer's parching.
</P>
<P>
   Against such a grand array of forces, it can be hard to imagine
how taking a shorter shower or watering the lawn less frequently
makes a difference. But individual action _ conserving water _ is
the basis for collective action, and collectively, the residents of
drought-stricken states can make an enormous difference in their
own welfare, both now, when stream levels are at record lows, and
in the future, when rain returns.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, of course, are forced to take the weather as it comes,
and they understand just how illusory any sense of expectation
based on what passes for normal really is. Consumers can scale back
water use to the bone with little more than inconvenience. But
farms, like many other forms of industry, require water for
economic survival, which is exactly what is at risk again this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The reserves of water in reservoirs and aquifers have been
steadily diminishing. So have the economic reserves of American
farmers, who find themselves bringing their products to market, if
they survive this dry season at all, at depressed prices. Neither
of these problems, drought or farm income, can be solved with a
sudden flurry of attention.
</P>
<P>
   They require long-term commitment and the changing of habits
that are so persistent we have come to call them normal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
