<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVORY-COAST-NATIONALI     08-07 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORY-COAST-NATIONALISM-ART-830(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHERMEN FEEL XENOPHOBIA IN `PURE IVOIRIAN' PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AYAME, Ivory Coast _ In this quiet lakeside town, far from the
trucks rumbling along the highway south of here, fishermen from
Mali lived peacefully for four decades alongside the local
Ivoirians, trading, mingling and even intermarrying.
</P>
<P>
   Then, over several nights of violence, the Ivoirians set fire to
the fishermen's houses. The Malians fled to Abidjan, the country's
commercial capital on the Atlantic Coast. From there, convoys
carried 2,500 of them 600 miles north to the deserts of Mali, the
landlocked country most of them had never seen before.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains here now _ besides the few Malians who dare not
fish, or even identify themselves as non-Ivoirians _ is a fierce
and growing sense of nationalism: Ayame for Ivoirians only. Next on
the expulsion list are migrant plantation workers from Burkina
Faso, warned a group of Ivoirian fishermen paddling back to shore
aboard their pirogues on a recent morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each his turn,'' said Clement Yao, 29, cackling with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming,'' Miniambue Amon, 40, said.
</P>
<P>
   The real reasons behind what occurred in Ayame are still in
dispute a year later, too laden with emotion to yield anything but
a Rashomon-like retelling. But what is clear is that Ayame _ as
well as Sassandra, a coastal town where a similar incident
involving fisherman from Ghana occurred in December _ has become a
touchstone in the debate over national identity.
</P>
<P>
   That identity has a name: ivoirite. Translated from the French,
it means the quality of being Ivoirian; its power derives not from
its definition, which has been left vague, but from the open or
hidden meanings people ascribe to it.
</P>
<P>
   The concept has already become the driving issue in the
presidential elections of next year, crucial elections for West
Africa, where the Ivory Coast has long been a stable and relatively
prosperous nation in a troubled region and the home of investments
from the West.
</P>
<P>
   To its chief supporters, including President Henri Konan Bedie,
ivoirite amounts to a positive form of nationalism that seeks to
unify the country's different ethnic groups around common values,
surely an important goal on a continent where ethnic rivalries
undermine nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To achieve peacefully the formidable leap between an ethnic
consciousness and a national consciousness, the reference mark of
identity must be strong, and that fixed point is called ivoirite,''
Bedie wrote recently in the Paris-based magazine Jeune Afrique.
</P>
<P>
   Auguste Miremont, the parliamentary leader of the Democratic
Party of the Ivory Coast, the president's party, said ivoirite was
needed because Ivoirians themselves were being marginalized in a
country where at least one- third of the population of 16 million
was born abroad. ``It became necessary for the Ivoirian to be able
to assert his identity, to be able practically to affirm his
existence, which was drowning in an undefined mass,'' Miremont
said.
</P>
<P>
   To its detractors, including the political opposition, ivoirite
is nothing less than an attempt at marginalizing the country's
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concept inspired by fear, by the rejection of the
other, the rejection of what is different,'' said Aly Coulibaly, a
member of Parliament of the Rally of the Republicans, the main
opposition party. ``It's a concept with the musty smell of
xenophobia that is dangerous for national unity.''
</P>
<P>
   On a continent where political leaders routinely use ethnic
divisions for political gains, the concept of ivoirite has marked
something of a new development: the attempt to forge a national
identity in a country, like so many in Africa, drawn capriciously
by colonial map makers.
</P>
<P>
   The notion also signified a departure from the post-independence
history of the Ivory Coast, whose longtime ruler, President Felix
Houphouet-Boigny, died in 1993. Inspired by genuine feelings of
openness toward fellow Africans and the need for cheap labor,
Houphouet-Boigny had long made it easy for foreigners to come here.
</P>
<P>
   The Malian fishermen gravitated to Ayame, a town of about 11,000
people, four decades ago, after the construction of two
hydroelectric dams changed the flow of the Bia River and created a
propitious lake. The local Ivoirians, who cultivated cocoa and
coffee, did not engage in commercial fishing, said the town's
mayor, Blaise Aka.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, with unemployment running high among Ivoirian
youths, the mayor said he and other officials urged them to take up
commercial fishing and gave them subsidies to get started. The
Malians refused to share the lake with the Ivoirians, Aka said,
citing that as the reason behind the eventual conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was purely an economic problem,'' the mayor said. ``It was
not a problem of ivoirite. We talk of ivoirite in the sense that
one has to be proud to be Ivoirian.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the house of one the few remaining Malians, though, the
residents did not see it that way. The owner, Ibrahim Nabo, 37, sat
in a chair, while two friends sat on carpets and drank hot tea,
telltale signs of difference from the Agni ethnic group dominant in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the conflict between the Ivoirians and Malians, Nabo
at first denied that he was Malian. ``I am Ivoirian! I am
Ivoirian!'' Nabo said, his voice quavering.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that no problems existed between the Ivoirians and
Malians. Then one of his friends, Bocar Toure, said that Nabo's
mother had been so heartbroken that she had gone back to Mali for
good. For decades, the two groups had gotten along here, Toure, 36,
said, but in recent years, the Ivoirians had become intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be open people,'' Toure said. ``We felt that
there was freedom here. We even admired them.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was that most of the fishermen were eventually taken
to Mali in convoys organized by individual Malians, the Malian
government and the Ivoirian Red Cross. There are no plans for them
to return.
</P>
<P>
   The governing party, perhaps in response to these events, has
recently tried to soften ivoirite's image.
</P>
<P>
   Ivoirite first came to the forefront of political discourse in
the year leading up to the 1995 presidential elections, with stark
talk of who was a ``pure Ivoirian'' and who was only a
``circumstantial Ivoirian.'' The government of Bedie _ who first
became president in 1993 as the head of a party in power since
independence from France in 1960 _ changed the electoral code in
1994 to require that a presidential candidate be born in the Ivory
Coast to parents both born here as well.
</P>
<P>
   The change was clearly intended to frustrate Bedie's main rival,
Alassane D. Ouattara, a former prime minister whose father, the
president said, was born in Burkina Faso. Ouattara, while insisting
that his father was Ivoirian, bowed out of the race and returned to
his job as a deputy director of the International Monetary Fund in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was resurrected last year when Ouattara announced his
intention of returning to the Ivory Coast to contest in the
elections of October 2000. In recent months, the president's party
drummed up the ivoirite campaign to such a peak that when Ouattara
made his long-awaited return here one week ago, and was named the
head of the Rally of the Republicans, the debate over whether he is
a pure Ivoirian dominated the news media completely.
</P>
<P>
   But given the concept's roots in the political battle against
Ouattara, a Muslim northerner, Ivoirians in the north have begun to
feel like targets. Politically so far, the government-controlled
news media have defined the agenda and focused exclusively on
Ouattara's origins. (In 1995, when some journalists questioned
Bedie's roots and wrote that his mother was actually born in Ghana,
the government had them arrested.)
</P>
<P>
   Its energies consumed with responding to this issue, the
opposition news media have barely paid attention to the
government's recent setbacks, including the European Union's
decision to cut off all aid after widespread fraud was discovered
in the Ministry of Health's billing practices.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the fate of Ouattara's candidacy remains unclear. A
nine-member Constitutional Board, whose composition is controlled
by Bedie, is unlikely to rule in favor of Ouattara, who may be
counting on popular support and international pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In Ayame, the two fishermen who had warned that migrants from
Burkina Faso would be expelled next said they believed that
political opportunism and ivoirite were inextricably linked. They
supported it, nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's certain is that we don't want Ouattara,'' Amon said,
citing his Burkina Faso origins. Yao said he wanted a change
because the governing party has held power since independence. But
he said he would vote for Bedie over Ouattara anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the PDCI much,'' Yao said of the governing party.
``But when Bedie talks of ivoirite, I agree with him. Ivoirians
first!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-AFRICA-WAR-NYT &LR;      08-07 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AFRICA-WAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BUSINESS OF WAR IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Aug. 8:
</P>
<P>
   In many African nations, the natural resources that should be
used to feed and educate people are instead being used to destroy
them.
</P>
<P>
   The government and guerrillas in Angola, for example, are
selling the country's oil and diamonds to buy weapons and pay
soldiers in a 30-year civil war that has made the nation perhaps
the most miserable in the world. In Congo and Sierra Leone as well,
natural wealth is fueling catastrophic conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But no warring party can make an arms deal alone. Outside
nations and companies are also profiting. They should be helping
instead to limit the ability of African warlords to sell a
country's patrimony and to block the flow of weapons to Africa's
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Colonialism, which allowed Europe to extract Africa's natural
resources, left behind leaders who exploit gold, diamonds, timber,
oil and even wildlife to benefit their own regional or ethnic
groups _ or their own bank accounts. Several of Africa's wars are
waged partially over control of these resources. Zimbabwe, Uganda
and other nations supporting the government or guerrillas in
Congo's war got involved in part to preserve _ or to grab _ Congo's
mining concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign corporations and mercenaries, often those who had
American or Soviet connections during the Cold War, have also
financed and transported weapons in exchange for mines.
</P>
<P>
   These resources can buy plenty of tanks, guns and missiles,
keeping wars going long after the political rationale is gone.
Loot, not better government, has motivated the psychotically brutal
guerrillas of Sierra Leone. They trade the diamonds they control
for arms through neighboring Liberia, under the sponsorship of
President Charles Taylor, their longtime patron.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Africa's weapons come from Ukraine, Bulgaria and other
former Soviet bloc countries, traded by Western arms dealers using
forged documents. The governments are either unable or unwilling to
stop this. In other wars, weapons are sold openly by Russia and
China.
</P>
<P>
   The world's growing recognition of the role of outsiders,
however, opens a new opportunity to cut these pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the United Nations placed an embargo on the sale of
diamonds controlled by Jonas Savimbi, the Angolan guerrilla leader.
Once backed by Washington and apartheid South Africa, Savimbi lost
his patrons after the Cold War ended and he broke repeated promises
to disarm or respect elections and cease-fires. But diamonds have
brought him more than $3 billion in the last eight years, according
to a new U.N. report.
</P>
<P>
   The embargo has been ineffective. De Beers, the diamond giant,
denies that it violates the embargo, but many independent experts
dispute this. The United Nations is now seeking ways to strengthen
controls. One proposal backed by Washington would require all
diamonds to have credible certificates of origin.
</P>
<P>
   It is easier, however, to stop a shipment of tanks than one of
diamonds. The former communist nations need pressure and technical
help to crack down on arms sales. But more effective, perhaps,
would be action against the arms smugglers, largely Western
Europeans and Americans. These smugglers are often working within
the laws of their home nations and are almost never prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Washington adopted laws governing American arms traders
abroad, but so far no one has been brought to trial. Such laws, and
the will to enforce them, are important, as Western nations are the
only participants in this global problem with working courts and
the possibility of being shamed into ending their role in Africa's
misery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1402EDT &QL; 
