<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-07 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CELEBRATING THE BROWNS' TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something wonderful is about to happen in Cleveland, but it
should be celebrated all over North America. A community is
regaining its beloved football team, which it lost through no fault
of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Browns, the real thing, are rising from the ashes
of ownership greed and disloyalty. The team played its last game in
December 1995, and then the material goods of the franchise were
hauled to a new home in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, against all precedents, the National Football
League agreed that the nickname, the colors, the uniform, the
statistics, the very memories, belonged to the people alongside
Lake Erie. Now that team has been resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to know how much the new stadium cost, but I am
positive the burghers of Cleveland would never have raised that
much money for the frayed city school system. The economists who
make sense to me claim that most jobs from a football team are
selling peanuts eight home games a year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the gates will soon open in downtown Cleveland, and at
the very least, a man named Art Modell was not allowed to
expropriate the history of a franchise, and that is something to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the real Cleveland Browns will play an exhibition
game at the National Hall of Fame in Canton in the state of Ohio.
On Aug. 21 the real Cleveland Browns will play their first home
exhibition in the new stadium in downtown Cleveland. And on Sept.
12 the real Cleveland Browns will play their first league game at
home against their old Rust Belt rivals, the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   These milestone games reflect the persistence of dogged,
faithful people in Cleveland, but the victory is not local. It
speaks to every city that ever loved and lost a team.
</P>
<P>
   This victory does not mean Monte Irvin and Whitey Lockman are
going to magically resume hitting baseballs in the shadow of
Coogan's Bluff. (Go look it up on some search engine, kid.) But it
does mean that fans everywhere now have an example of the good name
of their team being left behind when the moving van chugs into the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Leading rusher, Baltimore Ravens, Jim Brown, 12,312 career
yards. Huh? I'd like to see somebody try telling that to Brown
himself. But Paul Tagliabue, the commissioner of the NFL, made sure
Modell could not ransack Marion Motley and Lou Groza along with the
current players.
</P>
<P>
   This great triumph by the fans of Cleveland came too late to
save the name Dodgers from being trundled off by the O'Malley clan.
If there is any justice in the world, the team visiting Shea
Stadium in New York Sunday afternoon should be called the Los
Angeles Diggers, in honor of the team's Australian owner, rather
than a hallowed Brooklyn nickname.
</P>
<P>
   The great nicknames, the histories both grand and modest, await
their rightful claimants, the way the Cherokee nation can be heard
chanting along the Trail of Tears, if you are quiet and listen
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   When the hockey team in the Canadian capital of Ottawa ceased
operation in 1934, no other National Hockey League team had the
gall to use its nickname until an expansion team was plunked back
in Ottawa in 1992, appropriately renamed the Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Who is to say that heroes like Walter Johnson and noble managers
like Gil Hodges and Ted Williams could not be recalled with a third
Washington Senators?
</P>
<P>
   The predators took a vibrant hockey franchise from Quebec City
to Colorado, but maybe that lovely name Nordiques will once again
be trilled on a crisp winter night in La Belle Province.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams are just dead and gone, the victims of westward
migration, the new demographics. St. Louis Browns. Providence
Steamrollers. Hartford Whalers. The spiritual heritage of the
Syracuse Nationals _ the crew cuts and tiny satin shorts and
fisticuffs and the deadeye one-handed set shot of Dolph Schayes _
still belongs to the tiny Snow Belt city.
</P>
<P>
   There were legal reasons they couldn't, but I am convinced the
new Major League Soccer franchise in the Meadowlands in East
Rutherford, N.J., would have resonated far better with fans if the
team had been named the Cosmos, after that brief dynasty of Pele
and Beckenbauer. Instead, they were forced to go with the clumsy
name MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be realistic. The victory of the Cleveland Browns will not
bring Johnny Unitas back to Baltimore or Roy Campanella back to
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But all of us who had our teams taken away from us can rejoice
when the familiar brown-orange-and-white uniforms soon become
saturated in good old-fashioned Great Lakes mud and snow. The
people of Cleveland have won one for all of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
