<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ALBANY'S LAST-MINUTE LABORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Aug. 8:
</P>
<P>
   Although Gov. George Pataki and the New York Legislature tied
the record for the latest budget in Albany's history, the $73.3
billion package negotiated last week is cause for at least modest
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature resisted the urge to spend last year's $1.8
billion surplus, saving it instead to cover the cost of previously
enacted tax cuts. It wisely restored cuts the governor had proposed
in Medicaid, tuition aid for low-income students and
prekindergarten classes. At Pataki's request, legislators approved
$839 million for child care for working mothers. With increases for
school construction and remedial programs, it becomes clear that
children and mothers did well this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature was nearly as judicious in dealing with crime
and dangerous behavior. It unfortunately left the counterproductive
Rockefeller drug laws on the books, but it agreed on an important
bill to ensure safe access to abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful measure would make stalking a crime, while yet
another, known as Kendra's Law, would allow a doctor or family
member to get a court order to compel a mentally ill person to get
treatment. The law was named for Kendra Webdale, who was killed
when a former mental patient shoved her onto New York City's subway
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But the usual last-minute frenzy to agree on numbers left a lot
of other important business on the sidelines. There was no action,
for example, on campaign finance reform and no effort to improve
the state's ridiculously porous lobbying laws. Once again, the
Senate failed to address the issue of hate crimes. All these issues
need addressing in the special session scheduled for this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Legislature distinguish itself on environmental
matters, a signature issue for the governor. It finally unraveled a
jurisdictional mess that has blocked the construction of new power
plants in the state, but it brushed off pleas from
environmentalists to impose new pollution controls on older,
dirtier plants and to revive the state's once-robust energy
conservation program.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Assembly and the Senate passed laws preventing New York
power plants from selling their excess pollution credits to
coal-fired Midwestern power plants whose wind-borne pollutants are
a major cause of acid rain in the Adirondacks. But a ridiculous
turf war prevented the two chambers from reconciling their modest
differences.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers did, however, grant themselves an increase in
their per diem pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
