<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-07 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE GUY WHO COULD   HAVE BEEN MCGWIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sports highlights came on, featuring Mark McGwire reaching
another statistical milestone and Darryl Strawberry making another
sobering comeback. McGwire hit his 500th home run Thursday night,
an achievement Strawberry would have long since reached had he not
become baseball's home office for waste.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he joined the Mets in 1983, Strawberry hit 280
home runs over nine baseball seasons that were nothing like the
homer happy years to come. Over the last seven and two-thirds
seasons, marred by illness, injury and mostly insult to himself,
Strawberry has hit the grand total of 52 in the puny sum of 961
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade when baseball developed a clear entrepreneurial
strategy to juice up the game, marketing the long ball, is it
unreasonable to wonder if Darryl Strawberry would have made his own
run at Maris had he not let his career go to drink and drugs?
</P>
<P>
   I will leave the projections of exactly how many more home runs
he would have hit to the capable people at the Elias Sports Bureau
and just say this: A lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all the talent and ability in the world, but I'll never
know what I might have achieved with it,'' Strawberry once told me,
probably in 1995, when the Yankees rescued him from baseball's
phantom zone.
</P>
<P>
   The comebacks have begun to blur, but as far as I'm concerned,
Strawberry can keep coming back, as long as George Steinbrenner
will have him. Strawberry has become one of the easy targets in
sports, a cheap morality tale. The reality is that he is not
America's scourge _ any more than Steve Howe was _ as much as he is
another sad case.
</P>
<P>
   Why are some people so determined to wish or shout the likes of
Strawberry away, to banish the self-destructive and turn them into
the homeless of sports? What is gained by placing a limit on the
number of opportunities for a man who poses little threat to the
welfare of baseball, or anyone, excluding himself and his family?
Is it possible or even beneficial to make professional sports the
clean suburban street it was decades ago, when issues were largely
kept behind family doors?
</P>
<P>
   The industry riddles should all be so easy to crack as the
Strawberry case. I have a much harder time explaining to my own
sons why Latrell Sprewell is such a New York folk hero so soon
after choking his coach and then navigating his car on the
California freeway the way he drives to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Inebriated adults cheering hockey brawls and greedy television
moguls selling garbage like wrestling are more of a threat to your
child's social development than a player who blows millions of
dollars for powder up his nose. For as long as Strawberry puts on
the pinstripes, they will be a reminder of the prison of
professional limitation he has locked himself in, with no way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There goes the guy who could have been McGwire'' would be one
befitting perspective when Strawberry makes his inevitable return
to Yankee Stadium and is trotted out as a part-time left fielder, a
pinch-hitter, a spare part.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is better off when society's ills are hidden in the
closet. Given the facts, I would suspect that most children would
prefer to emulate McGwire's success than Strawberry's failure,
which is why Major League Baseball's procrastination on banning
androstenedione in the face of too many red flags is irresponsible
and indefensible. Bud Selig sure was quick to slap a suspension on
Strawberry, though, to set the ``right'' example.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, before anyone knew what andro was, John Lucas was
already talking about how the sports drug culture had perceptibly
shifted, from the recreational street plague to the problem of
enhancement. The former basketball star, a recovering addict who
later became a counselor and coach, told me that sports teams still
bring him in, expecting and preferring the standby just-say-no
speech.
</P>
<P>
   He had moved on to another kind of lecture, though. He knew the
more prevalent dangers were in the pills that are dispensed,
legally and otherwise, to athletes of all ages who embrace the idea
that they are not trapped in the bodies they are born with.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire wanted it both ways: to be the adult who had the right
to take his own risks and the role model who could speak out
against child abuse. In refusing to acknowledge that the two
McGwires were one and the same, he sent the unfortunate message
that was encouraging young people to abuse themselves.
</P>
<P>
   His defenders said androstenedione couldn't help him hit home
runs, but that missed the point. The implication was that McGwire
needed the juice to sustain such a physically demanding pace. He
did the right thing last week, even if he waited four months to
announce he had stopped taking andro, obviously to quiet those who
said the home run record was artificially attained.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate he has been hitting them the last few weeks, McGwire
may go for 75. His legend will be that much greater. Strawberry,
conversely, will belt a few homers in September, maybe a couple
more in the playoffs. The unfulfilled decade will end for him, and
the numbers will speak for themselves. The truth is much worse than
a stadium full of boos.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is no model, but he does have a role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
