<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-WATER-STUDY-480     08-07 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-WATER-STUDY-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE POOR, WATER IS UNSAFE AND YET COSTLY, STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The poorest people in the world are paying many
times more than their richer compatriots for the water they need to
live, and are getting more than their share of deadly diseases
because supplies are dangerously contaminated, an international
panel of experts concluded last week.
</P>
<P>
   The reason may be that the price of water is kept artificially
low by government subsidies, making the water systems inefficient
and unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   Such systems, then, simply bypass the poor, who in desperation
turn to private water carriers. The private providers may charge up
to 100 times the municipal rates for water of very dubious quality,
in which diarrheal diseases and other infectious diseases thrive.
The cheaper, subsidized water then flows to better, politically
more influential neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Invariably this results in inadequate services, with many of
the rapidly growing poor neighborhoods going without municipal
services,'' said a report published last week by the panel, the
World Commission on Water for the 21st Century, which is supported
by U.N. agencies, a number of governments and the Ford Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Serageldin, a vice president of the World Bank and
chairman of the water commission, said in an interview that in some
cases the poorest families spend as much as 30 percent of their
income on water. ``Yet subsidies are defended in the name of the
poor,'' he added. ``This perverse situation has got to be
tackled.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that an end to subsidies and a system of graduated
fees use may be the solution. Under such a system, fees could be
based on water use. ``The poor always use less water than the
rich,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Water systems in developing countries are often inefficient,
losing as much as 40 percent to 60 percent of available water in
the process of providing municipal services and raising costs,
Serageldin said. By contrast, he added, a city like Singapore, with
well-maintained facilities, has a waste rate of only 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report, the culmination of a year of research,
compared prices of water in European cities with those in the
developing world and found that in richer countries people
generally paid many times more for piped water than what their
middle-class or richer counterparts pay in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Germans, for example, pay $2.16 for a cubic meter of water; in
Ireland 61 cents. In Jakarta, Indonesia, the charge would be 9
cents, and in Pakistan, a city dweller, however rich, pays 6 cents
to 10 cents per cubic meter. Good water services cannot be provided
at those prices, Serageldin said, adding that cities in the third
world may need to contract out parts of the system to private
investors, including community development groups that have been
springing up in many developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of creative ways of involving the community
and the private sector,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Indonesia, one such project, called the Kampung Improvement
Program, has helped people cover open drains for sanitation and
install standpipes that each bring reasonably clean water to every
three or four families. In Pakistan, the Orangi Pilot Project has
reached 650,000 people in a poor neighborhood of Karachi, the
largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't need a flush toilet in every home or a faucet in
every room,'' Serageldin. ``But with a standpipe for every three
units, with adequate pit latrines and other forms of treatment, the
services can be there and the health of the children can be
maintained.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9309 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDLIFE-REFUGE08-COX     08-07 2211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDLIFE-REFUGE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Call of the Wild: Colorado woman Dr. Doolittle of the San Juans
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Melissa Margetts will never forget the
time she sliced open the bulging stomach of a critically wounded
cow elk that had been hit by a car hours earlier on top of Dallas
Divide.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency roadside cesarian yielded a calf in obvious
distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grabbed her by the back legs and spun her around so the
centrifugal force would get this fluid out of her lungs,'' explains
Margetts. ``I had given her mouth-to-mouth and it took four minutes
to get her going.''
</P>
<P>
   The calf, nicknamed Junebug, was nursed back to health and
released into the wild last December.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts is a modern day Dr. Doolittle meets MacGyver.
</P>
<P>
   Take the time she rescued a baby porcupine from its mother's
womb using only her Swiss Army knife, cinnamon dental floss and a
little ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first C-section,'' Margetts said. ``I got the uterus
out and opened it up and got the baby out. The placenta was
attached to it and I thought with a human baby you tie off the
umbilical cord so they don't bleed to death, so I had cinnamon
dental floss in the car, and I thought, what the heck.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby, dubbed Stickers, was featured on a National Geographic
Explorer television special with Boyd Matson.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts, 43, is the brainchild behind the Rocky Mountain Ark
Wildlife Rehabilitation Center hidden away on a 14-acre spread high
in the San Juan Mountains near Telluride. She jokingly refers to
her wildlife refuge as the ``Damn Nice Ranch'' because that's what
she said to herself when she spied the rugged plot of land located
off of a dirt Forest Service access road.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Margetts has rescued thousands of wild and
domestic animals, which has garnered her the title ``Animal Lady''
with the locals.
</P>
<P>
   Current residents include, Spike, an African-crested porcupine;
Wyle E. Coyote; a homeless donkey dubbed Jackson Browne; Elvis the
mutt; and a sassy exotic parrot named Diego, who seems to have
picked up a bit of office lingo from his previous owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right!'' screeches the brilliant blue and yellow bird from his
perch next to the deck.
</P>
<P>
   It's just after 10 a.m. and Margetts and an intern, Ann Allen,
make the usual feeding rounds _ which take place every four hours
around the clock _ armed with containers of mealworms for the
birds, a bucket of milk for the fawns, and roadkill for Ruby the
mountain lion. Elvis and Jackson Browne trail behind for company,
occasionally chasing each other. It seems one of them has forgotten
that he is a donkey.
</P>
<P>
   A typical season at the Ark produces as many as 150 animals,
many considered hard luck cases after tangling with the most
dangerous creature of all _ humans.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Chaos, a great-horned owl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This couple was driving from California to their home in
Arizona,'' begins Margetts, as Chaos listens perched on her gloved
arm. ``They were driving at night and they hit him and thought he
was just stunned. They put him in a box and kept him overnight
while they continued to drive and their dog got into the box and
totally mangled him. The dog tore off his left foot and it was
hanging by a thread and his left wing was dangling. They put him
back in the box and thought he would be dead and continued to drive
to Arizona. He was still alive when they got there, so they thought
the most peaceful way to die was when you freeze to death. They
stuck him in the freezer and left him there for 30 hours and when
they checked on him, he was still alive. They finally called the
sheriff's department and asked what to do. The sheriff's department
picked him up and took him to Liberty Wildlife where his left wing
was amputated and his left foot was sewn back on. This was good
intentions really gone awry.''
</P>
<P>
   Margetts is a woman on a mission. She's on call 24 hours a day
and can often be found behind the wheel of her green and white
critter mobile fashioned from an old ambulance, picking up wounded
animals and bringing them back to the Ark for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary goal is wildlife rehab and reintroduction into the
wild,'' she said. ``All we are is a second chance for these guys to
be free. There's no guarantee. They die in the wild all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   With just barely a 63 percent survival rate, many of Margetts
animals are too critically wounded to survive and must be
euthanized. Those that make it are released back into the wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``The animals that I get attached to are the ones that I don't
think are going to make it,'' said Margetts. ``I am down at the
incubator at 2 o'clock in the morning and I've got my fingers
crossed and I am prepping myself for the idea that this animal is
more than likely going to be dead. Those are the ones that bring
tears to your eyes when it finally comes time to open up the box
and you see them tear across the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Animals that are maimed or unable to survive in the wild for
various reasons are retained for education programs at schools and
national parks for both children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can plant a seed in one kid, you never know what kind
of a difference they will make,'' said Margetts. ``If you inspire
one kid not to throw that plastic six-pack container in a bag
without cutting it up and he tells his son who becomes a school
teacher and tells more kids _ you never know how it is going to
steamroll.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her education programs, Margetts has been
featured in People magazine for her pet lending library, believed
to be the only one of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
   For five bucks, kids can get a library card and check out a
plethora of pets, including chinchillas, rabbits, guinea pigs,
hamsters, snakes, birds, pygmy goats _ even a tarantula spider in a
locked viewing box.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my favorite animal in the pet lending library,'' said
Margetts, while holding up what appears to be a gigantic New York
sewer rat. ``This is Howard Stern.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ark is also part of the International Placement Program
where animals are placed from all over the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   That's how she acquired a webbed-footed beaver named Wally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came from Montreal, Canada, and his dam had been blown
up,'' Margetts said. ``The parents were killed and the two babies
floated to the surface. A couple brought the babies home and they
tried to feed them but didn't do it properly, so they got metabolic
bone disease which caused their legs to break. They were taken to a
zoo, but the zoo didn't want them, so they were put on the
placement program list.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruby, a sleek mountain lion with haunting green eyes, was
rescued when she was just 10 days old from a fur farm in Iowa where
she was going to be used as a lab animal for nutrition experiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her, she is part of my family,'' said Margetts, who
once had a finger partially eaten off by a badger and has been
taloned by an eagle. ``She is not in captivity because I want her
to be. She is in captivity because she would be three times as
dangerous as one in the wild because she doesn't have any fear of
humans. I don't want anyone left with the idea that it is cool to
go out and get these animals and keep them as pets. They don't make
good pets and they are not happy being pets.''
</P>
<P>
   Margetts uses Ruby in the mountain lion safety classes she
teaches in Colorado, Wyoming and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, a black bear cub rescued last month, was brought to
Margetts after nearly starving in the wild after her mother was
found dead. Although an exact cause of death could not be
determined, officials with the Division of Wildlife believe the
mother bear was poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings is scheduled for release in November. That's when
colder temperatures and shorter days will force the young bear cub
into her natural cycle of hibernation. She will be sedated and
taken to a man-made den at an undisclosed location for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts said if Hastings, or any other wild animal, is going to
survive in the wild, it is absolutely critical they have minimal
contact with humans. For that reason, she only goes to the bear
cub's pen when it is necessary to feed and replenish water and
shovel out waste.
</P>
<P>
   Talking is prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to their release into the wild, animals undergo an
intensive ``demanning'' process where Margetts and her volunteer
assistants beat on pots and pans with silverware or bang on the
side of their pens three times a day in an effort to make the
animals afraid of humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not to harass the animals,'' Margetts said, ``but
we want them to have negative human contact. That's the hardest
part of the job. These guys start to follow you around after a
while and you have to start scaring them, banging on pots and pans
and flipping blankets and yelling and screaming. You want them to
run from you every time they see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Margetts' compassion for critters began at an early age while
growing up in Telluride. Her father, a medical doctor, often
doubled as the town vet and would bring home animals for Margetts
and her half dozen brothers and sisters to nurse back to health.
</P>
<P>
   She gleaned much of her medical knowledge from Dr. Dad, who was
known to dissect the chicken before dinner and pointing out things
like tendons and joints to anyone who would listen.
</P>
<P>
   After a short stint in Minnesota as an engineer for Honeywell
designing laser eyepieces for anti-tank weapons, Margetts heard the
call of the wild and followed it back to her hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Life hasn't always been easy for the auburn-haired animal lover
who firmly believes that one person can make a difference. She
survived a first marriage to an alcoholic husband which ended in
divorce. In 1992, she was diagnosed with non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma.
The cancer went into remission after several bouts of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   The quick-witted pied-piper of the animal kingdom uses humor to
deal with life's ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   Like when she married Steve Margetts, 44, a custom home builder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a dog once in his entire life,'' she quips. ``He met me
and I had 67 animals.''
</P>
<P>
   It ended up with Margetts promising to keep the permanent animal
head count to under 50 and Steve buying a lifetime supply of
Benedryl.
</P>
<P>
   To seal the deal, Margetts turned to her new husband and said,
``I thought you'd bring me flowers,'' to which Steve replied, ``I
brought you road kill instead.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in the door and said, 'You've got to see what I
brought home for you,''' Margetts said. ``This man had gotten out
of his truck and dragged a big, bloody, nasty roadkill into the
back of his truck _ it was something I would have left. He was so
proud of himself, then he made me wipe the blood off his shoes and
get out there at night with Dawn dishwashing liquid, a broom and a
hose and clean out his truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Margetts is never short on animal stories. She remembers the
time a woman offered her $20 and told her to go to the grocery
store after she spotted Margetts tugging on a dead animal carcass
she was attempting to bring home to her animals.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time she yelled at her son Jake to put his
toys away only to find out later that he had put his toys away
before going to bed and it was the baby beaver who was dragging
them back out at night in an attempt to build a dam across the
doorway.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts and her husband Steve once trapped an out-of-control
badger inside a Rubbermaid container. Taz, as the badger was
affectionately called, was making horrible noises and the container
was flipping all over the place as the two struggled to keep it
intact. It was then that Steve turned to Margetts and said with a
straight face, ``Don't you wish everything was made like
Rubbermaid?''
</P>
<P>
   And she remembers the time a couple gave her a pair of milk
goats but neglected to tell her that they only produced milk if
they got to listen to the country radio station, KKXK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them's country goats,'' she remembers the man telling her.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts takes a moment to reflect on her life as rain pours
from the dark storm clouds that have gathered overhead near the San
Juan Mountain range. After watching four otters gleefully swimming
in the enclosed otter pond outside her living room window, she
turns and says, ``If I won the lottery, I would still be doing this
on Monday. Even if I didn't have a dime to my name, I'd be doing
this on Monday. It's a fulfillment in my life that I would have a
hard time explaining to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   She just hopes she has many more Mondays. In November 1998,
Margetts cancer returned. She underwent surgery to remove masses
from her pancreas and stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, she has lost 80 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   In an unexplainable role of reversal, it's the animals who are
now keeping Margetts alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe the animals have had more to do with healing
me than I had to do with healing them,'' she said, quietly. ``I
feel that I have made a difference, not only in the lives of
thousands of animals, but also the kids. If I died tomorrow, that
would be perfectly fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
