<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-JUDICIAL-WATCH-     08-07 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-JUDICIAL-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDICIAL WATCH OPENS OFFICE IN CALIFORNIA  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Judicial Watch, the conservative Washington
organization that has filed more than 40 lawsuits against the
Clinton administration and others, seeking evidence of alleged
corruption, has opened its first satellite office in the nation in
a suburb of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the group say they will use the location, in San
Marino, Calif., to handle its litigation stemming from what they
broadly call Chinagate, the involvement of foreign money in the
1996 presidential campaign. Opening the office made sense, they
said, because many of the figures involved in the litigation live
in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch said it also intended to begin monitoring, on a
state level, the performance of judges and judicial ``activism,'' a
term usually used to describe liberal judges who apply the law in
unusual ways. ``We'll try to monitor and provide a balanced report
on what is really going on in the courtroom,'' said Mike Pendleton,
Judicial Watch's lawyer here.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's leaders say they have no political agenda and
are only trying to root out corruption and encourage judges to take
a restrained approach to the law.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats in California see the group as a Republican front.
According to financial statements filed by Judicial Watch, the
organization received $800,000 in grants last year from foundations
controlled by Richard Mellon Scaife, the conservative millionaire
and Clinton critic. In Washington, the group has filed dozens of
lawsuits seeking information on subjects that include the propriety
of the release of FBI files and the selection of Democratic
contributors to participate in overseas trade missions.
</P>
<P>
   News of Judicial Watch's arrival in California has unsettled
some in Democratic legal and political circles. Adam Schiff, a
Democrat who is the chairman of the state Senate judiciary
committee and who recently held hearings on judicial independence
from other branches of government, has expressed concern about how
judges may be affected by Judicial Watch's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff's spokesman, Paul Hubler, said ``Judges shouldn't have to
be looking over their shoulder when they make legal decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he was hired to run Judicial Watch's western office,
Pendleton monitored judicial nominations and appointments for the
Free Congress Foundation, a conservative group that favors a
culture based on Judeo-Christian values.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Klayman, one of the Judicial Watch founders, said the
organization opened the California office because a large number of
its supporters are in the state and because California is at the
forefront of governmental and legal issues. ``It's an important
state when it comes to issues of judicial activism and conduct,''
Klayman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
