<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-07 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DID SCURRY CHEAT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world championship was in the balance when Briana Scurry
strode to the goal line on July 10 in the Rose Bowl. The American
goalkeeper had picked out her victim, the third Chinese player to
take a penalty kick in the shootout that would decide the Women's
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one girl _ her body language didn't look very positive,''
Scurry said later. ``It didn't look like she wanted to take it.
She'd been running on the flank and she was tired. I looked up at
her and said, `This one is mine.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing to choose which opponent was most likely to be
weak. It was another thing for Scurry to choose her tactics. By her
own admission, Scurry decided to improve her chances by ignoring
the rules of the penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   In a quick and practiced move, Scurry bolted two steps forward _
in violation of the rule _ and cut off the angle for Liu Ying, her
opponent. With superb reflexes, Scurry then dived to her left and
tipped Liu's shot wide of the goal. That one stop would shortly
give the United States the championship, and newfound fans of
soccer would admit they were teary-eyed watching Scurry's
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the poised goalkeeper has become one of the most
popular of the Yanks, but there has been a minor swell of criticism
that the Americans had to break a rule in order to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen things on the Internet,'' said another goalkeeper,
Mike Ammann of the MetroStars of Major League Soccer. ``People are
saying, `Wow, Briana Scurry cheated.' But they don't understand
that part of the game. What Briana did was perfectly normal. She
took a step and the referee didn't call it. I don't call that
cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry is on vacation, and chose not to come to the phone when
she was called the other day. But her position was staked out soon
after the final game when she told The Los Angeles Times:
``Everybody does it. It's only cheating if you get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it that simple? Has sport become so intense, so important,
that athletes can justify deviating from the rules? Is there a
difference between gamesmanship and cheating? Golfers are disgraced
if they do not penalize themselves for even an inadvertent nudge of
the ball. Baseball players are suspended if caught doctoring their
equipment. But in between there are a vast number of tactics that
are both technically illegal and widely accepted, even praised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professionalism is not sportsmanship,'' said Chili Davis, a
respected 39-year-old with the New York Yankees who is seen as a
manager in the near future. ``If you don't succeed, you won't be in
your profession for long. In our society, it's not about good or
bad. It's about who's on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're caught roughing up the ball or corking your bat,
that's cheating,'' Davis added. ``But short of that, I would do
anything I could to hit the ball 20 feet farther and help my team
win. I owe it to my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same way with phantom tags at second base. I accept
that. The infielder leaves it up to the umpire to decide. You take
your chance, and if they call it, you can't whine and moan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Dennis Rodman,'' Davis said, referring to
basketball's finest rebounder, who shoves, holds and taunts
opponents when the three referees are otherwise occupied. ``He's
one of the smartest athletes you'll ever see _ on the court. Most
of what he does is not just rebounding, it's a head game.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposing view is presented by Donna LoPiano, the director of
the Women's Sports Foundation, and a former world-level softball
pitcher as well as the former director of athletics at the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gamesmanship is just another word for cheating,'' LoPiano said
the other day. ``It's one thing for a pitcher to say to a batter,
`Would you like a changeup?' and then you throw a fastball. It's
another thing to see what you can get away with.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was at Texas, LoPiano loved teaching a course called
sports ethics for a master's degree in sports management. ``There
were always two questions everybody got wrong,'' she said. One was
about a swimmer not giving it her best in a qualifying heat. The
other was about committing an intentional foul in the closing
seconds of a basketball game. Both are against the spirit and law
of the sport, LoPiano said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the kind of split-second edge that Scurry sought against
China, LoPiano said: ``It's a perfectly legitimate reaction for the
brain to tell the body when to move. It takes 1/25th of a second to
put your body in motion. I know that because I was a base-stealer
as well as a pitcher. If you react too quickly, that's a foul, not
cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that any win that comes as a result of a decision
to cheat is tainted,'' LoPiano said. ``It has to be. But not in
some awful way. This is not about Briana Scurry, but it just points
out human frailty.''
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the criticism of the World Cup tactic has come
from Americans who do not follow soccer, and are not familiar with
the widespread pattern of cynical fouls and blatant diving in the
men's game, as well as the beleaguered mind-set of goalkeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people forget is that shooters should score 90 to 95
percent of the time on penalty kicks,'' said Ammann of the
MetroStars. ``Soccer just changed the rule this year allowing us to
move laterally before the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that, many goalkeepers would ``cheat'' to the left or
right before the ball was struck. Now they ``cheat'' going forward,
always trying to gauge how much latitude they have.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, they have plenty. Esse Baharmast, the American who
was chosen to referee several games at the 1998 men's World Cup in
France, is now the director of officials for the U.S. Soccer
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to know is that Briana Scurry is also a
referee,'' Baharmast said the other day. ``She was chosen the best
youth referee in Minnesota in 1989, and she knows the law of the
game, and she also knows how to bend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baharmast said that during the intense physical conditioning and
technical preparation for the 1998 World Cup, he was shown video
examples of offside violations and flagrant fouls, but that
referees were not specifically instructed to crack down on forward
progress by goalkeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule is already there,'' Baharmast said. ``The referees
have all the tools. I don't think players think about cheating. All
they think about is saving the goal. But if they can take a little
advantage, have a little more control, then they do it. The referee
was there, and she did not call anything, so it was not cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   With no electronic assistance in soccer, the Swiss official
relied on her eyes, her experience and her judgment. Probably in
the next year, the world soccer body, FIFA, will pass out some
videos of goalkeepers taking one step over the line. Two things are
certain: Briana Scurry made a brilliant world-level dive to tip the
ball. And the result will stand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
