<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCBOYCOTT08-COX     08-07 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCBOYCOTT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impact of NAACP boycott doubted by some Myrtle Beach businesses
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. _ Waves wash peacefully under the
weather-worn planks of Pier 14, smack in the middle of the Grand
Strand, the jewel of Palmetto State tourism.
</P>
<P>
   It's just as calm on deck. Cashier Joe Daley sells bait shrimp
for $5.50 in Styrofoam cups, and plastic bottles of water bearing
the NASCAR logo.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours away, a political storm brews at the Statehouse,
where the Confederate battle flag flutters over its penny-colored
dome. In protest, the NAACP threatens an economic boycott of the
state, the last in the country to fly the flag over its capitol.
</P>
<P>
   A $14.5 billion statewide tourist trade hangs in the balance.
The amount includes $6.7 billion spent directly on things like
hotel rooms and food in places like Myrtle Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But so far on the Grand Strand, there's been nary a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's making a lot of waves,'' Daley said after
taking a drag on his Marlboro. ``Most people think the tourists are
going to come regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Charleston, civil rights groups _ including the Southern
Christian Leadership Council based in Atlanta _ already have
canceled conventions. State tourism officials worry that anxious
professional groups will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NAACP officials acknowledged that they have collected
financial information on about a dozen lawmakers who have pushed to
keep the Confederate flag flying. They hinted that they might
advocate boycotts of businesses that have contributed to the
campaigns of those legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Myrtle Beach could become a prime target of the proposed
boycott. It generates $5 billion in tourism spending. That's more
than $1 of every three bucks spent by tourists in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Confederate flag can be a souvenir. Stars and bars
beach towels hang on tourist-shop racks next to cotton prints of
Mickey Mouse, Elvis and the Budweiser logo _ your choice for
$11.99.
</P>
<P>
   Waterfront hotels line Ocean Boulevard. So do tourists who open
their wallets for the dazzling multitude of tie-dyed-shirt shops,
Calabash seafood buffets, mini-marts, driving ranges and kiddie
amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it. That's our business. Tourism,'' said Gloria Sapp,
73, who runs the Ocean Adventures miniature-golf course, where
water the color of Windex splashes over fake rock formations.
</P>
<P>
   The smell of Sapp's microwaved lunch of broccoli and macaroni
and cheese fills her small, wood-paneled attendant's booth. She
sets her food aside as a family of five pays $6 each to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you folks?'' Sapp asks. She's had practice polishing
her tourist-friendly tone. Her family has run a business on this
spot since 1939 _ first a restaurant, then the Carolina Hotel. Out
front, two knee-high lawn jockeys are painted white. Black eyes
poke through like lumps of coal on snowmen.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp shrugs off financial consequences that may follow if the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People national
board endorses the boycott during an October meeting. The NAACP
state conference in Columbia drafted the measure, which calls for
an economic boycott starting Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks don't play that much mini-golf,'' Sapp said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other full-time residents, she retells tales about the
black bikers weekend that comes here every Memorial Day _ something
like Freaknik on Harleys. ``It's a nightmare,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A former fourth-grade teacher, Sapp offers a measured response
to civil rights groups that maintain the Confederate flag stirs up
a history of racial oppression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help what happened a hundred years ago,'' Sapp said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its Charleston counterpart, the Myrtle Beach Convention
Center _ one of the most active in the state _ has lost no business
from the flag flap.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 650,000 people attended conventions in
Myrtle Beach. They booked 167,000 room nights and spent $26.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's been made an issue here,'' said Paul
Edwards, interim general manager of the city's convention center.
``I don't want to make it sound like I'm turning a deaf ear to it,
but we haven't had any calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a group does call and says we're canceling because of this,
we'd say we're not taking a stand on the flag issue, and we hope
that you see we represent all races.''
</P>
<P>
   The state tourism department is polling regional associations to
see who might respond to the boycott.
</P>
<P>
   As for the throngs of vacationing families piling their Dodge
Caravans full of kids, golf clubs and beach balls, tourism
officials hope the boycott has the same effect as the one eight
years ago in Arizona. There, voters initially refused to approve a
Martin Luther King holiday and a civil rights boycott cost the
state a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But vacationers kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``People, when they're looking at their leisure time, don't
really think in terms of political arenas,'' said Moke McGowan,
senior director of marketing for South Carolina's Department of
Parks, Recreation and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   A relative newcomer in the convention business, Charleston has
borne the brunt of early backlash. The National Urban League,
another major civil rights group backing the boycott, canceled its
convention scheduled to be next year in Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of State Democratic Chairs, an organization for
the 50 Democratic state party chairs nationwide, considered
canceling its November meeting in Charleston. Only a request by
Gov. Jim Hodges postponed the vote to cancel. Invited speakers
include Vice President Al Gore and New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley,
both campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years, the images coming out of South Carolina
do not point to a state that is one of the leaders in terms of the
New South, whether it be the issue of objecting to women attending
The Citadel or whether it be the flag issue,'' said Bill Moore, a
political scientist at the College of Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Myrtle Beach, the smell of cocoa butter sunscreen fills
the lobby of the Breakers resort. Men with overhanging bellies and
women in two-piece bikinis check in at the front desk. General
manager Vernon Brake says he can't help but pay attention to the
boycott threat. As tourism goes, so does his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a businessman, I am greatly concerned about it,'' Brake
said. ``But I don't feel I have much impact on it. We appreciate
all our guests, but I don't feel the approach being taken is the
best way to solve it or get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking down Ocean Boulevard with his camcorder propped on his
shoulder, Everett Wicks is one of the few black tourists in Myrtle
Beach. Blacks account for only seven in every 100 South Carolina
tourists, officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, a housekeeping supervisor from Baltimore, Md., said a
boycott might make a small economic dent. But it also might turn
off people who might have weighed the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would stop right there,'' said Wicks, as he and his wife
walked up Pier 14 past a peddler of frozen ice treats. ``It's like
drawing a line in the sand. People still like coming to South
Carolina to visit. People have a right to hear what the issues are.
If someone's already decided to have a boycott, nobody will
listen.''
</P>
<P>
   But some people are. One of them is Ashby Ward, CEO of the
Myrtle Beach Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   There's wariness in town, he said. Ward notes that the NAACP
resolution calls not only for black people to avoid South Carolina
but for all people to stay away till the Confederate flag comes
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably erroneous to think that this would just cost us
some black vacationers,'' Ward said. ``It could cost us more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
