</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES ARE BEHIND BUT NOT READY TO CONCEDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How quickly they forget.
</P>
<P>
   The operator answers the telephone at Turner Field, and the
caller asks for John Schuerholz.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the name, please?''
</P>
<P>
   The caller repeats the name, and he is disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   He calls a second time, again asks for John Schuerholz. This
time he gets the line of Jim Schultz, the Atlanta Braves' public
relations director.
</P>
<P>
   They sure are spoiled in Atlanta. Fall out of first place, slip
a couple of games back in the standing, and the man who designed
the championship team of the '90s becomes a nonperson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lasted only eight years,'' Schuerholz said. ``Fame is
fleeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will find out in the next eight weeks how fleeting
their dominance of their division is. They have won seven
successive titles and appeared to be well on their way to No. 8
until their own injuries and the New York Mets got in the way.
</P>
<P>
   When they entered the weekend in second place, the Braves found
themselves behind another team this late in the season for the
first time since 1994, a season that didn't interrupt the Braves'
title run because it was never finished. In the intervening four
seasons, the Braves were out of first place, going forward, no
later than July 3, May 18, April 12 and April 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no coronations in this business,'' Schuerholz said.
``Even though we've had a great run, there's nobody at the
beginning of the season who says we crown you champions. You've got
to go do it. You have to stay healthy and have a mix of veterans
and young players. We've done that for eight years and we thought
we had done it this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves lost Andres Galarraga, their No. 1 run producer,
with cancer even before spring training. They lost Kerry
Ligtenberg, their closer, to elbow surgery before the season. And
now they have lost Javier Lopez, their good-hitting catcher, and
Odalis Perez, one of their starting pitchers, for the season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, John Smoltz, one of their trio of fine starters,
has been plagued periodically with a bad elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the perennial winners appear vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, who has guided the teams Schuerholz has put together,
refuses to accept condolences. In fact, he shrugs off questions
that suggest the Braves have any kind of problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, there's nothing wrong, there's absolutely nothing
wrong,'' the manager said stoically. ``We just have to put together
a win streak.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he quickly pointed out that the Braves have overcome
deficits before, in 1993, for example. The Braves that season were
nine and a half games behind San Francisco on Aug. 7 but won 39 of
their last 50 games, beating Colorado on the last day of the
season, while the Giants were losing to Los Angeles. The Braves
finished with 104 victories to the Giants' 103.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card didn't even exist then, so the Braves had to
finish first to reach the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is we're not worried about the Mets or the Phillies
or the Yankees,'' Cox said. ``We're just worried about ourselves.
We can't do anything about those teams until we play them. We just
worry about our own team. That's where our mind-set is.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz worked feverishly in the days leading up to last
weekend's nonwaiver trading deadline to secure reinforcements for
Cox's depleted troops. He obtained Jose Hernandez, a defensively
versatile player with some power, and Terry Mulholland, a veteran
pitcher, but he was unable to pry first baseman Fred McGriff out of
Tampa Bay's clutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some question,'' Schuerholz said, ``about whether we
could reasonably assume we could buttress up this club sufficiently
in the absence of those guys to give us a chance to win. But the
way our guys played, I felt that's the least we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   But the general manager was willing to go only so far. The Devil
Rays' asking price for McGriff was exorbitant, he felt, and he did
not make the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the acquisition of Hernandez and Mulholland, we tried to
address two areas we felt some vulnerability,'' Schuerholz said.
``We wanted to stay in the fight. We weren't ready to retire to the
corner and say it's all over. There's still some fight left in our
guys and we wanted to send in some troops to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Making no concession speech, Schuerholz said the Braves thought
it would be appropriate to end the '90s with another championship.
``I'm not delivering any eulogies here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   And for those doubters who think this is the beginning of the
end for the Braves, that there has to be a time when they don't
win, Cox said: ``This may not be the year that we don't win. We may
still win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
