<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: HOT (AND COLD) PITCHING; NO MUZZLE FOR MCRAE;
BADMOUTHING GWYNN; ANGELS FOR SALE; UMPIRES MISS THE CALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, who began the season as George Steinbrenner's fat
toad, has made the Yankees feel good by winning eight consecutive
decisions in 12 starts, dating to his last loss on May 25. Rick
Reed of the Mets has a 7-0 record in his last 11 starts, dating to
his last loss June 4.
</P>
<P>
   But neither has gone the longest without losing. Armando Reynoso
of Arizona has only one defeat in his record, and he incurred it
April 27. He has since started 16 times, winning six and emerging
with no decision 10 times. John Halama of Seattle has made 13
starts since joining the Mariners' rotation May 25, winning seven
and losing none.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the won-lost ledger, Jeff Weaver of Detroit
has gone the longest without winning, sustaining an 0-5 record in
12 starts since last gaining a victory May 27.
</P>
<P>
   An Upfront Guy
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine read something
in a newspaper article he didn't like. Brian McRae heard that
Valentine thought he was the player who had said it anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say it,'' McRae said. ``I don't work that way.
Anybody who knows me knows that I don't play that game. If I'm
going to say something, I'm going to put my name to it. I own up to
it. That's how I am and that's how I always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point was McRae's remark after a game late last season
that teams try harder to beat the Mets because they don't like
Valentine. McRae did not try to hide behind anonymity, and
Valentine didn't like the comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just repeating what I heard,'' McRae said. ``I didn't
initiate it. I'm sure that's not the first time he heard it. A lot
of teams wanted to beat us. I don't think that's anything that's
shocking news to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine no longer needs to fret about what McRae might say in
his own clubhouse. The Mets traded him to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure if I have something to say, I'm going to say it,''
McRae said, explaining his outspoken nature. ``That makes me feel
better. I'll bring things up and maybe say something that needs to
be said. Somebody's got to say it. Whatever repercussions it has,
that's fine. I feel better because I said what I thought I had to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old outfielder was asked if anyone had ever told him
his direct way might not be the best in a sport like baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said, ``but that's the way I am. I'm not going to
try to change my personality. If you talk enough, if you've been
around enough, you're going to say some things that people don't
like. There's nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Misguided About Gwynn
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz, as he was on his way out the door after his trade
to the Yankees, and some other members of the San Diego Padres were
quoted in The San Diego Union-Tribune as saying that Tony Gwynn was
a selfish player. They came across as sounding petty and jealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Tony Gwynn and I know he's not a selfish individual,''
said Frank Robinson, the Hall of Fame player. ``The people who are
saying that have to be very small-minded. Evidently they have been
teammates of Tony, but they don't know Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, Robinson noted, has played for the Padres for 18 years
even though he could have earned more money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Padre at heart,'' Robinson said. ``He lives and dies
with the Padres. To say all he's thinking about is 3,000 hits is
very small. Tony's a true professional. He wants to win,''
</P>
<P>
   And furthermore, Robinson said, ``This is great for the ballclub
to have the interest and the attention of the people and the media.
The players should be saying thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   No Fairy Tale Ending
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Mickey Mouse and Donald Duck long to decide they
don't like baseball. Or more to the point, they don't like losing
money in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has said nothing publicly, Walt Disney Co. has made
it known within baseball that it wants to sell the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The team is having a disastrous season, which has done nothing
to encourage Disney to retain the Angels. Their performance has
certainly not lured loads of fans to the ballpark. Earlier in the
season, some of the players had differences with the manager, Terry
Collins, and more recently the Angels plummeted 13 games in the
standing in 19 days.
</P>
<P>
   After Disney's initial disclosure that it wanted to sell, some
baseball people heard that Mickey and Donald might be having second
thoughts. But the ``For Sale'' sign is up, even if no one can see
it.
</P>
<P>
   Blown Call
</P>
<P>
   The umpires readily acknowledge that their mass resignation was
a tactic meant to induce baseball officials to begin bargaining for
a new labor agreement. When officials opted instead to accept some
of the resignations, the umpires cried foul. The development
prompted an observation from a New York lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just proves,'' he said, ``that the umpires still don't know
how to call a strike.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
