<SLUG> BC-FBN-ASST-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLYING THE NFL'S ASSISTANT COACHES FOR BETTER BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Kennan is one of the most important men in the National
Football League these days. He is not a coach _ although he used to
be _ or a player. And he is not a billionaire owner. If he walked
through an airport, few people would know who he was.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kennan recently played a key role in avoiding what could
have been a very ugly situation between NFL owners and the more
than 400 assistant coaches who form the backbone of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Kennan, the former New England Patriots offensive coordinator,
is head of the NFL Coaches Association, and just several years ago
the group was considering a massive strike.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches wanted improved health benefits and retirement packages,
which in some ways were highly inadequate and not in line with what
the league provided its players and game officials.
</P>
<P>
   Then Kennan took control of the group early last year. What
Kennan found was a group that remained highly skeptical that the
assistant coaches could improve their position without taking
drastic action.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennan was able to persuade the association to wait and
trust that he could make something happen through negotiations.
Kennan, with the support of the players' union, made progress
fairly quickly by using calm, intelligent arguments with the NFL
instead of hard threats.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a series of agreements between the assistants and
the NFL that were kept secret until recently. The deals have swayed
even the most radical of the assistant coaches, who now believe the
league is serious about listening to their demands.
</P>
<P>
   Many NFL assistants are unlike high-profile head coaches such as
Bill Parcells and Mike Shanahan, who receive lucrative,
incentive-laden contracts. Instead, the majority of the assistants,
like the strength coach or the person who teaches the defensive
backs, receive far less pay and may often have to worry about job
security. According to Kennan, 25 percent of all coaches are
dismissed every year. And health benefits for assistants in the
past have been mediocre at best.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kennan, the league was mostly unresponsive to the
complaints of the assistants, who then became bitter about their
situation. Last year a small number of assistants walked out of a
league-sponsored coaching seminar as a form of protest. After that,
some coaches wanted to stage further protests by wearing black
armbands during a game or file a class-action lawsuit. Others
wanted to strike.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, all of that talk seems to be in the past,
because the league has addressed many of their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   First, the NFL standardized the health and dental insurance
plans for the coaches. In the past, different teams had different
plans. One team's package was considered excellent while other
plans were severely lacking. Now there is a single policy for all
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the life insurance policy of each assistant was doubled,
to $500,000 from $250,000. Several recent deaths and long-term
illnesses of assistants may have played a factor in this agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Third, those over 65 years old who have coached in the league
from 1998 on will receive $1,200 a year toward supplemental medical
coverage. This is the only agreement coaches are not completely
happy about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the fact they did something in that area,'' one
offensive assistant said. ``But it is still kind of cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennan and the NFL are working on two remaining issues. The
coaches would like to lower the retirement age and standardize the
league's severance package.
</P>
<P>
   Once the agreements were reached, however, the league did not
inform the coaches, several of them said. The assistants had to
learn the news from Kennan.
</P>
<P>
   Kennan, commissioner Paul Tagliabue and George Young, the senior
vice president of football operations, have been the main
negotiators. Kennan said Tagliabue and Young had been honest and
open-minded and had listened to what Kennan had to say. The talks
have always been amicable.
</P>
<P>
   The league had to be extremely careful in its dealings with the
coaches. Owners and league executives feared other groups stepping
forward if they placated the coaches. What if the trainers formed a
union and started making demands? Or the office secretaries? Or the
people who get water for the players?
</P>
<P>
   The difference with the assistant coaches is that no other group
in professional football puts the same amount of time into their
jobs that the coaches do. Not even the players work 12-to-15-hour
days. Stress is a daily companion.
</P>
<P>
   Some assistants believe there remains a small chance the
association might be forced to file a class-action lawsuit against
the league if their final demands are not met, but that number is
few. There is a better chance that both sides will reach an
agreement on each issue without any sort of labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do this professionally,'' Kennan said. ``We do not
want to do anything drastic. I am listening to and believing George
Young and the commissioner. I trust them and their word.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennan is now touring training camps and spreading the word of
the agreements to the assistant coaches, fielding questions and
informing them of the next steps. He is, of course, extremely
popular these days. It is easy to understand why. &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
