<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEATLEY DIDN'T FIT IN MIAMI
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Running back Tyrone Wheatley arrived at the Miami Dolphins' camp
last week and was told by the team that his services were no longer
needed. It was probably devastating to Wheatley but, as strange as
it seems, the Dolphins were probably doing him a favor.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami coaching staff knew early in training camp that
Wheatley, a former No. 1 draft pick by the New York Giants, was not
going to make the team. The Dolphins have one of the deepest
backfields in the league, and most backs on coach Jimmy Johnson's
roster are faster and hungrier than Wheatley. So Wheatley had to
impress the coaches immediately just to have a chance to make the
team. Obviously, he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coaches were also concerned about Wheatley's lack of
aggression when running up the middle in drills, the same concern
expressed by the coaching staffs of Dan Reeves and Jim Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a difficult pro career for Wheatley, the 17th
overall pick out of the University of Michigan in 1995. When
Wheatley was drafted by the Giants, he was immediately disliked by
Reeves because the former head coach wanted running back Rashaan
Salaam instead. (Salaam has also had a career below the
expectations for him.)
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Wheatley and Fassel was not much
better. Wheatley felt Fassel never had an open mind about him, and
Fassel thought Wheatley was a complainer with a questionable work
ethic. Wheatley was once so frustrated with his lack of playing
time that he requested a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Wheatley's size _ he is 6 feet and 235 pounds _ a
team will always take a chance on him. In fact, several days after
Miami released Wheatley, the Oakland Raiders, the official home
base for wayward NFL souls, signed him to a contract.
Coincidentally, he is now a teammate of Salaam's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rod Woodson, after 47 career interceptions, 164 games and 7
Pro Bowls at cornerback, has moved to safety with the Baltimore
Ravens. He is 34 years old and age can slow even the best. But
because of his athleticism he might make another Pro Bowl after
this season _ at safety.
</P>
<P>
   _ Running back Barry Sanders might meet with William Clay Ford,
the Detroit Lions' owner, at the end of the week. Ford wants a
chance to pull Sanders out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several Giants players say they have noticed a more intense
and aggressive Jim Fassel this year in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   _ The former Giant safety Tito Wooten has signed with the
Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Six No. 1 draft picks remain unsigned, including the third
overall selection by Cincinnati, quarterback Akili Smith.
</P>
<P>
   _ Green Bay defensive tackle Gilbert Brown, who has been
criticized for his weight problems, has lost significant weight,
coach Ray Rhodes said. Neither Brown nor Rhodes is saying exactly
how much.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
