<HEADLINE>
UT TOWER, SITE OF SNIPER ATTACK, TO REOPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Texas landmark designed as a monument to
higher learning only to become infamous as a deadly sniper's perch
will reopen to the public next month amid hopes that visitors will
be more enamored with its view than curious about its violent past.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas at Austin plans to allow public tours of
the observation deck of the campus' 231-foot-high tower beginning
Sept. 16. The deck has been off-limits since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Campus officials said they hope the deck's reopening helps to
dim the memory of Aug. 1, 1966, when Eagle Scout and ex-Marine
Charles Whitman ascended to the perch and began spraying bullets
from high-powered rifles at people crossing the university's mall
and nearby city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman killed 14 people and wounded 31. Earlier in the day, he
killed his wife and his mother in their homes. He died in the tower
in a gun battle with police.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old tower was also the scene of nine other deaths,
two accidental falls and seven suicides.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, during a media tour, UT-Austin assistant vice
president Steve Kraal said the reopened deck will have adequate
safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Metal detectors will be installed and armed guards will be
stationed on the first floor and on the deck, which is being
wrapped with a stainless-steel cage-like lattice fastened to the
deck's cheek-high masonry rail.
</P>
<P>
   The lattice will ensure the deck's safety while allowing
visitors a clear view of the state Capitol, the Austin skyline and
the Texas Hill Country, Kraal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a vision of Austin you can't get from any other
place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tours will be run from 6 p.m. until dark, and all day Saturday
and Sunday. Cost will be $3 and visitors will be allowed to spend
about an hour on the observation deck.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
