u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTAL-ILLNESS-JOURNE     08-07 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-ILLNESS-JOURNEY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAYING ENDED A LONG EFFORT TO SAVE A MENTALLY ILL WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos of Susan Fuchs and her brother are being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She was the child of Holocaust survivors, born in
Brooklyn on Christmas Eve of 1959 with good looks, keen
intelligence and a big brother determined to protect her from all
the evil in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But when her battered body was found in Central Park on July 22
this year, the police identified Susan Fuchs by a food stamp card
and said her last address was a homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Her descent from middle-class promise to violent death at
society's margins was part of a 20-year journey through the New
York mental health system. In the end, family members maintain, the
system failed her, accepting her resistance to treatment though it
was symptomatic of her mental illness, and frustrating their own
desperate efforts to keep her safe.
</P>
<P>
   The case also underlines how difficult it can be to help the
most severely mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Public concern over the dangerously mentally ill spurred Gov.
George Pataki and state lawmakers to agree last week on legislation
giving the courts new authority to order former mental patients to
comply with treatment or face re-hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the lobbying for the new law focused on mental patients
charged with crimes, but Susan Fuchs herself _ repeatedly
hospitalized against her will, deeply resistant to taking
medication, and tracked by relatives ready to try anything to help
her _ also seemed to be an obvious candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fuchs, who was 13 when his sister was born, and his wife,
Gloria, say they would have used the law if it had been enacted
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a close look at Susan Fuchs' troubled history, through
interviews, court records and hospital documents, suggests that
even in her case, the practical effects of the law would have been
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Susan Fuchs cycled through psychiatric wards,
assisted-living programs, emergency rooms and homeless shelters,
laws intended to protect mental patients were ignored at crucial
points, and a hard-line policy of patient confidentiality made it
hard for relatives even to find her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there was going to be a disaster,'' Gloria Fuchs said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fuchs had covered a table in their antiques store on
Atlantic Avenue with a jumble of documents and notes compiled in
their 20-year battle to save Susan Fuchs: court orders,
correspondence from doctors, hospitals and insurance companies, her
Regents scholarship award, her first suicide note.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Susan Fuchs disappeared, she was injured, said her
brother, a former high school teacher with a graying ponytail who
founded his antiques and carpentry business with his wife 20 years
ago, when their own daughter was born _ and just before his smart,
pretty sister fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Fuchs graduated as a math major from SUNY-Binghamton
despite serious symptoms of mental illness beginning at 15, despite
a major breakdown in college. She kept spiraling downward, caught
in the grip of ``a bipolar affective disorder, manic, severe with
psychotic features,'' in the words of a doctor's diagnosis in a
Feb. 12, 1991, court affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Courts repeatedly found her a danger to herself or others and
committed her for involuntary hospital treatment and medication,
but only when someone knew or cared enough to make her madness a
legal matter. And when Susan rejected her family members, in part
for their role in her commitments, in part because of her paranoid
delusions, the system helped her disappear into the streets, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, relatives do not have to wait for a family
member with such a history to become dangerous before petitioning
the court to order the person to submit to outpatient treatment or
face commitment. But the person still would have to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Susan Fuchs was discharged from one of the dozen
private and public psychiatric hospitals that treated her, Gloria
Fuchs called social workers, psychiatrists, nurses and homeless
shelter clerks in an effort to find her, hunting for a weak link in
the chain of patient confidentiality that shut the family out.
</P>
<P>
   Once, in 1996, they discovered her in a homeless shelter in
Canarsie, Brooklyn, naked, bruised and delusional, her clothes
stolen by other shelter residents. Another time, about two years
ago, she walked into their antiques store, barefoot, distraught and
covered with sores.
</P>
<P>
   Four months before her death, they waited with her until 4 a.m.
in the emergency room of Maimonides Medical Center in Brooklyn to
secure her psychiatric admission, after she had declared that she
had no family, because aliens had taken over her relatives' bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital discharged her at her request within a week rather
than seeking a court-ordered commitment, releasing her to an
address it would not tell the family, her brother said. Police
investigators now say it was a homeless shelter, though an appeals
court ruling in 1993 bar transfers to shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to abide by the hospital's policy of protecting
patient confidentiality,'' Eileen Tynan, a spokeswoman for
Maimonides, said in declining to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   The new law allows a judge to order a patient like Susan Fuchs
into the hospital for a 24-hour assessment by doctors to determine
if court-ordered outpatient treatment is suitable. But if the
patient refuses to comply with its terms, a doctor could put the
patient in the hospital involuntarily for a maximum of 72 hours.
For a longer commitment, the old standard of dangerous behavior
must be met.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Fuchs' delusions had repeatedly proved dangerous. When she
had an apartment, she set small fires to burn ``secret papers,''
according to a doctor's court affidavit. More recently, emergency
room records show, she inflicted injuries on her own face until she
was black and blue.
</P>
<P>
   On that occasion, in January of this year, a nurse at New York
Methodist Hospital summoned Tom Fuchs, telling him his sister had
been in a padded observation room in the emergency room for three
days. No psychiatric beds were available, and doctors said she was
too psychotic to release, Methodist Hospital officials confirm.
Fuchs signed her out and drove her to Maimonides hospital himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Maimonides, which obtained a 60-day court order of
involuntary commitment after that episode, discharged her as soon
as the order expired _ to the apartment of a woman who had herself
been released from a mental ward only 48 hours earlier, the Fuchses
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was insane, like a Kafka play,'' Fuchs recalled, adding
that by the time they discovered the address a few days later,
Susan had moved on.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``That does not constitute a proper discharge in any way, shape
or form,'' said Shelley Nortz, director of policy for the Coalition
for the Homeless, which won a class-action lawsuit against what she
called ``patient dumping'' in 1993. Under law, she added, New York
Methodist itself should have transported the patient to another
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Financial pressures have quickened discharges, and made
hospitals less likely to try to renew involuntary commitments, said
Barbara Jones, a lawyer for Mental Hygiene Legal Services, which
represents patients at commitment hearings. ``Even when we're
advocates for the patients who want to leave, we're sometimes sorry
the facility didn't try to keep them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   State hospitals are under pressure, too, she said. Since the
mid-1990s, when Susan Fuchs was treated at the South Beach State
Psychiatric Center on Staten Island, the population of such state
centers has been cut by 40 percent, to 6,000. For outpatient
services, like case managers who can monitor difficult patients,
waiting lists have grown.
</P>
<P>
   Studies of outpatient commitment have found that patients with
good outpatient services did equally well with or without a court
order. The new law's budget, $40 million, is mainly for medication.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Fuchs had long rejected psychotropic drugs, which can be
heavily sedating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a vegetable on medication,'' she wrote in the early 1980s
before leaping into the Hudson in a suicide attempt. ``I can't
think. I can't read. I can't enjoy anything. ... I can't live
without my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   That time, someone pulled her from the water. This year, Tom and
Gloria Fuchs wanted to put her in a hospital long enough to try
newer drugs, or at least to keep her from predators. ``A woman
alone, deranged, wandering on the street without her glasses, so
myopic she couldn't even read a street sign _ she's just going to
get hurt,'' her brother said.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Fuchs was an adult, and they were not even her
parents. Her mother, Miriam Fuchs, a 77-year-old Auschwitz survivor
who declined to be interviewed, lives half the year in Florida. Her
father, Philip, died more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   From Susan's perspective, moreover, the system did not promise
safety. Her brother said she had been sexually assaulted in
psychiatric units by other patients.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, the Fuchses caught up with her as she picked up
documents at Services for the Underserved, a nonprofit agency that
sponsors the supervised-living program that she had left in
January, after battering her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look like my family but their bodies have been taken over
by others,'' she told a social worker there, according to Gloria
Fuchs' notes. The social worker called the police and an ambulance
to take her back to Maimonides.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, the Fuchses retained a lawyer to draw up a petition
under a recent guardianship law, asking the court to rule her
mentally incapacitated _ a procedure that would cost several
thousand dollars, and that required Susan Fuchs to be served with
papers.
</P>
<P>
   But she was already gone again. Maimonides had not sought a
court commitment this time. The Fuchses were outraged. No hospital
knew the severity of Susan Fuchs' illness better than Maimonides,
they say. Marvin H. Lipkowitz, the chief of psychiatry, had been
one of her first doctors. Gloria Fuchs appealed to him.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled him as telling her: ``People like you in this
situation have long abandoned their mentally ill relatives. I think
you should explore in yourself why you are still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the exchange, the psychiatrist responded, ``I may
have said something like that.'' But he stressed that he had not
meant his remarks critically. ``I was left admiring the woman,'' he
said. ``Her involvement was very prolonged and had been met by all
sorts of rejection. Many families simply abandon the case.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the hospital that abandoned Susan, Gloria
Fuchs contends, and she feels the issue was money. In the emergency
room just before that last, brief hospitalization, she said,
hospital employees realized that private insurance had lapsed.
Susan Fuchs' mother had dropped the $160 monthly premium, Tom Fuchs
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No patient gets treated differently because of the financial
coverage,'' Lipkowitz countered. ``The general rtle is that when a
tragedy in life occurs somebody has to be blamed. I am truly sorry.
I feel for these people.'' But he added, ``You have only half the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   In bipolar disorders, he said, ``The individual who can be quite
psychotic at some times can become quite normal at another time.
You cannot force medication on someone who does not seem obviously
psychotic.''
</P>
<P>
   To Gloria Fuchs, his responses amounted to telling them to wait
until the next time Susan got hurt. Then, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   On July 22, at 2 a.m., several people heard a woman screaming in
Central Park but did not call the police. At 11 a.m. Susan Fuchs'
half-naked body was found there, her head smashed in with a rock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
