<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COUPLE-CRUSHED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLDING HANDS, THEN A TORRENT OF BRICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPLEWOOD, N.J. _ They had walked the tree-lined streets of this
town for most of their lives, raising their family in a 2 1/2 story
home not far from the main drag and choosing to remain after their
two children had grown up.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Shire had recently marked his 75th birthday at a family
celebration arranged by his wife, Phyllis. Neighbors dropped by
with champagne, toasting the couple's closeness and the years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the Shires left to take their usual walk down
Maplewood Avenue, holding hands in the cool breeze. As they passed
Bill and Harry's Chinese restaurant shortly before 7 p.m., there
was the sound of a crack, and a section of the building's brick
facade came tumbling down.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Shire, 67, was killed instantly, according to police, and
Shire was critically injured by the debris that fell from the
facade. He remained in critical but stable condition Saturday at
University Hospital in Newark, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not know what caused the torrent of bricks to give
way. ``Engineers will have to check to see what if anything was
wrong with the building,'' said Maplewood Police Director Paul
Gizzo.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the phone at the home of the building's
owner, identified by police as Harold Bobrow, said he would not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, neighbors stood by the buttressed facade, some leaving
flowers near where the couple had fallen, others speaking of the
perfect love the Shires shared.
</P>
<P>
   They were lovebirds, a devoted couple who were always holding
hands, said Pat Ross, co-owner of the real estate company next door
to where the accident occurred. ``You would see them almost every
night: he wearing his hat and she nicely dressed for their
stroll.''
</P>
<P>
   According to their neighbors, Shire was a psychologist and Mrs.
Shire often sold antiques. The couple, who had celebrated their
47th anniversary in June, took a trip to Europe every year in the
late summer, neighbors said. Last summer it was Italy. On Monday or
Tuesday, they were to leave for a trip to the Netherlands,
relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just seemed to be gloriously happy,'' said Linda
Kraushar, their next-door neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The couple were on their way to the Maplewood Theater to see
``The Thomas Crown Affair'' when the accident occurred. At the
time, the street was crowded with people walking to dinner or to
the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us were in the pizza parlor just by there when we
heard the crash and all these people came screaming in, `The
building's exploded,''' said Elaine Bloom, 55, who was also on her
way to the theater. ``We all ran outside and everyone was trying to
pull bricks off this elderly man and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was finally able to sit up but she never moved,'' Ms. Bloom
said, shaking her head. ``It's amazing more people weren't hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
