<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI PLAYS DOWN TEPIDNESS OF PATAKI'S ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after receiving an endorsement from Gov. George
Pataki that was noticeably lacking in political fanfare, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani said Saturday that the governor's support would
provide an important bulwark in his anticipated run for the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said at a City Hall briefing that the endorsement on
Friday, in which Pataki urged the mayor's major Republican rival to
drop out of the race, would prevent damaging divisions within New
York state's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the romantics and political spinning that goes on,
providing unity within the Republican Party is what is important,''
Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is really important for New York is to have a Republican
elected to the Senate,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the seemingly subdued nature of Pataki's statement,
in which he said the mayor had ``earned the right'' to receive the
backing of the state's Republican Party, Giuliani voiced no
dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate very much the governor's support, and I look
forward to working with him,'' Giuliani said, adding that he and
the governor had had ``a fairly lengthy conversation'' in recent
weeks about the prospect of his run for the seat being vacated by
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat. He declined to specify when
that conversation had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the governor had called him on Friday morning to
tell him of his decision to make a statement of support,
effectively withdrawing his backing from Rick Lazio, the Long
Island congressman widely regarded as Giuliani's chief opponent
within the party.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani dismissed suggestions that Pataki's endorsement could
have been stronger or had more impact on voters, since it was made
with little advance notice on a Friday afternoon in August when
many are preoccupied with weekend travel or other summer
activities. Speculation about the governor's timing ``is just
political spin,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   And he said nothing would have been gained if the governor had
orchestrated his statement in the fashion of most high-profile
political endorsements, with the bestower of support standing
shoulder-to-shoulder with the grateful candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he did it just the right way,'' Giuliani said. ``It
is far more forceful if somebody just stands up and announces his
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has so far declined to respond to the governor's
announcement. But through a spokeswoman, Mollie Conkey, he said
Saturday that had no intention of withdrawing from the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Long, chairman of the New York state Conservative party,
a group whose support has long been regarded as critical to
Republican Party candidates in the state, said he had talked
briefly with Lazio about the governor's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not tickled pink, certainly not a happy camper,'' Long
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani acknowledged Saturday that the governor's endorsement
was certain to create temporary tensions within the Republican
party, but he described the strain as inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may take three months, four months or into next year, but
there will be unity within the Republican Party,'' he said, adding
that such unity was crucial as part of an overriding theme in his
campaign that a Republican senator, joining a Senate in which
Republicans now have a majority, would benefit New York state
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also characterized the competition between him and
Lazio as a reflection of ``strength and a diversity of talent''
within the state's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   And with that, the mayor segued into a criticism of his
anticipated Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats can't even produce a candidate from this
state,'' he said. ``The Democrats must be in pretty bad shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
