<HEADER>
A9355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERROR-TRIAL-KORAN-64     08-07 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-TRIAL-KORAN-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEOLOGICAL DISCUSSION ON TESTIFYING EMERGES IN TERRORISM CASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Va.)  (rk) 
 By   BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In refusing on Thursday to release a Florida man
jailed for declining to testify before a grand jury investigating
the bombings of the U.S. Embassies in Africa last August, a federal
judge cited an unusual source: the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hide not testimony,'' wrote Judge Robert P. Patterson Jr. of
U.S. District Court in Manhattan. ``He who hideth it, verily his
heart is sinful. Allah is aware of what ye do.''
</P>
<P>
   The reluctant witness, Ihab M. Ali, 36, of Orlando, Fla., had
told Patterson that the Koran taught Muslims to do nothing that
``will cause harm to innocents.'' Testifying, he said, would be
regarded by his community as ``a major sin'' and ``a betrayal of
our beliefs as Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, of course, sharply disagreed. In one hearing
last month, a federal prosecutor, Patrick J. Fitzgerald, read aloud
from the Koran, quoting its admonition not to hide testimony, and
another that ``witnesses must not refuse when they are summoned.''
</P>
<P>
   If the proceedings before Patterson began to sound like a
religious studies seminar, it was not surprising. The contempt case
_ the first known to have occurred in the investigation of Osama
bin Laden, who authorities suspect is the mastermind of the
bombings _ has touched on the sensitive issue of how the government
treats Muslims in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have charged that the government's investigation
into terrorism has unfairly targeted Muslims, an assertion the
government roundly denies.
</P>
<P>
   The government has not said why it wants to question Ali. The
most recent indictment in the case shows that prosecutors suspect
that some of bin Laden's associates have been active in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Ali told Patterson that his refusal to testify was rooted in his
distrust of the government, transcripts show, and he said that his
view was reinforced by the depiction of Muslims in news reports and
in entertainment media. He cited the movie ``The Siege,'' which he
said ``stereotyped Muslims always as being terrorists,
fundamentalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts on Islamic law said they disagreed with Ali's
interpretation of the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   One noted scholar, Khaled Abou El Fadl, who teaches at the
University of California at Los Angeles School of Law, said he
tended to agree that federal law enforcement discriminated against
Muslims. But he added, ``The Koran specifically says that even if
the testimony is going to lead to harming someone, as long as it's
the truth, you must say it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mohammed Al Hanooti, an imam at a mosque in Falls Church,
Va., disagreed. He testified last month in support of Ali, telling
Patterson that Islamic law ``gives him the right to abstain from
giving testimony in case it hurts him or it hurts any other
Muslim.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali, who is being held in a small ninth-floor cell in the
Metropolitan Correctional Center, segregated from the general jail
population, told the judge that further confinement would not
change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather endure the punishment in this world,'' he said,
``in jail or under any conditions, rather than go endure the
punishment in the hereafter, which is everlasting. This is my deep
belief.''
</P>
<P>
   In one hearing last month, the prosecutor, Fitzgerald, tried to
undermine Ali's position with a series of questions about
hypothetical situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw a non-Muslim person kill a Muslim,'' Fitzgerald
asked, ``would you testify about that in an American courtroom?''
Ali said he would. In several other scenarios outlined by the
prosecutor, Ali also agreed that he would probably testify.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald asked how Ali reconciled those responses with his
refusal to cooperate in the investigation of the embassy bombings,
which killed 223 people, including Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's different,'' Ali said, ``because here you have
Muslims of all different nationalities or different countries being
targeted.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In refusing to release Ali, Patterson wrote that he hoped that
more jail time would encourage Ali to reconsider his position. On
the civil contempt charge, Ali may be held for up to 18 months, and
possibly longer, unless the judge concludes he will not change his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the judge and the witness appear at loggerheads
in interpreting the Koran. At one point, Ali told the judge that he
was afraid that if he testified, his family, who live in Egypt,
might be harmed by bin Laden. He said the government's offer of the
witness protection program was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever protection they might offer, no matter how grand it
may be,'' Ali said, ``I doubt very much that they will give me
protection on the day of judgment, when I'm confronted with my
Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson reminded Ali that the grand jury was secret, and that
his testimony would not be disclosed. But Ali noted that when he
was first held in contempt during a secret appearance in U.S.
District Court in May, a newspaper article quickly reported it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, Patterson suggested, the issue of his family's
protection was then moot. ``I don't know whether they use this
expression in Egypt,'' the judge said, ``but it seems to me the
water is over the dam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope not,'' Ali replied. ``Otherwise, millions will
drown.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge tried to make his point slightly differently. ``Maybe
I should say the horse is out of the barn,'' he said, saying he
could not see how unjust harm could come from truthful testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But Ali remained undeterred. ``I stand by my reasons,'' he said.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
