</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AFRICA-ILLICIT-DIAMONDS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY TRY TO CURB DIAMOND TRADE THAT FUELS AFRICAN WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo note.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concerned that diamonds are financing and
perpetuating wars in Africa, the Clinton administration is
considering actions aimed at halting the illicit-diamond trade,
administration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of uncut diamonds from rebel-held mines to market
centers around the world _ valued at hundreds of millions of
dollars a year _ is keeping rebel armies in Angola, Congo and
Sierra Leone supplied with tanks and assault rifles and even
uniforms and beer, U.S. and European officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Control of these mines has been an obstacle to peace efforts in
African hot spots, and officials hope that by cutting off the
gray-market diamond trade they can also choke off the flow of arms,
stop the endless killing and hasten peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds are not the only way in which rebels pay for weapons,
but experts in Africa and the trade say cutting it off would have a
substantial impact.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is likely to propose a global marketing
system, by which diamond sales must be accompanied by documents
declaring the source of the precious stones and their destination.
</P>
<P>
   From the fields in Africa, diamonds reach dealers in Belgium,
Israel and Ukraine, where the unscrupulous turn the ready cash into
weapons. The largest weapons pipeline into Africa is controlled by
Russian organized crime figures who work with diamond brokers, U.S.
and European officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight years, the Angolan rebel organization, known
as Unita, has raised $3 billion to $4 billion from diamond sales,
according to a recent report by a U.N. committee on Angolan
sanctions. An arduously worked-out peace accord for that country
collapsed late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The brutal war in Sierra Leone, which left thousands maimed and
mutilated, was prolonged by at least 18 months because of the
ability of the rebels to quickly trade diamonds for arms, an
administration official said last week. A delicate agreement ending
that war was signed in July.
</P>
<P>
   At the middle levels of the State Department, the African
diamonds-for-weapons trade has been under study for several years.
But the problem has not penetrated more senior levels because wars
in Africa are not generally seen as affecting America's strategic
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after an intelligence study, which had been slow in coming,
illustrated how the trade works to perpetuate rebellion in Africa,
top administration officials appear to be ready to back a plan that
would try to regulate the diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how such a marketing regime would be implemented in
various African nations and European diamond centers is undecided,
officials say. It could take the form of a U.N. program, a
multilateral treaty or a voluntary agreement within the diamond
industry.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to be an idea that is gaining support outside
government channels. Human rights organizations, including those
that led the campaign to ban land mines, are now talking about a
public education campaign aimed at highlighting the
diamonds-for-weapons trade.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the world's largest diamond company, DeBeers
Consolidated Mines Ltd., said in an interview that it would support
tighter controls on the trade. DeBeers, which controls about 70
percent of the world's diamond sales, views the growing flow of
illicit diamonds as a potential threat to its ability to influence
prices.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Its support would surely be welcomed by the administration,
which had expected DeBeers to resist any move to regulate the
market since the company has done quite well under the current
system.
</P>
<P>
   DeBeers has repeatedly maintained that it does not buy illicit
diamonds, a claim that U.S. and British officials dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all for it,'' a DeBeers spokesman in London, Andrew
Lamont, said about any proposal that the administration might
advance to strengthen controls on the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suits our interests,'' he added. ``The illicit trade only
serves to destabilize the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamont added that he thought the countries of southern Africa
whose economies are heavily dependent on diamond sales _ Botswana,
Namibia and South Africa _ would also welcome more stringent
controls on the trade.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Belgium, which has resisted entreaties from the Clinton
administration to crack down on the gray-market diamond merchants,
appears to be changing its attitude. In Antwerp, the diamond
trading center of Europe, officials have asked for help from U.S.
law enforcement agencies to combat the growing power of Russian
organized crime figures, who launder money through diamond
merchants, according to U.S. officials in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The diamond trade, which is highly secretive and governed by
informal arrangements, has been difficult to regulate. A U.N.
embargo against buying diamonds from Unita, the Angolan rebel
movement, has been largely ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamond revenues constitute the essential component of Unita's
capacity to wage war,'' Robert R. Fowler, Canada's ambassador to
the United Nations, wrote in a recent report to the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is reluctant to talk publicly about
what steps it is considering to curb the diamond trade in order to
avoid the perception that a regulatory regime would be imposed on
African states by the powerful West, said an administration
official who spoke on the condition of anonymity. Britain is also
supportive of tighter controls and is working with the
administration on proposals, U.S. and British officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1619EDT &QL; 
