<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.Y.-POLICE-BRUTALITY     08-07 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-POLICE-BRUTALITY-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BY CONVICTED OFFICER'S WIFE ATTACKS LOUIMA VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
 (js) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Charles Schwarz spends 23 hours a day alone in a
small Manhattan jail cell, his wife and other relatives are
mounting a campaign maintaining that he was wrongly convicted of
helping a fellow police officer torture Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Andra Schwarz says, is to supplement the legal
arguments that her husband's lawyers plan to make in appealing his
conviction two months ago in a trial involving a case of horrific
police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the public knows and believes in us, it will be easier for
judges to see that something happened that shouldn't have
happened,'' said Mrs. Schwarz, 39, referring to the jury's verdict.
She contends that her husband's trial was unfair because the jury
did not hear all the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I write letters and reach out'' to labor unions,
national police groups, clergy members and other individuals and
organizations, she said, describing an effort to gain support for
rallies and prayer vigils that the family hopes to hold in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a full-time job,'' Ms. Schwarz said Friday, explaining
why she had not returned to her job as a paralegal at a Manhattan
law firm since the trial in federal court in Brooklyn ended June 8.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury convicted him of having joined in depriving
Louima of his civil rights, Schwarz was immediately taken to jail
to await being sentenced to as much as life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Schwarz and her husband's lawyer, Stephen C. Worth, said
that Schwarz was locked in a 6-foot-by-9-foot cell at the
Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan for 23 hours a day on
weekdays and for 24 hours on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Worth said his client was kept isolated from the general jail
population for his own protection. Former police officers are
generally segregated because they are considered prime targets for
assault by other inmates, especially if they have achieved a high
level of notoriety. Although Schwarz and his co-defendant, Justin
A. Volpe, are on the same floor, they ``don't see each other,''
Worth said.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors who convicted Schwarz found that in August 1997, he
held Louima down in a bathroom of the 70th Precinct station house
while Volpe, also an officer at the time, rammed a stick into
Louima's rectum. Louima had been arrested in a street brawl in
which the officers mistakenly thought he had punched Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Louima suffered severe internal injuries in the attack, which
set off a furor that drew national attention and was racially
suffused because Louima, a Haitian immigrant, is black and the
officers are white.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe pleaded guilty during the trial, but Schwarz maintained
his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   And Schwarz still maintains that innocence, his wife said
Friday. ``The system failed him,'' she asserted, calling his trial
``a travesty'' because the jury had not heard an account from Volpe
that exonerated him.
</P>
<P>
   She was reflecting an argument that has been advanced by his
lawyers, but rejected by the trial judge as well as by prosecutors.
The argument, ``to put it charitably, lacks merit,'' the judge,
Eugene H. Nickerson, said a week and a half ago as he refused to
dismiss the conviction.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Volpe, too, faces up to life in prison. Sentencing dates have
not been set for either man. Both were dismissed from the police
force when they were convicted. And Schwarz faces a second trial on
a charge that he and two other officers conspired to obstruct
justice by lying to investigators about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Louima testified at the first trial that the driver of the
police car that brought him to the station house _ Schwarz,
according to police records _ held him down in the bathroom. Two
other officers testified that they saw Schwarz walk Louima,
handcuffed and with his pants down, toward the bathroom. The
prosecution said such evidence left no reasonable doubt of
Schwarz's guilt, but Worth argued that Louima and one of the other
officers had lied and that the second officer's testimony was
inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   The jury did not learn that Volpe, through his lawyer, told
prosecutors during the trial that Schwarz had not participated in
the torture. But Nickerson ruled that this was because Worth had
made a ``tactical decision'' not to call Volpe as a witness, and
thus the jury's lack of knowledge on this point was not grounds for
dismissing the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Schwarz was not persuaded. ``You can make all the legal
arguments about tactics,'' but her husband did not receive a fair
trial, she insisted Friday. ``We are not going to give up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
