<SLUG> BC-NJ-BRUSH-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUSH FIRES MULTIPLY IN PARCHED NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The drought in New Jersey has turned brush into
kindling along roads and railroad lines, and in forests and parks,
as a surge in unusually large brush fires has caused extensive
traffic and rail delays and further diminished the state's
dwindling water supply.
</P>
<P>
   William Cane, the director of the state's Division of Fire
Safety, said there were 444 brush fires in the state last month,
but only 171 in July last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rainfall has been below normal each month so far this year, and
during that period the state has had 1,557 brush fires, but it had
only 975 in the comparable period last year, said Cane, whose
agency monitors the state's 750 local fire departments as well as
firefighters working in state parks and forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a marked increase in fires because it doesn't
take very much to get them started,'' Cane said. ``Thank God, we
haven't had a major disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Plante, assistant division warden with the state Division
of Parks and Forestry, said that because of the drought, the brush
fires were larger than usual and burned longer. Last year the brush
fires averaged about a half-acre, and this year they are five times
that size, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when it is this dry,'' he said, ``it takes a lot more
water to put them out. Under normal conditions a two-acre fire
would require 1,000 gallons to extinguish. But we have had to put
100,000 gallons on some of them because of the depth of turf
problem below the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Plante explained that the drought had penetrated far below the
surface, especially in the state's expansive peat bogs and the
watershed over the 3 million acres his agency monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Fires on such deeply parched land can smolder for days, he said,
threatening any time to burst back into flame. To control such
fires, he said, firefighters must often lay temporary sprinklers to
keep an area wet for as long as 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of breezes is one thing that has helped keep
things from getting out of hand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brush fires have caused many delays in recent weeks along the
state's commuter rail lines and Amtrak's Northeast Corridor, said
Kenneth Miller, a spokesman for New Jersey Transit. When such fires
start, he said, local firefighters alert train dispatchers, who
hold up trains to prevent them from being damaged or endangering
firefighters working close to the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   On many days in July there were scattered brush fires near rail
lines almost daily, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On July 26 we had three, and that's unusual,'' said Miller.
``On Aug. 5 we had one in Ridgewood on the Bergen County Line that
delayed nine trains from nine minutes to 43 minutes during the
morning rush hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Cane, the state fire official, said fires were frequently caused
by discarded cigarettes, by sparks thrown from train brakes or by
hot metal parts of cars and trains touching dry brush beside roads
and railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 days ago, Plante said, a driver towed a trailer along
Interstate 80 in the far western part of the state, unaware that
one of the trailer tires was flat and that its wheel rim was
scraping the ground and sending off sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were starting little fires all along the roadside and
didn't know it,'' Plante said. ``When we can prove exactly how such
fires started, we will send the people a bill to cover the cost of
putting it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
