</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CLARIDGE-CASINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL CASINO FALTERS IN THE LAND OF THE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ Almost everybody in town _ from blackjack
dealers to retiree gamblers to the men who push the rolling chairs
along the Boardwalk _ has heard about the financial problems at the
Claridge, the smallest of the casinos, which touts itself as the
friendliest.
</P>
<P>
   But in a place that survives on stubborn optimism, many people
insist that things could get better for the Claridge, which, in
1981, was among the first casinos to open, and which recently
announced that it was planning to file for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Atlantic City casinos have gone or are going through
reorganization, even though the industry is booming _ gambling
revenues here have gone up every year since casinos arrived two
decades ago. And in that time, only one casino has actually gone
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't too much of a surprise,'' said Lucille Pagach of
Toms River, who had come here the night before to gamble with
friends and had heard about the Claridge's troubles. ``A lot of
these hotels go into reorganization.''
</P>
<P>
   But gambling in Atlantic City today is not what it was when it
was legalized here in 1978, and industry analysts and others say
the Claridge will have to make several major changes to its small,
aging property to compete with its far bigger, far richer rivals in
an ever-more-competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   For the city's smallest casino, just off the Boardwalk in the
shadow of its giant, glitzy neighbors, the trends do not bode well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the Claridge shutting its doors and getting out of
the gaming industry altogether,'' said Michael Pollock, publisher
of Michael Pollock's Gaming Industry Observer, a newsletter that
tracks gambling trends. ``But I do see it'll need at a minimum a
large infusion of capital and to become a part of a larger gaming
company. It's swimming against a large consolidation tide.''
</P>
<P>
   The week before last, Claridge Hotel and Casino Corp., the
casino's owner, missed a deadline for a $5 million interest payment
on its debt, an $85 million mortgage taken out in 1994 in the form
of bonds to pay for expansion. The company plans to file a Chapter
11 reorganization petition, which will free it from the threat of
creditors' lawsuits pending the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   The owners also reported that the casino lost $269,000 from
April through June and lost a total of $1.5 million for the first
six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Casino officials, however, have said they are optimistic about
securing new investors who can plow more money into the company,
and they have assured their 2,200 employees that no layoffs are in
the offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process we're going through is the process established
under the law for a company to have time to do the kinds of things
you have to do to prevent going out of business, and they are not a
precursor to going out of business,'' said Robert Renneisen,
chairman and chief executive of the Claridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Claridge opened as a hotel in 1931, when Atlantic City was a
seaside playground for the middle class, in a stately red-brick
building facing the ocean. It limped through the 1970s, when many
businesses were suffering in this city in decline, until opening a
casino at the start of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many years later, Atlantic City has a dozen casinos, a new
convention center, a spruced-up entry from the new Atlantic City
expressway and a highway tunnel under construction to connect the
marina area to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The city's gambling revenues are even higher than those of Las
Vegas _ $4 billion in 1998 compared with $3.2 billion from Las
Vegas, according to the state casino commissions in both places.
(Las Vegas, however, earns more revenue from nongambling sources,
like entertainment, hotel-room receipts and other retail
enterprises.)
</P>
<P>
   Several casinos have been renovated in the last few years,
bracing for competition from two mega-casinos that are expected to
open soon. But many casino operators said they hoped that if the
bigger casinos lured more tourists for longer visits, every casino
would benefit.
</P>
<P>
   But as the game changes, it will be tougher for the smaller
players to compete. The Claridge's cash flow for the last 12 months
was about $8.5 million, compared with the Trump Taj Mahal's $131
million. Besides its smaller size, the Claridge also has to contend
with not being directly on the Boardwalk. It is about a city block
away, past a park, which makes it easy for some patrons to ignore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1626EDT &QL; 
