<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9389 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-RACE-MOMS-MORTALITY     08-07 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RACE-MOMS-MORTALITY-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL DISPARITY: BLACK WOMEN DIE MORE OFTEN IN CHILDBIRTH
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to delete photo note)  
 (ATTN: Conn., D.C., Ga., Mo.)  (Eds: Kristiina in 3rd-to-last cq.) 
(nk) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eight months pregnant, Deborah Edwards smoothed a
thin hospital gown over her bulging belly, nibbled at a graham
cracker and ticked off the reasons she had spent a week confined to
the maternity ward of George Washington University Hospital here.
</P>
<P>
   At 42 she is, in medical parlance, of ``advanced maternal age.''
She had no prenatal care until last month: after 20 years of
marriage and two adopted children, she had no idea she was
pregnant. She weighs 208 pounds, up from 196. She has diabetes,
which puts her baby in danger. And her high blood pressure has
worsened into pre-eclampsia, a condition that could kill her if it
is not carefully monitored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned,'' she said, ``but I'm not worried. I know I'm
being cared for.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a good thing, because Mrs. Edwards possesses another
characteristic that statistically puts her at risk during delivery:
She is black.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the Clinton administration has set a goal of
eliminating racial disparities in health by the year 2010, medical
experts are struggling to understand one of the most glaring, and
least talked about, disparities of all: death in childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   In a study made public this spring, the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta reported that black women in the
United States were nearly four times as likely to die during
delivery, or shortly thereafter, as white women. The disparity,
which has remained about the same for the last four decades, holds
true even for women who, like Mrs. Edwards, are middle class and
have health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The findings _ coupled with the awareness-raising efforts of a
Connecticut man whose wife died in child birth _ have renewed
interest among scientists and legislators in a problem that many
people think no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also making for strange political bedfellows in
Washington. On Tuesday, Reps. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., and Jo Ann
Emerson, R-Mo., convened a panel of doctors, women's health
advocates and CDC officials to discuss maternal mortality and
garner support for a bill, introduced in June, that would provide
additional federal money to study it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get together, whether Democrat or Republican,
pro-choice or pro-life, white or black,'' Ms. Lowey said, ``to get
the best research, the comprehensive data, the right programs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dying in childbirth, in this country at least, is still
extremely rare. But several facts trouble federal health officials.
First, while infant mortality has declined steadily over the last
decade, maternal deaths have remained unchanged, and experts think
as many as 70 percent could be prevented. Second, the 4-to-1 racial
disparity in maternal deaths is among the greatest gaps in public
health. (The gap is narrower for more common problems, including
infant mortality.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the most recent year for which statistics are
available, 327 women died in childbirth in the United States. When
the CDC examined deaths over a nine-year period, from 1987 to 1996,
it found that one black woman died for every 5,102 who gave birth;
among white women, the figure was one in 18,868. While the deaths
are few, said Dr. David Satcher, the U.S. surgeon general, ``the
disparity is important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were comparing black women in this country with women in
Tanzania,'' Satcher said, ``we would be talking about how great we
are doing. We are not. In this country, we have a certain standard
of expectation about the risk of women dying in pregnancy, and
black women are off the scale right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this are varied, and not well understood. Black
women are more prone to obesity, hypertension and diabetes,
conditions that can complicate pregnancy. Poverty plays a role, as
does the drug and alcohol abuse that sometimes goes along with it,
experts say. So, too, does poor prenatal care.
</P>
<P>
   Yet black and white women generally suffer the same types of
complications. For every maternal death, CDC officials say, 1,600
women are admitted to hospitals for pregnancy complications that
are not related to delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paradox that we have is that mortality is about four to
five times higher among blacks, but morbidity, or complications,
are only 1.5 times higher,'' as measured by hospital admissions,
said Dr. Hani Atrash, chief of the CDC's pregnancy and infant
health branch. ``What worries me most is that it may be true that
blacks and whites have the same rate of complications,'' he said,
but blacks may seek medical care ``at a later stage and with more
serious conditions, and therefore their mortality is higher.''
</P>
<P>
   In the District of Columbia, where the majority of residents are
black, these numbers come as no surprise to doctors; the rate at
which women die in childbirth is higher here than anywhere else in
the country. At D.C. General Hospital, the city's largest public
hospital, as many as three-quarters of all maternity patients are
high risk.
</P>
<P>
   Most obstetricians are afraid to talk about losing patients. But
the doctors at D.C. General are surprisingly direct. Dr. John S.
Selden, who has worked at the hospital on and off for the last 13
years, told of a death that occurred just a few months ago: a woman
in her early 30s, already a mother of six, suffered an amniotic
fluid embolism, an extremely rare condition in which fluid from her
womb escaped into the bloodstream and lodged in her lung. She died
on the operating table, moments after a Caesarean section.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was alive and alert to the point where the baby was out,''
Selden said. ``The nurses showed her the baby. I'm sure that's the
last thing she remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Selden said there was no way to predict the woman's death, and
outside experts agreed. But, they said, if scientists and public
health officials spent more time researching maternal mortality,
they might find ways to better handle _ or even to prevent _ such
unpredictable complications, so that they did not escalate into
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   One researcher, Dr. Roberto Romero, chief of the perinatology
research branch at the National Institute on Child Health and Human
Development, suspects that amniotic fluid embolism is, in fact, a
``chronic process that could be identified in women who are
admitted to the hospital.'' Romero said he was planning a study of
the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, officials at the CDC, as well as at the
American College of Gynecologists, are pressing state health
officials to resurrect the practice of performing maternal death
reviews. Currently, said Dr. Jeffrey C. King, who is leading the
effort for the obstetricians' group, only 25 states conduct
in-depth examinations every time a pregnant woman dies.
</P>
<P>
   But even where the reviews are conducted, some say, they are not
always thorough enough. Dr. Janet L. Mitchell, a New York City
obstetrician who performed reviews for the city until a few years
ago, said she wanted to interview relatives of women who died, in
an effort to understand how socioeconomics and lifestyle contribute
to the racial gap. But she could not get government financing for
the work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to back away from the medical causes,'' she said,
``and begin to take a much more ethnographic, anthropological
approach to analyzing this tragic outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Black or white, the tragedy of death in childbirth cannot be
underestimated. Five years ago, Arny Goodman, who is white, became
a widower and a single father when his wife, Deborah Sorkin,
suffered a catastrophic hemorrhage while delivering their second
child, a baby girl. Ms. Sorkin was 38; the couple's newborn
daughter died, as well. Goodman was left with the task of telling
his son, who was not quite 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Andrew, Mommy's not coming home again, ever.' He just
froze. He instantly knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, who lives in Manchester, Conn., a suburb of Hartford,
said his wife suffered placenta accreta, in which the placenta
burrows deep into the uterine wall, intertwining itself with the
blood vessels. Goodman responded by suing the state of Connecticut,
which owns the hospital where his wife died, and turning himself
into an expert on placenta accreta. He began a one-man crusade to
heighten scientific interest in the condition and in maternal
mortality in general.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the National Institute of Child Health and Human
Development held a two-day conference on postpartum hemorrhage and
placenta accreta, and invited Goodman to speak.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told the conference, ``There has got to be some
uniform way of having a doctor look at these risk factors, utilize
ultrasound and arrive at a high index of suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman settled his suit with Connecticut; he said he cannot
discuss the terms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mitchell, the New York obstetrician, says Goodman's vehemence
illustrates a cultural difference in the way many blacks and whites
respond to unexpected deaths, a difference she said helped explain
why blacks had not been more vocal. The National Black Women's
Health Project, an advocacy group in Washington, recently has begun
to try to collect stories of black women who have died in
childbirth or been affected by pregnancy complications. But
Mitchell said that when she worked at Harlem Hospital, she tried to
start a support group for black mothers whose babies had died.
Nobody came.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cultural differences in grieving,'' she said. ``For
communities of color, especially those of African descent, it tends
to be much more individual, spiritual and inward. They don't have a
need to be in a support group. They would much rather do this
privately.''
</P>
<P>
   That same sense of spirituality has been both a guide and
comfort to Deborah Edwards, the George Washington University
Hospital patient, during her difficult pregnancy. Mrs. Edwards, who
is a deacon in her church, said she had no intention of becoming a
terrible statistic. She is now watching her diet carefully,
something she has never done before, and her obstetrician, Dr.
Kristiina Parviainen, says she follows doctors' orders with
precision.
</P>
<P>
   So, while Parviainen debated the length of her hospital stay,
Mrs. Edwards was looking to a higher authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm believing in the Lord,'' she said. ``He knew my health
condition before I got pregnant. He knew my age before I got
pregnant. If he decides, at 42, to bless us with a baby ... .'' Her
voice trailed off for a bit. ``I just believe in the Lord.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
