u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABA-PAUL08-COX     08-07 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABA-PAUL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crossing the line: Goal is more minority lawyers
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _William G. Paul, a fifth-generation Oklahoman and
former general counsel of Phillips Petroleum Co., will be sworn in
this week as the new president of the American Bar Association
during the group's annual meeting in Atlanta. Paul, 68, a member of
the Oklahoma City law firm of Crowe &AMP; Dunlevy, will serve a
one-year term.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the 400,000-member ABA, Paul's main initiative
is to increase minority participation in the legal profession. He
and his wife, Barbara, recently gave $50,000 to the new ABA Legal
Opportunity Scholarship Fund as part of the initiative. In a recent
interview with Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Bill
Rankin, Paul discussed his plans for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the level of minority participation in the legal
profession, and why does the ABA need to increase the level now?
</P>
<P>
   A: The population of our country today is 30 percent of color,
and we're moving to a population of 50 percent of color within a
few decades. The legal profession is 92.5 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   This disparity is extremely important because the legal
profession is the connecting link between the people, society and
the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   We all want to continue to live under the rule of law. The legal
profession must reflect society or it cannot serve as that
connecting link.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the ABA doing about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: We've got five action groups working on it: a legal education
group, primarily deans of law schools; a corporate counsel group,
headed up by Charles Morgan, the general counsel of BellSouth,
who's a real leader in this field; the private law firm and bar
association group; the judicial clerkship group; and a financial
aid and scholarship fund-raising group.
</P>
<P>
   We need to harness all of our resources to gain the interest of
young people who are members of racial and ethnic minorities in
attending law schools. ... But then we've got to help them and
support them. Legal educators tell us that to make significant
progress, we've got to have financial support for them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where will the money come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: At this meeting, we're kicking off the ABA Legal Opportunity
Scholarship Fund. In two weeks, we have already raised $200,000.
Our goal is $1 million this year, and we have higher aspirations
than that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the main obstacles facing members of ethnic and
racial minorities who want to begin a career in the law?
</P>
<P>
   A: ... A phrase I've heard a lot is ``critical mass.'' A person
of color looks at a law school and thinks of going there and looks
at the faculty, and there's nobody on the faculty who's a minority,
or there's only one or two, and that's a negative. Or they look at
the student body and there's just a sprinkling of minority
students, and the words I've heard are, ``There's no critical
mass.'' You've got to have a critical mass for this to work, for it
to be attractive.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the impediments, some of the things we've got
to address. ... There is some good news in the law schools. The
student bodies today of the ABA-accredited law schools, and that's
almost all of them in the country, are about 20 percent people of
color. That's a good number, but it's not good enough when the
population is 30 percent, galloping toward 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are other problems facing the legal profession?
</P>
<P>
   A: Anecdotal evidence shows that we in the legal profession are
becoming separated from the people we serve. One reason is that our
delivery system _ the way we deliver legal services _ just doesn't
fit today's environment the way it fit 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What we're seeing in the world of e-commerce on the Internet is
that people want instant communication.
</P>
<P>
   So technology, through the Internet, may be the road to enable
us to reach tens of millions of clients and potential clients who
are not being served and who do not now have meaningful access to
the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In Georgia, the General Assembly enacted a law this year
banning the filing of lawsuits against the gun industry just four
days after the city of Atlanta had filed such a lawsuit. Other
state legislatures as well as Congress have been enacting
legislation curtailing the types of lawsuits that can be filed and
the amount of awards plaintiffs can receive. Is this a threat to
justice?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, it's not a threat to justice. ... We lawyers take the law
as we find it. The people give it to us through the Constitution
and through the legislature. If the people of the state of Georgia
say it will be the public policy of this state that no lawsuits can
be filed by municipalities against the gun industry, that's the
law.
</P>
<P>
   What is important is that the legal profession maintains its
independence. There's got to be a lawyer out there somewhere to
represent every cause, every position, every point of view. The
quicker the people of our country can come to understand that, the
better off we'll all be.
</P>
<P>
   There ought to be a lawyer out there somewhere who's willing to
take a case to test the constitutionality of Georgia's new law. And
society ought to applaud that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
