<HEADER>
A9397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-ARCADES-REAL-630     08-07 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-ARCADES-REAL-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: RESTORING CLEVELAND'S HISTORIC ARCADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT SHAROFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The renovation of three historic arcades downtown is
sparking hopes that the city's long-moribund Euclid Avenue retail
strip will be reborn as a mixed-use street of shops, hotels and
condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Euclid Avenue is, or was, to Cleveland what Fifth Avenue is to
New York and Michigan Avenue is to Chicago: the main downtown
avenue for shopping and sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the turn of the century, it was compared with the Unter den
Linden in Berlin and the Champs-Elysees in Paris,'' said Ted Sande,
deputy director of the Cleveland Restoration Society, a nonprofit
group dedicated to preserving historic architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the glory has faded. Of the four department stores that
dominated the street, only one, the former Higbee's, now operating
under the Dillard's nameplate, remains. The rest of the street
consists mainly of four- to six-story buildings with first-floor
stores and office space above that. They date from as early as 1870
but are interspersed with a few newer and larger buildings and have
been in decline for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the older buildings do not work as office space any
more,'' said Richard Sheehan, vice president and director of retail
services for the local office of Grubb &AMP; Ellis Co., a national real
estate concern with offices downtown. ``They do, however, work for
hotels and residential units.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, two developers _ with considerable help from the mayor's
office, which has repeatedly singled out the revitalization of
Euclid Avenue as a key development goal _ are stepping forward with
projects that not only promise to inject new life into the street
but also will save and restore three of the most remarkable
structures in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   The three are the Old Arcade, at 402 Euclid Ave., and the
Colonial and Euclid arcades across the street. The developer of the
Old Arcade is Bruce Abrams, owner of LR Development in Chicago, a
company that specializes in historic renovation projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Colonial and the Euclid are being renovated by a partnership
of John Carney, Robert Rains and John Marcus. Carney and Rains have
developed a number of downtown residential projects, while Marcus'
family has owned the two arcades for over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The arcade is a European concept _ one thinks of the Galleria
Vittorio Emanuele in Milan, Italy, and the Burlington and
Piccadilly arcades in London _ that never really caught on in the
United States until they were reborn as enclosed shopping malls
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, for reasons no one is quite sure of, has three of the
covered shopping passageways on the same block. (A fourth, which
was further up the street, was torn down in the 1960s.)
</P>
<P>
   The most spectacular is the Old Arcade, which was built in 1890
with $867,000 raised from a consortium of local businessmen that
included John D. Rockefeller. The architects were George H. Smith
and John Eisenmann, both of whom had long careers in Cleveland.
Smith also designed the Colonial Arcade.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 50 years, the building was the home of some of the
city's finest carriage-trade retailers. One of the more notable
tenants was the Stouffers restaurant chain, which began there as a
stand-up milk bar in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Properly speaking, the Old Arcade is actually three buildings _
two nine-story Romanesque office towers separated by a five-story,
600-foot-long arcade topped with an elaborate glass skylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really majestic,'' said Jonathan Sandvick, president of
Sandvick Architects, a Cleveland concern that is handling the
renovation. ``I can remember coming down here as a child with my
grandmother on the streetcar and being awed by the space. It's one
of the things that made me want to be an architect.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The interior is a riot of cast-iron columns and trusses,
terrazzo floors, marble staircases and elaborate glass and brass
storefronts. Around the perimeter of the skylight are 44 cast-iron
lion's heads, the eyes of which at one time lighted up; they will
do so again after the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The skylight has 1,800 panes of glass, all of which need to be
replaced along with much of the iron-and-steel support structure.
``The skylight is a big issue,'' Sandvick said. ``Right now, a lot
of the glass is only marginally held in place. It needs urgent
repair.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Abrams, the skylight alone will cost $2 million to
renovate. The total project will cost $60 million, $10 million of
which is coming from a combination of grants and low-interest loans
from the city and various private foundations.
</P>
<P>
   After the renovation, the first two floors of the arcade _ which
also has an entrance on Superior Avenue _ will become a food court
and shopping mall, while the rest will be occupied by a 295-room
Hyatt Regency hotel. ``It's a dramatic building,'' said Scott
Miller, executive vice president of development for Hyatt Corp.
``And it has the ultimate atrium.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandvick added that because of the age of the facility and the
fact that none of the space was originally designed with a hotel in
mind, there will be considerably more than 100 different hotel-room
layouts. ``We'll probably set the record,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The project will begin this fall and will be finished early in
2001, Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, the renovation of the Colonial and Euclid
arcades is much further along. The two are part of a
seven-building, 330,000-square-foot complex that occupies part of a
block between Euclid and Prospect avenues. Several of the buildings
are in the middle of the block and are almost unreachable from the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the buildings were built from 1898 to 1911, while the
seventh was built as part of the current renovation. At one time,
the complex housed a hotel on the Prospect Avenue side, offices in
the upper floors of the Euclid side and retail stores along the two
arcades.
</P>
<P>
   Although smaller in scale, the two arcades each have their
distinctive glories. The most arresting is the Colonial, a
two-level, 435-foot-long Georgian Revival structure with a pitched
skylight running the length of the passageway.
</P>
<P>
   The Euclid, which parallels the Colonial, is one level with
terra-cotta walls and a soaring barrel-vaulted ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Now the seven buildings on the site are being renovated into a
180-room Residence Inn by Marriott. The two arcades running through
the buildings are being retained as retail spaces. The architect
for the project is again Sandvick.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the two with the Old Arcade, he said: ``The interiors
were in worse shape here. The skylight was missing in the Euclid,
and the Colonial's needed substantial repair. Also, there's a lot
of highly decorative spaces in the Colonial that were just covered
over with drywall and needed to be restored.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our customers will find it very appealing,'' said
Mark Hemmer, vice president of operations for Cleveland-based
Amerinns Corp., which operates a number of Marriotts in the area.
``The building has style and architectural features you couldn't
afford to do in a new building today.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the features, in addition to the arcades, are a beaux-arts
ballroom on the second floor with original art-glass skylights and
a lobby area dominated by a series of stained-glass windows left
from the original hotel that occupied the space.
</P>
<P>
   John Marcus, whose family will continue to own the complex after
the renovation, said the project's cost is $30 million, $4 million
of which is coming from the city. The project will be finished by
the end of the year, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ARCHITECTS-REAL-2T     08-07 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, ARCHITECTS ARE IN DEMAND AND ON THE MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Freshly recruited from a corporate colossus, the new
president strides into a rapidly growing company in search of even
higher profits, untapped markets and maybe an acquisition or two.
</P>
<P>
   The description could fit many Wall Street firms. But the firm
in question is Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill. You can easily spot its
architects, planners and interior designers. They're the ones
dressed completely in black among all those navy blue and charcoal
gray suits in the canyons of the financial district.
</P>
<P>
   That Skidmore now does business from 14 Wall Street, on a
crossroads it shares with the New York Stock Exchange and J.P.
Morgan, is in one sense coincidental. (The firm just needed
affordable space.) In another sense, it is an apt metaphor for the
state of the profession at the moment. Like Wall Street,
architecture is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Skidmore had 200 employees in New York, down
from a peak of 425 in 1988. The firm moved downtown last October
into space designed for up to 325 employees. There are now 340.
</P>
<P>
   Hellmuth, Obata &AMP; Kassabaum, by some rankings the largest
architectural firm in America, has doubled the size of its New York
office since 1994, from 50 to 100 employees. So has Gensler,
another national giant, whose New York office has grown from 169 to
334 employees in the past five years. The ranks at HLW
International's New York office have risen from 215 to 310 in the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Good fortune is also visiting small firms. Wendy Evans Joseph
has watched her practice at 500 Park Ave. grow from one person in
1994 to six today. ``I could have 20 people, there's so much work
right now,'' she said. Her projects include a V-shaped,
cable-stayed pedestrian bridge over East 63rd Street for
Rockefeller University and, in Dallas, the Women's Museum: An
Institute for the Future.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Washington, too, has as much work as she can handle in
her 10-person office at 271 W. 125th St. But she depends on
government agencies and nonprofit institutions for jobs: a new
station for the Franklin Avenue shuttle in Brooklyn, four clinics
for the Interfaith Medical Center in Brooklyn, 27 homes in central
Harlem, two schools in New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the only black architect whose majority of work is
public work,'' she said. ``It goes back to the root of how
potential clients select architects. A lot of it has to do with who
you know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few of us who can say we're benefiting from the
boom,'' Ms. Washington said. ``It would be great to participate and
not just see it through the glass.'' Because salary levels have
risen faster than fees, she cannot afford the extra staff she needs
and so finds herself working longer hours.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from help-wanted advertising, the demand for architects
is greater than it has been in a decade. In July 1989, The New York
Times ran an average of 42 ads for architectural positions in its
Sunday classified section. In July 1994, with the real estate
market in tatters, the average was 25 ads. Last month, it was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the demand is the scarcity of experienced architects in
their late 30s and early 40s. ``There is a missing generation,''
said David Childs, the chairman designate of Skidmore. Despairing
of their prospects earlier this decade, they either got out of
architecture or never got into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were taking jobs that smaller firms would have taken,''
recalled A. Eugene Kohn, a founding principal of Kohn Pedersen Fox.
``Smaller firms were taking jobs that new firms might have taken.
And new people were saying, `Forget it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did they go?'' asked Walter Hunt Jr., a managing
principal of Gensler. ``Maybe they're running a bed-and-breakfast
in Vermont. Maybe they're fishing.'' It is widely supposed that
those embryonic architects wound up in other parts of the country
or related fields like construction management and real estate
development.
</P>
<P>
   Their absence is keenly felt. ``What's generally available is a
zero- to 8-year experience level,'' said Carl Ordemann, the
managing principal of the New York office of Perkins &AMP; Will. ``Then
there's a substantial gap in the 8- to 15-year level. Every office,
across the board, is suffering from that gap. You can't do jobs as
well without those people as part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of experienced architects allows some of them to
command salaries in the range of $60,000 to $70,000 _ a small
fortune for architectural staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing for the profession at one level,'' said
Kenneth Drucker, director of design and senior principal at the New
York office of Hellmuth, Obata &AMP; Kassabaum, ``but at another level,
the fees were lowered to remain competitive and they haven't
rebounded. They've stayed low, salaries have risen and headhunters
are pursuing your professional staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Balsley, a landscape architect who designed Gantry Plaza
State Park on the Queens waterfront, would not want to return to
the old days. ``If anyone complains about working weekends,'' he
said, ``I'll show them the help wanted ads from eight years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he noted that higher salaries and the cost of
computer equipment and programs had pushed up operating costs.
``We're not even close to being as profitable as we were in the
'80s,'' Balsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Balsley's concerns are signs that the Flatiron
district in Manhattan, where he and many other architects have
offices, may be growing too popular _ and too pricey. He would love
to stay in 119 Fifth Ave., at 19th Street, he said, but ``with all
the IPO brats running around with million-dollar bills hanging out
of their pockets, landlords won't even negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas Kondylis &AMP; Associates is preparing to leave 3 W. 18th St.
in October for new quarters at 31 W. 27th St.
</P>
<P>
   Kondylis is designing Trump World Tower at the east end of 47th
Street and Larry Silverstein's River Place complex at the west end
of 42nd Street. His office has grown from 28 to 64 people since
1994. ``The rents in the Flatiron district have gone up,'' Kondylis
said. ``So the new area for architects is the West 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, the movement over time has been downtown. The
highest concentration of membership in the American Institute of
Architects is in ZIP code 10003 around Union Square, which takes in
parts of Ladies' Mile, the Flatiron district, Greenwich Village and
the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 50 percent of our firms are now below Union
Square,'' said Rolf Ohlhausen, the immediate past president of the
New York chapter of the AIA.
</P>
<P>
   Another area that architects are discovering is the financial
district. Nearing the end of its lease in 600 Madison Ave., at 58th
Street, Pei Cobb Freed &AMP; Partners is scouting for new quarters and
has cast its net as far downtown as Wall Street. ``Many buildings
that were considered Class B have been upgraded,'' said George
Miller, the managing partner. ``They present what we believe to be
the best value in today's market for the architectural community.''
</P>
<P>
   Gensler, at 1 Rockefeller Plaza, has a ``Wall Street studio'' _
25 people in 1 Liberty Plaza at Broadway and Liberty Street _ to
serve financial institutions like J.P. Morgan and the Federal
Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore moved 10 months ago to the former Bankers Trust Co.
Building at Wall and Nassau Streets, a landmark completed in 1912
and expanded in 1933, topped by a stepped pyramid like the ancient
Greek Mausoleum at Halicarnassus.
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore is one of the largest firms in New York, if not the
largest. And it probably has the highest public profile, with
commissions that include the new Pennsylvania Station, the new
International Air Terminal at Kennedy International Airport, the
new New York Stock Exchange, the Columbus Centre complex at
Columbus Circle that includes Time Warner headquarters, Bear
Stearns headquarters on Madison Avenue and one of the new Times
Square towers.
</P>
<P>
   As its lease neared an end at the old Daily News Building at 220
E. 42nd St., Skidmore began a search for new space. ``Where we
really wanted to be was the Hudson Street corridor or Ladies' Mile
but there was nothing available in those two areas,'' said T.J.
Gottesdiener, a partner.
</P>
<P>
   The firm was in an awkward position. ``We're not big enough to
threaten the mayor that we're going to move to New Jersey,'' Childs
said, ``but we're also not in the 3,000- to 4,000-square-foot
range.''
</P>
<P>
   After looking as far afield as Long Island City, Queens,
Gottesdiener settled on 14 Wall St. as meeting three key criteria:
floors as large as possible (Skidmore has 72,000 square feet on
three floors); a safe, convenient location, and ``rents we could
sustain when the market turned'' _ low $20s a square foot annually,
compared with the high $20s on 42nd Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
