<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NBA-DREAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING ANOTHER CHANCE, AND NOW SHOOTING FOR THE NBA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Throughout the game, Horace Jenkins and Shaheen Holloway had
been talking to each other. Each jibe was accompanied by a smile,
each shot matched by the other's. Now, late in a Jersey Shore
Basketball League playoff game at St. Rose High School in Belmar,
N.J., Holloway asked his teammates to clear out so he could take on
Jenkins one on one, just like the two players would do in
off-season playground games.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway's game has been fine-tuned at Seton Hall, but Jenkins
has almost always played on the playground. So before Holloway's
teammates could step away, Jenkins reached in and poked the ball
free, taking off for a breakaway layup almost before Holloway could
cough out the final syllables of his command.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway may have already known the skills that the rail-thin,
6-foot-2-inch point guard possesses from their meetings in
recreation centers and on playgrounds. But Jenkins caught the
attention of many more observers this year. After a career that
appeared to be going nowhere, Jenkins, 24, has pushed open the door
with his considerable talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while I just looked at it and said, maybe it's not meant
for me,'' Jenkins, who plays for William Paterson, said recently.
``If it doesn't happen from basketball then maybe it just wasn't
meant to be. Then, with me getting another opportunity, which you
rarely get in life, I realized that I am getting a chance. I think
someday _ I want you to quote this _ someday I think I'll be
playing in the NBA. It's a dream, but I know I can play with these
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The tale began on the courts of New Jersey around Elizabeth and
Newark, where Jenkins learned his craft. At Elizabeth High School,
though, he confounded his coaches by giving little effort in the
classroom and being academically ineligible his senior year. He
spent a year at Union County College, but the birth of his first
child distracted him from the classroom and the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, college coaches remained tempted by his combination of
athleticism and skills, with speed and leaping ability complemented
by a silky shooting touch and a willingness to defend.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Rebimas, the coach at William Paterson, persuaded the
school to take a chance on Jenkins. After only a semester of
classes at Union Junior College, Jenkins had achieved the necessary
grades to join the William Paterson team in January.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped in and immediately made an impact last season,
helping to take a 3-5 team to the national semifinals in Division
III. He averaged a team-high 21.9 points a game and was named the
New Jersey Athletic Conference player of the year and Eastern
College Athletic Conference co-player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It was his play at William Paterson that earned him an
invitation to the Jersey Shore league, and Jenkins believes the
run-and-gun summer league has taken him closer to realizing his NBA
dreams. Last week he was matched against Rick Brunson, the Knicks'
backup point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Rick on him and we had Anthony Mason and Conrad McRae
inside,'' said Greg Kapalko, the RKE Athletic coach. ``He'd go by
Rick and you'd just see this arm rising over Mason and McRae for a
layup.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins finished that game with 38 points, and was named a
first-team all-star, alongside the likes of Lloyd Daniels and Notre
Dame's Troy Murphy, after averaging 34 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me able to prove it against a player like Rick Brunson,
people look up to someone like that, but I take it as a
challenge,'' Jenkins said. ``I was inspired to go out and try to
prove that if this is an NBA guy then I can play with an NBA guy. I
just went out there and did the best that I can do. Fortunately, I
came out with 38 points, 10 rebounds, eight assists and four
blocks. I guess the numbers speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins realizes where he went wrong before. ``I think I always
had the smarts to do it,'' he said, ``but I never put forth the
effort and time for school. I thought it was only about the
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that he will stay at William Paterson for
his two remaining years of eligibility. ``Playing at William
Paterson really opened up a whole lot of opportunities for me,''
Jenkins said. ``Somebody is going to recognize talent. If you've
just downright got the ability to do it, no matter what the age,
you can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go right and the opportunity presents itself in the
correct way, I don't think I should have to spend two years in
school. I'm not saying I will do that, but with my ability, if the
opportunity comes, I'm going to take advantage of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
