<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMES-OR-IKEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR TOWNS COLUMN: NEIGHBORHOOD IS SUPERSEDED BY SUPERSTORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ To make way for the New York region's third
Ikea furniture superstore, this city has officially declared a
patchwork of working-class homes and mom-and-pop factories
``blighted,'' fit for no better fate than the crunching bulldozers
of urban renewal. But go tell Ruth McGruder that her neighborhood
is blighted and she'll give you a tart piece of her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just like family here on the street,'' she protested,
padding barefoot on her porch. ``It feels to me, if we weren't poor
people, they wouldn't come here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old, five-foot Mrs. McGruder thinks the house she
rents for $600 a month with her sister Willie Mae and where she has
helped raise a dozen nephews and nieces has been a fine home. Sure,
it's not the princely Victorians she cleans for a living, but she
has filled it with touches that have meaning and that tell of her
battle to eke out some beauty in a life of two failed marriages and
other harsh moments.
</P>
<P>
   When she moved here 30 years ago, she painstakingly enveloped
her front porch with the baby hedges she had carried with her from
her mother's yard in rural Alabama. The hedges are now nine feet
tall. She has added pots of zinnia, petunias and geraniums, and a
maple she found as a sapling in the nearby lake where she fishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I set out all these plants _ I bought 'em and set 'em out,''
she said with a molasses drawl impervious to the influence of the
Northern gentry she works for. ``I'm used to sitting out on this
porch, nobody bothering nobody. I feel this is my home.''
</P>
<P>
   She has crowded the porch with faded chaises and charcoal
grills, all handed down to her along with three refrigerators, a
1950s hi-fi set and a mahogany dresser at prices even Ikea will
never beat. ``My white people give me all my stuff,'' Mrs.
McGruder, who is black, says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   New Rochelle's development commissioner, Joseph Madonna, has a
powerful argument that the Swedish retailer, by obtaining a 16-acre
plot for assemble-it-yourself furniture in southern Westchester,
will bring in $2.5 million annually in sales taxes. Less persuasive
is the contention that Ikea will bring in 300 jobs. The
neighborhood's factory owners say there are far more than 300
workers here already, skilled stonecutters, electricians and car
mechanics, not Ikea's low-wage, often part-time clerks.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials never bothered to find out very much about
exactly who lives and works in the neighborhood they will soon
subject to eminent domain. If they did, they would have had to
acknowledge flesh-and-blood people, deeply entangled in their homes
and workplaces, who are frightened at the thought of pulling up
roots and relocating elsewhere, even if the city compensates them
at fair market value.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the 50 businesses, like Jerry Newmark, whose factory
makes cutting tools, and Stephen J. Wodraska II, who repairs roofs,
have spent lifetimes taking risks, cultivating customers, bringing
their children into the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trading lives for dollars,'' Newmark said. ``Why
should Ikea get the use of eminent domain and not us? You read any
encyclopedia description and they say eminent domain is for public
use, a highway or reservoir.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 34 homes, there are people like Josephine Notaro, who was
born in her green cottage 80 years ago when neighbors raised pigs
in their yards and the corridor that now constitutes Interstate 95
was a swamp. Her parents and her husband died at this address. Now
she owns it free and clear and wants to live out her days with her
aged brother, Martin, reading dime-store novels on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   People here look out for each other. Factory workers watch the
houses when residents are off to work. The residents protect the
factories from graffiti and break-ins at night. Blacks and whites
who may have eyed each other suspiciously decades ago have become
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea's arrival, though, seems like a done deal. If he is forced
to move, Wodraska says, he will worry not only about how to retain
his customers but also where to find neighbors like Mrs. McGruder
to sweeten the sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruth watches out for the neighborhood,'' he said. ``We'd have
to take her with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
