<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-BR     08-07 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-BRAWL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD FEELINGS LINGER AFTER YANKS' BRAWL WITH MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The New York Yankees and Seattle Mariners engaged in a
game so hideously long and dull Friday night that fans began
streaming out of Safeco Field in the fifth inning. Those who
remained witnessed a nasty ninth-inning brawl that created a binge
of ill will.
</P>
<P>
   Some teammates in the Yankees' clubhouse were annoyed with Jason
Grimsley, whose actions served as the spark for the fight. Joe
Girardi said he would never forget how Seattle's Frank Rodriguez
tried to hurt him. Manager Joe Torre chastised the way the
home-plate umpire, Gary Cederstrom, handled the moments preceding
the fracas. And Chad Curtis and Derek Jeter apparently have an
issue to sort out _ something Curtis wanted to settle in the
clubhouse afterward, in full view of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just part of baseball _ it's been a part of baseball
since Ty Cobb,'' said Chili Davis, who was among those most heavily
involved in the shoving and pushing and tackling in the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams said, ``It was like a war zone out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been an eminently forgettable game before the craziness
at the end, both sides seemingly resigned to the fact that the
Yankees were on the way to an 11-8 victory. Paul O'Neill, Williams
and Scott Brosius all banged homers in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez, however, made the shortest start of his
major-league career. Plagued by control problems, he allowed three
hits, three walks and three runs before a perplexed Torre removed
him after a third of an inning. Nonetheless, the Yankees rolled
along toward their 66th victory. The first 4 1/2 innings required 2
hours 28 minutes, and by the sixth inning, players from both teams
were often swinging at the first pitch, in an unspoken
collaboration to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of Seattle runners reached base against Grimsley in
the bottom of the eighth, and Alex Rodriguez slammed a three-run
homer, closing the Yankees' lead to three runs. Grimsley's next
pitch sailed over the head of Edgar Martinez, and was followed by a
fastball into Martinez's side.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley insisted later that he had not thrown at Martinez
intentionally _ ``I have too much respect for a hitter like Edgar
Martinez,'' he said _ but if he had not done it on purpose, he was
at least guilty of terrible timing. ``They started it,'' said Lou
Piniella, the Seattle manager. ``It was blatant. I thought the
first pitch at Edgar maybe got away from Grimsley, but the second
was obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Cederstrom ejected Grimsley immediately, a decision Torre
understood completely; all he asked Cederstrom was how much time
Mariano Rivera would have to warm up. Torre, too, was unhappy with
Grimsley, convinced until a later conversation with Grimsley that
the pitcher had hit Martinez intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Before the eighth inning ended, Torre was ejected after arguing
for the second time in the game with the first-base umpire, Doug
Eddings, on an out or safe call. So Torre would watch the rest of
the ugliness unfold on his television in the visiting manager's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rodriguez had entered the game for the Mariners in the
fifth inning and took the mound for the ninth, with Jose Mesa
warming up in the bullpen _ an obvious sign that retaliation would
take place, Curtis said later. Luis Sojo grounded out, and after
throwing a pitch low and outside to Chuck Knoblauch, Rodriguez
drilled the second baseman in the backside.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch flipped the bat away nonchalantly and jogged toward
first, the score seemingly settled, the intent of Rodriguez obvious
to all. Perhaps a dozen Yankees said later that they fully
understood Rodriguez's actions, that he had just been retaliating
for Martinez's being hit.
</P>
<P>
   But Cederstrom did not eject Rodriguez. Instead, he walked
slowly to the mound to talk to the pitcher, with players and
coaches on the Yankees' bench screaming at him all the while to
throw Rodriguez out.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella then stepped out of the Seattle dugout and called for a
reliever. Cederstrom, reacting to the angry yelling from the
Yankees, began to stalk toward their dugout, until the third-base
coach, Willie Randolph, interceded, stepping in between Cederstrom
and the bench. Don Zimmer, running the Yankees in Torre's absence,
stepped onto the field to challenge Cederstrom's decision. Frank
Rodriguez, probably thinking the Yankees were yelling at him, began
to scream at the enemy dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi, standing near home plate as the on-deck batter, then
told Rodriguez to stop yelling, adding that if he wanted somebody
in the Yankees' dugout, then he should go after him. Rodriguez
dropped his glove and charged Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   He hit the Yankees' catcher twice, knocking him to the ground,
and players and coaches from both teams rushed onto the field,
Williams and Davis and Jim Leyritz and Shane Spencer all trying to
reach Rodriguez just in front of the Seattle bench. Zimmer, moving
on two bad knees, was knocked down and struggled to get up, his
heart racing; Torre and others said later that they had worried
about Zimmer, in the middle of the scrum.
</P>
<P>
   Davis pinned Seattle coach Steve Smith to the ground, hands
around Smith's neck _ ``I owe somebody an apology,'' Davis said
later _ and Williams knocked down catcher Dan Wilson in a rage.
``Something inside me snapped,'' Williams said, referring to the
moment when he saw Girardi go down.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez punched Leyritz; Paul O'Neill grabbed Wilson and then
felt himself being collared around the neck by Stan Williams, the
Seattle pitching coach. Finally, the fighting stopped.
</P>
<P>
   During the fight, Jeter came face to face with Seattle's Alex
Rodriguez, a close friend, and the two appeared to be joking as the
nastiness drew to a conclusion. Curtis, a hardened veteran, began
saying something to Jeter in front of the dugout _ he seemed to be
telling Jeter that a fight between two teams was an inappropriate
place for fraternization.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Curtis approached Jeter in the clubhouse, with perhaps a
dozen reporters in the vicinity, and sought to continue the
conversation. Jeter made it clear he did not want to discuss his
feelings at that time, gesturing toward reporters, and he refused
to talk any further, eventually walking away.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said afterward: ``There was a little difference of
opinion there, and I think it's something that is just between us.
It's nothing big and nothing I'm going to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Once players from both teams were cleared from the field,
Cederstrom and the other umpires met, and decided to eject one
player: Girardi, who exploded when he learned he had been thrown
out, throwing items from the dugout onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He punches me and I got thrown out,'' Girardi said. ``I'm
having a hard time sorting all this out. I get hit twice in the
head and I get thrown out. I've never punched anyone in my life and
I still haven't. I'm not going to punch him. But he tried to hurt
me and I'm not going to forget that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankie Rodriguez had a job to do and nobody has a problem
with that. It was intentional, and everybody knew that, but the
umpire didn't throw him out. When he doesn't do his job, that's why
the rest of it occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``It baffles me why Girardi was thrown out. I guess
he should've stood there and let somebody kick the heck out of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer argued about Girardi's ejection, griped about the way the
whole game was handled by umpires, and when he mentioned Eddings'
series of questionable calls at first base, Zimmer was ejected,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Mariners have a history of altercations, this
being among the worst. ``It was just ugly, and let's forget it and
play tomorrow,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella: ``We did what we had to do to protect our
players. And if the Yankees do it again tomorrow, we'll do the same
thing again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
