<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDS: Deletes: BISCAYNE, CHINA-ARMS, ABA, IOWA-BIKE, BUSH-AFFIRM
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CoxNet Cox News Service budget
 &HT;    FOR SUNDAY, August 8, 1999
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Chante LaGon at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Rick Christie, home 301-352-7777, cell phone
301-910-6248.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-ALDAY _ ATLANTA _ It's a minor blessing, for sure, but
Leigh Ann Barton's sister Kelly thinks its a good think Mark Barton
killed himself, sparing the family the ordeal of a trial of another
mass murderer who victimized them. Kelly and Leigh Ann's great aunt
(their living grandmother's sister) was Mary Alday. (Sanford,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-VICTIMS _ ATLANTA _ Marci Brookings, 29, who was wounded
in the shoulder blade, has done a good deal of her coping and
healing by attending the funerals and the mass memorial to the
people killed by Mark Barton. Cathy Vancamp's healing is spent in
the isolation of intensive care, blinded by Mark Barton's bullets.
Sang Yoon has entered counseling and wonders how he will pay his
medical bills. We look at how the 13 surviving victims are doing a
little more than a week after the shootings. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ABA-PAUL _ ATLANTA _ Q&AMP;A with incoming American Bar Association
President William Paul, on diversity in the legal profession.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCBOYCOTT_ MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. _ Vacationers and tourism folks
talk about the impending boycott of South Carolina by the NAACP,
Urban League and SCLC. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-PITT _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Tobacco has been a force unto
itself in Pitt County's economy and social existence since the turn
of the century. But times are changing. A variety of factors have
conspired to threaten tobacco's cultural and financial legacy in
Pitt County, to threaten a way of life. (Staff, The Daily
Reflector) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TAX-IMPACT _ WASHINGTON _ What's in it for me? That's what many
Americans wonder whenever Congress passes a big tax bill, even one
that is sure to be killed by a presidential veto. This time, the
answers are even more complex than usual. For example, when all the
provisions kick in, the basic savings for a household with a
$50,000 income can vary from far more than $1,000 to far less than
$400. Here's why. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-COMPLIANCE _ WASHINGTON _ In a hugely popular move,
Republicans in 1995 required Congress to abide by the laws it
enacts for the rest of the country. It was the first plank of the
GOP ``Contract With America.'' Four years later, the lawmakers have
begun to live under many of the provisions of 11 health, safety,
labor and anti-discrimination laws. But Capitol Hill has not quite
put itself quite into a straitjacket of regulations. (Malone, Cox
News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE _ WASHINGTON _ When New York's Fresh Kills landfill is
closed at the end of next year, an additional 13,000 tons of
garbage will flow daily into what the Supreme Court has ruled is
``interstate commerce.'' The ruling means that, absent
congressional action, officials of other states will be unable to
keep large trash hauling firms from bringing the refuse into their
states and landfilling it. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE-OHIO _ Ohio is one of the states most likely to receive
the New York garbage. A Q&AMP;A with Sen. George Voinovich, who has
introduced a bill that would give states authority to regulate
out-of-state garbage. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Like the blind men grasping the
elephant, government antitrust lawyers and the world's largest
software enterprise see the results of the Microsoft trial in
starkly different terms. Both viewpoints will be laid out in
book-length volumes that go this week to U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson, who will use them to prepare ``findings of fact''
that it turn will provide clues to where the landmark trial will
end up. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-FUNDING _ WASHINGTON Two years ago, Congress passed
legislation designed to encourage more Medicare patients to join
managed care plans. Since then nearly 200 plans have quit Medicare
or reduced their coverage. HMOs say the government is shortchanging
them, but others say HMOs are still receiving too much money.
(Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-LANDMINES _ BAGHDAD _ Hassan Hussein Darwish and his fellow
villagers in Iraqi Kurdistan had a problem and he and his friends
set out to solve it. Their land in northernmost Iraq was laden with
mines from the areas frequent combatants _ Iraq, Turkey, Iran. For
years and with barely any training or equipment, Darwish cleared
thousands of mines. Finally, he found one he didn't recognize and
it blew out his eyes and blew off his hands. Now disabled and
living in a squalid block home in Erbil, he lives to describe the
dangerous life of what U.N. workers ``village de-miners.'' ``We
didn't come to the mines. The mines came to us,'' Darwish says. ``I
was born there and my living depends on the land . . . of course,
you are face to face with death at any moment.'' (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CRISIS _ MOSCOW _ Bank closings. Food shortages.
Political upheaval. Predictions of social unrest. Last August 17,
the value of Russia's national currency plummeted as the country
slid headlong into an economic crisis -- and the world held its
breath. But the crisis did not result in catastrophe. Things aren't
much better in Russia, but they haven't got worse, either. After
the heady boom years of '96 and '97, economic achievement in Russia
today is measured by the bad things that haven't happened. (Holmes,
Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in both International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MAGNITOGORSK, Russia _ Once the pride of the
Soviet Union, the massive mining and steel works in this Urals
mountain city illustrate Russia's obstacles in competing in the
world economy. Once the world's biggest steel-producing plant,
Magnitogorsk's output is half of what it was a decade ago and
quality is low. Even Russia's automakers choose to import steel
rather than buy locally because the inferior Russian steel can't
hold paint. The factory survives on barter deals, pays its
employees with credits to be used at the company store and still
measures success the old-fashioned Soviet way _ not by profit, but
by production. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in both International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOX _ Data on the Russian economy. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). 12. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in both International and Financial categories.
</P>
