<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 7, 1999 -- MENTAL-ILLNESS-JOURNEY-2,
8-7 -- Susan Fuchs, shown in the early 1980s, was killed in July in
Central Park. Her descent from middle-class promise to violent
death at society's margins was part of a 20-year journey through
the New York mental health system. The case underlines how
difficult it can be to help the most severely mentally ill.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 7, 1999 -- MENTAL-ILLNESS-JOURNEY-1,
8-7 -- Tom Fuchs, at his antiques shop on Atlantic Avenue in
Brooklyn, spent two decades trying to help his mentally ill sister,
Susan Fuchs, who was killed in July in Central Park. Her descent
from middle-class promise to violent death at society's margins was
part of a 20-year journey through the New York mental health
system. The case underlines how difficult it can be to help the
most severely mentally ill. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LONDON -- Aug. 7, 1999 -- BRITISH-PUB-MAKEOVER-2-B&AMP;W,
8-7 -- A British Pub in 1944. British pubs have come a long way
since 1944 when they served as the social center of the village,
and mostly male patrons drank ale. The pub as downmarket watering
hole, a neighborly spot serving pints of warm beer, a spot where
the ghosts of Dickens and Dr. Johnson hover in the air, is rapidly
being displaced by the pub as trendy cash cow. (British Council/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 7, 1999 -- BBN-METS-VENTURA, 8-7 --
Robin Ventura, in a game against the who is leading the way as the
Mets try to secure their first post-season berth in 11 years.
Two-thirds of the way through his first season in New York,
Ventura, the Mets' third baseman, is hitting .303. He leads the
club in home runs, with 25, and runs batted in, with 90. In many
ways, he leads the club, period. (Barton Silverman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BALTIMORE -- Aug. 7, 1999 --BALTIMORE-MAYORAL-RACE-2,
8-7 -- Baltimore City Council President Lawrence Bell III, the
leading black candidate for mayor of Baltimore at his campaign
headquarters. The primary field includes 17 Democrats, seven
Republicans and three independents. But only the top three
Democrats were rated as having any chance of being elected mayor.
All the candidates talked of a turnout of little more than 100,000
voters in this city of 675,000 residents. (Marty Katz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BALTIMORE -- Aug. 7, 1999 --BALTIMORE-MAYORAL-RACE-1, 8-7
-- Martin O'Malley, center, announcing endorsements last week for
his candidacy for mayor of Baltimore, including one by Howard P.
Rawlings, a General Assembly delegate, holding folder. The primary
field includes 17 Democrats, seven Republicans and three
independents. But only the top three Democrats were rated as having
any chance of being elected mayor. All the candidates talked of a
turnout of little more than 100,000 voters in this city of 675,000
residents. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WELLFLEET, Mass. -- WELLFLEET-PSYCH-RETREAT, 8-7 --
Julius Newman, a professor of social work from Hartford, Conn.,
talks with Dr. Jack Esterson, center, and Dr. Evelyn Bettauer,
right, married psychologists from Glastonbury, Conn., on Ballston
Beach in Truro, Mass., near Wellfleet. The area's reputation as a
psychiatric summer retreat is so solid that some of the recent
change in the psychotherapy world is reflected in the evolution of
their summer chat and study while relaxing at Wellfleet and
neighboring Truro. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- Aug. 7, 1999 -- BRITISH-PUB-MAKEOVER, 8-7 --
Amanda Rimmer, the landlady of the reinvented and now trendy Bull
and Last pub in north London, with her baby daughter, Emma Amelia,
and Massimiliano Magnani, who is both the pub's chef and Emma
Amelia's father. The pub as downmarket watering hole, a neighborly
spot serving pints of warm beer, a spot where the ghosts of Dickens
and Dr. Johnson hover in the air, is rapidly being displaced by the
pub as trendy cash cow. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Aug. 7, 1999 -- AFRICA-DIAMONDS-2-B&AMP;W-2, 8-7
-- Diamonds mined from central Congo in 1997. Concerned that
diamonds are financing and perpetuating wars in Africa, the Clinton
Administration is considering actions aimed at halting the illicit
trade in the precious stones, according to Administration officials
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Aug. 7, 1999 -- AFRICA-DIAMONDS-1-B&AMP;W, 8-7--
Londeke Funidi sifts a palette of gravel in search of diamonds at a
camp deep inside a forest in central Congo in 1997. Concerned that
diamonds are financing and perpetuating wars in Africa, the Clinton
Administration is considering actions aimed at halting the illicit
trade in the precious stones, according to Administration officials
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AYAME, Ivory Coast -- August 7, 1999 --
IVORY-COAST-NATIONALISM, 8-7 -- Ivoirian fishermen, who have
replaced Malian fishermen driven from Ivory Coast after decades of
living there, in their canoes on a lake fed by the Bia River. Ayame
-- as well as Sassandra, a coastal town where a similar incident
involving fisherman from Ghana occurred in December -- has become a
touchstone in the debate over national identity. All that remains
in Ayame now, is a fierce and growing sense of nationalism: Ayame
for Ivoirians only. (Norimitsu Onishi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- August 7, 1999 -- GREATER-ALBANIA,
8-7 -- Albanians wait outside a Prizren jail run by German
occupying forces, who have sought to crack down on soaring crime.
Much of the problem has been attributed to gangs from neighboring
Albania. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) VRAGOLIJA, Yugoslavia -- August 7, 1999 --
KOSOVO-SHELTER-2, 8-7 -- With the Albanian flag flying, members of
the Sllamniku family replace the roof of their house in the village
of Vragolija. With the first chills of Kosovo's long and miserable
winter just two months away, the family has given up on their
expectations for reconstruction help from the Western powers that
drove the Serbs out of Kosovo. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PEC, Yugoslavia -- August 7, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SHELTER-1,
8-7 -- Residents of Pec cope as best they can with an
infrastructure destroyed in the war. Promised aid is slow in
coming. With the first chills of Kosovo's long and miserable winter
just two months away, many have given up on their expectations for
reconstruction help from the Western powers that drove the Serbs
out of Kosovo. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
