<DOCNO> NYT19990807.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-VENTURA-ART-     08-07 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-VENTURA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA IS IN THE SPOTLIGHT HE TRIES TO AVOID 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reggie Jackson came to New York proclaiming he was
the straw that would stir the drink. Robin Ventura is more than
content being one of the ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   But whether he likes it or not _ and it is obvious he does not _
the spotlight is now on Ventura, who is leading the way as the Mets
try to secure their first postseason berth in 11 years. Two-thirds
of the way through his first season in New York, Ventura, the Mets'
third baseman, is hitting .303. He leads the club in home runs,
with 25, and RBIs, with 90. In many ways, he leads the club,
period.
</P>
<P>
   Just two and a half years after it seemed his career could be
over because of a horrible ankle injury, Ventura has turned himself
into a candidate for the most-valuable-player award in the National
League. Not that he wants to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sit here and talk about myself,'' Ventura said
before he doubled and scored the winning run in the Mets' 2-1
victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers at Shea Stadium on Friday
night. ``I realize that's part of playing here. But that doesn't
mean you have to like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Schueler, the general manager of the Chicago White Sox,
Ventura's team for his first nine major-league seasons, said:
``Robin's quiet. But he's a quiet leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews are the part of the job that Ventura detests the
most. ``That and traveling,'' he said, ``and sometimes traveling's
all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura also leads the Mets in one-liners, which he always
delivers with a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of being a teammate,'' Ventura said of his sense
of humor. ``I don't mind cutting up with the guys. But I don't
necessarily feel everybody has to know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura has had an immediate impact on the Mets, not just on the
field but also in the clubhouse following victories, where the
Doors' ``L.A. Woman'' now blares because of its lyrics, ``Get your
mojo rising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin's very reserved, but he's also very funny,'' said Mike
Piazza, citing a gag Ventura pulls on the team plane involving
phony Austin Powers teeth. ``He's a great guy to have on your team.
But he's obviously not looking for the spotlight. That's why he
fits in very well with this ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   John Franco grew up in Brooklyn rooting for the Mets and has
pitched for them for 10 years. While riding to the ball park in
Milwaukee last week and reflecting on Mets history, Franco, without
any prompting, came to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Robin Ventura is the best free-agent signing in the
history of this franchise,'' Franco said. ``He has to be.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, the Mets' top pinch-hitter, Matt Franco, was
sitting in front of his locker. In the middle of a conversation, he
quickly changed the subject as he watched Ventura pass by. ``Has
the MVP talk started yet?'' Franco asked.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk would have seemed unlikely when Ventura, who grew up
in Southern California, somehow ended up playing college baseball
at Oklahoma State. ``That was the only scholarship I received,''
Ventura said. ``It was probably because I couldn't run.''
</P>
<P>
   He could hit, though. He had a 58-game hitting streak for the
Cowboys as a sophomore, won college baseball's equivalent of the
Heisman Trophy in 1988 and won a gold medal with the 1988 Olympic
baseball team in Seoul, South Korea. Ventura would later be named
the college player of the decade by Baseball America magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura still can't run, at least not very well _ he has one
stolen base in two attempts this season. And when he broke and
severely dislocated his right ankle sliding into home plate in a
spring training game in 1997, there were doctors who said Ventura
might never play again.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ventura came back in late July, a week ahead of the
most optimistic schedule. But he hit just .262 the rest of the
season. Last year, he needed to hit .337 over the final month just
to finish at .263.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I ever thought I wasn't back,'' Ventura said.
``But I would feel better at certain times.''
</P>
<P>
   Schueler of the White Sox said: ``It's hard to tell whether he
slowed up because he never ran good. We noticed a lack of range.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura still won his fifth Gold Glove award last season, and he
said he did not think the injury had anything to do with his
struggles at the plate. But the White Sox made only a belated
attempt to re-sign him, and by then he had already decided on the
Mets, choosing them over Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets wanted me to play third base,'' said Ventura, who
knew that Cal Ripken plays third in Baltimore. ``And a lot of the
guys had called and said this was going to be a really good team
and that I'd be a good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The main callers were Piazza and pitcher Al Leiter, who had both
just re-signed with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically lied the whole time,'' Ventura said, his
expression unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura added that Yankees first baseman Tino Martinez also
called to say that Shea Stadium would be a good place for him to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Sold.
</P>
<P>
   There were those who thought the Mets overpaid for Ventura at
$32 million for four years. Mets General Manager Steve Phillips was
not one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finished the year very well,'' Phillips said. ``And he only
drove in 90 runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually 91, a total he is about to surpass with seven weeks
remaining in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to try to explain it,'' Ventura said. ``And I
don't care to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who has never hit higher than .295 in a major-league
season, has a good chance of finishing over .300. He is on a pace
to hit 37 homers and drive in 133 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for someone who was not even named to the National
League All-Star team this season. In fact, Ventura _ who averaged
23 homers and 94 RBIs over the six seasons before his injury _ has
been selected to just one All-Star Game, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Five players since 1979 have won the MVP award without having
been selected to the All-Star Game, however. And even if he does
not become the first Met to win the award, Ventura will probably
not care.
</P>
<P>
   Just call it a hunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
