<HEADER>
A9423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-NOTES-NYT &LR;      08-07 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GIANTS, A LESSON ON REPLAYS 
CORDIAL QUARTERBACKS 
TESTING THE WATERS 
SPECIAL DEVELOPMENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Coach Jim Fassel had a group of game officials
visit the New York Giants' training camp this week to help explain
some of the new rules the NFL will implement this season. The chief
topic of conversation was the reinstitution of instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new guidelines, coaches can challenge an official's
ruling on two plays in each half, though not in the final two
minutes of either half, when such replay reversals are in the hands
of a replay official watching the game.
</P>
<P>
   If a coach's challenge is not upheld, his team will lose a time
out. Fassel believes there will not be as many challenges as fans
expect, but more important, he believes that a lack of
understanding of the replay rules will lead to controversy.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Fassel described a hypothetical play in which an
opposing quarterback fumbles the football while in his passing
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose we recover the fumble but the officials on the field
have already ruled it an incomplete pass because his arm was moving
forward,'' Fassel said. ``I could challenge it, but I don't get the
ball if they agree with me. That's what people have to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officials would say that the whistle blew on the play as
soon as the ball hit the ground. So even if I win the challenge,
all they would do is put the ball down at the site of the fumble
and give the ball to the other team. All I gain is seven or eight
yards. And that's if it's conclusive. Otherwise, I lose a time out.
So it may not be worth it to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know these things are going to happen and people are going
to be screaming at me in the stands to challenge it and I'm going
to be standing there doing nothing. But they have to understand the
whole rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he had already told his players not to try to
persuade him to challenge an official's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been so many times when a player has said to me, `I
caught it,' and later you watch the film and find out he didn't,''
Fassel said. ``And I told them not to watch the stadium scoreboard
replay and make a decision either, because that replay is not
always the replay they use to check a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordial Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   The much anticipated quarterback duel between the starter, Kent
Graham, and his celebrated backup, Kerry Collins, has been calm and
largely uneventful. Both are throwing the ball well in training
camp practices. Collins has probably turned more heads with his
play, in part because he is new to the team and partly because his
teammates might have expected less given his uneven performances in
the league the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the two passers coexist placidly, giving each other room for
the series of interviews each is asked to conduct daily. Graham is
tactful on the subject of Collins, even if he was angry when the
Giants signed Collins and miffed that the team never raised his
salary to bring it close to Collins' pay.
</P>
<P>
   Collins acknowledges that Graham is the starter and is careful
not to say that his immediate aim is to win the starting job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Testing the Waters
</P>
<P>
   There continue to be spirited exchanges between the Giants'
offensive and defensive units at camp. There has not been an
all-out brawl as there was earlier in the week, but during Friday's
practice running back LeShon Johnson and linebacker Jessie Armstead
had to be separated after a running play up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Armstead is one of the team's top trash talkers while Johnson is
perhaps the team's most quiet and serene player. But after Armstead
said he was going to test Johnson on the next play, Johnson
answered, ``I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson carried the ball on the next play, linebacker Corey
Widmer put a crunching hit on him. Johnson kept his feet and raced
downfield _ with his offensive teammates applauding.
</P>
<P>
   Special Developments
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have spent more time working on their special teams
than in either of two previous camps under Fassel. The special
teams coach, Larry Mac Duff, has been noticeably louder, chiding
and encouraging his troops almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were 28th in the NFL in punt returns last season and
tied for 27th in kickoff returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
