<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE'S ANDRO REPORT NOT GETTING GOOD PLAY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news story last week was like a blur. Here today, gone
tomorrow. You had to look fast, and in some newspapers, look long
and hard. And then maybe you found it.
</P>
<P>
   ``markmcgwirenolongertakes androstenedione.''
</P>
<P>
   Got that? Got a problem with that kind of news coverage? If not,
you should.
</P>
<P>
   One August ago, under World War III-type headlines, Mark McGwire
was being portrayed as a synthetic slugger, pumped up with muscles
made from chemistry. As he attacked baseball's home-run record, he
was under attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Asterisk Gang marched on Bud Selig's office, demanding that
if the record fell, which it did, McGwire's feat be tagged as
pharmaceutical-aided.
</P>
<P>
   It mattered not that ``andro'' was a legal diet supplement in
major-league baseball. Or that it was sold over the counter. Or
even that muscle mass is an elementary element on the list of what
makes great hitters.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was immediately labeled a cheater once it was learned he
used a supplement that was banned by the NCAA and by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In some minds, McGwire's 70 home runs will always be tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Except...
</P>
<P>
   In the quest for his 500th career home run last week, national
attention became focused again on McGwire. And again, the question
of andro came up, prompting McGwire to say he had been waiting for
someone to ask.
</P>
<P>
   His answer should have become a much bigger story than it did.
McGwire claimed he stopped using andro at the start of this season.
He didn't like the message being sent to youngsters, and if
marketed in a responsible way, this is a supplement to be used by
only fully ]mature adults.
</P>
<P>
   But add it up.
</P>
<P>
   With andro, McGwire is currently on a home-run binge equal to
last season. When he surpassed the 500 mark with two homers on
Thursday night, he had hit 17 in 21 games, and stood at 44 for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   So where's all the retractions from last August?
</P>
<P>
   If McGwire is telling the truth, and there's no reason to doubt
him, andro had nothing to do with what happened last season.
Shouldn't that have been the World War III-screaming headlines last
week?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, I have no way of knowing what fuel McGwire puts in
his body. It might be Wheaties. It might be Exxon Supreme.
</P>
<P>
   But going back to his younger days in Oakland, there have always
been those eager to label McGwire as something other than a guy who
thrived on mom's home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   He was and is a weightlifting addict. Over the years, McGwire
has grown into the most imposing physical specimen in sports. Take
any of those 300-pounders in the NFL, and they all appear fat and
out-of-shape next to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   But for much of his career, he was often sidelined by injuries.
Whispers of the body breaking down due to steriod use were heard in
baseball. Only, however, when he began his pursuit of 62 homers
last season did McGwire come under full fire. And that was because
a reporter noticed a bottle of andro pills in his locker, then
researched the subject, and wrote a story. McGwire freely admitted
he used andro, unaware of the firestorm that would follow.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, he doesn't ``use,'' and the home runs still come,
yet the story of no more andro was found in some papers just below
the fishing report from Possum Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   But in discontinuing andro, McGwire might be hardly alone in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, it was being treated as the greatest thing to
come along since ice cream,'' said Tim Lang, the Rangers'
major-league and organizational conditioning coach. ``But from that
bandwagon time, the andro thing has really tailed off. I know some
of our players found it to be like a placebo. It did basically
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang, known for being very conservative on diet supplements, was
one of many lost voices who was saying last August the McGwire
issue was being completely overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to try and educate players on all this _ give them
the pros and cons,'' he said. ``From there, it's up to the player,
just as long as it's a legal substance. And andro is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang said a certain number of Rangers players were using andro
last season, long before the McGwire controversy. ``None of them
use it this year, not because of what happened with McGwire, but
because they didn't think it was a factor,'' said Lang. ``These
were big and strong guys when they were taking it, and they are
still big and strong guys.''
</P>
<P>
   A few other Rangers, according to Lang, are trying andro this
season. ``As long as everyone understands possible side effects,
and there may be some, it's not that big a deal as long as baseball
approves it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only with McGwire did it become a large deal. In fact, it became
almost a nightmare. Based on what's happening this season, it was a
nightmare over nothing.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
