<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-WOO-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SEES DISCRIMINATION, BUT ALSO GAINS FOR BLACKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Vice President Al Gore, wooing blacks and liberals at
a conference organized by the Rev. Jesse Jackson, said Saturday
that America had ``not openly acknowledged'' its legacy of
discrimination, especially ``the pain of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is seeking the Democratic presidential nomination,
also lashed out repeatedly at Republicans as greedy and unfair, but
did not mention his Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, who
spoke at the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition conference here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the Clinton administration was doing too little to
help poor children.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first two-term Democratic president since Franklin
Roosevelt,'' Bradley said, ``the number of children in poverty in
America has barely blipped down.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who made unsuccessful presidential bids of his own in
1984 and 1988, has said he has not decided which of the two
Democratic candidates he will endorse.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in introducing the vice president, Jackson described
him as ``perhaps the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore praised Jackson as a civil rights hero and recalled the
work of his own late father, Al Gore Sr., in championing civil
rights as a senator from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that blacks in America had benefited greatly from the
economic prosperity of the Clinton era. And he said the White House
had promoted diversity at the highest ranks, noting that seven
blacks had been appointed to Cabinet positions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won perhaps his biggest applause when he called for an end
to racial profiling, which includes the practice of singling out
blacks for police questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``DWI is a crime _ DWB is not,'' he said, contrasting driving
while intoxicated to ``driving while black.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also reiterated his call for a $1 increase in the minimum
wage, preschool for all American children and strong affirmative
action policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said on Friday that he was organizing his campaign
around the theme of racial unity. ``I'm staking my presidential
campaign on the belief that over 50 to 60 percent of Americans,
including white Americans, want to have racial unity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also voiced skepticism at Gore's vow to end the practice
of racial profiling if he became president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Why wait?''' Bradley said. ``Why doesn't he walk down
the hall, put the executive order in front of the president and ask
him to sign it?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Saturday that the Clinton administration could take a
big share of the credit for a rosy economic picture, which included
substantial gains by blacks. He said the rate of poverty among
blacks was at its lowest point in the nation's history and the rate
of home ownership among blacks was at its highest.
</P>
<P>
   But he said some places of deep poverty and desperation in
America seemed almost untouched by ``these times of plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here today to tell you I am not satisfied and I know we
can do better,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the average family wealth of blacks was about
one-tenth that of whites, a disparity he attributed to generations
of discrimination. He also lamented that nearly a half-century
after the Supreme Court ruling that struck down segregation in
public schools, more than two-thirds of black children attended
schools where minority students predominated. Children in those
schools, Gore said, were some 16 times more likely to be poor than
children in predominantly white schools.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president criticized what he described as the
undercounting of blacks and members of other minorities by the
Census Bureau. And he pledged to support stiffer penalties for
attacks based on a victim's ethnicity or religion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also sprinkled his speech with references to religious
faith. ``I believe that God's hand has touched the United States of
America on purpose and not by accident,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore criticized a Republican plan approved by Congress this week
that would cut taxes by $792 billion, saying that the top 1 percent
of income earners would see as much relief as the bottom 60 percent
combined.
</P>
<P>
   He described the plan as a ``special interest smorgasbord'' that
would ``tear the country apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
