<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-VICTIMS08-COX     08-07 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-VICTIMS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forever bound by misfortune
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade and Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kenny Doonan's hope returned with a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Doonan was in a Northside Hospital room watching over his
youngest son, Brent. Mark O. Barton had shot him four times: in the
stomach, chest and arms. A fifth bullet grazed his face.
</P>
<P>
   It was early July 31, two days after the Buckhead shootings, and
doctors had earlier removed a tube from Brent's throat that had
prevented speaking. The clock read 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad. Dad. Get my clothes,'' Brent whispered from his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' Kenny Doonan asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting out of here,'' his son whispered back.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment of relief for Brent's father, even though his
son is still in the hospital recovering from the flurry of shots at
the All-Tech Investment Group office where Brent is part owner. The
joy from that whisper equaled the happiness when Brent _ the middle
of three kids _ was born 26 years ago today, Kenny Doonan said.
</P>
<P>
   Brent is improving, but, like many of the 13 wounded, he is a
long way from being healed.
</P>
<P>
   He has trouble sleeping. At night memories of the shooting haunt
him. He has asked the hospital to send his get-well flowers to the
gravesides of the nine people who did not survive.
</P>
<P>
   He has had nurses wheel him down the hall to visit one of his
employees, 22-year-old Meredith Winitt, who was shot in the back.
She has been upgraded to fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical is going OK,'' Brent said. ``What's so hard for
me to get over is the emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEKING A PAINLESS DEATH
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of seconds, Marci Brookings had prepared herself to
die. She works at Momentum Securities, where Barton started firing
his two handguns around 2:50 p.m. on July 29.
</P>
<P>
   Hit in the left shoulder blade, she fell and played dead. All
she could do was lay on the floor and think of a painless death as
Barton continued his rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the first shot didn't hurt,'' Brookings said. ``I
was comforting myself on the floor. I was thinking the next one
won't hurt either.'' Brookings flew to Houston to attend Monday's
funeral of another shooting victim and co-worker, Kevin Dial. She
has been to other memorial services for the shooting victims. She
feels lucky to have lived and has thought about the people who
died. And their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy is over, but nothing is normal,'' Brookings said.
``My wounds will heal far before my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Yuzef Liberzon has been close to death on a ventilator at Grady
Memorial Hospital since the shooting. The Ukranian immigrant from
Kiev was a taxi driver who took up day trading because he wanted a
less dangerous job. Barton fired one bullet into Liberzon's head.
Surgery removed the bullet, but his family was unsure whether the
39-year-old man would live, friends say. Liberzon is in critical
condition at Grady but expected to live.
</P>
<P>
   Liberzon had health insurance, but a fund has been set up to
help his family. Many in the tight-knit Russian community continue
to drop off food and money at the condominium he shares with his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``People realize this could have happened to anyone,'' said
Lenny Veksler, a friend who was sitting beside Liberzon when he was
shot. ``None of us know what we could face. So that makes people
become human, become softer.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the shooting, Brent Doonan had planned to celebrate his
birthday by bar-hopping with friends. The limousine was lined up.
Instead, he will celebrate the day, which is also his mother's
birthday, with family at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as he spoke about his birthday and recovery, Brent
was out of his bed, sitting up in a chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful to be alive,'' Brent said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
