</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf cart spill gives Santiago a bruising
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ When the Falcons practiced in Jacksonville
last summer, coach Dan Reeves said a solid morning session ``set
the tempo'' for an NFC Championship season.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's practices with the Jacksonville Jaguars at Furman
University, the tempo was set when starting tight end O.J. Santiago
fell off a moving golf cart on his way to the practice fields.
</P>
<P>
   He badly bruised himself on the left side from the butt to his
calf, and might have sprained his knee.
</P>
<P>
   No structural damage is feared, but that clearly annoyed Reeves
on a day when 13 players missed all or part of camp with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time something moves, you can get hurt,'' said Reeves, who
earlier in training camp nearly ran over Furman president David Shi
in a golf cart while Shi was jogging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys were running a little bit late, they get in a hurry,
and all of a sudden a guy falls off the cart.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegedly, the accident occured when several carts were weaving
among each other on an incline.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he went flying when the cart cornered too fast, he
said, ``It was something like that. I'm not going to say much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from my ankle all the way up the hamstring. We'll know
more later. I'll be out there as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Next
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will be off today, and in fact several veterans
headed back to Atlanta on Saturday night. They must return in time
for meetings at 7 p.m. today. The team will practice Monday,
perhaps just once because so many players are hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad and ugly
</P>
<P>
   The good _ Strong-side linebacker Keith Brooking had an
interception in morning passing drills.... Rookie wide receiver
Eugene Baker made several nice catches, including one in the end
zone where he barely got his second foot down for a touchdown....
In the afternoon session, quarterback Chris Chandler was sharp, and
completed his first six passes in one drill.
</P>
<P>
   The bad _ Right tackle Ephraim Salaam had a much better
afternoon than morning: At one point in the early session, Jaguars
rookie end Chris White pushed him straight backward on his butt,
and on the next play ran right past him. ``It was one of those
days,'' Salaam said.... Wide receiver Tim Dwight made some nice
catches, including a touchdown in the afternoon where he just got
his feet in. But he dropped several passes Saturday, and
occasionally had problems beating coverage at the line.... Running
back Ken Oxendine fumbled twice on one play.... Jacksonville
cornerback Aaron Beasley got past tight end Rod Monroe to block a
Morten Andersen field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The ugly _ In the afternoon, reserve defensive tackle Bob
Kuberski got locked up with Jaguars rookie guard Anthony Cesario
when their helmets got tangled at the face mask.
</P>
<P>
   Stone Mountain update
</P>
<P>
   Falcons officials could decide by Monday whether to go forward
with plans to build a two-story, 70,000-square foot facility in
Stone Mountain Park in time for the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   President Taylor Smith, general manager Harold Richardson and
others met Friday with officials from the park and Silver Dollar
City, the Branson, Mo.-based company that manages the park.
</P>
<P>
   Present aches and pains
</P>
<P>
   Missing both Saturday practices were defensive end Chuck Smith
(sprained right big toe), center Todd McClure (right knee), wide
receiver Chris Calloway (sprained left ankle), tight end O.J.
Santiago (bruised left side), wide receiver Eric Harris (back),
defensive end Brett Williams (knee).
</P>
<P>
   Wide receivers Ronnie Harris (groin) and Terance Mathis (back)
left in the midst of the morning session, as did reserve cornerback
Eli Williams (right knee), and defensive tackle Ben Huff (sprained
right foot).
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, reserve middle linebacker Ruffin Hamilton
(right knee) and cornerback Michael Booker (right thigh) were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The future
</P>
<P>
   Brett Williams has cartilage damage in his knee, and will be out
another couple weeks, maybe longer if ligament damage is
discovered. Smith might return to practice next week after missing
every session since opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Elijah Williams will miss at least two weeks with minor tearing
of his medial collateral ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton hyperextended his knee, and strained his quadricep
tendon. He won't practice Monday, but could return next week.
</P>
<P>
   McClure, who tore the anterior cruciate ligament July 30, almost
certainly is out for the season, and running back Gary Downs
already is on injured reserve after undergoing surgery for a torn
lateral collateral ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Byron Hanspard was rested in the afternoon
practice, as planned, while continuing his recovery from last
year's serious left knee injury
</P>
<P>
   Tight checkbook
</P>
<P>
   A season-ending knee injury July 30 to running back Gary Downs
and McClure, who almost certainly end up on injured reserve, will
cost Atlanta $575,000 and $183,333, respectively, or about 1.3
percent of the $57.3 million salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The team has about $250,000 left under the cap, meaning even if
the Falcons wanted to get a talented player released elsewhere, the
front office would have to create room by cutting players with high
salaries, or restructuring some contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   There was a crowd of about 1,000 in the morning, 2,400 in the
afternoon.... Backup left guard Greg Bishop got some work at No. 1,
and his first work at No. 3 center.... Jacksonville guard Todd
Fordham, a former All-State player at Georgia's Tift County High,
went down screaming Saturday morning. He tore the medial collateral
ligament in his left knee, and more damage may be found today.
While he was screaming, Chuck Smith yelled from afar, ``Hang in
there, big dog.''... The Falcons offense appeared surprised in the
morning during 9-on-7 drills when Jacksonville defensive
coordinator Dom Capers was blitzing safeties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
