<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons `Jag-ged' in joint practice
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ The Falcons' young wide receivers got plenty
of work in Saturday's joint practices with the Jacksonville
Jaguars. That's the first part of the good news.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the bad news is they had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Starting split end Chris Calloway is on crutches after spraining
an ankle Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Ron Harris, strained a groin muscle Saturday
morning, and starting flanker Terance Mathis left the field after
twisting his back.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis returned in the afternoon; Harris did not.
</P>
<P>
   Including previous injuries, 13 players missed all or part of
Saturday's work.
</P>
<P>
   In a scrimmage in Jacksonville last year, the Falcons ``set the
tempo'' for their NFC Championship season, according to coach Dan
Reeves, when they got the better of the Jags.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it was the other way around, especially in the
matchup of the Falcons' offense against Jacksonville's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys worked hard, but understand, Jacksonville didn't come in
here thinking it was just a regular practice,'' Mathis said. ``They
want to measure up to where we are. We did decently; we can
practice a lot better. We have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday started off on the wrong foot, or leg, when starting
tight end O.J. Santiago fell off a moving golf cart on the way to
practice. He badly bruised his left leg, and was limping in street
clothes the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of set the tempo as far as injuries were
concerned,'' Reeves said. ``You see some of the deficiencies you
have when you practice against somebody else. We need our better
players.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other injuries, as reserve defensive tackle Ben Huff
(sprained right foot), reserve cornerback Eli Williams (sprained
right knee), reserve middle linebacker Ruffin Hamilton (sprained
right knee), and cornerback Michael Booker (strained right thigh)
went down.
</P>
<P>
   The news wasn't as bad for the defense, although defensive
tackle Shane Dronett said, ``It wasn't as good as last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Things went better in the afternoon, when the offense was more
crisp, although reserve quarterbacks Tony Graziani and Sherdrick
Bonner struggled.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive intensity was good in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reeves didn't seem thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have not done any extra conditioning after practice
since training camp started, and he said Thursday he felt players
were in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the injuries are typically associated with poor
conditioning. This on a team that had starters miss just 20 of a
possible 352 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because I thought we came in here in really
good condition,'' Reeves said. ``It doesn't take but one or two
plays offensively, and you get a really bad taste in your mouth.
I've got several bad tastes in my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
