<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some unfinished business for Waltrip
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Darrell Waltrip, who earlier in the week said he
was leaving Winston Cup driving after the 2000 season, had an early
retirement at the Brickyard 400 on Saturday. The No. 66 Ford drove
off the track after only 58 laps because of ignition problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going down the back, I was thinking about trying to pass
(Dale) Earnhardt and them,'' Waltrip said. ``I pulled out and (the
car) quit ... it just died and wouldn't fire back up.''
</P>
<P>
   The early exit was the final part of an emotional weekend for
the 52-year-old. On top of the retirement announcement, Waltrip had
to qualify because he was out of provisionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come back next year, I hope I don't struggle like I did
this week,'' said Waltrip, who started 35th. ``The announcement and
barely getting in the race ... then to have a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to a great run today. I thought we had a
good car and were up for that, but obviously we left something
undone here.''
</P>
<P>
   Big words from Little
</P>
<P>
   Chad Little launched an attack on Geoff Bodine after they mixed
it up in consecutive turns on lap 43, with the second tangle
sending Little into the wall and out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a brain-dead maneuver (by Bodine),'' said Little, who
was uninjured. ``I got bumped by a bald-headed cue ball.'' After a
long pause, the Ford No 97 driver said, ``I'm not saying anything
because I'm counting to 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot Wheels on fire
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty had the scariest wreck of the day. On lap 72, the No.
44 Hot Wheels car blew a right front tire in turn 1 and slammed
into the retaining wall at an estimated speed of 170 mph. Petty
climbed out with no assistance as the car's front end burst into
flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must have ran over something on the track,'' Petty said of the
flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   Extra Laps
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Craven, who finished 38th, signed with Midwest Transit
Racing to drive the No. 50 Chevy for the remainder of the season.
... While the majority of the field was in the pit, Dave Marcis
sneaked to the front on lap 75. At age 58, Marcis became the oldest
driver to lead a lap at the Brickyard 400. The previous record was
set in the '94 event by Harry Gant _ then 54 years old. Marcis was
forced out on lap 143 because of a smoking engine. ... Jeff and
Ward Burton battled it out for fifth place and family pride during
the final 10 laps. The cars exchanged the lead several times, with
Jeff edging his older brother at the checkered flag. ... Ricky
Rudd, in desperate search of a sponsor for next year, helped his
cause by finishing ninth _ his first top 10 of the season. ``We
needed (this),'' Rudd said. ``We're nervous, with not having a
sponsor yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch down to a point
</P>
<P>
   While Brickyard winner Dale Jarrett holds a seemingly invincible
lead in the Winston Cup points standings, the Busch Series is as
tight as it gets. Dale Earnhardt Jr., who finished fifth in
Friday's Kroger 200, has a slim one-point advantage over Matt
Kenseth in the standings, 3,102 to 3,101. Jason Keller of
Greenville, S.C., won the race under a caution flag from the pole.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
