</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez suspension starts; Simon sent down, Matos brought up
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eddie Perez settled his problem Saturday. Now the
Braves have one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Perez dropped his appeal of his four-game suspension, not so
coincidently the morning after he caught Greg Maddux, and began
serving his punishment for fighting Philadelphia's Paul Byrd last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better to do it now, rather than later, I guess,'' Perez said.
``We just talked with (National League president Len) Coleman on
the phone. There's no chance to get a game less (reduction). He
said, ``No, no, no.'''
</P>
<P>
   The upshot for the Braves: they lose a catcher plus a .314
hitter. The club recalled catcher Pascual Matos from Class AAA
Richmond to back up Greg Myers. But in order to open a spot on the
25-man roster, they were forced to send rookie first baseman
Randall Simon back to Richmond, where by option rules he must stay
for at least 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't go, they have to release someone like Ozzie
(Guillen) or Otis (Nixon) or somebody like that,'' Simon said.
``Bobby (Cox, Braves manager) says he tried to think of all kinds
of way to try to leave me here but they couldn't do anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rookie Bruce) Chen is here now and there's no one else with
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Matos's stay will last only as long as Perez sits out, when they
Braves will pull the hottest bat they can find in Richmond. There
is not prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a bunch of guys,'' manager Bobby Cox said, naming Brad
Tyler (.290, 21 HR), Howard Battle (.292, 20 HR), Toby Rumfield
(.269, 12 HR) and Marty Malloy (.307, 7 HR). ``All kinds of names
popped up. I'm just leaving it to the organization to bring us a
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon is not only leading the team in average but had helped
solidify defense at first base, with just three errors in 451 total
chances. Ryan Klesko returned to first Saturday, making his first
start there since May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Keith Lockhart lasted just two batters Saturday
before a collision with San Francisco's F.P. Santangelo opened a
gash in Lockhart's lower lip, sending him to Piedmont Hospital for
two stitches and precautionary X-rays on his jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he comes in here (this morning) not feeling well, it's a
different story,'' said assistant trainer Jeff Porter. ``But as of
right now, he can play (today).
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart was injured trying to cover first base on a Santangelo
bunt, after Klesko, in his first start at first base in 68 days,
got crossed up on covering duties. Lockhart arrived at the base
late to take pitcher Terry Mulholland's throw, just in time to take
Santangelo's elbow to the head, causing him to bite through his
bottom lip.
</P>
<P>
   Odalis returns
</P>
<P>
   Just two days after elbow surgery, rookie Odalis Perez visited
the clubhouse before the game, a more encouraged man than a week
ago. In a ``Tommy John'' procedure by Birmingham surgeon James
Andrews, a tendon from Perez's left wrist was tranplanted in the
elbow to replace a torn ulnar ligament. Andrews also removed a bone
spur. The average recovery time is 12-to-18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me everything this good,'' Perez said. ``I don't
think it'll be necessary to be out for a year. That's what they
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   With a 3-for-5 day, catcher Greg Myers increased his average to
.421 (8-for-19) with six RBIs.... Giants left fielder Barry Bonds
missed the game because of back spasms that forced him out of
Friday night's game.... Newcomer Jose Hernandez made his debut at
first base after a pinch-hit single in the sixth. Although he has
played at every position but pitcher or catcher in his career, he
has spent the least time at first (seven games).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
