<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-ALDAY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family ask if they could've saved daughter
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The press of information-hungry journalists. A nation
imposing its attention on a South Georgia town. Gory details of a
family wiped away at the hands of a brutal murderer.
</P>
<P>
   For Leigh Ann Barton's grandmother, Pauline Vandiver, it all
seems nearly as familiar as the sweet tea she makes for her family
on a hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six years ago, Vandiver's first love, Aubrey Alday, was
shot to death in the notorious slaughter of the Ned Alday family in
Seminole County. Vandiver's brother also was then married to Ned
Alday's sister. Escaped convict Carl Isaacs and three other men
killed six people execution-style following a bungled burglary at
the Alday home. Isaacs and his accomplices remain in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Now 78, Vandiver has watched her extended family endure murder
trials and years of legal wrangling over the death sentences given
to the Aldays' killers. It has all been background noise in the
life of Leigh Ann Barton's sister, Kelly Argo, but the 35-year-old
mother of four is well aware of the kind of pain that comes from
being so close to one of Georgia's worst mass murders.
</P>
<P>
   Argo considers it something of a blessing that Mark O. Barton,
44, killed himself after killing her 27-year-old sister, his two
children and nine office workers in what is now known as the worst
mass murder in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our family can go through another 20 years of
trials.''
</P>
<P>
   But without a trial to direct the family's emotions, they are
left to seek the clues to Barton's evil that they missed before.
They are left to pick apart a thousand smiles, and wonder whether
they came from a devoted husband or a calculating murderer.
</P>
<P>
   LIKABLE MEMBER OF THE FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Argo is clear about this: She didn't just lose a sister, a
niece and a nephew that she loved dearly. She also lost a brother.
</P>
<P>
   Argo and her husband, Gary, 37, had grown close to Barton during
his four-year marriage to Leigh Ann. When visiting Leigh Ann's
family in Macon, the Bartons always stayed with the Argos at their
five-bedroom manufactured home, neatly accented with hunter green
shutters on tan siding. Barton helped Gary dig stumps out of the
sandy dirt to make way for the home off a Jones County back road
southeast of Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Barton was one of Gary's groomsmen for the Argos' 1996 wedding.
He walked two grandmothers and Leigh Ann's mother down the aisle.
The couples' wedding anniversaries were so close they would often
celebrate them together. A game of Pictionary was a regular event
for the foursome.
</P>
<P>
   Gary and Barton grew particularly close. They spent countless
evenings over a hot grill, talking and cooking. They fried turkeys
over holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark liked things hot,'' Kelly Argo recalled. ``He could make
some chili that could tear your mouth up.''
</P>
<P>
   The families' children also grew close. Kelly's son, Derek, 12,
and Barton's son, Matthew, 11, spent hours swimming in the Argos'
above-ground pool and playing video games on Derek's Nintendo 64.
Gary and Barton would often team up against the boys to play a
James Bond game.
</P>
<P>
   Barton's daughter, Mychelle, 7, loved to hike with Kelly's
6-year-old daughter, Calyn. Gary would mow paths for the girls in
the tall brush behind the house. Gary found it odd that Barton
never spoke of his dead wife, Debra Spivey, the mother of his
children, or her 1993 murder. Not once in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get to know a friend like that you just talk about
anything,'' Gary said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also noted that the Barton rental home in Morrow had no
photos of Spivey, though Barton kept a college photo of her in his
wallet. Family members said Barton wouldn't let his children talk
about their mother or her murder. On Mother's Day, Leigh Ann, not
Barton, would take the children to their mother's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly admitted she had concerns early on about Barton, who was a
suspect in the bludgeoning deaths of his first wife and his
mother-in-law, Eloise Powell Spivey. But the Argos had grown
comfortable in the knowledge that Leigh Ann was ``thoroughly
convinced'' her husband had nothing to do with the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``After spending four years with him, I honestly didn't believe
he was capable of it,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs to the contrary, though.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Leigh Ann told Kelly she discovered a receipt for a
$1 million insurance policy Barton had taken out on her. It
frightened her, Kelly recalled. Leigh Ann had also found a tax
document in which Barton said he earned more than $460,000 the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   When Leigh Ann asked about the money, Barton admitted he
received an insurance settlement from his first wife's death. She
asked whether they could pay off their $6,000 in debt and buy a
house. Barton said no. The money was his and she shouldn't benefit
from his former wife's death, Barton told her. This upset Leigh
Ann, who had been working 60 hours a week to support the family
because Barton was not working.
</P>
<P>
   After Leigh Ann left her husband in October, he finally told her
that he had lost all of the money day trading.
</P>
<P>
   Barton promised to stop. It was a promise he wouldn't keep.
</P>
<P>
   Around March, Kelly helped Barton make a list of 40 things he
had to do in order for Leigh Ann to get back with him. One of them
was to quit day trading. Kelly remembers Barton's insistence that
he could make just as good a living day trading as working at a
salaried job.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Barton told Gary that he had made several thousand
dollars day trading. Kelly scolded Barton, who told her he had his
trading under control. Barton began calling the Argos less. Barton
and his children eventually moved back in with Leigh Ann.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Leigh Ann was killed, Kelly got a nervous feeling at
work, like something was wrong. She called home to make sure her
children and husband were all right and found them fine. Even then,
Kelly wasn't suspicious enough of her brother-in-law to think it
might be Leigh Ann who was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, hours after the shootings in Buckhead, next-door
neighbors flagged down Kelly as she drove her Mazda minivan down
the dirt road to her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark has gone on a rampage and he's killed a bunch of people
in Buckhead,'' Argo recalled a neighbor saying. ``I asked
immediately, what about Leigh Ann and the babies?''
</P>
<P>
   Gary called Leigh Ann's work to find out where she was.
Co-workers said she had taken a couple of days off. Kelly knew all
her sister's days off. Something was wrong. Before long, the news
came: Three people were found dead in the Bartons' Stockbridge
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to get dressed without her helping me pick
out clothes,'' Kelly said tearfully, as she talked about her
sister's clothes still hanging in the bedroom Barton and Leigh Ann
used.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Kelly has an overwhelming desire to apologize for
Barton to the familes of the office workers he killed in Buckhead.
She spoke to someone from each of the families at Wednesday's
citywide memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   A CIRCLE BROKEN
</P>
<P>
   Another of Leigh Ann's three sisters, Dana Reeves, wondered how
such a strong, close family wasn't able to stop Barton before it
was loo late. Maybe it's because the girls kept their marriage
problems to themselves, she concluded, surrounded by shampoos and
conditioners in the Macon hair dressers' supply store she manages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Leigh Ann just got involved with the wrong person. Her
entrapment was the kids,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Before she identified Leigh Ann's body for Henry County police,
the last time Reeves, 32, saw her sister was at a May birthday
party for Kelly Argo's daughter Lea. The fourth sister, Amy
Vandiver, 28, was there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The four of us just sat in Kelly's den and just laughed and
cut up,'' she remembered.
</P>
<P>
   She talked about how Leigh Ann moved out of her mother's home
before her senior year and moved in with Reeves to get some
independence. She remembers how Leigh Ann used to slip Reeves' baby
girl out of the crib at night and cuddle her in her bed.
</P>
<P>
   Now she balances those images with the body bags she saw police
carry from Leigh Ann's Stockbridge apartment. She remembers wishing
it was someone else in the bags, and that the sisters were still
four strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from a circle to a triangle now,'' she said,
looking toward the holidays. ``That's when it's really going to
hit, when we're not all there.''
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONS OF GUILT
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Ann's father, Joe Vandiver, is the kind of man who gets
his packs of Marlboro lights from a carton, but who remembers the
three times in his life he's been drunk.
</P>
<P>
   He says ``I love you'' after phone calls with relatives and hugs
his close friends. But this Vietnam veteran won't cower from a
threat and he won't hesitate to use one of his guns to defend his
family.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Vandiver isn't the type to meddle in his children's
affairs, but he likes to know where they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to hear from her all the time, as long as
somebody heard from her,'' Vandiver said, exhaling smoke from his
nostrils as he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Since his daughter's death, details of the Alabama police
investigation of Barton in his first wife's death have hit Vandiver
like sledgehammers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not blaming myself for the deaths of any of them, I just
wish I had had more information so I could have done something to
spare my daughter and these two children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vandiver said he never got close to Barton because he didn't
trust him. In fact, he told his daughter on several occasions that
he believed Barton killed his first wife and mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of heartburn when I realized they were seeing
each other,'' Vandiver recalled. ``She assured me I was wrong. It
wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if he had gotten closer, he could have seen something to
change his daughter's mind, Vandiver said.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Vandiver talked to Leigh Ann, whom the family
called Honey, was two weeks before her death. She had called to say
she was back home after a business trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very brief conversation. I think I was headed out or
something like that,'' he said, peering into the kitchen table. ``A
real, really brief phone call. That won't happen that way ever
again.''
</P>
<P>
   At Leigh Ann's burial, Vandiver insisted on shoveling the dirt
onto his daughter's grave. In the South Georgia heat, at a small
family cemetery out in the fields near Ocilla, he dripped over a
shovel while two of Kelly Argo's children used their hands to scoop
dirt onto their Aunt Honey's grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seen her come into this world and I'm going to see she's put
up right,'' Vandiver told his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
