<HEADLINE>
COMPLETELY INCOMPLETE SEASON FOR METS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Overlooked because of all the ex-Dodgers at Shea
Stadium this weekend is a strange record the New York Mets are
close to setting. They have a chance to become the first
major-league team to win a division title without pitching a
complete game.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, only one Mets starter has even been permitted to return
to the mound for a ninth inning. That was Orel Hershiser, who went
eight innings against the Marlins on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it more amazing is that they are doing it despite
losing closer John Franco last month. Armando Benitez has taken
over the job, but the Mets also acquired relievers Billy Taylor and
Chuck McElroy at the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets aren't entirely alone in this phenomenon: Of the six
division leaders, the Indians have just one complete game, the
Rangers two.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem so long ago that Hershiser pitched 15 complete
games for the Dodgers in 1988, a figure that's been matched only
twice since, by Jack McDowell, with the White Sox in 1991, and
Philadelphia's Curt Schilling last season. &QL; 
Expect some boos
</P>
<P>
   There will be big crowds this week when St. Louis comes to
Philadelphia and it has little to do with Mark McGwire. Phillies
fans want a chance to boo J.D. Drew, the second overall pick in the
1997 draft who refused to sign with them. This will be Drew's first
trip to Philadelphia and teammate Ricky Bottalico, the former
Phillies closer, has advised the 23-year-old outfielder to wear a
helmet in the outfield. ``He laughed, but I was serious,''
Bottalico said. ``I told him it's not going to be like two minutes
of booing, it's going to be all game, all day. He's never been to
Philly and I tried to make him realize it's not like St. Louis.'' &QL; 
Getting younger
</P>
<P>
   In attempts to reach the playoffs the past few seasons, the
Chicago Cubs stockpiled veteran players at the expense of
prospects, including Kennedy High's Jon Garland, who was sent to
the White Sox two years ago for reliever Matt Karchner. Now that
they are well out of the race, the Cubs are trying to reverse the
trend. In the deal that sent Terry Mulholland and Jose Hernandez to
Atlanta, Chicago received left-hander Micah Bowie, who got hammered
Tuesday by Montreal, and right-hander Ruben Quevedo, a 20-year old
Venezuelan who actually was the key to the deal. In his
minor-league career, Quevedo is just 20-20 but has 366 strikeouts
and only 108 walks in 363 innings. &QL; 
Big money
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Marlins and their No. 1 draft choice _ right-hander
Josh Beckett _ are still $3 million apart. But last month they did
sign a 16-year-old Venezuelan shortstop named Miguel Cabrera for a
$1.8 million signing bonus, more money than 22 of the 25 players
make on the Marlins roster. Only Alex Fernandez ($7 million), Cliff
Floyd ($2.5 million) and Jorge Fabregas ($1.85 million) have higher
salaries. Landing Cabrera, who already is 6-foot-2 and 190 pounds,
was considered quite a coup for the Marlins, who outbid the
Dodgers, Yankees and Braves. As for Beckett, if he is not signed he
will enter a junior college or Texas A&AMP;M and the Marlins will not
be able to negotiate until after the spring season. &QL; 
No Giant steps
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, which survived losing Barry Bonds for more than
two months earlier this season, might not be so lucky with Jeff
Kent on the disabled list with an inflamed left foot. The Giants
looked overmatched against West-leading Arizona when they lost two
of three earlier in the week. In Wednesday's series finale, an 8-4
loss, the Giants dropped Mark Gardner (3-9, 6.88) from the rotation
and promoted Joe Nathan from Triple-A Fresno. Nathan allowed five
runs, including three homers, in the first inning and was gone by
the second. He was sent back to the minors after the game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
