<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HAMBLETONIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF POSSESSED SETS RECORD FOR MILE IN HAMBLETONIAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Trainer Ron Gurfein and driver Mike
Lachance are considered the odd couple of harness racing, but the
two men have combined to dominate the industry in recent years.
Saturday afternoon they teamed up for their third Hambletonian
title in the past six years by capturing the 74th edition of the
most prestigious event in harness racing in the fastest mile ever
trotted.
</P>
<P>
   Self Possessed gave the excitable Gurfein and the quiet Lachance
the $1 million Hambletonian in the bright sunshine at the
Meadowlands in grand fashion. Self Possessed captured the first
event of the triple crown for 3-year-old trotters in 1:51 3/5,
breaking the previous record of 1:51 4/5 set by Beat The Wheel in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Self Possessed crossed the finish line, Gurfein
raced into the middle of the Meadowlands Racetrack and gave
Lachance a bear hug. The two men said afterward that Saturday's
triumph was just as sweet as their others, with Continentalvictory
in 1996 and Victory Dream in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I loved him,'' Gurfein said of his meeting with
Lachance in the middle of the track. ``He made 35 good decisions. I
wasn't happy that he didn't leave early, but he got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Lachance's key decisions was to take Self Possessed away
from the rail after taking the lead near the halfway point. He
avoided any chances of injury and led his horse to a 5 1/2 length
victory over Angus Hall, a stablemate.
</P>
<P>
   Self Possessed did not break stride, the way he did in the
Beacon Course, the biggest race leading into the Hambletonian.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just cruising,'' Lachance said of Self Possessed. ``He
did everything on his own. He's strong and has a good head on his
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   The entry left as the overwhelming favorite and brought their
owners the bulk of the $1 million purse. The two brought $750,000,
with Enjoy Lavec, the third-place finisher, earning $120,000 in the
field of 10. Raffaello Ambrosio, the third horse in the entry,
finished fourth and earned $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell, the winner of five Hambletonians, including last
year's, with Muscles Yankee, was the driver of Angus Hall Saturday
afternoon. Campbell had another successful day, adding another
title to his legendary career.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell captured his first title in the $500,000 Hambletonian
Oaks for 3-year-old pacing fillies when he rallied with Oolong down
the stretch to finish ahead of Lovelytobehold. Oolong is a
granddaughter of Superbowl, the last triple crown winner, and she
covered the mile in 1:54 4/5.
</P>
<P>
   ``She raced well last week, but she was better today,'' Campbell
said about Oolong, who was in seventh place most of the race.
Campbell got her into good position after three horses broke stride
before the half.
</P>
<P>
   The $400,000 Mistletoe Shalee for 3-year-old fillies was the
first stakes race of the afternoon, and it was captured by French
Panicure. Driven by George Brennan, French Panicure covered the
mile in 1:50 4/5, equaling the stakes record, and finished a length
ahead of Marfa Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bow Tie took the $131,000 U.S. Pacing Championship with a
strong finish even though he started on the outside. ``He can do
just about anything,'' said Luc Ouellette, the driver of Red Bow
Tie, who covered the mile in 1:48 4/5 for his eighth victory in 14
starts this season. He finished a head in front of Day in a Life.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of excitement was created in the eighth race when
Galleria set a world record for a filly by covering the mile in
1:49 1/5 in winning the inaugural Free for All, an invitational for
mares.
</P>
<P>
   In the $135,000 Oliver Wendell Holmes for 3-year-old pacing
colts and geldings, The Panderosa, the overwhelming favorite at
1-5, broke stride around the first turn and never recovered. Space
Shuttle (1:50 4/5) and Seven Card Hanover (1:51 1/5) won their
respective divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Magician took the $424,000 Nat Ray Final by a head over
Supergrit. Driven by Dave Miller, Magician took over the lead at
the half and held on for his fourth victory of the season in 14
starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
