<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SUPPAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPAN GETS FRESH START WITH ROYALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ His Kansas City Royals teammates appreciate Jeff
Suppan's colorful wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Suppan's wearing his Hawaiian shirts the day before he
pitches now,'' reliever Scott Service barked in the visiting
clubhouse at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day in August,'' Suppan hollered back.
</P>
<P>
   The Don Ho look is nothing new for the 24-year-old Crespi High
product. Suppan began the tradition in 1996 while pitching for the
Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his appetite for Hawaiian attire, Suppan's career hasn't
been all flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals are Suppan's third team since the Red Sox made him
their second-round pick in 1993. Considered one of Boston's
brightest pitching prospects, he made his big-league debut at 20
and won seven of 10 decisions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox found Suppan expendable and left him unprotected for
the 1998 expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a kinship with former Boston pitching coach Al Nipper,
Suppan was excited when the Diamondbacks selected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't frustrated at all about being unprotected. It was fun
for me to go to the West Coast. And I was going to a whole new
team. That was a new start for me and a new start for a lot of
things,'' he said. ``When you get picked by that first
organization, you think you'll be there forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks gave up on him in less than a season. Suppan
went 1-7 with a 6.68 ERA and was sent to the minors for two months
before the Royals purchased his contract last Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, a small-market franchise struggling to contend,
can't afford not to gamble with young pitchers such as Suppan who
have upside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have projects here. We're getting the best talent we
possibly can, but there are a lot of projects,'' Royals manager
Tony Muser said. ``We have a lot of guys that other teams didn't
keep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soupy's earned the chance to pitch every fifth day. He has a
chance to get to the next level. He's taking advantage of the
opportunity he has here.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppan is wise enough to know the Red Sox and Diamondbacks made
business decisions in letting him go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   And he's learned to cope with the game's instability and
constant roster shuffling at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals had enough confidence in Suppan to stick him in the
rotation right away. With the recent trade of Kevin Appier, Suppan
and Jose Rosado are Muser's most effective starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a guy like Kevin Appier who's been here his whole
career, and just like that, he's traded. I look at being with three
organizations already as a good thing because I've already
experienced moving around,'' Suppan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of roadblocks last season. The Diamondbacks gave
me a lot of opportunities to perform. I didn't pitch well. They had
to go with who they thought could get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it is, yes this is a game. But it's also a
business. And for that team I didn't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppan is more focused on giving the Royals some much-needed
innings. His 6-6 record is misleading compared to a 3.86 ERA that's
among the top 10 in the American League. There was even some talk a
couple of months ago of making the All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   He's averaged a shade less than seven innings among 21 starts
and registered his first career shutout last Tuesday when he
five-hit the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works hard. He studies the game. He studies the hitters.
It's hard to find a 24-year-old who studies the game like he's a
28-year-old. He's getting an early start,'' pitching coach Mark
Wiley said.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan admits he's more comfortable in the American League, but
his bat seems conducive to the designated hitter-less National
League. He had six hits in 22 at-bats with Arizona last season.
</P>
<P>
   And on July 18 at Wrigley Field, Suppan collected the first RBI
by a Royals pitcher since interleague play began.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan singled down the left-field line with runners on first
and second in a typical bunt situation. Muser let his pitcher swing
away, and Suppan bounced the ball past drawn-in Cubs third baseman
Tyler Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitcher thinks he's a good hitter,'' a grinning Suppan
said. ``I was a pretty good high school hitter. I try to put the
ball in play, get guys over with the bunt. That's all important.''
</P>
<P>
   So too is deciding what color Hawaiian shirt to wear to the
ballpark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
