<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett hot streak `as good as it gets'
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Dale Jarrett dominated Saturday's Brickyard 400
the same way he has the Winston Cup points race.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford No. 88 driver crossed the brick-laden finish line 3.351
seconds ahead of his nearest competitor at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. Jarrett, who led 116 of 160 laps, increased his advantage
in the standings to 274 points over Mark Martin, the biggest margin
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anybody to shake me to wake me up,'' Jarrett
said. ``It's as good as it can get right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With his second victory in four years at the Brickyard, Jarrett
joined Jeff Gordon as the race's only two-time champions. Bobby
Labonte finished runner-up, while pole-sitter Gordon passed Martin
at the end to capture third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good car all day long, but we couldn't run with
Jarrett,'' said Labonte, who won at Pocono Raceway July 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale is on a pretty good roll,'' Gordon said. ``It's like they
were bidding their time getting those top fives early in the season
and everything started clicking. Boom, now they are getting wins
and that team deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Jarrett's fourth win, 16th top five, and 18th top 10 in
20 races this season. What made Saturday's victory even more
satisfying is that Jarrett cruised into the winner's circle in the
car that ran out of gas in last year's Brickyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shed a lot of tears (last year),'' owner Robert Yates said.
``We couldn't even joke about running out gas for sixth months.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett gambled again this time and won. During his final pit
stop, crew chief Todd Parrott opted to only change the two right
side tires. It saved 8-9 seconds, and Jarrett was fortunate enough
to finish without any major handling problems.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was a family affair. Jarrett's father, former
Winston Cup driver Ned Jarrett, spotted for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an advantage to have Dad up there as long as we kept
him from commentating,'' Jarrett said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
