<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday,
Aug. 8. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FISHER-LANDMINES: LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Tyson Malik occasionally
clambers into a 750-square-foot concrete box filled with sand
inside Nichols Hall on the University of Kansas campus here and
buries objects at varying depths. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His cohort, Abhijit Apte, then activates weird-looking antennas
along the box's edges that track to and fro as they deliver signals
into a computer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pair is looking for land mines _ pinpointing exactly what
Malik has planted beneath the sand and their precise location. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who says Kansas is a dull, unexciting place? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By JIM FISHER. 1,000 words. Will move on the ``a'' wire.
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-TAPES: WASHINGTON _ Most people know the story of
Watergate, but relatively few people _ historians, researchers,
occasional tourists, Nixon junkies _ have taken the time to listen
to it unfold in conversations the president recorded. That could
change markedly on Jan. 1, when 264 hours of White House tapes will
be available for public duplication and sale for the first time.
Currently, tapes cannot be reproduced, much less distributed.
</P>
<P>
   By KEVIN MURPHY. 1,000 words. Will move on the ``a'' wire.
</P>
<P>
   INS-OFFICE _ KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Immigration and
Naturalization Service will open an office near Springfield, part
of an expansion into emerging centers of immigration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 45 Quick Response Teams will target immigrant smuggling,
document fraud, employment violations and other crime in 11
states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new office in Strafford, Mo., reflects the changing
demographics of the Ozarks, part of a shift in immigration patterns
nationwide. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, poultry plants and factories in the Ozarks have
attracted thousands of immigrants from Latin America. The newcomers
have transformed many small towns as they fill schools, housing and
churches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Jaromin, deputy district director, said southwest
Missouri also is seeing its share of illegal immigration and
related crime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe it is a problem. That is part of the reason
we're going out there,'' said Jaromin, whose Kansas City office
will oversee the team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new INS office will open Sept. 1 about 10 miles east of
Springfield. The office will employ 11, including seven special
agents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By OSCAR AVILA. 750 words. Will move on the ``a'' wire. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
