<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARTINEZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ PROVES DODGERS DEAD WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Dodgers haven't forgotten the way they misjudged
Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   And if by some miracle they ever do, Martinez will be there to
tap them on the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, an uninspiring Orioles-Tigers game was on the
television in the Red Sox clubhouse. Suddenly, Martinez stood up,
pointed at the monitor and pierced the silence in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``There he is!'' Martinez said, a haughty grin creeping across
his face. ``There's the man I got traded for.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Delino DeShields, the disappointing infielder the Dodgers
acquired for Martinez following the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   DeShields fouled out on the first pitch. Martinez's smile grew
wider. All that was missing was former Dodgers general manager Fred
Claire and a box of tissues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They traded me because I wasn't durable enough,'' Martinez
scoffed. ``How durable has (DeShields) been? How many times has he
been on the disabled list?''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has done plenty on the mound to make the Dodgers regret
the deal. He has won 89 games for Montreal and Boston. He is
working on his second Cy Young award. He has taken Greg Maddux's
place as the top pitcher in baseball. He was the hometown MVP of
last month's All-Star Game at Fenway Park, striking out five in two
innings, including the trifecta of Sammy Sosa, Mark McGwire and
Larry Walker.
</P>
<P>
   That should be all the revenge Martinez needs. That, and knowing
that Claire forever will live in infamy because of his one badly
flawed deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez isn't satisfied to let his post-Dodger
accomplishments speak for themselves. Almost seven years after the
fact, Martinez still stews over being discounted by then-manager
Tom Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy could be the greatest manager ever,'' Martinez said.
``But he was dead wrong when he said Pedro will never go five
innings as a starter. I've gone seven years in the big leagues, and
I haven't been sitting down, either. I've been pitching, working,
throwing innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, renowned Dodgers physician Frank Jobe, perhaps in an
effort to deflect lasting criticism from Claire, admitted in a
published report that he advised the Dodgers to trade Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe believed that Martinez was a breakdown waiting to happen, a
Ferrari engine in a Yugo chassis. His slight frame simply couldn't
handle the strain of throwing a 95-mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Martinez hasn't blown out his arm. His ligaments aren't the
slightest bit frayed.
</P>
<P>
   Bone chips? He's never heard of them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is the rather large chip on Martinez's
shoulder, the kind that won't show up on a magnetic resonance
imaging scan.
</P>
<P>
   And Jobe's comments only gave Martinez another reason to vent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (messed) up,'' Martinez said of Jobe, the man heralded as
an expert in the field of sports medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be called the best doctor in the world, but I don't
think he knows how to judge a pitcher's stamina. I'll take my
chances against any of them. Tommy Lasorda and his comments, Dr.
Jobe and his comments. They might be the greatest baseball men of
all time, but they really made a big mistake when they doubted
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez finally missed a turn in the rotation this season.
After a horrible outing July 18 against Florida, he was placed on
the DL with soreness in his shoulder and missed three starts. Talk
of a 30-win season evaporated as quickly as it had begun.
</P>
<P>
   But it was hardly a breakdown. Just a little fatigue, Martinez
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seven years, I think it's OK to rest for three weeks,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Red Sox are concerned, Martinez earned the
breather. He has a 15-3 record in 20 starts this season. He has a
70-strikeout advantage over Chuck Finley for the American League
lead. Aside from that one bad start, he has been unhittable.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox will get about 12 more starts out of Martinez this
season, including today against the Angels, and they need to
squeeze every victory they can out of their ace. Entering the
weekend, they were one game behind Toronto for the wild card, but
had sagged to 10-11 since the all-star break.
</P>
<P>
   Being sidelined for the first time in his career made Martinez a
tad worrisome. Watching his team slide at the same time made him
angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got me in a really bad mood,'' Martinez said. ``It was like
being in the boxing ring and not being able to throw a punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has one more body blow to deliver to the Dodgers,
though. His older brother and mentor, Ramon, is in the final stages
of rehabilitation for the Red Sox. Pedro believes his brother will
return and pitch effectively _ and that the Dodgers will regret
letting another Martinez go.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it for the Dodgers for 11 years. I don't see why he
can't do it here, too,'' Pedro said. ``They thought they'd fly to
the World Series without Ramon. That was another big mistake they
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they didn't learn their lesson with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
