<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION CENTER TO OPEN AS PART OF EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service will open an office
near Springfield as part of an expansion into emerging immigration
centers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 45 Quick Response Teams will focus on immigrant smuggling,
document fraud, employment violations and other crimes in 11
states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new office in Strafford, Mo., reflects the changing
demographics of the Ozarks, part of a shift in immigration patterns
nationwide. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years poultry plants and factories in the Ozarks have
attracted thousands of immigrants from Latin America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jaromin, the immigration agency's deputy district
director, said, however, that southwest Missouri also was seeing
its share of immigration violations and related crime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe it is a problem. That is part of the reason
we're going out there,'' said Jaromin, whose Kansas City office
will oversee the team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new immingration office will open Sept. 1 about 10 miles
east of Springfield. The office will employ 11, including seven
special agents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 7,000-square-foot center will not offer services such as
issuing visas. Agents will focus on enforcement instead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The center will keep undocumented immigrants for brief stays
during processing. Some residents had feared that the center would
function as a jail, but officials said no one would stay
overnight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest immigration agency figures show about 18,000
undocumented immigrants in Missouri, although Jaromin said he
thought those estimates were low. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bill Hodgson, who works in the Hispanic ministry for
the Diocese of Springfield-Cape Girardeau, said his immigrant
parishioners hoped the agency did not become heavy-handed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be some effect on our community, but it's too
early to say what it will be,'' he said. ``We know (immigration
agents) have their job to do, but we hope they will treat everyone
fairly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials in Washington and some experts say immigrants
are moving away from traditional drawing points such as Texas and
the Southwest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Krikorian, executive director of the Center for Immigration
Studies, said those states had become so saturated with newcomers
that ``immigrants themselves are ... looking for greener
pastures.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The immigration agency also will add new teams in Arkansas,
Colorado, Georgia, Iowa, Kentucky, Nebraska, North Carolina, South
Carolina, Tennessee and Utah. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Krikorian and Jaromin said southwest Kansas, which has drawn
thousands of immigrants to work in beef-packing plants, would have
benefited from a stronger presence by immigration authorities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the agency, which operates an office in Wichita, has no
immediate plans for a center in western Kansas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
