<SLUG> BC-NIXON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC WILL BE ABLE TO DUPLICATE NIXON TAPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About two or three times a day, someone takes a
seat at the National Archives at College Park, Md., clasps on a
clunky headset, hits a button on a cassette player and eavesdrops
on history.
</P>
<P>
   The people who do this are hearing private White House
conversations between President Richard M. Nixon and his aides in
the Watergate crisis, which culminated in his resignation 25 years
ago Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most people know the story of Watergate, but relatively few
people _ historians, researchers, tourists, Nixon junkies _ have
taken the time to listen to it unfold in conversations the
president recorded.
</P>
<P>
   That changes Jan. 1, when for the first time 264 hours of White
House tapes will be available for public duplication and sale.
Currently tapes cannot be reproduced, much less distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Historians and archivists are not quite sure what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Will the tapes be packaged into a sort of Watergate greatest
hits of key conversations, such as the so-called ``smoking gun''
tape of Nixon discussing the Watergate break-in or the one in which
John Dean warned Nixon of a ``cancer on the presidency?''
</P>
<P>
   Or will there merely be a flurry of the media playing the same
tapes, followed by general disinterest among all but Nixon buffs
and historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good question,'' said Karl H. Weissenbach, director of
the Nixon Presidential Materials staff at the National Archives.
``Whether they will be used for late night comedy or whatnot, I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The archives plans to hire a private vendor to duplicate the
tapes for sale to the public, the media, libraries and other
interested parties, Weissenbach said. He did not yet know how the
tapes would be grouped or priced.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes will be issued as part of a 1996 settlement between
the Nixon estate, which has fought their release at various stages
for years, and a group that wanted the process sped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been out long ago, of course,'' said Stanley
Kutler, who wrote Abuse of Power: The New Nixon Tapes and battled
the Nixon estate over the tapes. ``As long as Richard Nixon was
alive, we were not going to have these. He did not want to confront
the embarrassment once more in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon supporters said the problem with 264 hours of tapes about
Watergate and abuse of power was that they were only a fraction of
the nearly 4,000 hours of White House conversations Nixon recorded
in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Those tapes, forced onto the public record before other tapes
because of the Watergate investigation, distort Nixon's larger
record as president, said John H. Taylor, executive director of the
Nixon Foundation and the Nixon Presidential Library and Birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were extraordinary achievements in foreign and domestic
policy, but because of the way the tapes were released, there has
been a preponderance of focus on Watergate,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1996 agreement, 2,338 hours of Nixon tapes on issues
mostly unrelated to Watergate will be released in the next several
years. Only then can the full effect of the tapes be known, Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extent to which they may destroy him, they may also rescue
him,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, the pubic dissemination of the Watergate
tapes probably will bring a new round of disdain for Nixon, even
though some transcripts have been in publication for 25 years,
Kutler and others said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like hearing it,'' Kutler said.
</P>
<P>
   On microphones Nixon planted inside his desk, in the Oval Office
fireplace and on his phone, he is heard plotting with aides to
cover up the Watergate break-in, blunt the FBI investigation and
pay hush money to potential witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to the tapes is a chilling and profoundly depressing
experience, because you are literally an acoustical fly on the
wall,'' said William Doyle, author of Inside the Oval Office: The
White House Tapes from FDR to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening in real time, with legs banging on desks and
ashtray scraping.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the key conversations, however, are hard to understand,
even with transcripts, because people moved about and sometimes
spoke softly. Nixon did not tell aides he was taping.
</P>
<P>
   The tape considered to have been the last straw for Nixon's
presidency came to public attention four days before his
resignation. It was a June 23, 1972, conversation in which he
approved a plan to halt the FBI's probe of the burglary six days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On that tape and others, Nixon can be heard giving tacit
approval to crimes suggested by aides. But sometimes Nixon outright
orders crimes to be committed.
</P>
<P>
   A year before Watergate, for example, Nixon ordered then-chief
of staff H.R. Haldeman to have someone break into the Brookings
Institution in Washington to see whether the liberal think tank had
any documents that would undermine his policies in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're to break into the place, rifle the files and bring them
to me,'' Nixon said. ``Just go in and take it. Go in around 8 or 9
o'clock. And I mean clean it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle alluded to that tape in his book, saying it reflected a
blustery Nixon who sometimes gave orders his aides did not take
seriously. No one broke into Brookings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of Richard Nixon's operating style was that many of
these crimes in progress were mere fantasy,'' Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon wrote in his memoirs that he was probably foolish to have
the taping system but that he never thought the tapes would become
public. The tapes, however, are bound to resurrect divisive public
attitudes about Nixon, one scholar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has that capacity to polarize,'' said Roderick P.
Hart, a professor of communication and government at the University
of Texas and an author of several books on verbal political styles.
</P>
<P>
   The Nixon on the tapes is not the Nixon most Americans heard in
public, Hart said. Publicly, Nixon tended to craft his words, to
not exaggerate as some politicians do, Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his public speeches he was a very careful person,'' Hart
said. ``In private, he is just kind of a roustabout. The
public-private distinction there might be pretty stark for most
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
