<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-JARRETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT STAYS HOT WITH BRICKYARD WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ With every left turn of every lap of every race,
Dale Jarrett is hunkering down for the ride of his NASCAR Winston
Cup lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Before it ends in November, it could rival Jeff Gordon's 1998
dream season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anybody to shake me and wake me up,'' said
Jarrett, shortly after exiting Victory Lane at the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway as winner of the Brickyard 400 for the second time.
``It's as good as it can get right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after he embarrassingly ran out of fuel while leading
this race at halfway, Jarrett and crew chief Todd Parrott redeemed
themselves with a Gordonesque show of domination.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett led 117 of 160 laps around the 2.5-mile Speedway,
flicked off the challenges of Gordon, Mark Martin and eventual
runner-up Bobby Labonte, and stretched his championship lead to a
season-high 274 points.
</P>
<P>
   And just to spice it up for car owner Robert Yates and
approximately 320,000 fans, Jarrett and Parrott rolled the dice on
a two-tire pit stop during the day's last caution period. It was a
show of bravado right out of the ``Jeff Gordon/Ray Evernham NASCAR
Championship Handbook''.
</P>
<P>
   ``To compare my and Jeff's seasons ... we've had the kind of
breaks we saw them have,'' said Jarrett, who pulled away in the
final 14 laps to a 3.351-second margin of victory over Labonte.
``You have to give the crew a lot of credit for that. There's a lot
of comparisons, but right now, things are really going our way.''
</P>
<P>
   His fourth victory of 1999 allowed Jarrett to tie Gordon and
Jeff Burton for the lead in that category after 20 of 34 races.
Jarrett, 42, would have to hustle to tie Gordon's single-season
record of 13 victories from last year, and originally compiled by
Richard Petty in 1972. But more important for Jarrett as he chases
his first Cup championship, he now has 16 top-five and 18 top-10
finishes. Those numbers are similar to ones Gordon compiled while
cruising to his third title last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how to win a championship,'' said Gordon, who
scrambled to finish third in the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes
Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I think he's very, very tough right now.
It's like they were just biding their time getting those top-fives
early in the season, and all of a sudden everything started
clicking for him. Boom, now they're getting wins and they're doing
a great job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's too easy for 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett averaged 148.228 mph on the way to his 22nd career Cup
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Jarrett's gasoline gaffe opened the door for Gordon
to become the first two-time winner of the Brickyard 400 last
August. Yesterday, Jarrett became the event's second two-time
champion after he and Parrott left no detail to chance _ especially
in the fuel-mileage department.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the trouble we had earlier in the year at Las Vegas and
the trouble we had here last year, the last thing we wanted was to
have a fuel problem,'' Parrott said. ``We did spend three or four
hours just making sure how much fuel we could pick up and how much
fuel the car used under cautions _ just exactly what it took.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who took the lead for the sixth time on Lap 118, was
fueled to run to the finish when veteran Dave Marcis blew an engine
and brought out the third and final caution on Lap 143. The lead
pack, including Jarrett, Martin, Jeff Burton, Labonte and Gordon,
all chose to pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd had already told me that we were good on fuel,'' said
Jarrett, who was driving the same No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford
Credit Taurus he wheeled here last year. ``Then the caution came
out and I said, `Here we go again.' We agreed to come in and take
two tires. We had no idea what it would do to the car. But really,
it was the best it was all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's two-tire stop prompted a similar strategic move by
Labonte, who had been trying to track down the leader despite an
engine that had developed a mysterious miss over the final 40 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed the 88 car a lot today,'' said Labonte, a native of
Texas and driver of the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac Grand
Prix. ``Jarrett didn't slip or slide. He ran a perfect line all
day, a better line than I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see if Dale wins 13 races to see if he's doing
better than Jeff did last year. I'm not sure if they're `dominant.'
But when they're on, they're on.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
