<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves hit hard, save Mulholland
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The new pitcher won a game. The new catcher knocked in
a couple runs. The refitted Braves are apparently finished with the
introductions and have embarked on a modest win streak.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Terry Mulholland allowed three of the first four men
he faced to score but still won his 100th game in his debut with
the Braves as they swarmed San Francisco's embattled pitching staff
in 15-4 laugher Saturday afternoon. The victory was their third in
a row, putting them at 12-11 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   A win today would give the Braves their first sweep in eight
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are starting to swing the bat,'' said Ryan Klesko,
who hit two RBI doubles. ``You're going to go through the little
ruts during the year when you're not scoring as many runs as you
want. But we're playing good ball the last couple days.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams has stoked the top of the order. He was 3-for-5
with a double and a three-run home run (a career-high 11th),
bringing his totals for the past 10 games to .381 with four home
runs, 13 RBIs and nine runs scored. For the seventh time in that
run, he batted leadoff and all three hits came off right-handers, a
hint to manager Bobby Cox and his search for a dependable leadoff
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to hit whomever is on the mound,'' Williams
said. ``Sometimes the clearest message you send is not through
words.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan hit his 20th home run and catcher Greg Myers, on
the same day Eddie Perez dropped his appeal and started serving his
four game suspension, had a two-RBI game, giving him six in six
games since rejoining the team.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland spent his first inning is distress, giving up six
hits and a 3-0 lead to the first seven men he faced. When the
Braves reclaimed a 4-3 advantage, he also served a home run to
Charlie Hayes before blanking the Giants through the sixth,
allowing just two hits to the last 15 men he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
