<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OMAHA-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERSHIP GATHERING IS SHORT OF CANDIDATES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ If Republicans want a competitive fight for their
party's presidential nomination, they did not find much
encouragement here on Saturday at the Republican Midwest Leadership
Conference, which attracted more than 800 delegates from 13
Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   What the event did not attract was presidential candidates. Six
of the 10 contenders passed up this gathering, which had been
billed as a crucial opportunity for Republican hopefuls to sell
themselves only a week before an important straw poll in
neighboring Iowa _ and to draw precious press attention in that
state.
</P>
<P>
   The only candidates who showed are battling at the bottom of the
pack: Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher; former Gov.
Lamar Alexander of Tennessee; Gary Bauer, former head of the Family
Research Council; and Alan Keyes, a radio personality.
</P>
<P>
   The shabby attendance is an example of the peculiar dynamics of
the Republican contest for the White House in 2000. Although the
first voting is six months away, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is so
dominant in polls and in amassing campaign funds that he can pass
up most events. And with the front-runner not participating, most
of Bush's rivals do not feel compelled to, either.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders who did take part played to this audience in the
heartland by emphasizing their proposals to help farmers. But
mostly, they picked on Bush, characterizing him as a glitzy,
big-money candidate who is not versed in the issues. They presented
themselves as populists who could get by without massive donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very strange way to pick a president,'' groused
Alexander, who is trying to keep afloat a campaign that is nearly
broke. ``The worst thing that could happen to the Republican Party,
or to the country, really, is if we let big money or big media pick
a nominee before the race starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he continued, ``then we wind up in the middle of a
debate with Albert Gore or Bill Bradley and find we've got somebody
who's not ready to be president. And then we get 16 years of
Clinton and Gore _ and maybe eight of Hillary after that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the last gathering of the Republican Midwest Leadership
Conference, in Indianapolis two years ago, the scene was far more
lively. There were double the number of prospective candidates.
Campaigns passed out bumper stickers and set up hospitality suites
(with well-stocked bars and trays of canapes) to court Republican
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush addressed the conference in Indianapolis. It was a
move his advisers later regretted: the governor was not prepared
for the national spotlight and drew critiques for delivering a
lackluster speech. Since then, he has stayed clear of such cattle
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between this event and the one in Indianapolis also
reflects the unusually early unfolding of this presidential
campaign. Because so many states have moved up the dates of their
contests in 2000, the nominees may be known by mid-March. The
compressed calendar has resulted in early fund-raising, early
campaigning, and, perhaps, the unusually early emergence of a
leading candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who is dipping into his inherited fortune to finance his
campaign, depicted Bush as beholden to moneyed interests. ``You'll
have to take it up with Governor Bush why he passes up these
opportunities to talk to interested Republican activists,'' he
said. ``Ultimately, you win not by being anointed by the elites in
Washington or by the lobbyists. The way to do it is to take your
message to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking, rhetorically, to goad Bush into a debate, Bauer
asserted: ``Our front runner has views on a number of issues that
are quite different from where the party has gone in the past. We
need to debate about those things. And I would encourage him,
however much he likes Austin, Texas, to come to events like this
and give Republican voters, Republican leaders, to take the measure
of him. Not just how well he flips a pancake.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, a former State Department official, warned Republicans
against ``anointing the winner before we get to the voting booth.''
He added, pointedly, ``We face a crisis in this country of
arrogance. In that arrogance they spit in the face of the American
voter.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Moore, the Nebraska secretary of state, read the audience
a letter from former Vice President Dan Quayle, who dropped out
because his mother was sick. But Moore did not hide his displeasure
at Pat Buchanan, the conservative commentator, who decided Saturday
morning not to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decided at the last minute to go to a parade in Des
Moines,'' Moore said. ``So I'll let you do with that information
what you wish.''
</P>
<P>
   But many delegates did not seem particularly exercised at the
no-shows. Beth Long, a state assembly member from Lebanon, Mo.,
said she was glad that her preferred candidate, Bush, was not here
because he is already popular with this audience. ``For him it
might have been preaching to the choir,'' she said. ``His time is
better spent on people who are undecided.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
