<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MCGARITY-TEX </SLUG>
 
COWBOYS ROOKIE RECEIVER McGARITY WINNING SUPPORT 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ When training camp opened two weeks ago,
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey had a simple assessment of rookie
receiver Wane McGarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``His role on the football team is that he's a rookie trying to
make the football team,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   But after a barrage of injuries to wide receivers, most notably
the season-ending loss of James McKnight to a torn anterior
cruciate ligament three days ago _ and McGarity's early impressive
play _ Gailey has been forced to re-evaluate the former Texas star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity for someone to come in and make plays,''
Gailey said. ``Wane's doing some good things. It will be
interesting to see how he takes advantage of this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity, already considered a candidate for punt and kickoff
return duties, is now the primary backup to Michael Irvin and is
being measured for a role in the Cowboys' four-receiver set.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-8, 191-pound speedster is just one of a number of
players the Cowboys' coaching staff will be watching in tomorrow's
preseason opener against the Cleveland Browns in Canton, Ohio. The
coaches will want to find out not only if the players can make the
team, but more important, can they be key contributors this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have to come out and step up,'' McGarity said. ``My
chances of making the club and getting on the field have improved.
It's unfortunate the way James got hurt. I don't want to see it
happen that way, but I am going to take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of McGarity's getting a chance because of an injury
was not lost on him either _ considering his pedigree of five knee
surgeries in high school and college combined. His injury-plagued
history were reasons few people, including himself, thought he
would have a shot at playing in the NFL at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, it was all about having a senior season,'' said
McGarity, who blew out his left knee as a junior and wasn't even
expected to play as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL was not on my mind. Knowing my injury history, I
wouldn't have gave myself a chance to be here at all. I worked hard
to have a good season and didn't worry about the NFL. I just let
that come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity, who now sports a tight Afro hairdo after wearing
dreadlock-like braids in college, came back to become the lightning
to Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams' thunder in the Texas
offense last season.
</P>
<P>
   A San Antonio native, McGarity caught 58 passes for 1,087 yards
and nine touchdowns as a senior, while capturing the attention of
an important person _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give Jerry Jones credit for this one,'' scouting director
Larry Lacewell said. ``Jerry Jones liked McGarity. He got enamored
with him as a kickoff return man and his ability to make big plays.
I can remember Jerry oohing and ahhing over it.''
</P>
<P>
   The oohs and ahhs have continued since Jones personally selected
McGarity in the fourth round of the 1999 NFL draft. McGarity has
impressed Gailey with ability to field punts, while his speed,
hands and overall skills as receiver have been noticed by
quarterback Troy Aikman and Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wane has been impressive in my opinion,'' said Aikman, who has
shown little patience with rookie receivers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know about the injuries he's had over the last five or
six years. If he can stay healthy, I think he's a guy who can play
at this level. I know that. He's looked good in camp and made some
good catches. He's got tremendous quickness. I think he's a guy who
has been very well-coached in college. He's done some good things
that a lot of guys just don't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin went a step further, saying, ``Wane is going to be a
big-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him in the fourth round and that was a steal,'' Irvin
said. ``I study people. I look at Wane a lot like \RSteelers
first-round draft pick\S Troy Edwards. I don't see where
\REdwards\S was much better than Wane to make three rounds
difference. Wane is going to be here and be a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity said he appreciates the support from his teammates and
is grateful to Jones for believing in him. However, he said he's
not taking anything for granted. ``I've come a long way,'' McGarity
said. ``But I'm not finished. I got to get in the playbook more and
continue to work hard to make the most of my chances.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
