<HEADLINE>
CAUTIOUS EDMONDS RETURNS TO OUTFIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Outfielder Garret Anderson was a late scratch from
Saturday's game because of a twisted left ankle suffered Friday
night when he slipped chasing down a double by the Red Sox's Troy
O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Anderson meant Jim Edmonds got his first start in
center field this season. He served as the DH in his first five
games after returning from shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds wasn't expected to return to the outfield for another
week or so because the Angels were concerned he might reinjure the
shoulder diving for a ball or running into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds found himself with a decision to make in the second
inning on Nomar Garciaparra's drive to deep center. Instead of
trying to make a spectacular catch and crashing into the wall,
Edmonds played the carom and got the ball in quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I thought about out there today was running
into a wall,'' Edmonds said. ``I just have to use my best judgment,
considering the circumstances. I've got to figure out what approach
to take in each situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds said he was glad to be back out there but would have
liked the game to have a better ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun at first,'' he said. ``But it was a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   For Anderson, the game was only the second he's missed all
season. He is listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Silent Salmon: Tim Salmon's eighth-inning home run Saturday was
his first since returning from a sprained left wrist that cost him
62 games.
</P>
<P>
   He went 87 at-bats without a home run _ including 75 since
returning July 17 _ the last one coming April 29 vs. Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   But after losing 14-3, Salmon wasn't in a mood to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got waxed, it's not a good day to talk about myself,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
