<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARK-GORE-FUNDRAISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE STOPS BY; CLINTON PLAYS GRACIOUS HOST  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ If Vice President Al Gore is worried that
President Clinton is dragging down his own presidential bid, he did
not show it Saturday as he flew into Clinton's home base here and
exploited the president's legendary ability to draw a crowd _ and
money.
</P>
<P>
   At the first of four fund-raising receptions that the president
was sponsoring for his vice president in the next several weeks,
Clinton lavished the kind of praise on Gore that had repeatedly
eluded previous vice presidents so early in a campaign season. This
came amid reports of a strained relationship between the two as
Gore had sent mixed signals about whether he welcomed such a close
association with a man whose scandals have wearied the nation with
what pollsters call ``Clinton fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that his own actions might have tainted Gore,
Clinton said Saturday night, ``Whatever anybody thinks about
whether I was right or wrong about a given issue, when the history
of the last six-and-a-half years or next year-and-a-half is
written, there is one thing that no one will be able to question,
and that is that Al Gore was by far the most influential and
effective and productive vice president in the history of the
United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The president took credit for putting Gore on his ticket in
1992, called him ``my friend and partner,'' and said the vice
president was ``a good and decent man'' who had supported him
``through thick and thin.''
</P>
<P>
   In conveying that loyalty, Clinton used unusual and sometimes
unfortunate phrasing, saying that Gore ``has been at my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, when Gore officially announced his
candidacy, he went to some lengths to separate himself from the
president. He said that Clinton's extramarital affair with a White
House intern, which led to his impeachment, was inexcusable and
bemoaned ``that awful year we went through.'' He also said he had
had many disagreements with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And yet in December, on the day the House voted to impeach
Clinton, Gore declared that Clinton was one of the country's
greatest presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Gore was a gracious guest on Clinton's home turf, but
hardly effusive. ``Now there's a real friend for you,'' Gore said
at Saturday night's fund-raiser in the one setting where his
remarks were made public. ``I've been awful proud to be his partner
and work on the tremendous success that Bill Clinton has provided
for our country.'' He then launched into his usual campaign speech.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was operating on virtually no sleep after continuous travel
and a rigorous three-day backpacking trip with his son, Albert III,
up a snow-covered Mount Ranier. Aides said that Gore and his son
each carried 65 pounds of gear, encountered hailstorms and that the
hike was so challenging, some in their party dropped off.
</P>
<P>
   After the hike, Gore arrived in Seattle about midnight on
Friday. He then flew to Chicago, landing about 6 a.m. on Saturday,
and spoke to the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition conference before flying
here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Clinton in a discussion with farmers at a coffee shop,
strolled with the president through a food court and met privately
with a group of 200 black leaders. Saturday night they attended a
fund-raising reception, where the vice president wore cowboy boots
with his suit, and a private mix-and-mingle event. He spent
Saturday night here and planned to fly to New Hampshire on Sunday
to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Every step of the way, the president served as his warm-up act.
Introducing him Saturday night, Clinton said of Gore: ``If
everything was on the line and I had to pick an American to make a
decision that I knew would be good for my country when my daughter
is my age, I would pick Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of those who watched the two Saturday were skeptical
that Clinton's ``help'' was a good thing. Standing on a street
corner, Bryan Fink, 36, a Methodist pastor from Conway, Ark., said,
``If Gore weren't so close to Clinton, it would probably help him
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Brady, 72, a retiree from North Little Rock, said Gore
paled in comparison with Clinton. ``He has the same ideas that
Clinton has, but Gore doesn't have the personality and charisma,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Saturday night's reception, Donald Parks, 79, who owns a
telephone company in Prairie Grove, Ark., said he was a big fan of
Clinton, though he wanted to ``wring his neck'' at times. But he
said he was ``a little apprehensive'' about the effect Clinton was
having on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake for Gore to take him on,'' Parks said, ``but he
doesn't really have a choice. Still, if he didn't have the close
connections with the president that he has, he wouldn't be as
effective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
