<SLUG> BC-RAC-DELMAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZEL TRICK EARNS HIGH PRAISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR _ Good thing Mazel Trick can't read his trainer's
quotes, or his sturdy legs might be creaking under the weight of
expectations this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Frankel, not shy but also not one to hype his horses
unrealistically, is comparing the winner of Saturday's $245,000 San
Diego Handicap to a certain other ex-turf specialist who found
happiness on the main track.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 4 for 4 on the dirt,'' Frankel noted after the six-length
victory by Mazel Trick and Chris McCarron. ``That's how Cigar
started, remember that?''
</P>
<P>
   Mazel Trick has a long way to go to match Cigar's 16 consecutive
victories and two Horse of the Year titles.
</P>
<P>
   But after sprinting to a Hollywood Park 7-furlong record
(1:19.97) in the Triple Bend Handicap in June, and after destroying
a modest field in the decade's fastest San Diego (1:40.68), Mazel
Trick at least looks like a threat in the one race Cigar couldn't
win.
</P>
<P>
   That's Del Mar's Pacific Classic, the $1 million race in which
Dare and Go prevented Cigar from breaking Citation's winning-streak
record in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Mazel Trick will have to step up in class when he faces three of
the toughest older horses around _ Victory Gallop, Real Quiet and
Malek _ in the Aug. 29 Pacific Classic. And the 4-year-old colt
will have to stretch out to attempt 1\ miles for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Raw talent can never be discounted, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look too weak today at the end of the race,''
Frankel said after the 1 1/16-mile San Diego, the major local prep
for the Pacific Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Mazel Trick tracked long-shot Tibado for half a mile, zipped to
the lead at the rail on the far turn, then laughed at River Keen in
the stretch while Budroyale ran a poor fourth and last.
</P>
<P>
   Mazel Trick had his first five races in France before being sold
to former Kentucky Gov. Brereton Jones and the 3+U Stable. For the
new owners, Frankel started him in a turf sprint at Santa Anita in
October, and the son of the brilliant sprinter Phone Trick finished
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But since switching to dirt tracks with his next start, Mazel
Trick is unbeaten, the victories coming by increasing margins.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel said this might be the fastest horse he's had in a
33-year, Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might (also) be the best,'' the trainer said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day for horses with ``future star'' quality.
</P>
<P>
   The co-featured, $150,000 Sorrento Stakes for 2-year-old fillies
was dominated as expected by Bob Baffert-trained Chilukki and David
Flores. As with Mazel Trick, Chilukki won by six lengths. She has
won all four starts _ by 25 lengths combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's another breed,'' said Chris Antley, who rode runner-up
November Slew.
</P>
<P>
   Chilukki ($2.40) and Mazel Trick ($3.40) are part of an amazing
run of racing at Del Mar. Twelve consecutive races on Friday and
Saturday were won by favorites before the streak was snapped in a
claiming event.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Hambletonian _ harness racing's Kentucky Derby _ was
won in world-record time by favored Self Possessed and driver Mike
Lachance. The New Jersey-based colt trotted the mile at the
Meadowlands in 1:51 3/5 Saturday to knock one-fifth off the record
Beat the Wheel set five years ago on the same track. . . . At
Saratoga, 3-year-old champion Banshee Breeze and Jerry Bailey toyed
with Beautiful Pleasure and won the Go for Wand Handicap. . . . At
Canterbury Park in Minnesota, 6-year-old Aplomado and jockey Laffit
Pincay won a $100,000 sprint for California trainer Vladimir Cerin
on the Claiming Crown card. . . . Walter Greenman was reported to
be in good spirits at Scripps Hospital in La Jolla after surgery
Friday to remove a brain tumor. The 59-year-old trainer was
expected to go home as early as today. . . . Victory Gallop's
scheduled trip from Saratoga to Del Mar was delayed from Friday to
Tuesday because of a cough, trainer Elliott Walden said. . . .
Manistique goes for her ninth win in 11 starts in today's Chula
Vista.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
