<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, FATE IS KIND TO DALE JARRETT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The fuel efficiency of a stock car can mean the
difference between winning and losing in Nascar Winston Cup racing.
Dale Jarrett knows that, having seen the little red light on his
dashboard come on at inopportune times.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed appropriate that fuel efficiency was poised to
determine Jarrett's fate again, Saturday in the Brickyard 400. The
memory of what happened to him here one year ago weighed heavily on
many people's minds. Jarrett was strong and out in front, again.
But did he have enough fuel stay there? No one knew for sure.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, fate was kind to Jarrett. The Winston Cup
points leader didn't have to watch for the little red light.
Jarrett, who ran out of fuel midway though last year's race and
finished 16th, got the break he so desperately needed, in the form
of a caution late in the race. He refueled and drove away from the
field over the final laps to capture his second checkered flag at
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess after last year, you wonder what scenario is going to
play out,'' said Jarrett, who led 117 of 160 laps. ``I had a good
lead, and they told me we could make it on fuel. I was saving a
little bit of fuel at that time. Before the caution came out, I was
saying: `Here we go again. What do we do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief, said: ``The last thing we
wanted to do was have a fuel problem. We spent several hours
testing, figuring out how much fuel we were using. Knowing how many
laps we could go really helped us today.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory, Jarrett's fourth this season, gave him a 274-point
lead over his fellow Ford driver Mark Martin, who finished fourth.
Bobby Labonte, in a Pontiac, finished second; Jeff Gordon made a
late charge to finish third in a Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When those guys got to racing side by side, that certainly
made things easier on me,'' Jarrett said of running away from the
pack late in the race. ``This is as good as it can get right
now..''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's car could turn slightly more than 40 laps on a full
tank. But having refueled with 42 laps remaining, it would be
close. That was when he got a break. Dave Marcis, who generally
runs in the back of the pack, slowed on the track after his engine
blew up with 17 laps left. The yellow flag came out, and Jarrett
and the other leaders pitted. Jarrett took on fuel and two tires
and emerged from the pits in front of Labonte, Martin and Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Jarrett avoided another fuel emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I think we shed a lot of tears as we left here,''
said Robert Yates, who owns Jarrett's car. ``We couldn't even joke
about running out of gas for six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the fuel drama, the race was rather dull. It featured
few lead changes and even fewer exciting moments on the track. Six
drivers led Saturday's race, but the final lead change occurred on
Lap 79.
</P>
<P>
   Many drivers complained during the week that this track had one
racing groove _ the fastest part of the track. And when there is
just one, that means overtaking is very difficult. The result is
often a ho-hum race with few passes. That was certainly the case
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who is the only other driver to win the Brickyard 400
twice, said: ``Jarrett was dominant last year at this race before
he ran out of gas. They've got it together right now. They really
do. They're going to be tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who battled handling problems all day, provided the most
exciting moments over the final stages of the race. With seven laps
remaining, Gordon was in sixth place. But Gordon, who was the pole
sitter, picked off Ward Burton, Jeff Burton and Martin over the
final laps to reserve a spot on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we could make our way up through there,'' Gordon
said, ``But we ran out of laps.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has been the runner-up in the Winston Cup championship
twice. But that doesn't seem likely after Saturday's victory, which
put an exclamation point on his breakout season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I don't want anybody to shake me and wake me up,''
Jarrett said. ``When you're second or third in the points, you have
to rely on the guy in front of you having problems. It's a lot more
fun to be in control of your destiny. It's great to be leading in
the points championship, and my opponents see the races counting
down, and they realize they are running out of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-07-99 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
