<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BOGGS-3000-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGGS HOMERS FOR HIS 3,000TH HIT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For his milestone of the moment, Wade Boggs decided to be
different. On the previous two nights, Mark McGwire had slugged his
500th home run and Tony Gwynn had lashed his 3,000th hit. Boggs
followed with his 3,000th hit Saturday night, but he did not attain
that elite circle routinely.
</P>
<P>
   After putting himself in position by stroking singles in the
third and fourth innings, Boggs cracked a home run in the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays' sixth inning at Tropicana Field in St. Petersburg,
Fla., becoming the 23rd player to reach 3,000 but the first to get
there with a home run.
</P>
<P>
   There had been 16 singles, five doubles and one triple as
3,000th hits, but no home run before the 41-year-old Boggs
connected against Chris Haney, a journeyman left-hander, who had
entered the game for the Cleveland Indians at the start of the
inning. When the ball landed in the right-field stands, it was only
Boggs' second home run of the season and the 118th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   As he joyously rounded the bases, Boggs pointed skyward in a
tribute to his late mother, pointed skyward again a few steps
before he reached home plate, then got down on his knees and kissed
the plate as he completed his historic 360-foot trot.
</P>
<P>
   His feat completed an incredible three-night run for major
league baseball. Never before had its players achieved these
legendary numbers on consecutive nights. In 1970, the only previous
season in which three players attained those plateaus, Ernie Banks
hit his 500th home run on May 12, Hank Aaron rapped his 3,000th hit
on May 17 and Willie Mays chipped in with his 3,000th hit on July
18.
</P>
<P>
   In the only other comparable coincidental occurrence, Rod Carew
stroked his 3,000th hit and Tom Seaver pitched his 300th victory on
the same day, Aug. 4, in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire's St. Louis Cardinals played Gwynn's San Diego
Padres on Thursday night, the two players could have become the
first duo to achieve their magic numbers in the same game. Then
Friday night Gwynn and Boggs, whose illustrious careers have been
parallel for 18 years, could have become the first players to hit
3,000 on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they each had a night and the spotlight to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs entered Saturday night's game with 2,997 hits. Facing
Charles Nagy, the Indians' leading winner with 12 victories, Boggs
grounded to second in the first inning. But in what would become a
wild-scoring affair that Cleveland won by 15-10, Boggs batted again
in the third and the fourth innings. Each time he rapped a
run-scoring single to right, catapulting himself one hit away from
his goal.
</P>
<P>
   Haney, who has extended his mediocre career because his species,
the left-hander, is always in demand, relieved Nagy at the start of
the sixth, making his third relief appearance for the Indians.
Boggs, the third scheduled batter in the inning, had batted against
Haney 13 times previously. He had collected four singles and two
walks, certainly no home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Lowery was at first base when Boggs swung at Haney's 2-2
pitch, a hanging breaking ball, and drove it over the right-field
fence. Boggs hit his only other home run this season against Mark
Portugal at Boston's Fenway Park, where he began his career in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   After he arose from his emotional romp around the bases, Boggs
was greeted on the field by his father, Win; his wife, Debbie, and
their 12-year-old son, Brett, who was the Devil Rays' bat boy.
Boggs grew up and played Little League baseball in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs walked in his final time at bat.
</P>
<P>
   While Gwynn was the 11th player to collect all 3,000 hits with
one team, Boggs amassed his with the Red Sox (2,098 in 11 seasons),
the Yankees (702 in five seasons) and the Devil Rays (200 in one
and two-thirds seasons).
</P>
<P>
   Boggs and Gwynn are the sixth pair of players to reach 3,000 in
the same season, but obviously the two who did it the closest to
each other. The last duo to reach 3,000 in the same season were
Robin Yount and George Brett, three weeks apart in September 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs became the seventh player in the 1990s to get to 3,000, a
total that matches the seven who did it in the 1970s. Cal Ripken,
on the disabled list with an ailing back for the second time this
season, will make it a record eight in the 1990s if he gets the 32
hits he needs.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs also is the third-oldest player to get his 3,000th hit,
trailing Cap Anson and Dave Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs gave notice of his hitting prowess early in his career. In
his second season, 1983, he began a streak of seven successive
200-hit seasons, reaching a career-high 240 in 1985. The only
player to have more than seven straight 200-hit seasons was Willie
Keeler, who did it eight times from 1894 through 1901.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
