<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9684 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     08-07 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE MEADOWLANDS: WILDERNESS ADVENTURES AT THE EDGE OF A CITY &LR; 
By Robert Sullivan. Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95. Much is buried in
this swampy region of New Jersey, from the remnants of the original
Pennsylvania Station to (perhaps) the remains of the labor leader
Jimmy Hoffa. The author explores the terrain, noting nature's
triumphs over sludge. Last year in The New York Times Book Review,
Robert Pinsky called this a ``provocative, audacious book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ETERNAL CURSE ON THE READER OF THESE PAGES &LR;  By Manuel Puig.
University of Minnesota, $15.95. The forbidding title is actually
the opening line of the jailhouse journal of Ramirez, a former
political prisoner in the author's native Argentina. Ramirez, 74,
can't remember anything; Larry, 36, who pushes him in a wheelchair
around Greenwich Village in New York, doesn't have much to
remember. The novel, the first Puig wrote in English, examines the
men's symbiotic relationship. ``Puig spins a fascinating web of
words, capturing the reader's attention with his uncanny ability to
develop plot and character through dialogue,'' Allen Josephs wrote
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has also restored to print  &UR; BLOOD OF REQUITED
LOVE &LR; , translated by Jan L. Grayson ($15.95), Puig's novel about
the troubled inner life of Josemar, a manual laborer in Brazil.
``Puig is adept at parodying people's awkward attempts to find a
language for their emotions,'' Jean Franco wrote in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALING LESSONS &LR;  By Sidney J. Winawer with Nick Taylor.
Routledge, $16. There was a terrible irony in the diagnosis Andrea
Winawer faced: intestinal cancer was a disease on which her husband
was an expert. He describes how her suffering taught him an empathy
that his medical training could not have done. This memoir
``reminds us to live fully, intensely,'' Abraham Verghese wrote
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLORIE &LR;  By Caryn James. Penguin, $12.95. This novel by the
chief television critic of The New York Times has an unusual
heroine: an elderly widow trying to hang on to her house, her
independence and the memory of her husband. ``One cannot help being
moved by her plight and by the unanswerable questions she asks,''
Richard Burgin wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHILDREN OF CAMBODIA'S KILLING FIELDS: MEMOIRS BY SURVIVORS &LR; 
Compiled by Dith Pran. Edited by Kim DePaul. Yale University,
$14.95. The murder of Cambodians by the Khmer Rouge was so
widespread that it is hard to believe anyone survived. These
testimonies, gathered by Dith Pran, a photographer for The New York
Times who himself escaped the killing, build ``a solid, irrefutable
censure of one of humanity's most shocking crimes,'' Lance Gould
said in The New York Times Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One woman's experience has been restored to print in  &UR; THE STONES
CRY OUT: A CAMBODIAN CHILDHOOD, 1975-1980 &LR; , by Molyda Szymusiak,
translated by Linda Coverdale (Indiana University, $12.95). Writing
under the name given her by her adoptive parents, Polish exiles in
Paris, the author describes how she and three younger cousins
became the only survivors of 20 members of her original family.
``This is a powerful and compelling story,'' Jane Hamilton-Merritt
wrote in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   David P. Chandler analyzes the leader of the genocide in
 &UR; BROTHER NUMBER ONE: A POLITICAL BIOGRAPHY OF POL POT &LR;  (Westview,
$16), reissued in a revised and updated edition. The dictator
emerges here as a ruthless ideologue and megalomaniac who also
managed to be a charismatic politician. In 1992 the reviewer
Frederick Z. Brown called it ``an absorbing and authoritative
portrait ... and a fascinating insight into Cambodia's cruel
history.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DOWER HOUSE &LR;  By Annabel Davis-Goff. St Martin's Griffin,
$13.95. Taking place in the 1950s and '60s, this novel captures the
faded glory of an Anglo-Irish family that clings to its aristocracy
despite its lost wealth. ``The book feels like a Christmas dinner:
rich, heavy, extravagant, lush _ and traditional in a way that no
one would dream of objecting to,'' Jacqueline Carey wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING AWAY WITH MURDER: HOW POLITICS IS DESTROYING THE
CRIMINAL JUSTICE SYSTEM &LR;  By Susan Estrich. Harvard University,
$12.95. A law professor proposes radical ideas that are really
old-fashioned ones: restricting efforts to shape juries and
allowing jurors' common sense, not expert opinions, to prevail.
``Estrich writes with verve and wit and style,'' the reviewer Akhil
Reed Amar wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ESSENCE OF THE THING &LR;  By Madeleine St. John. Carroll &AMP;
Graf, $11.95. A finalist for Britain's Booker Prize in 1997, this
novel begins with an abrupt end: Nicola, the heroine, returns to
her London flat after buying cigarettes, only to be greeted by her
lover's demand that she move out. It is ``a brisk, sophisticated
and artful narrative,'' Gardner McFall wrote earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FOREIGN STUDENT &LR;  By Susan Choi. Harper Perennial, $13. They
are an unlikely couple: Chuck, formerly Chang, a student who has
fled a war-shattered life in 1950s Korea, and Katherine, the
daughter of a wealthy Southern family. But both have nightmares to
escape. ``Choi brings hundreds of small scenes to life, then uses
them to construct an intricate portrait,'' Kimberly B. Marlowe
wrote in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
