A9689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HALLFAME-HNS &LR;      08-07 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALLFAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Dickerson makes himself at home
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CANTON, Ohio _ From Sealy to Canton, Eric Dickerson took a
circuitous route to the Pro Football Hall of Fame. His
record-breaking career spanned 11 years and four cities, and he
left the game as one of the greatest running backs in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Dickerson was voted into the Pro Football Hall of
Fame on the first ballot. On Saturday, he was enshrined among pro
football's immortals with Lawrence Taylor, Ozzie Newsome, Tom Mack
and Billy Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here is such an honor,'' Dickerson said before family,
friends and former teammates in the audience as well as a national
television audience. ``It validates every hit I took, every
cold-weather game I played, every contract dispute I went through.
It makes it all worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weekend, I've been just like a kid in a candy store. I'm
overwhelmed by it all. When I saw Otto Graham for the first time,
it was like, `Wow! That's Otto Graham.' I'm in awe of these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Counting the Class of '99, there are 199 members of the Pro
Football Hall of Fame. More than 50 returned for the annual
festivities that culminate with the Pro Football Hall of Fame Game
on Monday night when the new Cleveland Browns make their debut
against the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I got emotional in the parade (Saturday morning),''
Dickerson said. ``At a luncheon (Friday), I saw so many of the Hall
of Famers walking with canes. I'm sure the day will come when I'm
their age and I'm using a cane, and I hope some new inductee will
say, `Wow! There's Eric Dickerson.'''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference before the induction ceremonies, Dickerson
was asked about his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sealy was a small town when I was growing up, and it's a small
town today,'' he said. ``But football was king when I played at
Sealy High School, and football's still king today.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson rushed for 13,259 yards, third on the NFL's all-time
list behind Walter Payton and Barry Sanders. He played 4{ years
with the Rams, 4{ with the Colts and one each with the Raiders and
Falcons before retiring after the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest seasons were with the Rams. He rushed for more than
1,800 yards in three of his first four seasons, including an
NFL-record 2,105 in 1984, breaking O.J. Simpson's record of 2,003.
His season record still stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking the record meant a lot to me because it kind of
legitimized me,'' Dickerson said. ``My record's stood for 14 years,
but I believe it'll be broken. When it is, I'll be there to
congratulate the player who breaks it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Barry Sanders doesn't come back, I think (Denver's) Terrell
Davis has the best chance among today's backs.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dickerson was one of the greatest running backs, Taylor
was definitely the greatest linebacker in history. He might be the
greatest defensive player in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three people have been instrumental in my pro football career
_ (Giants owner) Wellington Mara, (former Giants general manager)
George Young and (former Giants coach) Bill Parcells,'' Taylor
said. ``When you mention great owners like George Halas, Paul Brown
and Art Rooney, you have to mention Wellington Mara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did he take care of me professionally, but he cared
about me on a personal level probably more than he should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's legal, financial and substance-abuse problems have been
well-documented. But he kept his problems off the field and never
gave less than 100 percent in games. He helped the Giants win two
Super Bowls under Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, the Jets coach, was unable to attend because of a team
scrimmage Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's the coach of coaches,'' Taylor said. ``My relationship
with Bill is kind of like a 30-year marriage _ you really don't
talk any more, but you know you love each other. Our relationship's
not the kind where we have to keep reaffirming our feelings for
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was having a difficult time choosing between Parcells and
Mara to be his presenter. His son, Lawrence Taylor Jr., who goes by
T.J., made the decision easy. The 17-year-old, who resides in
Charlotte, N.C., asked his father if he could introduce him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such an exciting day for me and my family, especially
my son,'' Taylor said. ``I think he'll be proud of me and himself.
Plus, he might be able to get some girls out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank my children for understanding that people do
make mistakes in life and being able to forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   A huge crowd of Giants fans in the audience shouted ``L.T.''
over and over during the three-hour ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it means to be inducted, Taylor said, ``Hall of
Famers realize the crime isn't getting knocked down; the crime's
not getting back up.''
</P>
<P>
   As loud as the Giants fans were, they were often drowned out by
fans of the new Cleveland Browns, who barked and chanted, ``Oz-zie,
Oz-zie,'' each time Newsome's name was mentioned or his picture
appeared on one of the Jumbotrons.
</P>
<P>
   Newsome, who caught more passes than any tight end in history,
played for Bear Bryant at Alabama before the Browns drafted him in
the first round in 1978. After his 13-year career ended, he moved
into the front office, where he ran the football side of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   When owner Art Modell moved the team to Baltimore and they
became the Ravens, Newsome went with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never betrayed the Cleveland Browns,'' Newsome said. ``If
the team hadn't left, I'd still be working for the Cleveland
Browns, and this would probably be a little bit bigger enjoyment,
but it's still great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to mentally prepare for this moment in a lot of
different ways, but one thing kept coming back to me. Coach Bryant
once told me, `Ozzie, in all circumstances, show your class.'
That's what I'm trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Modell, who is still vilified in Northern Ohio, didn't attend
the ceremonies. He has vowed never to return to Ohio because of
threats against his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day I was elected, Art called me and told me not to
mention his name because he didn't want to be a distraction,''
Newsome said. ``I wish Art were here because he's played such a big
part in everything I've done since the Browns drafted me in 1978.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Newsome mentioned Modell at the news conference, he
didn't mention him in his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Newsome sent the pro-Browns crowd into hysterics when he
said, ``It's going to be great to see those orange helmets and
white jerseys by the lake (Erie) again. I still have such
compassion for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland has the greatest fans in the world. It (moving the
team) was nothing the fans did, but they're the people who
suffered. I'm happy for them that football's back, hopefully, for
the rest of their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
