 VETS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas' Applewhite hasn't missed a beat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ Well, Major Applewhite didn't lose his starting spot at
the first practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but I might lose it at the second one,'' the Texas
quarterback joked after a Saturday morning workout at Whitaker
Field, the Longhorns' first full-squad practice.
</P>
<P>
   Jokes aside, Applewhite, who as an unheralded redshirt freshman
had one of the finest seasons statistically of any quarterback in
school history, is not likely to think his starting spot
threatened. Especially if he continues to be as sharp as he was in
the team's first installment of its two-week-long two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was deep balls and crossing routes to Kwame Cavil,
ins and outs to Ryan Nunez, or hooks and stops to a slew of tight
ends and running backs, Applewhite was on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense really clicked for a first practice,'' offensive
coordinator Greg Davis said. ``The skill position players were on
time, with very few miscues. That is a direct reflection of how
hard they worked over the summer to come in ready to go. There was
a lot of retention from the spring. It looked nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen Chris Simms and Adam Hall had their shining moments,
much to the delight of a crowd estimated at 1,200, but Applewhite
was the highlight. And that is how it should be for an offensive
squad that lost its top running back, receiver and starting and
backup tight ends. Make no mistake, this is Applewhite's offense,
Major's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my team,'' Applewhite said. ``I'm not going to take
credit for wins or take blame for losses. It's everybody's team _
special teams, defense and offense. All I can do is be the best
quarterback I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy that. Applewhite is in charge, and you can see why. No
one on the team works as hard in the film room to prepare, so he
rarely sees anything unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   He walks with an air of confidence and control, yet there he was
sprinting downfield at the first workout, trying to be the first to
pump up fullback Ricky Brown after a spectacular diving grab.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite said his weight (205 pounds) is the same as a year
ago, but he looks stronger thanks to added bulk in his torso.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the most telling difference between himself and the two
freshmen battling for the No. 2 spot is noticeable during passing
drills. Simms and Hall will drop back and loft beautiful 50-yard
spirals downfield that a few seconds after release fall harmlessly
to the ground. Applewhite's spiral, while above average, might not
be as tight and his ball might not come at the same velocity, but a
few seconds after his release, a Longhorns receiver gets an ovation
after a reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still learning, but they're getting better and they're
going to get better each practice,'' Applewhite said. ``Right now,
they just have a lot to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing they, and those anticipating trouble at the top
because Applewhite does not have running back Ricky Williams to
carry the load, have to learn is Applewhite is the man.
</P>
<P>
   He just won't admit it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
