<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Cubs-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' up-and-comers combine with Everett to crush Cubs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ The Chicago Cubs still haven't found a way to get Carl
Everett out, and now they have Russ Johnson to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   The hot-hitting tandem combined for eight RBIs, including a
career-high six by Johnson, in the Astros' 10-4 victory over the
Cubs on an overcast Saturday afternoon at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   The first pitch was delayed 26 minutes because of rain, and the
Cubs no doubt would have waited longer if it meant stalling Everett
and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Everett homered from both sides of the plate and Johnson was
4-for-6 as the Astros won for the 11th time in their last 15 games
in the Windy City. The offensive support was more than enough for
Scott Elarton, who allowed two runs on four hits and tied his
career-high with nine strikeouts in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of things going our way today,'' manager Larry
Dierker said. ``We had some good clutch hitting by Russ, Carl had
another good game, and Scott threw the ball really well. You can't
ask for much more than what we got today.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton quickly righted himself after a couple of mediocre
innings to start the game _ he retired 14 in a row at one point _
to win his first major-league game as a starter. His fastball,
slider, curve and changeup finally showed up on the same day, which
was bad news for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   After making 26 relief appearances to start the season, Elarton
(6-3) had struggled to gain command of his entire arsenal in his
first six starts. If Saturday was any indication, the adjustment
period may be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest key was my changeup,'' Elarton said. ``I haven't
really had it since I went into the rotation. I really had all four
pitches working, which surprised me because this is the first time
I've put everything together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to know that I've still got it. I wasn't sure how
long the adjustment period would take.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, it was just a matter of repetition. Perhaps
the same is true for Johnson, who struggled to find his rhythm at
the plate as a part-time player but is flourishing with more
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has started seven of the last 12 games at third base,
the last four in a row.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed the best day of his brief big-league career with a
two-run single in the third inning, a two-run double in the fourth
and RBI singles in the eighth and ninth. It was the fourth time
this season an Astro has delivered six RBIs in a game and the first
since Everett did it against the Expos on June 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a big RBI guy,'' said Johnson, who
only had 11 RBIs in 46 games before Saturday. ``I'm more of a
table-setter _ get on base and try to score a run. But that's not
the way it worked out today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing the ball really well right now and I'm making good
contact. When you're doing those two things, good things can
happen. I'm getting a chance to play right now, and I want to
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has started 23 times, has 10 RBIs and seven runs
scored in his last seven games. He has added 34 points to his
batting average during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as that is, it may not be enough to call him the
hottest Astro.
</P>
<P>
   That title goes to Everett, who was activated from the disabled
list Friday. After going 4-for-5 with five RBIs in the first game
of Friday's doubleheader, Everett was 3-for-5 Saturday. He homered
from the left side against Cubs starter Kevin Tapani in the second
inning and from the right side against reliever Felix Heredia in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine a guy being out (20 games) and coming
back the way Carl has,'' Dierker said. ``He's hit three home runs
in his last two games and hasn't shown any signs of lingering
problems from his (strained hamstring) injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said, ``He hurt us last year and he's
hurt us this year. We've got to make better pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's first homer gave the Astros a 1-0 lead. The Cubs
rallied in the bottom of the second on Gary Gaetti's two-out,
two-run double after Elarton walked two batters.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Everett took care of that, combining for five RBIs
from the third through the seventh innings. Their production made
it easy to overlook a mini-slump by Jeff Bagwell, who has just
three hits in his last 24 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just look to your horses to win games every single
time,'' Everett said. ``St. Louis is a prime example of that. You
have to get a contribution from everyone, and that's what this team
has been able to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really comfortable at the plate right now. I'm trying not
to think too much. I'm just trying to hit the ball hard somewhere.
I'm going to ride it out for as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Everett didn't drive in all the runs; it only seemed
that way. Craig Biggio had a RBI single in the eighth and Glen
Barker drove in a run in the ninth with a single to center.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs scored late on Henry Rodriguez's two-run homer in the
ninth off Doug Henry, who has allowed seven home runs in 17
appearances _ the most by an Astros reliever despite Henry missing
58 games because of elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Tapani (6-10) gave up five runs _ three earned _ and seven hits
in six innings as he lost his seventh straight decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very good behind him,'' Riggleman said. ``We're
not a good defensive ballclub. It's not a strength of ours. We have
to make the plays for our starting pitchers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
